 NOT JUST ANOTHER OPENING FOR DISPUTED MCNALLY PLAY 
 (l) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than the usual opening-night aticipation
surrounds Tuesday evening's performance of ``Corpus Christi,''
Terrence McNally's play about a gay Christ-like character and his
gay apostles. Dueling protesters have announced plans to
demonstrate in front of the City Center: those who oppose the
production on religious grounds and those who support it based on
free expression.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights, which
describes itself as the nation's largest Roman Catholic civil
rights group, organized the demonstration against the play. William
Donohue, the league's president, said he expected several thousand
protesters from various religious groups to show up near the
theater, which is on West 55th Street between Avenue of the
Americas and Seventh Avenue, in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a play which is replete with vulgarities, with
obscenities directed toward a world religion, I think that has to
be regarded as hate speech,'' said Donohue, who saw a preview
performance on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the protesters will be against the performance.
Barbara Handman, vice president and New York director of People for
the American Way, said about 200 people were expected to join a
silent march organized by her group, which focuses on civil
liberties. Their demonstration is scheduled to begin at 5 p.m. on
55th Street at Seventh Avenue and to continue until curtain time at
8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that people recognize that the First Amendment
gives us the opportunity to have so much expression that we can
have this play and we can also have the protest for this play,''
Ms. Handman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued on Monday, Lynne Meadow, the artistic
director of The Manhattan Theater Club, and Barry Grove, the
executive producer, said the theater ``understands that some people
have disagreed with the content of McNally's play, and firmly
supports and respects the public's right to express their
opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement added, ``Tonight's demonstration is a reflection
of the supreme importance of First Amendment rights, both for
artists and for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   McNally, the playwright, declined through a spokesman to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over ``Corpus Christi'' _ which follows the
contemporary Joshua from Corpus Christi, Tex., to Jerusalem _ began
to heat up in May, when theater officials received anonymous death
threats after details of the play's content became public. Early
accounts said the play featured a gay, Christ-like figure who had
sex with his apostles, although the version that has been performed
in previews includes only sensual kissing between Joshua, the
Jesus-like character, and Judas.
</P>
<P>
   When the protests began, the Manhattan Theater Club announced
that it would not produce the play, then reversed itself after an
outcry from artists and civil liberties organizations.
</P>
<P>
   To provide security for its audiences, the Manhattan Theater
Club has enlisted the help of Kroll Associates, a private
investigation and security company, as well as the New York Police
Department. People attending performances of the play, which began
previews on Sept. 22, will be required to pass through a metal
detector.
</P>
<P>
   At the first preview performance, about 200 protesters held a
prayer vigil outside City Center and theatergoers were handed
leaflets asking them to walk out of the play if they heard or saw
anything abusive to ``the sacred values of your neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   The play is to run through Nov. 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
