<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-SELLOFF-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SELLING CHOICE L.A. PROPERTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``f'' financial and ``n'' California news
files.) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Japanese real estate giants, caught in the global
credit crunch, are unloading marquee Los Angeles-area holdings at
significant discounts, real estate experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest example, Tokyo-based Shuwa Corp. is expected to
ask more than $2 billion but accept much less for its portfolio of
U.S. properties, including Arco Plaza in downtown Los Angeles, two
Century City office buildings and a high-profile office tower in
Glendale, nine miles north of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 sell-offs continue five years of steady liquidation
from Japanese players who amassed $77 billion in American real
estate assets. During the portfolio buildup, Asians bagged trophy
properties such as the Hotel Bel-Air and New York's Rockefeller
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But now Japanese banks and corporations that bought at the peak
of the market in the late 1980s are being forced to sell at prices
falling as far as 50 percent below what they paid. U.S. property
values gained back some of their value after the recession, but
this year's worldwide economic slowdown halted that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Shuwa is going to get a lower price than they
would have before the market disruption,'' said Stan Ross, vice
chairman and managing partner of E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal, a leading
tracker of Japanese real estate investment. ``Around the country,
you're seeing discounts of 5 and 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1997, Japanese owners were forced to unload $26
billion of U.S. holdings at a loss of $10 billion, Ross estimated.
When will the discounting stop? ``That's anybody's guess because
the market has been so disrupted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for prime U.S. office properties, which had recovered
since the recession of the early 1990s, have dropped in recent
months because of declines in the stock market and the perception
that real estate investment trusts bid prices up to unrealistic
levels in the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   That means buyers are likely to be opportunistic groups, looking
for bargains, rather than the pension funds and endowments that
traditionally invest in top-line commercial real estate, Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is unfortunate for Shuwa,'' said Grubb &AMP; Ellis
broker William Boyd. ``If they had put the portfolio up for sale a
year ago, they would have received higher offers than they're
getting now. The current crisis has only served to accelerate that
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal's Jack Rodman, managing partner of the
firm's Asian real estate operations, began advising Japanese
clients 18 months ago to sell U.S. holdings to real estate
investment trusts. He said he was largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is that the Japanese missed a window of opportunity to
cash out,'' Rodman said. ``Their timing continues to be poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd noted Shuwa paid $250 per square foot for the Glendale
property in 1988, a year after it was built by Reliance
Development. ``They bought at the height of the market, and it now
is most likely worth $210 a square foot,'' he said. ``It's kind of
a double whammy for them since the highest payers for those kind of
buildings may have retreated.''
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo-based Shuwa recently put its portfolio up for bid through
Eastdil Realty. The centerpiece of Shuwa's holdings is the 52-story
Arco twin towers, opened in 1972 with more than 2 million square
feet of office space and purchased in the late '80s by Shuwa for
$600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy rate in the building is now higher than 29 percent,
but economist Jack Kyser, who works in the building at the offices
of the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp., said the towers
remain an attractive site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property has aged pretty well, and it has a certain cachet
because of its unique character,'' he said. ``A buyer would be
betting on the future economic health of Southern California and
making a bit of a bet on the future of downtown. The key thing is
that downtown is the center of the freeway and rail mass transit
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuwa properties include two other downtown buildings _ the Gas
Co. building and the Chase Plaza _ as well as Taco Bell's corporate
headquarters in Irvine in neighboring Orange County and a pair of
Century City office structures. Kyser said there once was an
entitlement, since expired, for an 84-story structure on the Gas
Co. property.
</P>
<P>
   ``That entitlement was from back in the days when downtown L.A.
was the promised land,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Toronto-based real estate giant TrizecHahn Corp. reportedly has
bid $1.8 billion for the Shuwa portfolio. TrizecHahn, which
recently broke ground on a $380 million entertainment complex on
Hollywood Boulevard, did not respond to calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders stressed that the Japanese are not unloading
U.S. properties willy-nilly. ``What we're seeing is a continued
steady flow of properties come onto the market,'' Rodman said.
``It's going to continue to be a good buying opportunity for U.S.
investors with capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman estimated the Japanese retain $50 billion of the
properties bought before 1993 and said the holdings are now worth
between $35 billion and $40 billion. ``Instead of 50 cents on the
dollar, they can now get 70 cents on the dollar,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman said the Riviera Golf Course, the Nikko Hotel in Beverly
Hills and several downtown buildings, including 777 S. Figueroa,
the Hyatt Hotel and the 72-story former First Interstate
headquarters, are some of the prominent Japanese-owned properties
around Los Angeles likely to be sold in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman also said the properties may be easier to sell if Japan
can tackle its banking crisis. On Monday, Tokyo approved a package
of laws that will allow the government to spend up to $566 billion
to recapitalize banks and protect depositors, which may make it
easier for owners of U.S. real estate to strike debt-forgiveness
deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
