u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES14-C     10-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NLCS goes back to Atlanta after Braves' 7-6 win over Padres
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Michael Tucker, who spent much of the summer playing
his way out of the Atlanta Braves' future, guaranteed the club of
at least one more tomorrow Monday night. Evenings like this don't
happen in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two runs with five outs remaining in the season,
Tucker blasted a three-run homer off Kevin Brown, making a
win-it-now relief appearance, and powered the Braves to an
improbable 7-6 victory over the San Diego Padres. The Braves become
the first team in LCS history to force a Game 6 after losing the
first three games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta survived a two-run homer by Greg Myers off Kerry
Ligtenberg in the ninth inning when Greg Maddux came in to get the
final three outs.
</P>
<P>
   The series now returns to Turner Field, where the Braves will
attempt to draw even Wednesday afternoon. Left-hander Tom Glavine
will start for Atlanta. San Diego manager Bruce Bochy had planned
on starting Brown, but those plans are unclear after he threw 41
pitches in 1 1/3 innings of relief work and was charged with the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   The night appeared lost. Atlanta starter John Smoltz, undefeated
in his previous five postseason starts when the club was facing
elimination, gave up a Ken Caminiti two-run homer in the first.
After Atlanta finally scratched back to tie it in the sixth, Smoltz
allowed a John Vander Wal two-run homer with two out in the bottom
of the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   But in a remarkable sequence in the seventh, Ryan Klesko opened
the inning with a walk off Brown, who had relieved starter Andy
Ashby the
</P>
<P>
   inning before. Javy Lopez next delivered an infield single into
the hole at shortstop, and two batters later, Tucker yanked 3-2
pitch over the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who had driven in just 10 runs the entire second half of
the season while batting .186 in his last 156 at-bats, finished the
night with five RBIs. His seven RBIs in the postseason nearly
matches what he did the final three months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz had shut down the Padres' order after the first, allowing
two singles to 17 batters, when Wally Joyner came up with two out
and reached on an infield single.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal, who owns a .438 career average against Smoltz,
followed and quickly fell behind 0-2, before Smoltz left a fastball
slightly up over the outer half of the plate. Vander Wal, who hit
five homers in 109 at-bats this year, lined the pitch to the
opposite corner, clearing the wall only a few feet from where
Caminiti's ball had landed in the first. The homer gave San Diego a
4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker drove in the Braves' first two runs to bring them back
from a 2-0 deficit. He tied it in the sixth, after Andruw Jones hit
a two-out single and stole second on the next pitch. Tucker drove
Ashby's next pitch into center to bring Jones around for a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves took what should have been a huge inning in the
fourth and turned it into a one-run disappointment. Javy Lopez,
Andruw Jones and Tucker strung together three straight singles to
cut the lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cox let Smoltz swing away at the first pitch, but then called
for a safety squeeze, a sign that confused Jones, who had to go to
third base coach Bobby Dews for clarification. Ashby pitched out,
and although the ball was low and outside, Smoltz pulled his bat
away, sure that the squeeze play was off.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones had run with the pitch and was halfway down the line
when Hernandez began the rundown. He was retired 2-5-1 on an
embarrassment (and the Braves' second blown squeeze of the series)
that left Cox muttering expletives at the foot of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the miscue, Smoltz, two pitches later, placed a
swinging bunt that rolled dead two inches off the third base line
for Atlanta's fourth hit of the inning, placing men on first and
third. Ozzie Guillen ended the inning with a deep fly to center,
easily deep enough to score a runner from third had there been less
than two out.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz got off to the exact kind of start he wanted to avoid. He
walked No. 2 hitter Steve Finley on four pitches, and two batters
later Caminiti sliced Smoltz's first pitch to the opposite field
and just inside the left-field foul pole for an instant 2-0 lead.
The first inning has remained Smoltz's curse. Of the 58 runs Smoltz
allowed this year, 16 of them _ 28 percent _ came in during the
opponents' first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, who entered the game 3-for-13, hit his second homer of
the series, but the feat was a more personal one. The Padres third
baseman had gone 69 regular-season at-bats, plus three more in this
series, without homering against Smoltz, the longest he had gone
against any pitcher without a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
