<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN14-     10-13 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing like themselves again
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Maybe it came too late. Probably it came too late.
Still, winning Game 4 to force Game 5 beat the alternative. And now
comes John Smoltz, the winningest postseason pitcher ever, and if
Smoltz wins the NLCS returns to Atlanta, and if that happens . . .
</P>
<P>
   OK, we're getting ahead of ourselves. But the encouraging part
of Sunday's game _ other than the obvious bit about staving off a
sweep _ was that the Braves played like the Braves. They pitched.
They hit home runs. They showed the resolve they'd conspicuously
misplaced. They fell behind twice and were trailing as late as the
seventh inning. With oblivion beckoning, the Braves said, ``Thanks
all the same, but we'll head the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   This city was primed for a reckoning. ``Enjoy the sweep,'' said
the nice lady at the Qualcomm Stadium gate. The half-hour before
game time became a head-banging Lollapalooza. ``Sweep, sweep,'' the
throng chanted, and at that moment you could envision how this
would end: The Padres holding another narrow lead, Trevor Hoffman
trotting in from the bullpen, ``Hell's Bells'' blaring over the PA,
all heck breaking loose when the home team clinched its unlikely
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Hoffman didn't get to pitch. Ahead after six, the Padres
lost 8-3. Starter Joey Hamilton, asked to go two batters too far,
yielded a tying home run to Javy Lopez on the first pitch of the
seventh. Then Andruw Jones nubbed a ball toward second baseman
Quilvio Veras, who couldn't glove it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy summoned Randy Myers, the same Bruce Bochy who had
managed such a sterling Game 3 that he was named the Fox network's
star of stars. With two out, Myers faced Ozzie Guillen, lefty
against lefty. Guillen guided a single into left field, scoring
Jones and putting the Braves ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Then Keith Lockhart beat out another infield hit, a sure sign
that, at least for one night, things were breaking the Braves' way.
``They'd had a bunch of hits that just went through,'' Ryan Klesko
said. ``You just wonder, 'When's that going to happen for us?'''
</P>
<P>
   Myers loaded the bases and departed, replaced by Dan Miceli.
Andres Galarraga, 1-for-12 in the NLCS, drove Miceli's second pitch
over the wall in left-center field. Grand slam. The Braves had
scored more runs in the seventh than in the previous 34 innings
combined. Said Klesko: ``Sometimes that's all it takes for us _ one
big inning to turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Game 4 departure: The Braves managed to survive their
nemesis Jim Leyritz, who'd put the Padres ahead with a sixth-inning
homer off Denny Neagle. That looked for all the world like a death
blow, looked that way for maybe 10 minutes. Then Lopez applied the
kiss of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's a two-game series now,'' Bobby Cox had said
earlier Sunday. ``We need to win two here, then get back home and
see what happens.'' Afterward he amended his remarks: ``It's a
one-game series starting tomorrow, and then a two-gamer at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. You'd still rather be the Padres than the Braves. No team
has ever overcome a 3-0 deficit. Then again, no big-leaguer had hit
70 homers until this season of broken precedents. Could another be
about to fall? Said Klesko: ``It's always possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
