u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-TUCKER-COLUMN14-C     10-13 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-TUCKER-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The unfolding of a strange game
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ And this is how the NLCS, improbably, found its way
back to Atlanta. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Bottom of the first inning. Last thing John Smoltz wants to do
is walk the batter in front of Tony Gwynn. But he walks Steve
Finley. Then, after Gwynn flies out, Smoltz gives up a two-run,
two-out homer to a guy who had never homered against him, Ken
Caminiti. Padres, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top of the fourth. Remembering Smoltz's words of the night
before: ``The key (to coming back in the series) is that we have to
execute.'' The Braves have runners at first and third, one out, one
run in, Andruw Jones breaking from third, Smoltz squaring to bunt.
The Padres pitch out, and Jones is caught in a rundown. The inning
ends with the Braves getting one run out of four singles. This is
not the type of execution Smoltz had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top of the fifth. For the second time in the game, Chipper
Jones hits a ball hard. And for the second time, a San Diego
infielder makes a fine defensive play on him. Shortstop Chris Gomez
did it in the first inning, Wally Joyner now. The Braves were the
league's best defensive team in the regular season. In this series,
they have been the second-best defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top of the sixth. Andruw Jones is on second base with two out,
Michael Tucker batting, Smoltz on deck. An identical scenario
occurred in Game 1 of the Division Series. Both times, the opponent
inexplicably chose to pitch to Tucker rather than walk him to face
Smoltz. Against the Cubs, Tucker homered. This time, he singled to
tie the game at 2. Has Padres manager Bruce Bochy, Fox's ``player
of the game'' on Saturday, gone into a slump?
</P>
<P>
   _ Bottom of the sixth. Chipper Jones charges and barehands the
slow-footed Joyner's two-out ground ball, but drops it while
rushing a throw. To reiterate: The Padres are making the tough
plays in this series; the Braves are not. The next batter, John
Vander Wal, drills a two-run homer to left field. Padres, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top of the seventh. After a leadoff single, the Padres make a
surprising call to the bullpen. Kevin Brown, their scheduled Game 6
starter, makes the third relief appearance of his career. If it
works, Bochy's brilliance is certified; if it doesn't, the Braves
might not only win Game 5 but improve their chances for Game 6. The
crowd, for its part, loves the move. Brown retires three straight
Braves to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top of the eighth. Brown, a Cy Young candidate, proves far
less efficient as a middle reliever than as starter. He walks Ryan
Klesko and allows an infield single to Javy Lopez and then, with
one out, Tucker crushes a three-run homer to right. Three batters
later, Tony Graffanino's double off reliever Donne Wall and a San
Diego error lead to two more runs. Braves, 7-4. Few Braves had
tougher seasons than Tucker and Graffanino. And look at them now.
Who knows what happens back in Atlanta Wednesday and Thursday? But
already the Braves are the first team in baseball history to lose
the first three games of a best-of-seven postseason series and win
the next two.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tucker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
