</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES COME FROM BEHIND TO BEAT PADRES, 7-6
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It may not have been Game 7 of the World Series. But
the San Diego Padres and Atlanta Braves sure played Game 5 of the
National League Championship Series on Monday night as if it were
deciding their respective seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it came down to Tony Gwynn against Greg Maddux, with
the tying run on first in the bottom of the ninth. Maddux, who was
making his first relief appearance in 11 years, won the battle of
future Hall of Famers, retiring Gwynn on a hard-hit grounder to
first.
</P>
<P>
   And the Braves, who had rallied from a two-run deficit in the
eighth to score five runs, including an improbable three-run home
run by Michael Tucker off of Kevin Brown, to take a 7-4 lead, had
survived with a 7-6 victory, one that enables them now to head home
to Atlanta for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Both managers took huge gambles with their pitching aces. San
Diego's Bruce Bochy sent Brown out to protect a two-run lead in the
seventh, but after Brown surrendered the homer to Tucker, the
Padres looked as if they were going to fall five outs shy.
</P>
<P>
   But then Greg Myers delivered a two-run pinch-hit home run off
Kerry Ligtenberg in the top of the ninth to trim a three-run
deficit to one. And now it was Bobby Cox's turn to make a move.
</P>
<P>
   Out came Maddux, who nailed down the first save of his
professional career, leaving the 58,988 previously frenetic fans at
Qualcomm Stadium in utter disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's scheduled Game 6 starter pitching in the seventh
inning? Atlanta's scheduled Game 7 starter pitching in the ninth?
What a series this has been.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the first three games of the National League
Championship Series, the Braves, who now head home down 3-2, are
not only alive, they actually believe they can win. And why not?
Atlanta not only finally found a way to beat Brown (who was making
a surprising relief appearance for just the second time in his
career) for the first time in over two years, the Braves overcame a
pair of two-run home runs against starter John Smoltz in a game
Smoltz had all but guaranteed he would win.
</P>
<P>
   The only way Atlanta can secure its place in history, General
Manager John Schuerholz acknowledged before a Game 5 that was
managed as if it were the seventh game, is by winning another World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in Brown was a huge gamble on Bochy's part. Before the
game, Padres Pitching Coach Dave Stewart said that the Padres had
started Andy Ashby on Monday evening instead of Brown on three
days' rest because they did not want to make a panic-move.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown _ who had pitched a perfect inning of relief on July 4
_ had won his last six decisions against Atlanta, dating back to
1996. And, after Ashby delivered six solid innings, Bochy decided
to go for the kill. It is a move he may always regret.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who had shut the Braves out in Game 2 after defeating
them twice for Florida in last year's NLCS, had come on in the top
of the seventh with a runner on and promptly retired the side to
protect the 4-2 lead John Vander Wal had given San Diego with an
unlikely sixth-inning home run off Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan Klesko fouled off two full-count pitches to work a
lead-off walk in the eighth. Javy Lopez followed with a first-pitch
infield single to short. And, after Andruw Jones popped out to
first, Tucker stepped to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta right-fielder had already driven in the Braves'
first two runs with run-scoring singles in both the fourth and
sixth. This time, Brown fell behind 3-0 before getting the count to
full. With the crowd noise reaching an almost deafening pitch _ and
on what would become Brown's final pitch of the evening, and maybe
the series, as well _ with one fateful swing, Tucker took the life
out of both the Padres and their crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As the ball cleared the fence in right to give the Braves a 5-4
lead, Tony Gwynn doubled over at the fence as Brown did the same to
the left of home plate. The crowd gasped in unison, as Tucker had
driven in Atlanta's first 5 runs. And after the Braves rallied for
two more in the inning off Donne Wall, the Braves not only had a
3-run lead, they were about to go home.
</P>
<P>
   By winning Game 4 on Sunday, the heavily favored Braves had not
only avoided what would have been a humiliating sweep, but they had
also enabled the winningest pitcher in post-season history to make
one more start.
</P>
<P>
   And Smoltz was confident coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it like I'm not going to be the guy to let the
season end,'' Smoltz said late Sunday. ``It won't be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz could make so bold a prediction because he had been here
before. In the 1992 World Series and the 1996 league championship
series, Smoltz pitched on the road with the Braves trailing, 3-1,
and enabled Atlanta to take the series back home. In all, Smoltz
had pitched three times with the Braves facing elimination, and the
Braves had won each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we found a way to win Game 1, we found a way to win Game 2
and we found a way to win Game 3,'' Tony Gwynn said before the
game, the inference being that the Padres had already found their
way past the triumvirate of Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux
that makes up Atlanta's pitching core. ``Hopefully, we'll find a
way to win one more.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while there was no precedent in major league history of a
team coming back from a 3-0 deficit to win a post-season series, in
1996 against the Cardinals, the Braves rallied from a 3-1 deficit
behind the same three pitchers who were scheduled to pitch Games 5,
6 and 7 of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Braves seemed to exude a quiet confidence
before Monday night's game, even though they realized that they
still had their work cut out for them. Of the 22 teams who have
been down by 3-0 in a series, the Braves became only the fourth
team to win Game4. And no team had won again to force a Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to happen sometime,'' Atlanta President Stan Kasten
said today. ``But, for somebody to do it, it would require this
type of rotation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
