</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOMEONE SAY PANIC? JUST PASS THE BUTTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ There had been a strange sense in the air. The San
Diego Padres, the team that had gone up by three games to none and
then by three games to one in the National League Championship
Series, might have some cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because the heavily favored Atlanta Braves were the team
that had just won its first game in the series, on Sunday _ coming
from behind twice _ and now had the Cy Young triumvirate coming up
in Games 5 and, if it came to pass, 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   So Messrs. Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux were ready. And the
Padres? Well, Andy Ashby was the Padre pitcher next in the
rotation, and was slated to start on Monday night. Why, the Padre
pitching coach Dave Stewart was asked Sunday night, would Kevin
Brown, the relatively rested ace of the staff, not pitch in Ashby's
stead?
</P>
<P>
   ``To use Brown,'' replied Stewart, ``would be an act of panic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of Monday's game, guess who came in to
relieve for the Padres?
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown! Was this some kind of act of panic on the part of
Padre manager Bruce Bochy?
</P>
<P>
   Or was this so brilliant a move that it would dazzle the beastly
Braves, end this series and catapult the Padres into the World
Series?
</P>
<P>
   Brown had been virtually invincible in Game 2, throwing a
three-hit shutout in Atlanta, and striking out 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres on Monday night had taken the lead by 2-0, and then
the Braves had tied the game in the sixth. Just as they had done
the day before. And then in the seventh, Ozzie Guillen led off the
inning for the Braves with a single off Mark Langston, who had
replaced Ashby on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   A huge roar rose from the crowd of 58,988 in Qualcomm Stadium.
Here came the lengthy fast-balling, madly intense Brown, striding
in from the left-field bullpen. The crowd stood and cheered his
every pitch to pinch-hitter Greg Colbrunn, and he struck him out,
Colbrunn unaccountably breaking his black bat in half on his final
swing. Brown got the next two batters to fly out and pop up.
</P>
<P>
   This was Casey at the Mound _ and reversing the old ode and
saving Mudville.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were battling not only Brown and the Padres, but
their self-respect. They have been to seven straight league
championship series, and they have won one World Series. They are
either the greatest team of the 1990s or the greatest also-rans.
``If we don't advance,'' the Braves' general manager, John
Schuerholz said, ``it would be like an unfinished symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4, the fans chanted ``Sweep! Sweep!'' When that didn't
work, they switched in Game 5 to the conventional ``Charge!
Charge!''
</P>
<P>
   But hold on. It's the eighth inning and Brown walks the lead-off
hitter, Ryan Klesko. He gives up a single to Javy Lopez, but forces
Andruw Jones to pop to first. Up comes Michael Tucker, who had
driven in the Braves' two other runs. Brown delivers and Tucker
parks one over the right-field wall. The Braves, improbably, take
the lead, 5-4. At the mound, Brown bent over, his hands on his
knees, as though he had just been hit with a karate chop.
</P>
<P>
   No chants of ``Sweep!'' from the fans. No ``Charge!'' No
nothing. The ball park was as silent as the moon. And they stayed
that way as Brown was removed for another reliever, Donne Wall.
Poor Casey. He had, sadly, missed the boat again. The Braves scored
twice more in the inning to take a 7-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Padres scored two in the ninth, Bobby Cox took a
page from Bochy's book and brought in Maddux, who, unlike Brown,
preserved a victory in dramatic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Until Game 4, the Braves had scored just three runs in three
games. Their lumber, as their manager, Bobby Cox, had said in so
many words, was a-slumber. Then they awoke in Game 5, winning 8-3.
The Padres, however, could surely have avoided any thought of panic
with the cushion of knowing that no team in baseball history had
come back from a 3-0 deficit to win a four-of-seven series. Oh,
there had been two teams in hockey who had accomplished the feat,
but that's a horse of a different odor.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Braves did come back from being down 3-1
against St. Louis in the 1996 NLCS. And, come to think of it,
that's precisely where the two teams stood as they listened to the
singing of the national anthem before Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that but the Braves won the next three games against
the Cardinals by pitching their three Cy Young Award winners,
Smoltz in the fifth game, Maddux in the sixth and Glavine in the
seventh. All that was changed this time around was that Glavine and
Maddux would be transposed in the rotation. Not much of a change if
you happened to find yourself in the batter's box wearing a Padres
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any panic,'' said Ashby, before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   None, of course. None at all. None, perhaps, for Game 6, on
Wednesday in Atlanta, either.
</P>
<P>
   Or Game 7, when Brown would presumably next be available.
</P>
<P>
   Oh brother, this is getting as good as McGwire and Sosa. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
