<HEADLINE>
BLUE-CHIP PREP CHOOSES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC has received an oral commitment from Aaron
Graham, an inside linebacker from Bakersfield High School.
</P>
<P>
   Graham (6-foot-1, 220 pounds) chose the Trojans over Washington,
Arizona, Arizona State, California and Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the environment at USC and I wanted to commit
early,'' Graham said. ``Now I can concentrate on my senior season.
USC slipped into the No.1 spot on my list because it was nearby and
I thought I could get a good education.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham had favored Washington over the summer before switching
to the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   He is listed as a preseason All-American by SuperPrep magazine
and led Bakersfield with 22 tackles for losses last season.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is the fifth player to commit to the Trojans. USC has
also received commitments from Los Alamitos defensive lineman
Bernard Riley; defensive lineman Malcolm Woolridge of Boca Raton,
Fla.; tight end Jacob Rogers of Oxnard and linebacker Markus Steele
of Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   Bitten by the Bear: Cal stunned the Trojans in the second half
of its 32-31 victory with the use of the Bear defense, which
employs six defensive players rushing the quarterback. It became
famous when Buddy Ryan was the Chicago Bears' defensive coordinator
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Bear defense that allowed Cal to sack freshman
quarterback Carson Palmer in the end zone for a safety in the third
quarter, starting the Bears' 22-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped Cal record six sacks against the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   One reason it was so effective was that Cal used it sparingly
this season and the Trojans had not practiced intensely against it
during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out in the second half and caught us a little off
guard,'' tackle Ken Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Morton questionable: Tailback Chad Morton's status remains in
doubt this week. Morton participated in some light running Sunday,
but his bruised back continues to bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Nice debut: Defensive end Ryan Nielsen's switch to tackle was
considered a success. Nielsen made two tackles and had one of the
best performances on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal High graduate will probably play the position the rest
of the season because Marc Matock is not expected to return from
his broken ankle until late November at the earliest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
