<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN MAKES THE RIGHT MOVES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The headline in Monday's Daily Bruin proclaimed:
``Bruins Win Despite McNone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, quarterback Cade McNown hit just 10 of 24 passes at
Arizona. And yes, he has a 49.3 completion percentage in the last
three games. He has overthrown receivers. He has thrown into
coverage. He's even struggling with mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to make more routine plays,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's hardly ``McNone.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is 4-0, ranked No. 2, averaging 48 points per game, and
McNown is performing his most important duties with typical
proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   _He's making big plays. With the Bruins trailing Arizona 28-24
late in the third quarter, McNown dragged three Wildcats into the
end zone on a short touchdown run. A few minutes later, he threw a
perfect pass to Danny Farmer for a 64-yard touchdown that gave UCLA
control.
</P>
<P>
   _He's not making mistakes. In one of the Pac-10's most hostile
environments, with Arizona blitzers charging from all angles and
the crowd noise making it difficult to hear audibles, McNown did
not fumble or throw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Arizona quarterbacks Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins
threw two interceptions, which the Bruins converted into 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   _He's leading.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got up on us (in the first half) and had a little
momentum and some of the guys started to get scared,'' offensive
tackle Kris Farris said. ``Cade came over and said, `It's just like
the Cotton Bowl (when UCLA trailed 16-0). We'll be fine. We're
gonna win.'''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Defensive end Kenyon Coleman will play Saturday
for the first time since spraining his right knee Sept. 19 against
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Short stuff: Keith Brown was named UCLA's offensive player of
the week (91 yards, two touchdowns) and will start at tailback
against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman DeShaun Foster is No. 2 on the depth chart. Jermaine
Lewis is third.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ryan Nece was named defensive player of the week.
Kicker Chris Sailer received the special teams honor.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's ``College GameDay'' will broadcast live outside the Rose
Bowl on Saturday at 8 a.m. It's the show's first-ever West Coast
appearance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-BLUES-NYT     10-13 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-BLUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES DEFEAT RANGERS, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was not as if New York fans had nothing to cheer
and chant about on Monday night at Madison Square Garden. They made
a joyous noise late in the first period when the scoreboard screen
showed the image of David Wells, the New York Yankee pitcher,
sitting in the hockey crowd on an off night during the American
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go Yankees!'' the fans chanted repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, they could have said to each other, ``Let's go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing performance, the Rangers lost to the St.
Louis Blues, 4-2. The competition was not that close, and there
were plenty of empty seats at the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat left the Rangers with a 0-3 record and grouped with
the New Jersey Devils and the New York Islanders at the bottom of
the Atlantic Division. In three games, the Rangers have scored only
3 goals and 59 shots on goal. Against Philadelphia, Montreal and
St. Louis, they have been outscored by 12-3. And they have lost
most of their face-offs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that was one of the reasons Wayne Gretzky told Esa
Tikkanen to wait before stepping up to take a draw with St. Louis
ahead by three goals.
</P>
<P>
   Better to let the fans continue their ovation for Wells, Gretzky
figured, and Tikkanen obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Wells stopped by the Ranger dressing room.
``Touch me,'' Gretzky said to the hefty pitcher. ``Maybe the good
luck will rub off.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells extended his hands and they exchanged light slaps.
</P>
<P>
   Hands were just part of the problem for the Rangers' starting
goalie, Mike Richter, who gave up five third-period goals in a 7-1
loss at Montreal on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Richter took a seat after giving up three goals
in the first period to St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis. One of the
shots came from the neutral zone near the Rangers blue line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to stop the puck more,'' Richter said. ``I don't
mean to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Cloutier replaced Richter and played well in the last two
periods. But the early goaltending was only the beginning of the
Rangers' difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to implement Coach John Muckler's style of puck pressure,
the Rangers seemed flat-footed, as the Blues whipped around them.
One of the most telling moments came early in the evening when the
Rangers were trying to skate the puck out of their zone. They made
eight passes behind their blue line before icing the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot to think about,'' Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
   He has shaken up his forward lines, replacing Tikkanen on
Gretzky's left wing with Niklas Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Tikkanen, a veteran who came to training camp as a free agent,
won the left wing job alongside Gretzky. But he seems a step slower
now that the regular season has begun. With Sundstrom back
alongside Gretzky, as he was last season, the line helped set up
goals by Ranger defensemen Brian Leetch and Aleksandr Karpovtsev in
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't Tikky's fault,'' said Gretzky, absolving his
teammate of blame for that line's failure in the first eight
periods of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, and it might be that the good third period and
respectable final score created an illusion. The goals were scored
against a team that relaxed after thoroughly outplaying the Rangers
in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are idle until Friday night, when the Devils visit.
Muckler said he was not sure who would be his starting goaltender
for that night, and he may make more changes at forward.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to have Todd Harvey back from a hip injury to add some
muscle at right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Tikkanen seemed better at center, where the Rangers have no
regulars besides Gretzky and the rookie Manny Malhotra.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean, signed as a free-agent right wing, found himself
at left wing last night and had no shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Kevin Stevens, earning more than $3 million, was a
healthy scratch and was not happy about it. ``I can't help from
where I'm at,'' he said, referring to the stands.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how Muckler mixes and matches, the Rangers have
been exposed as a seriously flawed team lacking youth, speed and
depth. The natural impulse for fans will be to demand that Neil
Smith, the president and general manager, make trades for younger
skaters and scorers. But age and high salaries on the Rangers'
roster make it hard for a general manager to overhaul the team.
</P>
<P>
   One who won't go is Gretzky, trying to salvage something from
his 20th season and playing almost half the game. Between the
second and third periods, as his teammates skated off, Gretzky bent
over near the bench as if hanging his head.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he should have stopped in the television studio, where
Wells was telling the interviewer that the Yankees, too, lost their
first three games of the season. Look where they are now. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
