<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JAGUARS-     10-13 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-JAGUARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Unless the University of Florida and
Florida State are playing in Gainesville or Tallahassee, football
in the Sunshine State does not usually cause fans across the state
to get so worked up that they froth at the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, the Jacksonville Jaguars and Miami
Dolphins met in the regular season, and a ticket to the
Monday-night game at Alltel Stadium was so hard to get, you would
have thought the Gators and Seminoles were teeing it up.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Jacksonville vs. Miami, and a stadium-record crowd
of 74,051 watched quarterback Mark Brunell throw two fourth-quarter
touchdown passes to receiver Keenan McCardell to give the Jaguars a
28-21 victory over the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell and McCardell, the Houston native who resides in
Greatwood in the offseason, connected for the second time with 2:36
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After Olindo Mare missed a 54-yard field-goal attempt for Miami,
Jacksonville took possession at its 44. On the first play,
McCardell got behind cornerback Terrell Buckley and hauled in a
perfect pass from Brunell for a 56-yard touchdown that gave
Jacksonville the win and allowed the Jaguars to improve their
record to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great call,'' McCardell said. ``It was a post-corner
route. At a time like that, someone has to step up and make a play.
I'm paid to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the other half of this duo (receiver Jimmy Smith) goes
out with an injury (a pulled hamstring), it's time for me to earn
my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell completed 12 of 18 passes for 213 yards and the two
touchdowns. McCardell, who dropped a long pass in the first half,
had only three catches, but he made them count for 86 yards and
both touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie running back Fred Taylor scored the first two
Jacksonville touchdowns. The Jaguars allowed the Dolphins to score
three consecutive touchdowns before rallying in the fourth quarter
behind Brunell and McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell's perfect pass and McCardell's clutch catch ruined Miami
quarterback Dan Marino's best performance of the season. After
failing to pass for 200 yards in each of the first four games,
Marino was 30-of-49 for 323 yards and two touchdowns. But it wasn't
enough to keep Miami from falling to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put ourselves in a hole right off the bat,'' Miami coach
Jimmy Johnson said. ``Our guys hung in and put us in position to
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an exciting finish to a game that began in electrifying
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the way the Jaguars started the game, they should
have blown out the Dolphins, but Jacksonville did just enough to
let Miami stay close.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play, Taylor broke through the right side and
outran every Miami defender for a 77-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first quarter, the Jaguars began a six-play,
53-yard drive that Taylor finished with a two-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 14, Miami's offense finally put together a decent
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Marino completed five passes for 63 yards. On third-and-goal
from the two, he used a play-action fake and found tight end Troy
Drayton alone in the end zone. Drayton had to dive to catch the
ball for the touchdown. Replays showed the ball slipped through
Drayton's arms and touched the ground, but the officials didn't see
it.
</P>
<P>
   Miami didn't take long to tie the score. On their opening series
of the second half, the Dolphins needed 10 plays to cover 55 yards.
Because of penalties, they faced third-and-goal from the 23 but got
a tremendous break when safety Travis Davis was called for
interference, giving Miami a first down at the one.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' penalty rubbed out an end-zone interception by
Jacksonville's Donovin Darius. Two plays later, Karim Abdul-Jabbar
scored from the one to make it 14-14 with 10:29 left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Miami scored again on its next possession, going 63 yards in
nine plays. The 15-yard touchdown came when Marino found Drayton
alone on the left side for an easy score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
