u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAGUARS-DOLPHINS-     10-13 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS BEAT DOLPHINS, 28-21 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Miami and Jacksonville had never played a
regular-season game before Monday night, so who knew what to expect
in their Floridian fling?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of spurts, almost like a basketball game, was the way it
unfolded. And Jacksonville produced the final fast break, the one
that broke things open and gave it 28-21 victory before 74,051 fans
at Alltell Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville is 5-0 and in the American Football Conference
Central, Pittsburgh (4-2) trails the Jaguars in a race that could
be a Jaguars runaway. Miami (3-2) dropped its second straight.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brunell passes to Kennan McCardell produced two
fourth-quarter touchdowns that gave Jacksonvile the lead. And then
in the final minutes, with Miami and Dan Marino driving to showcase
the game's final spurt, Jaguars end Tony Brackens stole the ball.
There was 1 minute 51 seconds left and Miami was in Jacksonville
territory and Marino set up in the pocket near midfield. Brackens
raced around right end, slapped the ball out of Marino's hands as
Marino looked downfield and then Brackens recovered it, too, at the
Miami 48.
</P>
<P>
   Drive over. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was 29 of 47 for 320 yards with two touchdowns and one
interception. Brunell was 12 of 18 for 213 yards with two
touchdowns and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the toughest defenses we've faced and we had
to change things around a little bit,'' Brunell said. ``It worked.
There was a lot of talk going on out there. A lot of
extracurricular activities.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game of spurts. Jacksonville scored the game's first 14
points. Miami scored 21 consecutive points. And then Jacksonville
scored another 14.
</P>
<P>
   The final 14 came in the fourth, when Brunell twice hit with the
speedy and crafty Keenen McCardell. He is a receiver full of
juke-and-jive moves and he used both to score on grabs of 23 and 56
yards. The 56-yarder proved the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Jacksonville thought it was on its way to keeping the
Dolphins in check _ the Jaguars built a 14-0 lead and looked as if
they could do what they pleased _ the Miami defense answered by
putting more pressure on Brunell. The Miami offense answered with a
mixture of gritty runs and zinging Dan Marino passes where his
receiver kept leaping high and diving low to make big catches.
</P>
<P>
   Miami trimmed the Jacksonville lead to 14-7 just before
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   And then five minutes into the second half, Miami caught the
Jaguars at 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   And before the third quarter was over, Miami had the lead,
21-14.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Jacksonville and Miami spurts were consistent. It can
happen like that when quarterbacks get hot and when defenses get
hotter.
</P>
<P>
   This game began with a bang. Fred Taylor, the rookie back from
the University of Florida, took the first play from scrimmage 77
yards for a touchdown. It was a quick-trap-like cutback runner, a
quick-hitter up the middle where Taylor took the ball backside and
burst past the overeager Dolphins. Miami had a chance to track him
down and take him down near the Miami 10, but Taylor wanted to get
into the end zone. And he did. He simply fought throught the
Dolphins arms trying to pull him down from behind and carried
onward.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter Jacksonville outgained Miami 191 yards to
49 even though both teams ran 14 plays. Taylor's 2-yard run early
in the second quarter that made it 14-0 concluded a 53-yard,
six-play drive.
</P>
<P>
   Miami scored on the possession that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and Marino blew a chance for more points with 6:07 left
before halftime when Terrell Buckley intercepted Brunell at the
Jacksonville 36. Two plays later Marino was intercepted at the
Jacksonville 10 by cornerback Aaron Beasely.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Miami would respond after halftime with a third
quarter of domination. It led in possession time 10:11 to 4:49 in
the quarter. It led in first downs by 9 to 2 in the quarter. But
most important, it led in points in the quarter, 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   To start the quarter Miami produced a 55-yard drive that took
nine plays and finished with a Karim Abul-Jabbar 1-yard scoring
run. It was 14-14. And then Marino threw a beautiful strike in the
left corner of the end zone to Drayton for 15 yards for another
Miami touchdown. A little more than 11 minutes had elapsed in the
third quarter and Miami led 21-14 on touchdowns scored on its first
two possessions.
</P>
<P>
   It would not stand, though.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville had another spurt left. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
