</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANUCKS, CALLS FINISH OFF KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ The Kings thought they had tied the score. But they
never should have been trailing to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes remained in Monday afternoon's 4-2 loss
to the Vancouver Canucks. At the time, the Kings were down a goal,
pressing on a power play and trying for the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Moger's shot from point-blank range was stopped by Canucks
goalie Garth Snow, and the rebound came to Rob Blake in the slot.
Moger was pushed into the crease by Canucks defenseman Murray
Baron, and Blake fired the puck into the net.
</P>
<P>
   The red light came on, but almost immediately referee Stephen
Walkom, upon the advice of a linesman, was waving his arms, ruling
Moger had been in the crease. Walkom disallowed the apparent goal
and could not be dissuaded by the heated argument waged by Blake
and Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Alexander Mogilny scored into an empty net,
and the Canucks had opened their season by turning a one-goal
deficit after 40 minutes into a victory before a less-than-sellout
crowd of 16,071 at GM Place.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, whose home opener is Friday night against the Boston
Bruins, fell to 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll lose a game,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said of
Walkom's call. ``I don't mind losing a game. But I don't like when
games get taken away from me, and that's what happened right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The disallowed goal was actually the second of the game for the
Kings, and the second of the game involving Moger. In the final
minute of the second period, with the Kings leading 2-1, video-goal
judge Malcolm Ashford _ invoking powers granted those officials
this season _ called down to Walkom to disallow an apparent goal by
Philippe Boucher because Moger was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one, (Moger) definitely had his skates on (the
crease),'' Robinson said. ``But the second one was a bad call. He
was definitely pushed in. It makes for a heck of a long year when
you've got to battle both sides all the time. Just make it fair for
both. That's all I ask. And that's why I'm so in favor of having
the two-referee system. Then, you've got four eyes out there.
(Walkom) had a bad night tonight. I guess we all have bad nights.
That was definitely a bad night for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two calls, Moger said: ``The first call, I was in. On the
second call, there's no doubt I was pushed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the latter call, with 2:31 left in the game, Baron
said: ``I pushed him. Whether he made an effort to get out of the
crease, I don't know. I haven't seen the replay. They called it off
right away. Whoever made the call was sure. Whether the Kings had a
beef or not, I can't say.''
</P>
<P>
   Against a team that was the worst in the NHL's Western
Conference a year ago, a team that won only twice last year when
trailing after two periods, a team playing without disgruntled star
winger Pavel Bure, and a team with a defense that provided them
with lots of operating room, the Kings shouldn't have been trailing
late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But they took too many penalties _ the Kings were shorthanded
eight times in the game, for 14:15 of the game's 60 minutes _ and
were unable to capitalize on most of their opportunities. Both of
the Kings goals came off the stick of center Yanic Perreault, who
has scored three of their four goals this season.
</P>
<P>
   Perreault, a streaky player who finished second on the Kings a
year ago with 28 goals, gave the Kings an early 1-0 lead when he
fired home a loose puck after a deflected shot from the point by
Doug Bodger landed on his stick.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the game turned into a duel between Snow and Kings
goalie Jamie Storr, making his season debut. Peter Zezel finally
tied the score for Vancouver late in the second period on the
deflection of a shot by Todd Bertuzzi, but Perreault put the Kings
back in front on a shorthanded breakaway less than three minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver's Dave Scatchard tied the score 1:44 into the third
period _ Robinson said he thought the Canucks might have been
offside on the play _ and Zezel's power-play goal at 10:48 proved
the game-winner. Zezel scored on a well-placed blast from the right
faceoff circle that glanced off Storr's left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Zezel's shot had been a perfect one, Storr
said: ``It's still not acceptable on my part. I don't think
anything is perfect. It's something I've got to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson was less concerned with that than the victory he
felt had been taken from the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad,'' Robinson said. ``You work hard, and it's hard
to get points, and especially early on in the season you want to
get points. To have them taken away like that, that's very, very
disappointing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
