<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-TRAGEDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY PARTY ENDS IN TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Five-year-old Salvador Sanchez couldn't wait for
his father's birthday. That morning, he jumped up and down on his
bed, ecstatic that he and his eight brothers and sisters would be
reunited for the party.
</P>
<P>
   He took out his shiniest boots and crafted a birthday card in
Spanish: ``To my papa. I love you much. Happy birthday! From:
Salvador.''
</P>
<P>
   Salvador never got a chance to eat birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to a family beset by hardship and tragedy, a
hit-and-run driver struck and killed the youngster Sunday as he and
his 11-year-old brother tried to cross an unmarked crosswalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was asking me to put on his favorite boots to look nice,''
Sanchez's mother, Leticia Lozoya, said Monday in between crying and
burying her face in her hands. ``His boots are still waiting there
for him because he never put them on.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives are searching for the alleged driver, identified as
Reynaldo Chavez Manso, 21, who is accused of fleeing in a red
four-door 1983 Toyota Camry. He is described as a Latino, between 5
feet 7 inches and 5 feet 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The unmarked crosswalk in the Pacoima neighborhood north of
downtown Los Angeles has been a source of many near misses
involving children, according to residents and business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids go across all the time. I don't know why there's no
lighted crosswalk or stop sign,'' said David Salazar-Rodriguez, a
business owner. ``Sometimes, you think it's clear and, Boom! They
just come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident happened as the boys were returning home from a gas
station where they had gone to pump up the tires of their bicycle.
They had sneaked out of the house, said Lozoya, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador was hit by a car as the boy and his brother crossed
westbound on Remick Avenue at about 4:10 p.m. Sunday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador and his brother stopped in the center of the road, but
suddenly Salvador bolted into the path of the Toyota, said Officer
Connie Silber of the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Battazar Perez, a worker at the gas station, heard the impact.
``The other brother ran around like crazy trying to help his
brother,'' said Perez, whose eyes filled with tears while
recounting the incident. ``My stomach is turning. I love kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A witness chased the driver for three miles, hollering for him
to return to the scene, said Detective Humberto Fajardo of the
Valley Traffic Division. The witness did get the license plate
number: 2EQG614.
</P>
<P>
   It was a horrific end to a joyous day for the Sanchez family, a
family that already has suffered tragedy with one child and was
split up by Los Angeles County child welfare authorities.
</P>
<P>
   One of Salvador's brothers, Heriberto, 4, has been comatose for
a couple of years since he choked on food at home, said Marina
Sanchez, Salvador's aunt.
</P>
<P>
   That incident led the Department of Children Services to take
custody of the nine kids, Sanchez said. Four children and Salvador
went to a Panorama City foster home, and four others live with
their grandmother in Pacoima.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday was supposed to be special for Salvador because of
his father's 40th birthday and his family would be gathering at his
parents' home for the party, Sanchez said. He had been counting the
days until a judge would decide whether some of his older siblings
could be returned to his parents, his aunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Salvador's parents had saved enough to move from a single-room
home to a one-bedroom house in Pacoima, making them eligible to
take back their three oldest children, she said. And the
grandmother was trying to adopt the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been working as much as they could. She cleans homes
and he works in construction,'' Sanchez said. ``Now this happened,
so we don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
