</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS ENTER BYE WEEK SEEKING ANSWERS TO INCONSISTENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ The Seahawks enter their bye week convinced
they remain a playoff contender, but also knowing that changes must
be made if they are to advance to the postseason for the first time
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 21-16 loss to the Denver Broncos continued a three-game
flurry of mistakes and errors that also cost the Seahawks in road
losses at Kansas City and Pittsburgh the previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now 3-3, the Seahawks probably need to win seven of their
remaining 10 games to stay in the playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's too much to overcome,'' defensive end
Michael Sinclair said. ``If anything, it's frustrating. We've been
in these games and we've had a chance to win them. But we're not
getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this bye, we're going to have to evaluate a lot of
things _ a lot of things,'' he said. ``If we're going to call
ourselves a playoff team, we'd better start playing like one.''
</P>
<P>
   That evaluation process already has begun. Three big problems
must be addressed in this week's practices:
</P>
<P>
   (Insert bullet) Establish some offensive consistency. The
Seahawks rank 22nd in the league, a perplexing plunge from last
year when they were No. 3 overall and had the NFL's top-rated
passing game. The defense has scored a third of the team's 15 TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been sitting in here all morning trying to figure out
what's wrong,'' coach Dennis Erickson said Monday. ``We're just not
playing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the offense can't get the job done. There have
been enough flashes to indicate the pieces are in place. But there
also have been too many penalties (16 against eight different
players in the past two games) and not enough big plays (only one
longer than 50 yards in six games).
</P>
<P>
   Erickson plans to simplify the running game and balance the
attack with more passing _ the strength of last year's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got too many things that we're doing, so we're a little
tentative getting off the football,'' Erickson said. ``We've got to
condense it.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Seahawks to go with only five or six different
blocking patterns in the running game, and also to go right at the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Also look for more one-back formations featuring Ricky Watters,
and for rookie Ahman Green to become more involved in the offense.
Of course that's not saying much since Green has not carried the
ball in the past three games. But Erickson says Green will be used
to spell Watters, even if it's only four or five carries a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to try and improve ourselves offensively,'' Erickson
said. ``If we don't, we're in for some tough games.''
</P>
<P>
   (Insert bullet) Stop the run. The defense has played so well
it's difficult to find fault. But the Seahawks must improve their
efforts against the run. They rank 12th overall, but only 26th in
rushing defense, allowing an average of 147.8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis dashed and bashed his way to 208 yards Sunday.
Even without his 70-yard run late in the fourth quarter, he
averaged 4.8 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, Davis, Pittsburgh's Jerome Bettis (138
yards) and Kansas City as a team (131 yards) have rung up their
highest rushing totals of the season against the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Still on the menu are San Diego's Marion Butts (twice),
Oakland's Napoleon Kaufman (twice), Dallas' Emmitt Smith,
Indianapolis' Marshall Faulk and a rematch with Davis _ all among
the top 11 rushers in the league.
</P>
<P>
   (Insert bullet) Get more big plays from the special teams. The
most obvious problem Sunday was penalties _ six of them for
holding. But special teams coach Pete Rodriguez says they can be
corrected by working on better technique, and you can believe he
will have everyone working on better technique this week.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger concern is the lack of big returns and giving up too
many big returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we can still get the job done in the next 10 games.
There's no doubt in my mind, and I doubt there's very much doubt in
the players' minds,'' offensive coordinator Bob Bratkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating. We wanted to win for sure two of these last
three, if not one of these last three, and we didn't do it. But
it's not the end of the season. We're capable of beating everyone
else on our schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' remaining opponents are a combined 25-21. Toss out
the rematches with the Broncos and Chiefs and the record dips to
15-19. The Chargers (twice). The Raiders (twice). The Cowboys. The
Oilers. The Jets. The Colts. All winnable games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's probably writing us off already, that's fine with
me. It doesn't really matter,'' guard Brian Habib said. ``It's
early in the season. We've got a long way to go. We've proved to
ourselves we can play with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a team like Denver really tough. We blew it at the
end, but we definitely had a chance to win that game and I think
that's really something to build on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
