<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLEY CAN ONLY WATCH, WAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ For the second time in as many games in the new
season, Garry Galley watched from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, less than three hours before what would be a Kings' 4-2
loss to the Vancouver Canucks on Monday afternoon, Galley was busy
getting his workout for the day _ in the team's hotel exercise
room.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that a year ago the veteran defenseman signed with
the Kings as a free agent and was one of their major summer
acquisitions, the way this season has begun for the 35-year-old
Galley has to rank as a major disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Galley appears to be keeping the situation in
perspective and is trying to be patient as he waits for a chance to
play. Last year, he appeared in 74 games and was second among Kings
defensemen with nine goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing I've done,'' Galley said of being a healthy
scratch for the season's first two games. ``(Coach) Larry
(Robinson) has told me that. My age works against me. It's not like
I played badly. Larry just said he's got a lot of defensemen who
are all capable of playing. I'm not going to play as much as I'd
like to at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hanging in there. It doesn't mean I like it. You can go
about it two ways. You can let it eat you up, or you can know that
when you get a chance to play, you can play as hard as you always
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Not only did the Kings lose the game, they lost
center Ian Laperriere with a sprained left knee in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   Laperriere was injured in a collision with a Vancouver player.
He is scheduled to be examined today by team physician Dr. Ronald
Kvitne.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Robinson used the same lineup as on opening
night. In the first 120 minutes of the season, defenseman Rob Blake
has received the most playing time (52 minutes, 49 seconds on 58
shifts) and winger Matt Johnson the least (13:31 on 18 shifts).
Left wing Luc Robitaille has taken seven shots in each game (he's
scored one goal), and center Yanic Perreault is shooting 50 percent
with three goals on six shots.... Kings television announcer Bob
Miller celebrated his 60th birthday. ``I felt just as creaky
getting out of bed this morning as I did yesterday morning,''
Miller said when asked if he felt any different.... A Canucks fan
won $100,000 in a puck-shooting contest during the first
intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
