A3098 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      10-13 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING SEASON? UNTHINKABLE FOR WASHINGTON NOT TOO FAR-FETCHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sometime in the dark aftermath of a loss to Arizona,
the thought occurred to Josh Smith, the University of Washington
defensive end: Could this be the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want this to be the year the Huskies slip,'' he
said. ``I wouldn't want people looking back and saying, `Yeah, you
were part of that class that had a losing season.'''
</P>
<P>
   They don't talk a lot about it around the UW, because the
Huskies usually aspire to bigger things. But Washington has a
streak of 21 consecutive winning seasons, one that dates back
through 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The streak is tied with Florida State's for second-longest
current nationally, to Nebraska's 35, and is tied for 10th all-time
in the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost a non-issue to most Husky players, because to them,
a long time ago is 1990-92. That's when Washington was going to
three straight Rose Bowls, winning a national title and rubbing
elbows with college football's gentry, setting a tone that prevents
a goal of a 6-5 season from ever crossing their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasn't once,'' said Joe Jarzynka. ``I don't even consider
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Huskies 3-2; a rejuvenated, 4-1 California team
coming Saturday and Washington facing a nasty stretch of schedule
to finish the year _ at USC, at Oregon, UCLA and at Washington
State _ a losing season at Montlake is not as far-fetched as a
Clinton-Starr dinner date.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to either the Bears or Oregon State the following week
could put the Huskies at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shouldn't happen,'' Jarzynka said, referring to an end to
the streak. ``I refuse to let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is an 10{-point favorite over California and should
also be a strong choice over Oregon State. But as unthinkable as a
losing season would be to the Huskies, they can gain a greater
appreciation for the long-term success of the program by seeing how
other Pac-10 programs have occasionally stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Every other school in the Pac-10 has had a losing season in the
'90s. UCLA has had four in the past decade, Arizona State has had
two. Indeed, the Sun Devils (2-4), seen by some as a preseason
national-championship threat, might be working on another, with
games left to play at Oregon and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like, when teams win so much, and then they lose,
they lose confidence,'' says UW defensive tackle Mac Tuiaea. ``It's
almost like they don't know how to react, because they've never had
to deal with that kind of adversity before.''
</P>
<P>
   But Washington has managed to motor through NCAA scholarship
restrictions, demanding schedules and Pac-10 sanctions to prevent a
truly down year. Thirty of the 44 players on Washington's two-deep
roster this week were born after the Huskies completed their last
losing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you go through sanctions,'' said UW coach Jim
Lambright. ``It's hard enough without sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the streak (1977-78, 1989), the Huskies have been
3-3 after six games. In all three cases, they surged. The first
near-miss was in 1987, when they took a 5-4-1 record into the Apple
Cup here against Washington State, won the game and then survived
Tulane in the Independence Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Huskies were 5-4 when they made their biggest
comeback ever to beat Cal, 28-27. Then they lost to WSU to finish
6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday when the Huskies came down the tunnel, senior
offensive guard Tony Coats had tears streaming down his face. It
wasn't Utah State that aroused him, it was the urgency to restore a
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd wanted to write an article about us taking Utah State
lightly,'' Lambright said, ``Tony Coats would have folded you up
and stuffed you into the middle of Lake Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Huskies had a losing season, 1976, was the
last year they lost to Cal. Omen? The Huskies don't believe in
them, any more than losing seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
