<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLISEUM-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SUITORS PITCHING FUN ZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Developers working to bring a National Football
League team to the Coliseum are proposing a major sports and
entertainment-themed makeover for all of Exposition Park to turn it
into a top family destination.
</P>
<P>
   The concept _ involving interactive attractions, stores,
restaurants and movie theaters _ would complement the existing
complex of museums in Exposition Park, and would be located on the
current Sports Arena site and on 10 acres across Figueroa Street,
said those involved in formulating the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'd like to do is create a center of activity like Third
Street Promenade created for Santa Monica or CityWalk ... or Old
Town Pasadena,'' said Tony Christopher, president and chief
executive officer of North Hollywood-based Landmark Entertainment
Group.
</P>
<P>
   His company is brainstorming a master plan for Exposition Park
on behalf of New Coliseum Partners, headed by developers Ed Roski
Jr. and Philip Anschutz, who are trying to obtain an NFL franchise
for Los Angeles. Roski and Anschutz, who co-own the pro Kings
hockey team, also are developing the new Staples Center, the future
downtown home of the pro basketball Lakers and Clippers, and Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Exposition Park plan _ while only conceptual and secondary
to renovation plans for the interior of the Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum _ should allay concerns among NFL owners that the Coliseum
project has something to overcome as it vies with a proposal by
former superagent and Disney executive Michael Ovitz for a Carson
stadium-retail complex, and with a stadium plan in Houston, said
John Semcken, executive vice president of the Coliseum group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity there that we don't have anywhere else
in the country,'' he said. ``We want to make Exposition Park an
exposition again, make it a major tourist destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Landmark has 18 years of experience in this area, said
Christopher. The company has designed three Universal Studios
attractions, the Star Trek Experience at the Hilton Hotel in Las
Vegas and the Forum Shops at Caesars Palace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Exposition Park includes an NFL-themed attraction
where families might be able to pass, punt and kick together, among
other activities, Semcken and Christopher said. Landmark also is
proposing a Monorail-like people mover to carry visitors around
Exposition Park, Christopher said.
</P>
<P>
   No price tag has been placed on the proposal yet, Semcken said.
</P>
<P>
   The three groups competing for an NFL franchise are scheduled to
present their proposals to the 31 NFL owners Oct. 27 in Kansas
City. A final decision is not expected to be made at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum group also has hired NBBJ Sports &AMP; Entertainment of
Los Angeles to develop a new architectural plan that would take the
vast stadium designed for the 1932 Olympics down to 70,000 seats,
including 10,000 exclusive club seats.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to make it a more intimate NFL-style bowl while
respecting the architectural integrity of the Coliseum as much as
possible, said Dan Meis, NBBJ's principal designer.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum Commission is scheduled to vote Oct. 21 on a formal
agreement with New Coliseum Partners that would give them two years
to try to land an NFL franchise. Mayor Richard Riordan is backing
the group's plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 0129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
