A3106 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN     10-13 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTHRIDGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE MOUNTING FOR NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Last week it was cool to be ranked. It
created a tingly feeling at Cal State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, it's a little different. CSUN jumped to 16th in
both national polls, up seven spots in the Sports Network poll and
eight spots in the USA Today/CNN coaches poll, but expectations
have changed greatly after Saturday's 21-7 win against then-No. 18
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ecstatic about what the rest of the country thinks about
us right now,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said. ``We didn't
anticipate being up at the top of the standings right now, but you
can't lose a game, or two games, and it not be a big issue. You
lose it all. That's a luxury we do not have in football.''
</P>
<P>
   In its second week, the novelty of being ranked is wearing off.
When CSUN (4-1, 3-0 Big Sky), the leaders of the conference, plays
at Sacramento State on Saturday the rest of the Division I-AA world
will pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are at stake, and it will be that way for the rest
of the season. Or until CSUN drops a pair of games and falls out of
that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Holy Cow, we're in first place,''' Ponciano
said. ``We're going to dink around here and all of a sudden find
ourselves in a football game. That's the exciting thing. But then I
get back to reality and thinking about the task at hand, and that
is a potentially dangerous football team who will be exceptionally
fired up with us coming in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors are 103rd in the latest Sagarin ratings, which puts
them 15th among I-AA teams. The only other Big Sky team ranked
ahead of CSUN is Weber State (5-1, 3-1), which fell to No. 13 in
both polls after losing to Montana State.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly call: A week after seeing his own defensive line
brutally chop-blocked by Southern Utah, Ponciano didn't like a
couple of things he saw on the Montana game film.
</P>
<P>
   From his own players.
</P>
<P>
   So he called Grizzlies coach Mick Dennehy to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have outside receivers coming in and clipping guys in
the box, and when you see a back high-low with an offensive lineman
on a defensive lineman, that's a problem,'' Ponciano said. ``We
don't teach that, and it happened so I called Mick to apologize.
I'm very embarrassed that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Shifting the line: In an effort to get more production from the
offensive line, Ponciano said he's shifting Mike Barnes and David
San Vicente. Barnes, who started three games at left guard, is
expected to start against Sacramento State at left tackle. San
Vicente, CSUN's left tackle most of the season, will move to left
guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we need a bigger push inside and a quicker, more
athletic guy on the outside right now,'' Ponciano said. ``Those are
the answers we've come up with. We're having too many problems
there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Matadors' depleted defensive line should get some help
this week. Erik Gardner, Mike Colunga, Jacob Mageo and Patrick
Cwik, each of whom missed the Montana game, are expected to play
against Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner is the most intriguing of the returners. He injured his
knee in the opener against Boise State and hasn't yet returned to
contact drills.
</P>
<P>
   More honors for Swanson: For the third week in a row, CSUN
linebacker Brennen Swanson grabbed an award. Swanson, who had three
sacks and 11 tackles, was named the Big Sky Defensive Player of the
Week for the second time in three weeks. Swanson was the I-AA
National Player of the Week last week.
</P>
<P>
   Short yardage: The loss knocked Montana out of the top 25 for
the first time since the 1992 season.... CSUN quarterback Marcus
Brady dipped to No. 2 in passing efficiency (167.5) in the country.
He's completed 105 of 151 attempts for 1,338 yards, 12 touchdowns
and two interceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
