<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     10-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ Almost 7,000 empty seats greeted the Padres at Qualcomm
Stadium late Monday afternoon. This after San Diego had
consecutively drawn four of the largest crowds in postseason
history.
</P>
<P>
   Had the rats decided to leave what they perceived to be a
suddenly sinking ship?
</P>
<P>
   Goodness, the Padres were leading the NLCS three games to one _
a virtually insurmountable lead, based on a century's worth of
evidence _ and it was Columbus Day to boot. Maybe the city's
fair-weather faction, ever-inclined to hit the beaches, was
actually overconfident and had decided to save some expendable
income for those even more high-dollar World Series tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Which, oddly enough, still go on sale here tonight, damn the
torpedoes. The stadium PA man, between sobs, made the announcement
moments after the Braves had beaten the Padres 7-6, thanking the
fans for ``keeping the faith'' and saying he would see them in the
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. Ever hear the expression, ``whistling past the
graveyard''?
</P>
<P>
   John Moores, the kind, benevolent San Diego owner and expatriate
Houstonian, has said he loves baseball so much he almost can't
stand it. I wonder, however, if he still feels that way, after his
pride-and-joy ballclub, which was perched a mere four outs from
attending the Fall Classic and had its superhero Kevin Brown
throwing BBs, is now only going back to Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   Where there's suddenly a pretty decent chance it can do what no
team before it has ever managed: cough up a 3-0 lead in the
postseason. To hang on, the Padres have to get past either Tom
Glavine or Greg Maddux. No lock in that, is there?
</P>
<P>
   Especially with Brown, who remains the likely Game 6 starter
opposite Glavine on Wednesday night, suffering through an emergency
crisis of confidence. There will be a measure of scar tissue, if
not an open wound, after this, no matter how well he has mastered
the Braves in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking that Kevin's going to go anyway,'' Padres manager
Bruce Bochy said. ``We'll talk about it on the flight and then make
a decision tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta had erupted for six runs in the seventh inning Sunday _
four on Andres Galarraga's wake-up-call grand slam off Dan Miceli _
to steal its first win from the Padres' klutzy clutches. But that
was nothing compared to what the Braves accomplished Monday,
considering against whom they accomplished it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call Kevin Downtown Brown, because that's where Michael
Tucker took him with two men on in the eighth, mere minutes after
Brown, Atlanta's ber-nemesis of late, had strode heroically in from
the bullpen to what must have been the longest, loudest ovation
ever heard in these parts. The 58,988 who had ventured out were so
happy to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Their affection didn't last long, though. By the time the top
half of the eighth had concluded, Brown was slumped over in the
dugout, his cold, hard gunslinger's eyes turned downward in
despair, and the Braves, five runs the richer, were just far enough
in front, 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, they would need the two additional runs that
scored, in large part because of bonehead plays by San Diego, after
Tucker's full-count dinger off a Brown sinker that sank only in
figurative terms.
</P>
<P>
   When Greg Myers ripped a pinch-hit two-run shot in the Padres'
last-gasp ninth, it so unnerved Atlanta manager Bobby Cox that he
must have temporarily lost his mind, summoning Maddux from the
bullpen. Cripes, hadn't Bobby paid any attention to how Brown,
Maddux's stud-duck counterpart, fared in relief?
</P>
<P>
   But Cox's own bizarre gambit paid off, unlike poor Bochy's
botched move. Maddux, seeking his first save of the decade in his
first such appearance since his Cubs salad days, straight away
thwarted a would-be Kirk Gibson-redux scenario. He struck out the
pinch-hitting Greg Vaughn, who had pulled up lame in Atlanta last
week and hadn't played since, on three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Quilvio Veras then bounced to short before Maddux walked Steve
Finley to bring up Tony Gwynn, creating the ultimate of game-ending
matchups _ the best pure hitter of the modern era vs. its finest
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   That high-noon showdown went badly for the Padres as well.
Gwynn, 35-for-79 over the years against Maddux with nary a
strikeout, slapped a slow grounder to first base that Galarraga
handled by his lonesome. That was that. And so the Friars find
themselves in same.
</P>
<P>
   Plumb Tucker-ed out, they may be.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the baby-faced assassin, wonder if a No. 8 hitter
has ever done greater damage in a bigger game? Before his clout off
ol' Downtown, he had already driven in runs in the fourth and sixth
innings.
</P>
<P>
   His five-RBI outburst exceeded his total for the previous four
games by exactly five, although he had socked a two-run homer in
the first Division Series win over Chicago. Back then, the Braves
were in the midst of what would become a 10-game winning streak,
and their tortured pursuit of an elusive second world championship
of the '90s, after seven consecutive NLCS appearances, appeared a
most viable goal.
</P>
<P>
   As it does again. Although the Padres may still be leaders, they
probably feel more like followers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
