<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GOMEZ-NLCS-AZR &LR;      10-13 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-NLCS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT DOESN'T GET BETTER THAN THIS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _Wow! Incredible! Unbelievable! Extraordinary!
Stupendous!
</P>
<P>
   Attach whatever adjective you want to Game 5 of the National
League Championship Series and it still won't do justice to the
game that unfolded between Atlanta and San Diego at Qualcomm
Stadium on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain, Atlanta's heart-stopping 7-6 victory over
the Padres, who have lost two in a row after winning the first
three games, will surely be remembered as one of the greatest games
ever played, one that will be talked about for years.
</P>
<P>
   Players from both sides were mentally exhausted after Andres
Galarraga smothered Tony Gwynn's grounder to end 3 hours, 17
minutes of the highest type of drama sports has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   There was such a sense of urgency to this game that each manager
brought in his ace _ Kevin Brown for San Diego and Greg Maddux for
Atlanta _ to make a very rare relief appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It was Maddux, making his first appearance out of the bullpen
since he was a rookie with the Chicago Cubs in 1987, who got Gwynn
to ground out for the final out of a most memorable game.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux entered the game having started 499 of his 505 games
since turning pro as a scrawny 18-year-old kid from Valley High
School in Las Vegas. He left having registered the first save of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Maddux said. ``I don't think any of us was ready
to go home yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Braves did go home Monday night. But not to dwell
on what went wrong in 1998. Instead, the Braves' late-night
charter, which must have had a carnival atmosphere, had to be
filled with talk of rewriting history.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego grabbed a 2-0 lead in the first, only to watch Atlanta
chip away and tie the score in the top of the sixth before John
Vander Wal slammed a two-run home run off John Smoltz in the bottom
of the sixth, sending the 58,988 fans into a delirious state of
mind.
</P>
<P>
   There was Brown, who entered to a thunderous ovation with a
runner on in the seventh, retiring the first three batters he faced
to get out of the inning, receiving a wave of high-fives from his
teammates in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brown, the biggest of the Braves slayers, gave up a walk, a
single and a foul popout before Michael Tucker stepped into the
batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, an above-average fastball hitter, lined a 3-2 pitch into
the right-field bleachers. The deafening noise inside the stadium
fell silent, so much so that a baby crying on the other side of the
massive park could have been heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nobody's fault but my own,'' said Brown, making only
the third relief appearance of his brilliant career. ``I'm the one
making the pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   What appeared like a runaway just two days ago has shaped into a
history-making event. Never in the previous 18 times that a club
had grabbed a 3-0 lead in a best-of-seven series had the opponent
managed to force a sixth game. Now it has happened.
</P>
<P>
   In what has arguably been the greatest season in the 129 years
of major league baseball, why not have a club return from a 3-0
deficit for the first time?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would certainly be a fabulous end to a fabulous season,''
Atlanta General Manager John Scheurholz said. ``This is what it's
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The game took more twists and turns than the famous Coney Island
Cyclone roller-coaster. The dips made your stomach tingle and the
peaks brought you out of your chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mentally drained,'' San Diego center fielder Steve Finley
said. ``It was up, down, up, down. You didn't know what was going
to happen next. It was probably the best game I've ever been
associated with.''
</P>
<P>
   They came ready to party in San Diego on Monday night. There was
champagne chilling in the bowels of the stadium. There was plastic
wrap applied to the Padres' lockers that had to be torn down
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears 20-game winner Tom Glavine will oppose San
Diego's Sterling Hitchcock in Game 6 on Wednesday. Should there be
a Game 7 _ get ready for this one _ it will pair Brown against
Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Who says baseball has no drama? &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
