<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3112 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-DRUGTESTING-AZR &LR;      10-13 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGS POSE OLYMPIC QUANDARY   
 CHANGING PERCEPTION IS TOUGH AS DETECTION  
</HEADLINE>
 TESTING-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tests are high-tech. The drugs are sophisticated, hard to
spell and harder to define. Performance enhancing, recreational or
over-the-counter? The issues are complicated. The debate is
contentious.
</P>
<P>
   But the cause of all this consternation is simple, and the
result is as predictable as it is lamentable _ guilt by
association.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is one explanation of the exploding drug problem
from a longtime member of the International Olympic Committee's
medical commission during a panel discussion Monday. It's also an
explanation of why it's such a flash point for Olympic officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're free of drugs and you win today, you're still
suspected of having used drugs,'' Dr. Donald Catlin said at an
Olympic Congress workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Catlin believes that unless the trend and suspicion-fueled
perceptions can be reversed, the battle against drugs will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The recent death of Florence Griffith Joyner provides a chilling
example of both sides of the issue. Her record-setting times in the
100- and 200-meter runs before and at the 1988 Olympics were so
extraordinary that many assumed that they were achieved through
drugs. She never failed a drug screening. But that did not quiet
suspicions, which were raised again when she died at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sadly, FloJo's reputation hinges on the autopsy results. It's
the unfortunate fallout for positive tests that have scarred many
of the world's record-setting athletes, including Ben Johnson,
Randy Barnes and Michelle Smith. It, in fact, is a problem that
goes back as far as 1972 when U.S. swimmer Rick DeMont, currently a
University of Arizona assistant swimming coach, was stripped of a
gold medal for taking a respiratory medication prescribed by his
doctor. But the depth of the problem has multiplied as science has
discovered new and harder to detect means of building strength,
speed, stamina and endurance.
</P>
<P>
   More trouble came with this year's Tour de France, the crown
jewel of bicycle racing that was nearly canceled when a drug
scandal caused dozens of the world's best riders to be banned or to
quit.
</P>
<P>
   The controversies are forcing the U.S. Olympic Committee and IOC
to reassess the way they combat an issue that threatens sports'
entire credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Weightlifting was one of the first sports to be hit with
positive tests for steroid use and suspicions of wide-spread abuse
of performance-enhancing substances that are either new or go
undetected.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's seven-member panel included weightlifter Wes Barnett, a
two-time Olympian who has been urging vigilance in the drug battle
since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the discussion, Catlin, founder of the UCLA
Olympic Analytical Laboratory, turned to Barnett, a silver and
bronze medalist at the 1997 World Championship, and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't just congratulations for Wes because he won. We
think he won because, well, he's a weightlifter.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little debate about the lack of tolerance for
performance-enhancing substances in sports, but there is contention
on a number of other fronts. Namely:
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana and how it figures in the fight against
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The state of the battle, especially in the wake of home run king
Mark McGwire's use of over-the-counter androstenedione, which is
banned in the Olympics but not by baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The methods. Should the USOC hire and/or create an independent
agency to conduct testing? And how can the testing procedure
efficiently and economically be used to detect new substances?
</P>
<P>
   Catlin said the variety of drugs will continue to grow and could
overwhelm the ablity to detect them. Some are hormones, such as
testosterone, that are produced naturally in the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural, but you have to prove it is foreign,'' Catlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is a synthetic hormone such as EPO, the substance
that rocked the Tour de France. It can't be detected at all, Catlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think we're going to lose the battle,'' Catlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Catlin and panelists Baaron Pittenger of the USOC, attorney
Richard Young, Canadian physician Andrew Pipe, White House
representative Robert Housman and USOC anti-doping committee member
Christopher Lindsay still offered suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   The marijuana issue is at the top of their agenda, in large part
because of positive tests of a gold-medal-winning snowboarder at
the last Winter Games in Nagano and of 1996 Olympic sprinter Gary
Hall Jr., a gold- and silver-medal winner from Phoenix Swim Club.
</P>
<P>
   Housman, assistant to Gen. Barry McCaffrey of the National Drug
Control Policy, argued that Olympic sports should test for
marijuana. He cited health reasons and the athletes' responsibility
as a role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an elite athlete gets caught (using pot), the message is,
`Hey, I can do that, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the pot issue is another step on very slippery slope, Young
and Pipe argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to ask: Is it job-related,'' said Young, a Colorado
attorney and chairman of the International Court for Sports
Arbitration. ``It is not a performanceenhancing drug used in an
attempt to cheat. Marijuana is a social vice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to deal with a moral virus, then let's have a code
of ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the IOC is expected to make pot a prohibited
substance for all sports, according to Young, who added that
consistency is pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   At Nagano, it was not prohibited by the association that governs
snowboarding. In the Hall case, there were conflicting reports from
FINA, swimming's international governing body, about whether he had
committed a second offense in May when a positive test resulted in
a two-month suspension. One FINA official said he had tested
positive at the Atlanta Games. Another FINA official said pot was
not illegal at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   According to Young, FINA was wrong with its contention that Hall
was liable for a positive test in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``For drug-control purposes, it might might well have been
baking soda,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of how to wage the battle against
performance-enhancing drugs, there were proposals from Barnett and
Catlin.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett asked for further vigilance and strict enforcement of
bans that are too often lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to enforce the sanctions that we have,'' he said. ``I
keep finding myself suddenly competing against guys who I thought
had been banned for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett also had some offbeat ideas. He suggested spies to
infiltrate sports that are suspected of having a high-rate of drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett also suggested that scientists develop a counter pill
that would make athletes violently ill if they had been using
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something to stop them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catlin proposed a voluntary system, a highly publicized program,
for athletes determined to stop the abuse. Those athletes would
agree to be monitored at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them badges, and I mean the kind of badges that all
athletes would want,'' Catlin said. ``We would constantly notify
the public that these athletes are drug free.''
</P>
<P>
   Catlin and Pipe argued there could be a change in growing
pressure to use drugs. It is increasingly unacceptable because of
education and media messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all, we've got to change the culture of sport,'' Catlin
said.
</P>
<P>
   One step under consideration is in the approach. Thus far, the
USOC conducts its own testing. But that has created a perception of
a potential conflict of interest. In part, the USOC is in the
business of winning medals for America. The perception is that it
might be tempted to overlook drug use by its best athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts our credibility,'' said Pittenger, chairman of the
USOC's anti-doping committee.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the USOC study includes the feasibility of an
independent agency that also would work for the NCAA and
professional sports, according to Pittenger. The proposal is due
for consideration at the USOC's board of directors meeting in
April.
</P>
<P>
   A joint effort with pro sports is difficult because of the
acknowledged use of andro _ a precursor to testosterone _ by
McGwire, a 1984 Olympian before he went on to stardom with the
Oakland A's and St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do has been undermined by Mark
McGwire,'' Pipe said. ``Unquestionably, the issue has eroded much
of our work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see baseball's feet put to the fire on this. I
have seen the negative impact, in terms of suspicion, that this
kind of thing can cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has the right to believe that achievement in sports
is authentic and not artificial.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
