r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-13 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES' COMEBACK CULLED FROM HIGHER PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The talisman that had worked wonders for the Atlanta
Braves before in must-win National League Championship Series games
was on the mound. But on Monday you had to wonder if it wasn't the
St. Christopher's medal tucked away in the pocket of manager Bobby
Cox that did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-6 victory the Braves pulled off in Game 5 of the
best-of-seven series was a small miracle. Never mind what it says
in the Atlanta media guide about Michael Tucker coming to the
Braves two years ago from Kansas City. On this night he looked like
he was heaven-sent.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves didn't appear to have a prayer after Ken Caminiti and
John Vander Wal each smoked Atlanta ace John Smoltz for two-run
homers as the Padres took a 4-2 lead into the seventh inning and
trotted out their ace, Kevin Brown, for a rare relief appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Brown opened the eighth by walking Ryan Klesko. Javier Lopez
then singled to right. After Andruw Jones popped out, up to the
plate stepped Tucker, an outfielder of no real renown.
</P>
<P>
   Five outs. That's all the Padres needed to ice their first World
Series appearance since 1984. Tucker certainly didn't seem like
he'd be a major obstacle in their path; he had struck out twice and
flied out against Brown in Brown's nine-inning masterpiece in Game
2.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. This time Tucker took Brown to a full count, then
lifted a fastball over the right-field fence to knock the wind out
of the Padres and the 58,918 fans who had flocked to Qualcomm
Stadium to see San Diego punch its ticket to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most dramatic swing seen around these parts since
Kirk Gibson's shot against the Oakland A's at Dodger Stadium in
Game One of the 1988 World Series. By the time the stunned Padres
recovered their wits, the Braves had added two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Donne Wall replaced Brown and walked fellow reliever John
Rocker. After Ozzie Guillen struck out, Tony Graffanino doubled in
Rocker, advanced to third on the throw from the outfield and scored
on shortstop Chris Gomez' wild throw.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez' error would loom large when, in the bottom of the ninth,
Padres pinch hitter Greg Myers aimed to thrill, hitting a two-run
homer off Kerry Ligtenberg that brought the Padres to within 7-6
with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   Power-hitter Greg Vaughn, who had sat out the previous three
games with a strained left quadriceps muscle, was summoned to pinch
hit and Greg Maddux sauntered in from the Braves' bullpen _ yes,
you read that right. Maddux, making his first career postseason
appearance in a relief role, struck out Vaughn and got Quilvio
Veras to ground out. After walking Steve Finley he handcuffed Tony
Gwynn, who hit a weak dribbler to first baseman Andres Galarraga to
assure Maddux his first career save.
</P>
<P>
   So it was the Braves became the first team in major-league
history to lose the first three games of a postseason series and
force at least a sixth, to be played Wednesday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are now 8-4 when facing elimination in the NLCS and
don't think it hasn't dawned on the Padres that Atlanta's rich
legacy in the `90s includes rallying from 1-3 to the St. Louis
Cardinals two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That said, history remains firmly on the side of the Padres.
Only two teams in all of professional sports have prevailed after
falling behind 0-3: the Toronto Maple Leafs against Detroit in the
1942 Stanley Cup Finals and the New York Islanders against
Pittsburgh in the 1975 Stanley Cup quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres still have two match points, so to speak. But you
have to wonder if they'll be able to pick themselves up after
failing to keep the Braves down. If Games 4 and 5 were a stern test
of Atlanta's character, Game 6 will measure the Padres' fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we showed a lot tonight after what happened,'' Padres
manager Bruce Bochy said, straining to put the best light on a
dark, dark night. ``We kind of let the game get out of hand once
they took a one-run lead. But we battled back.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset the Braves thought they had a good chance in
this one because sending Smoltz to the mound in a must-win game is
like calling on John Elway to lead a last-minute touchdown drive or
Michael Jordan to score a last-second basket.
</P>
<P>
   He was 2-0 in NLCS elimination games, with an ERA of 0.82. Only
the Padres seemed unimpressed. Caminiti struck in the first and
Vander Wal in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz allowed nine hits in 62/3 innings. If not for Tucker,
that would have been all the opening the Padres needed to shut the
door on the Braves. Instead, they're still alive in their drive to
make those 106 regular-season wins mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of you have said we're one of the class organizations
in baseball and we're proud of that,'' said Braves general manager
John Schuerholz. ``We're proud of the fact we have put ourselves in
that position now for eight years. (It's) remarkable when you think
about this crazy economic situation in which we're forced to
operate to be able to continually keep a winning team. But we also
feel there is sort of the unfinished symphony. Unless we win the
World's Championship, we're not satisfied.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3117 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-13 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SAN DIEGO _ There still is time for those who abandoned the Atlanta
Braves' bandwagon to jump back on the steam-building carriage.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next stop: Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves wriggled free of the noose for the second game in a
row, claiming a 7-6 come-from-behind victory over the reeling San
Diego Padres on Monday night and sending the National League
Championship Series back to Atlanta's Turner Field for Game 6 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres still hold a 3-2 lead in the best-of-seven series,
but they are gradually losing their grip on the NL pennant they
seemed destined to own after taking a 3-0 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you we could make it interesting,'' Braves manager
Bobby Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox and counterpart Bruce Bochy managed as if there were no
tomorrow, and in Cox's case, there wasn't. Both managers used their
ace starting pitchers to protect leads.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux got the job done for the Braves, but Kevin Brown
finally ran out of magic. Braves right fielder Michael Tucker, who
was 3-for-4 with five RBIs, belted a three-run, eighth-inning homer
off Brown to give the Braves a lead they never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a pitch I could drive, and I was fortunate
to get a pitch like that,'' said Tucker, whose blast gave the
Braves a 5-4 advantage. ``I didn't miss it. I knew (a home run) is
what we needed to put us ahead. This was a great game. There have
been times in the playoffs where guys stepped up and did something
big, and tonight was my night.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who started Game 2 for the Padres, entered Monday's game
in the seventh inning when the Padres held a 4-2 lead. He was
making just the third relief appearance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had my best guy out there with a chance to win
the ballgame,'' Bochy said. ``He was rested, and I'll take my
chances there. Sure, it didn't work out, and I'll take
responsibility for that. But with Kevin out there, I have all the
confidence in the world. It didn't work out. It was a calculated
risk, but I thought it was well worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy said he would start Brown in Game 6 if his ace feels good.
Sterling Hitchcock will face Tom Glavine if Brown is unable to
answer the bell Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres didn't go down quietly Monday in the ninth inning.
They pulled within a run of the lead on Greg Myers' two-run
pinch-hit homer off Braves closer Kerry Ligtenberg. Not wanting to
leave anything to chance, Cox sent Maddux to the mound to secure
the victory. Maddux retired three of the four batters he faced to
earn the first save of his professional career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had (Maddux) planned all night long for one hitter, maybe
two or three,'' Cox said. ``It all depended on how he looked. I'm
sure the Padres felt the same way about Brown. I thought Kevin was
throwing good. They had a great opportunity to bring him in and
close this (series) out. We got lucky, hit a ball, and it went out
of the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-run homer was the Padres' only offense of the night. Ken
Caminiti, John Vander Wal and Myers each hit two-run dingers.
Braves starter John Smoltz served up the homers to Caminiti and
Vander Wal, but it was an otherwise good outing for Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Padres starter Andy Ashby clearly was working with less than his
best stuff, but he did a good job of pitching around trouble,
although he wasn't able to protect a two-run lead after the first
inning. Ashby allowed two runs on nine hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti's second home run of the series and his fifth career
postseason homer gave the Padres a 2-0 lead in the first inning.
With two out and teammate Steve Finley on first base, Caminiti
ripped a first-pitch fastball on the outside corner of the plate
down the left-field line and walked toward first base, hoping it
would stay fair.
</P>
<P>
   It did. And just like that, the Padres had seized the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves cut the lead to a run in the fourth inning on
Tucker's RBI single to right. Cox called for a squeeze bunt in the
fourth with Smoltz at the plate and Andruw Jones at third, but the
Padres sniffed it out to keep the Braves from tying the score _ at
least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the sixth inning when the bottom of the Braves'
lineup put together a two-out rally. Jones singled, stole second
and scored on Tucker's base hit up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy has pushed most of the right buttons during the
postseason, but his decision to let Ashby pitch to Tucker was
questionable. Had the Padres intentionally walked Tucker, they
could have faced Smoltz or forced Cox to pinch hit for his starting
pitcher. Either scenario appeared more favorable to the Padres than
pitching to Tucker, who is hitting .417 (5-for-12) in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, sure I wish I would have walked him if I had
known he was going to throw that kind of pitch,'' Bochy said.
</P>
<P>
   Vander Wal's dramatic home run off Smoltz in the bottom of the
sixth untied the game and put the Padres up by two runs. The crowd
of 58,988 was roaring with anticipation of a pennant-clinching
celebration, but the Braves killed those plans with their five-run
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Tucker's three-run homer in the eighth, the
Braves also scored a run on Tony Graffanino's double into the
left-field gap and another on a throwing error by Padres shortstop
Chris Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where we kind of let the game get out of hand,'' Bochy
said. ``We threw the ball away and allowed them to score that other
run. It's hard enough to overcome a one-run lead, let alone a
three-run lead. It's a tough loss, no question about it. When you
have a two-run lead and they come back on you, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the series shifting back to Atlanta, things don't
figure to get any easier for the Padres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
