<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-SHARON-STONE-ART     10-13 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-SHARON-STONE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARON STONE GOES UNGLAMOROUS IN 'THE MIGHTY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444. Overseas, contact Karl Horwitz in Paris at
33-1-47-42-17-11.) 
 (White has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Sharon Stone, Kieran
Culkin and other actors in scenes from ``The Mighty.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Interviewing Sharon Stone these days comes with a built-in
warning _ not to mention a beefy bodyguard and a publicist poised
at her shoulder.
 &HT;    Three hours before Stone showed up for our interview at Beverly
Hills' Four Seasons Hotel her publicist marched into the room,
denied published stories that said Sharon was pregnant and warned,
``If you ask any questions about the pregnancy or her marriage the
interview will end right there. ''
 &HT;    When Sharon eventually showed up she looked gorgeous as always
but seemed something less than exuberant, admitting, ``I'm tired.
I'm fighting a cold. I always get this way when I do publicity
tours.''
 &HT;    Stone's mission was to talk up a storm about ``The Mighty,'' a
film in which she plays the unglamorous mother of a severely
handicapped young son, played by 15-year-old Kieran Culkin, younger
brother of McCauley Culkin.
 &HT;    It's a warm, sad tale about two boys handicapped in different
ways who use their imaginations and fondness for the legend of King
Arthur to forge a remarkable friendship.
 &HT;    The picture _ a hit at Cannes this spring, also stars Gena
Rowlands, Harry Dean Stanton and ``X-Files''' Gillian Anderson in
an offbeat role as a loose, boozy broad.
 &HT;    But it's Stone who must sell the picture. She talks slowly and
without much fire, but looks pretty sensational in a gray cashmere
sweater and knee-high blue denim skirt, her blonde hair cut ultra
short _ ``I chopped it all off myself in a wild moment,'' she
explains.
 &HT;    ``Mighty'' director Peter Chelsom (``Hear My Song,'' 1991) says
when Stone read the script and agreed to play the plain-Jane role
he cautioned, ``Are you prepared to come as you are? You don't get
any special lighting or foggy filters for your shots.''
 &HT;    Stone, who also produced the picture, agreed; Chelsom says, ``It
was a commendable, noble ... and very intelligent thing for her to
do.''
 &HT;    The star herself makes light of the fact that Sharon Stone,
reigning Hollywood sex symbol should play a working-class mom. The
sexy image, she insists, is something male journalists have stuck
her with.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't exactly glamorous in `Last Dance,' was I?'' she
challenges, and indeed she did play a death row inmate in that 1996
picture. But it's difficult to forget that she zoomed her way to
the top of Hollywood's must-hire list after her role as the
psychopathic seductress opposite Michael Douglas in ``Basic
Instinct'' (1992).
 &HT;    Making ``The Mighty'' was different: ``I was impaled by the
emotion of this film,'' she says.
 &HT;    There have of course been big changes in her life in the last
year. For starters she got married, last Valentine's Day, to San
Francisco newspaper editor Phil Bronstein which caused her, she
says, to put less emphasis on her career.
 &HT;    It also brought her another home. In addition to the house she
owns in an upscale Los Angeles suburb, she now lives with her
husband in a high-rise apartment in San Francisco. And while Stone
wants to avoid motherhood and marriage topics, she did recount a
scary incident which took place a few weeks ago in the skyscraper
in the city by the bay.
 &HT;    The actress was trapped in an elevator for two hours between the
20th and 21st floors. She used her cell phone to call Bronstein,
who rushed to the building and talked her through the ordeal before
emergency rescue crews smashed their way to her from the adjacent
building and pulled her to safety.
 &HT;    ``The day after the rescue,'' Stone recalls, ``I fell apart when
I realized that the elevator could have crashed to earth and I
would have ended up an oil stain on the concrete. But strangely,
going through something like that brought Phil and I much closer
together. The rescue people were telling me to do one thing that
went against my gut instinct _ and Phil supported me by saying, 'Do
what you think is right.'''
 &HT;    Stone says she has become a regular housefrau and likes nothing
better than to bake up batches of cookies for her husband to take
to the guys on the paper. She's also developed a liking for writing
and has penned several short stories. ``I took a few lessons on how
to use a computer and finally was able to shop for three pairs of
jeans on the Internet. But it's not for me so Phil finally bought
me an old-fashioned typewriter.''
 &HT;    Besides ``The Mighty,'' she also stars opposite Woody Allen as
the voice of the princess in Dreamworks' new hit movie ``Antz.''
 &HT;    ``That was great,'' she says. ``I was able to do the voice-over
work in San Francisco without having to dress up in costume or
spend hours in a makeup chair.''
 &HT;    Her re-marriage and the fact that she hopes to become a mother,
says Stone, helped her weather turning 40 in March. (Her marriage
to producer Michael Greenberg ended after three years in l987.)
 &HT;    ``I often picked the wrong guy,'' she admits. ``I had problems
finding the right man simply because I never considered myself very
lovable. When boys came to my house when I was growing up it was to
see my younger sister Kelly. I was the ugly duckling in our family,
a real geek at high school. I had no sense of myself as a woman.''
 &HT;    But all that has changed since she met the macho Bronstein after
coming to San Francisco to star in this year's science fiction
movie ``Sphere.'' The film flopped but the romance blossomed.
Bronstein, say his friends, is a confident man with a strong sense
of his own identity who doesn't worry about becoming Mr. Sharon
Stone.
 &HT;    And he has certainly changed her perspective. ``I used to be in
love with my job _ and now I'm in love with my life and like my
job,'' says Stone. ``Stardom isn't the fuel of my soul any more.''
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
<TEXT>
reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</TEXT>
</BODY>
