<P>
   FURNITURE _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ You may not be able to afford an
exotic getaway, but that doesn't mean you have to miss out on the
travel. Furniture manufacturers have found a clever way to get you
to spend money at home instead of at the airport. They're designing
pieces inspired by places that will take you, vicariously, around
the world. And it doesn't hurt when a famous person's name is
attached _ a trend in itself among the thousands of manufacturers
who show their newest pieces each spring and fall at the world's
largest wholesale furniture exposition in High Point, N.C.
Thomasville Furniture Industries, for example, will introduce the
Ernest Hemingway Collection, inspired by places where the famed
author lived or worked _ Kenya, Key West, Ketchum and Havana _ when
the fall market opens Thursday. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   BREAST _ Evelyn Gresham knows what it's like to come to terms
with the words ``you have breast cancer.'' For the past year, she's
lived through the diagnosis, scares, fear, surgeries and drugs, and
now she helps others facing the same questions and uncertainities
through the volunteer, non-profit group Bosom Buddies of Georgia
Inc. ``One weekend, I went to visit a woman who, when she found out
(about her cancer), she bought a casket, she found a cemetery plot
and she just kept crying,'' said Gresham, 41. ``You lose it. You
ask yourself, `Why is this happening to me?' But you need to talk
to women who are surviving breast cancer. They've got the
information. They've got the experience.'' Women's awareness of
breast cancer and the need for early detection were raised last
week, when WSB-TV anchor Monica Kaufman disclosed that a small
tumor was detected in her left breast. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
