<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hope to hear `I do'? Avoid the don'ts
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Another Saturday night. Another long
ride home without having bagged any prey, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Alexander and Jeannie Long _ both 28, single and weary
of the hunt _ started joking about men. Not about keeping them (the
coup de grace!), but about losing them (no trick there).
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 2: Swing by Blockbuster and rent When Harry Met Sally.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 3: Call your ugliest friend for a ``girls' night out.''
This will make you look better.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 5: Read his old yearbook. Ask if he still has feelings for
Stacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were howling,'' Alexander says. ``We practically wrote the
book right there in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Long, both from Tallahassee, have been friends since
junior high. Now roommates in L.A., they work in the music industry
and call their home ``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning, we were talking about The Rules (last year's
controversial book on how to snare a husband) and how they were
manipulative and impossible,'' Long says. ``Then, we said we should
write a book about what girls really do.''
</P>
<P>
   The result _ which they illustrated with stick figures and
stapled together to give as Christmas gifts _ was How to Lose a Guy
in 10 Days ($6.99, Bantam).
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 7: Join his gym. Anytime you ``accidentally'' run into
him, call it a ``ka-winky-dink.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 8: Suggest abstinence. Then, next time it will be more
special.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 9: Fly your parents in to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   A friend called a literary agent in New York, and just two
months later, the pair had a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they're not losers (``we do have dates''), and they're
each looking for a guy with a sense of humor _ the kind of guy
who'd laugh at their book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Jackie Collins,'' Long says. ``But you might as well
be honest. Guys who read it are a lot more understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 10: Tell him he's changed, and you don't know him anymore.
Suggest therapy. Yell, cry, throw your shoe at him, collapse on the
hood of his car _ anything to get him back.
</P>
<P>
   Go to party. Meet someone else. Return to Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
