<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4050 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN14-COX     10-13 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid all the claptrap of modern-day life, is anybody listening?
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When I bought a new car a few years ago, one of the
features I enjoyed most was the sound system. The speakers were
like nothing I'd experienced in an automobile. It was like the
first time I heard, years earlier, music on Bose 901s. The sound
filled every cubic inch of space, expanding like air being pumped
into a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   At less than a quarter of maximum volume, the ordinary speech of
a news broadcast was audible and clear. For music I'd turn it up a
notch, and occasionally, if it was a piece I especially liked and I
was alone, I'd let it rip. But never to the halfway point. That was
too loud, the sound itself overwhelmed by sheer volume.
</P>
<P>
   Now I find myself turning it up higher than I once did, almost
to halfway. I don't think it's my ears and I know there's nothing
wrong with the speakers. I think I've become desensitized to sound.
I think most of us have. Not in the way a rock musician's ears are
blasted to bits, but in the everyday, incremental ways of expecting
everything to be louder than it has to be.
</P>
<P>
   On ESPN Chris Berman yammers away at high volume, words pouring
out faster than the ear can take them in. With Dick Vitale, the
basketball commentator, at least you know it's an amiable clown's
act. And both, after all, are only playing to a particular audience
_ this is TV sports, not C-SPAN. The excitement has to be urged on
people.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes a different matter when volume is obligatory
everywhere else. Not just at stoplights, where a car stereo blares
loud enough to be heard in all directions for a quarter-mile, but
in places where you wouldn't have expected it. Restaurants all of a
sudden have become noisy places, operating on the assumption that
patrons like the commotion. Try to find a quiet corner for
conversation. Pots and pans clang like cymbals, chatter at the next
table spills indiscriminately onto yours, the piped-in music drowns
out even Chris Berman.
</P>
<P>
   We don't like silence; we're afraid of it. It's no accident that
disputes over school prayer always seem to turn on the phrase
``moment of silence.'' You get the feeling, all denials to the
contrary, that it's that gap of soundlessness as much as prayer
that threatens people. The presumption is that someone should be
talking, explaining, gabbing every second.
</P>
<P>
   I happen to be reading a book by Stephen L. Carter titled
``Civility: Manners, Morals and the Etiquette of Democracy.'' Don't
be put off _ as I momentarily was _ by that word ``etiquette.'' I
grew up thinking it meant which side of the plate you placed the
knife on and which side the fork and spoon _ something I made a
point of learning and six months later forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's book hasn't received the reviews it deserves, and I
think I know why. Among other things, he thinks we're too ready to
trot out the tattered banner of the First Amendment every time some
pop music group records an album about women being raped. (Funny
how the First Amendment is always being pressed into service for
the least edifying causes.) But Carter, who teaches law at Yale,
knows something of the Constitution. More than that, he sees the
kind of people we've become:
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound, the noise, the sheer unrelenting loudness of our
world combine to make civility difficult to achieve. The challenge
of contemporary life is not so much that we are busy as that we are
blasted around the clock with the sounds of our society: raucous
music, insistent telephones, cynical newscasts, angry traffic.
Small wonder that we seem so selfish. Small wonder that the polls
say people think incivility is growing worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sold on civility, as Carter acknowledges. For
some it's hypocrisy, a form of social conditioning whose real
purpose is to mask deep social conflict. But vigorous debate in the
public arena is one thing and the everyday sounds around us quite
another. Whatever the causes, we've lost, it would seem, the
capacity to be quiet once in a while, to just shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Carter quotes former French Premier Georges Clemenceau, who said
the United States was ``the only nation in history which has
miraculously gone directly from barbarism to degeneration without
the usual interval of civilization.'' And then Carter says
Clemenceau was, of course, overstating matters to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't think he was exaggerating at all. Civilization was
two stops back, and we missed it. We were too busy gabbing,
yelling, remonstrating, all at high volume.
</P>
<P>
   In all the commotion, no one hears much, and the sounds we don't
hear at all are the sounds of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
