u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND14-COX     10-13 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vanity Fair focuses on 200 women
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably no surprise to most that Vanity Fair ($3.95) has
named Oprah Winfrey as the most influential woman in America.
Winfrey is one of the 200 female legends, leaders and trailblazers
featured in a dazzling pictorial portfolio by Annie Leibovitz and
30 other photographers. Anne Cox Chambers, chairwoman of Atlanta
Newspapers Inc. and former U.S. ambassador to Belgium, is
spotlighted as one of the leading women in media.
</P>
<P>
   Other categories, including entertainment, politics and book
publishing, feature the usual suspects: Madonna, Barbra Streisand,
Jodie Foster, Madeleine Albright, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Janet
Reno, Elizabeth Dole, Patricia Cornwell and Terry McMillan, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Graydon Carter notes that the special report represents a
milestone for the women's movement. ``A portfolio of this sort
would have been impossible 20 or 30 years ago''_ BOOKED: One of the
newest entries in the magazine field is Book ($4.95), a publication
devoted to literary matters. The debut issue features a cover story
on Tom Wolfe and his novel ``A Man in Full,'' and interviews with
authors Wally Lamb, Anna Quindlen and Jim Harrison. ``Book won't
just be about books,'' says editor Jerome Kramer. ``We're going to
write about people and places and ideas that are important to
people who care deeply about books.'' The Wolfe article offers
little new information, but the magazine has promise.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE NEWSWEEKLIES: Newsweek ($2.95) offers the most interesting
take on ``this tinny new impeachment war.'' Featuring photographs
of a painfully youthful Bill and Hillary Clinton _ all hair,
polyester and smiles _ the cover story, ``The Children of
Watergate,'' compares and contrasts many of the players in
Watergate and Monicagate. Even Henry Kissinger weighs in with an
essay on what it's like to conduct foreign policy in an impeachment
crisis. ``In such an atmosphere, normality and hysteria exist side
by side,'' the grand old diplomat writes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Time ($2.95) magazine offers a baffling special
report on ``How to Make a Better Student.'' Enjolique Aytch, a
17-year-old student at Atlanta's Grady High School, is one of
several kids with inspirational stories to tell, but these lessons
hardly seem revolutionary. The ``new'' tips for parents include: Be
role models, be involved, encourage learning, feed children's
passions and _ here's the wildest concept of all _ treat every
child as an individual. Well, duh.
</P>
<P>
   _ BEST SCI-FI: Entertainment Weekly ($2.95) takes us where no
magazine has gone before with a feature on the 100 all-time
greatest works of science fiction. Topping the list, of course, is
``Star Wars,'' the 1977 fable that rejuvenated a genre that had
fallen into a black hole. Close behind is ``Star Trek,'' the cult
series by Gene Roddenberry. Rounding out the Top 5 are ``The
Twilight Zone,'' ``Frankenstein,'' and ``2001: A Space Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   _ QUICK READS: Savannah, Ga. is not the only coastal city with
colorful characters. In the October issue of GQ ($3.50), Jack Hitt
remembers growing up in Charleston, S.C., with his own version of
Boo Radley next door. Three decades later, he discovers that Dawn
Pepita Langley Hall, who made headlines as one of the world's first
transsexuals, was not what she appeared to be. . . . In its
conspiracy issue, George ($2.95) raises questions about the
mysterious death of Clinton's Whitewater partner Jim McDougal,
probes the murders of Tupac Shakur and Biggie Smalls, and invites
filmmaker Oliver Stone to speculate about secret plots throughout
history.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
