<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-STYLE14-COX     10-13 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-STYLE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet the designers who make your clothes: Dana Buchman
 &HT;    (EDS: Third in a series _ contact CoxNet at 404-526-5456 if
previous stories are needed.)
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Target customer: A woman 35 and older,
who doesn't want to spend a lot of time getting dressed but who
also doesn't mind spending money on quality clothing at such stores
as Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue, Bloomingdale's and Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1987, Dana Buchman the company, a division
of Liz Claiborne Inc., has grown to a $200 million a year company.
It is opening two boutiques this year _ including a
4,000-square-foot boutique on Worth Avenue in Palm Beach _ to bring
the total to five. It also doubled its store space on 57th Street
in New York, and three or four other boutiques are planned for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   And Dana Buchman the person, a 46-year-old Memphis, Tenn.
native, is pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Her target customer is herself. She's not into the ``18-year-old
runway model thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear a pantsuit every day,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For Buchman and vice president of design, Karen Harman (the two
have worked together for 15 years), designing clothes is not about
their own artistic gratification. They study their customers,
traveling the country trying to get a sense of how the women who
wear their designs live and what they're looking for in corporate
or ``event'' attire. They make personal appearances, greeting
customers at the upscale department stores that carry any of the
six Buchman lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how our customer lives, her body configuration and
what she's comfortable in,'' says Harman.
</P>
<P>
   When they return to New York, they assess their works in
progress by trying to determine where such outfits would most
likely be worn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often ask each other, `Where are you going in that?' If we
can't figure it out, we scrap it or change it,'' Buchman said.
</P>
<P>
   They also survey all designs from the staff, including buttons,
beads and accessories. Recently, on a typical day, Buchman studied
a sheer, leaf-print, olive-toned scarf. ``If you put black in it,
then the lady will know what color shoes to wear,'' she said.
Practical and pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Her clothing lines range from size 2 to 24. The least expensive
piece is a $48 cotton and Lycra T-shirt. At the other end is a
cashmere trench coat at $750. A top-tier line, Dana Buchman Luxe,
features clothing styled with embroidery and beading and
transitional layering pieces _ short jackets over wide pants; long
jackets over short skirts. Luxe outfits _ in the $180 to $450 price
range _ are appropriate for office and evening wear, Buchman says.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: boxers. Why not? Buchman thinks it's a cute idea. She
wears them and a T-shirt for reading at home. She's into Dickens
and Edith Wharton, with a copy of The New Yorker thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Harman visited Palm Beach for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting ladies in cashmere twin sets and pearls,'' she
says. ``And there was a woman there just like that _ just one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She must be hired by the Palm Beach tourist authority to be
there,'' Buchman says.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion item they would banish: ``enormous shoulderpads.''
</P>
<P>
   Phrase they are tired of hearing from women: ``Oh, I could never
wear that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to shake them,'' Harman says.
</P>
<P>
   Coming tomorrow: Ann Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
Kathleen Sampey of the Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
