<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Oct. 13, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-HATECRIMES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Despite the brutal murder of a
gay man in Wyoming and increasing pressure to enact bias-crime
legislation, the leader of New York's Senate says he has grave
reservations about joining the 41 states that impose tougher
penalties on perpetrators of so-called ``hate crimes.'' By JOHN
CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   STANFORD-NOBELS (San Francisco) _ Stanford University physicist
Robert C. Laughlin and two other physicists working in the United
States win the Nobel Prize Tuesday for their discoveries of how
ordinary electrons interact to make the universe work the way it
does. It was the second year in a row a Stanford physicist has won
the Nobel for physics. Now Stanford has 10 Nobel winners. By LARRY
D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DEBATE (San Francisco) _ The debate between Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif., and Republican state Treasurer Matt Fong Monday
night marked a turn away from the topic of President Clinton's
sexual affairs, which at times has seemed the biggest issue in the
race. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   ENDANGERED-TURTLES (San Francisco) _ A campaign to protect
endangered sea turtles suffered a key setback last week when the
World Trade Organization ruled that the U.S. cannot force other
countries to equip their shrimp boats with devices that enable
turtles to escape shrimp nets. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GAY-ISSUES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Although Republican Dan
Lungren and Democrat Gray Davis don't talk about it unless asked,
gay marriages will be one of the daunting issues facing the next
governor _ 50 years after California became the first state to
recognize interracial unions. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-Y2K (Seguin, Texas) _ At midnight Dec. 31, 1999, a
health care worker will be stationed at the bed of every patient in
the Guadalupe Valley Hospital here. In addition to the traditional
medical equipment, the health care providers all will be holding
flashlights. Just in case the millennium bug _ known as the Y2K Bug
_ affects everything from coffee makers to ventilators, patient
care will continue. By ROGER CROTEAU.
</P>
<P>
   TSAI-SF (San Francisco) _ In a city where the dominant political
establishment revolves in tight orbit around one man, Mayor Willie
Brown, Rose Tsai, a candidate for the Board of Supervisors, is a
runaway meteor. Her election would upset a city hall where loyalty
to the mayor rules. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (San Francisco) _ Lynn Dix is suing Beretta U.S.A.
Corp., the maker of the 9mm pistol that killed her son, claiming
the company's failure to install an internal lock on its guns makes
it liable for his death. If she wins the case, which opened Tuesday
in Alameda County Superior Court, her lawsuit may lead to a new
climate in gun control practices. By JACOB H. FRIES.
</P>
<P>
   STOLEN-ANTIQUES (Hudson, N.Y.) _ Most fine arts and antiques
stolen in the United States are taken by someone who has no idea of
their value _ and then hocked to a dealer who, most likely, does
not know what he's buying is stolen. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-IMPLANTS (Undated) _ A few years ago, cosmetic surgeon
Henry Mentz rarely met a patient who wanted breast implants.
Instead, many women with silicone gel implants were clamoring to
have them removed amid reports they might be unsafe. But now his
office is swamped with women who are lining up for the surgery _
this time with saline implants. By CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   COLON-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Most Americans are unaware that
colorectal cancers are the second leading cause of cancer death and
will kill an estimated 56,500 people this year. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S-CENTER (San Francisco) _ The late real estate
developer-hotelier Ben Swig would be appalled at the idea: setting
aside an entire block of downtown San Francisco just for kids. On
Saturday, surrounded by some of the city's most high-priced turf,
nearly 10 acres of real estate atop Moscone Convention Center will
be dedicated and opened _ for children. By GERALD D. ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-CARDS (San Francisco) _ Plastic kills. Consumer
bankruptcy filings are up 66 percent in the last five years, to
1.35 million annually, according to the American Bankruptcy
Institute. Could it have to do with the fact that credit-card
solicitations totaled 3 billion last year? Harvard Law School
professor Elizabeth Warren thinks so. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LATIN (San Francisco) _ Private investors are betting
nearly $100 million that Latin America will be the next front in
the information revolution. StarMedia Inc., a 2-year-old New
York-based Internet company that publishes a multifeature Web site
exclusively for Latin America, has announced it had received $80
million in private funding. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKSTORE-BANKRUPTCY (Guilderland, N.Y.) _ Early this year, the
privately owned Lauriat's bookstore chain headed into Chapter 11,
the federal bankruptcy protection that allows a business to shield
its assets and keep operating while it works out some kind of plan
to pay at least some of its obligations to creditors. Now, the
downsized chain has a new plot plan. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRICAL-DEREGULATION (San Francisco) _ The 1996 state law
that broke the century-old grip of utility monopolies on power
generation and allowed customers to choose their own power provider
has been excoriated by consumer advocates as corporate welfare for
utilities. A group of them gathered sufficient petition signatures
to place on the Nov. 3 ballot Proposition 9, which would undo
elements of the law. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-TRINITY (Undated) _ There's the Irish cop and the
Irish priest and the Irish union mobster and the Irish substance
abuser. The bar they all hang out at is called ``Murphy's.'' The
family is the size of a small town. ``Trinity'' has more cliches
than a Harlequin romance novel. The funny thing about cliches and
stereotypes is, they are sometimes true. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INN-TRAVEL (Asheville, N.C.) _ Steeped in history but with
luxurious and modern conveniences, the Grove Park Inn in Asheville,
N.C., has served as temporary home to eight U.S. presidents, Henry
Ford, Thomas Edison, numerous royals and countless other
diginitaries. We take a look inside this landmark. By CAROL RUST.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Thanksgiving and Christmas may seem
far removed, but the time is now to plan for holiday travel. By SYD
KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Department of Transportation has
asked U.S. airlines to create peanut-free zones. But why stop
there? Welcome to Air Shattuck where the cabin interiors are really
special. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The vote by the House of
Representatives to conduct an inquiry into possible impeachment was
historic because Bill Clinton joined the short list of presidents
so entailed. But the transparently political nature of this
undertaking was clearly evident in the hours of debate preceding
the vote and in the vote itself. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In the aftermath of his
daughter's death in the Oklahoma City bombings, Bud Welch wanted
nothing less of the killers than ``to see them fry.'' Had anyone
told him then that he would one day travel almost 2,000 miles to
meet the father and sister of one of the killers, to embrace them
and weep with them, Welch would have thought that person insane. By
STEPHANIE SALTER,
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ State Treasurer Matt Fong's
candidacy for the U.S. Senate seat currently held by Barbara Boxer
is one indicator of the growing desire of Asian Americans for
national political power. Another is a quixotic movement launched
last month by a high-profile group of Chinese Americans. By WILLIAM
WONG.
</P>
