<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN MELBOURNE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SUSAN GOUGH HENLY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Forged with gold-rush money at the height of the Victorian era,
Melbourne is graced with grand public buildings, tree-lined
boulevards and decorous parks. While it may be the most British of
Australian cities, it also has one of the world's largest Greek
cities, a sizable Vietnamese quarter, neighborhood markets that
rival those in Paris, and a palm-fringed waterfront akin to Venice
Beach, Calif. Decades ago, Italian immigrants brought espresso to
its cafes. Today its restaurants are sophisticated and multiethnic,
drawing from the rich surrounding farmlands, vineyards and coastal
waters.
 &HT;    Trams still rattle along the middle of streets on the way to
distinctive neighborhoods that ring the city center:
fashion-conscious South Yarra, funky St. Kilda by the bay, the
terrace houses of Albert Park, retro Fitzroy and the bargain
shopping haven of Richmond, to name a few.
 &HT;    The people here are generally easygoing, but when it comes to
sports _ be it Aussie Rules football, the Melbourne Cup horse race,
the Australian Grand Prix auto race or the Australian Open tennis
tournament _ they display a rare fanaticism. Long before Sydney,
Melbourne was the first Australian city to host the Olympic Games
in 1956.
 &HT;    Melbourne's theater and live music scenes are among the most
vibrant in the country, and the National Gallery of Victoria has
one of the strongest art collections in the Southern Hemisphere.
With the Australian dollar near its 12-year low, this is an ideal
time for Americans to visit.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    The 13th Melbourne Festival, Oct. 15 to Nov. 1, is a celebration
of international and Australian performing and visual arts and free
street festivals, with this year's themes focusing on the family,
migration and indigenous culture. Highlights include ``Paintings
from Utopia'' by the Aboriginal artist Emily Kame Kngwarreye at the
National Gallery of Victoria, Sept. 8 to Nov. 22, and the
French-Albanian company Ballet Preljocaj's erotic ``Romeo and
Juliet'' set in a police state, Oct. 29 to Nov. 1.
 &HT;    Oz Opera and Company B Belvoir presents its remake of Leonard
Bernstein's ``Trouble in Tahiti'' Oct. 22 to 25, and performances
of the Abbey Theatre of Dublin's ``Secret Fall of Constance Wilde''
are Oct. 28 to Nov. 1. ``Teatro,'' Oct. 21 to 24, by the Italo-,
Greek- and Hispanic-Australian IRAA Theater and Canto Coro,
explores the stories of people living far from their countries of
birth searching for a home that does not exist. Tickets:
Ticketmaster, (61-3) 9256-8800.
 &HT;    The Victoria Racing Club's Spring Racing Carnival at Flemington
Racecourse, Oct. 31 to Nov. 7, is Australia's biggest annual
international sporting event, the culmination of which is the
Foster's Melbourne Cup.
 &HT;    More than a horse race, it is a 138-year-old tradition that
brings the nation to a stop (this year at 3:20 p.m. on Nov. 3) and
is full of all the pomp and fashion of its British counterparts.
Tickets, $48 reserved seating in lawn stand, $15 general admission
(based on $1.56 Australian to the United States dollar), through
Ticketmaster at www.ticketmaster.com.au.
 &HT;    Wine Australia, Oct. 22 to 27 at the Melbourne Convention and
Exhibition Center, offers a chance to sample more than 8,000 wines
from 350 Australian wineries, representing 42 Australian winemaking
regions. Visitors can meet the winemakers and match the wines with
the country's diverse cuisines. Tickets are $16 a day. Information:
(61-8) 8364-1122.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    Melbourne's city center encompasses a wide range of architecture
and shopping. For each of its major east-west streets there is a
bustling lane in between worth exploring. Stop by the 19th-century
Old Treasury Building, State Houses of Parliament, and the
elaborate Princess Theater on Spring Street and wander into the
nearby Fitzroy Gardens.
 &HT;    Collins Street offers the ultra-chic George's Department Store
(No. 162), the ornate old-world Block's shopping arcade (No. 282)
and a world of diversity in between. Slip into Flinders Lane for
the galleries; several specialize in Aboriginal art. Little Bourke
Street is in the heart of the city's Chinatown. Free city-circle
trams (painted burgundy and gold) run every 10 minutes and pass
many of the major sights, taking about 40 minutes to make the
circuit.
 &HT;    With almost 1,000 merchants in a series of landmark buildings at
the corner of Elizabeth and Victoria streets, the Queen Victoria
Market is a multicultural food mecca and a good place to pick up
picnic fare. Trading hours are Tuesday and Thursday 6 a.m. to 2
p.m., Friday 6 a.m. to 6 p.m., Saturday 6 a.m. to 3 p.m., Sunday 9
a.m. to 4 p.m. Two-hour tours ($9.60 or $11.50) are offered
Tuesday, Thursday, Friday and Saturday mornings. Bookings are
essential: (61-3) 9320-5822.
 &HT;    Several boat companies offer excursions on the Yarra River,
which winds through the heart of Melbourne. Southgate River Tours,
(61-3) 9682-5711, takes up to 12 passengers (every hour from 11
a.m.; $9) up to Herring Island sculpture park in a spit 'n polish
1918 steamboat. The sleek white Spirit of Melbourne, (61-3)
9696-0311, offers lunch ($29, departing 1 p.m.) and dinner cruises
($42, 7:30 p.m.). Both boats leave from Southgate and reservations
are essential.
 &HT;    Melbourne's tranquil Royal Botanic Gardens, bordering the Yarra
on Alexandra Avenue, offer a diverse selection of native and
imported plants. Highlights include the rain forest walk, the
eucalypts and the fern gully (where you may hear flying foxes
making a racket in the trees). A delightful teahouse sits beside
one of the lakes. Free tours depart from the National Herbarium (F
Gate) at 11 a.m. and 2 p.m. Sunday to Friday; (61-3) 9252-2300.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Sleek, hip and minimalist, the Adelphi Hotel, 187 Flinders Lane,
(61-3) 9650-7555, fax (61-3) 9650-2710, offers 34 Japanese-inspired
rooms with large stainless steel and glass bathrooms. There is a
rooftop lap pool. Double rooms start at $147, including a
Continental breakfast.
 &HT;    Across the architectural spectrum, the Tilba Hotel, on the
corner of Toorak Road West and Domain Street, South Yarra, (61-3)
9867-8844, fax (61-3) 9867-6567, is an Edwardian gem, with 18 rooms
and suites, all with private bath and individually decorated in
period furniture. Doubles: $90 to $125, including Continental
breakfast. The front parlor has chess and backgammon and a cozy
fire in cool weather.
 &HT;    Budget: The Avoca Bed and Breakfast, 98 Victoria Avenue, (61-3)
9696-9090, fax (61-3) 9696-9092, is one of a row of double-story
Victorian terrace houses in the delightful inner-city suburb of
Albert Park. Guests stay in one of three charming rooms ($80 to
$87), all with private bath and decorated in Laura Ashley-style
prints, and indulge in full cooked breakfasts.
 &HT;    The Olembia Hotel, a restored 23-room Edwardian guesthouse at 96
Barkly Street, in beachside St. Kilda, (61-3) 9537-1412, fax (61-3)
9537-1600, is one of the best bargains around if you don't mind
sharing one of the black-and-white tiled bathrooms. Guests can
enjoy the pleasant living areas and also cook their own meals in
the kitchen. The small, very clean rooms are $22 single, $32
double.
 &HT;    Luxury: The current hot hotel is the Hotel Como at 630 Chapel
Street, South Yarra, (61-3) 9824-0400, fax (61-3) 9824-1263, with
an eclectic upscale clientele of tennis stars, rock bands and
fashion and business elite. There are 107 studio rooms and suites,
all done in beige and light wood, some with whirlpool baths and
office facilities. A studio room is $308, open-plan suite $340.
 &HT;    Built in 1883, the Windsor Hotel, at 103 Spring Street across
from Parliament House, (61-3) 9633-6000, fax (61-3) 9633-6001, is
the only grand hotel of the Victorian era remaining in Australia.
Painstakingly restored, the hotel offers 180 rooms and suites with
overstuffed armchairs, 12-foot ceilings, cream marble bathrooms and
huge walk-in closets. Doubles start at $224.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    The restaurant of the moment, Circa, The Prince, 2 Acland
Street, St. Kilda, (61-3) 9536-1122, is dramatic with its designer
curtains, minimalist with its spare courtyard and large potted
olive trees.
 &HT;    The British chef, Michael Lambie, offers seared scallops with
potato salad and truffle oil before an entree such as bouillabaisse
with saffron potatoes and rouille, a garlicky sauce, and a
caramelized pear tarte tatin for dessert. Dinner for two with wine
is around $110. Currently serving lunch Friday and Sunday, dinner
Tuesday through Sunday; starting Oct. 5, lunch daily except
Saturday, dinner daily.
 &HT;    One of the latest additions to Melbourne's vibrant restaurant
scene is Langtons at 61 Flinders Lane, (61-3) 9663-0222, in a grand
basement space dominated by an open kitchen. The chef, Philippe
Mouchel, trained under Paul Bocuse. This is the place to see and be
seen. The food is classic with strong flavors delivered in delicate
portions.
 &HT;    Start with an orange- and cardamom-infused fish soup with
rouille and parmesan cheese followed by a duck medley ``pot au
feu,'' and, perhaps, a waffle served with chocolate ice cream and
chocolate sauce. Dinner for two with wine runs around $80. The
restaurant is open for lunch Monday to Friday and dinner Monday to
Saturday; the wine bar serves a more casual menu for the same meals
and is also open for breakfast Monday to Friday.
 &HT;    Guernica, 257 Brunswick Street, Fitzroy, (61-3) 9416-0969, looks
and feels like a Left Bank bistro, but its food is an exotic
melange of cultural influences that the restaurant calls modern
Australian.
 &HT;    It offers, for starters, drunken chicken with deep-fried Asian
cole slaw and chile mayonnaise followed by prosciutto- and
olive-basted lamb cutlets with spinach, caramelized garlic, field
mushrooms and goat cheese. Desserts might include a Jerusalem
artichoke and vanilla-bean creme brulee. Dinner for two with wine,
$70. Lunch daily except Saturday, dinner every night.
 &HT;    Toofey's, at 162 Elgin Street, in the inner-city Italian
neighborhood of Carlton, (61-3) 9347-9838, is arguably Melbourne's
finest seafood restaurant.
 &HT;    Stark and sleek, with amusing fish sculptures, Toofey's serves
nori rolls of prawn and garfish (a long, thin fish with delicate
white flesh), seafood risotto and the freshest fish of the day
cooked to perfection. Dinner for two with wine, about $75. Dinner
Tuesday through Sunday, lunch Tuesday through Friday.
 &HT;    Chinta Ria Soul, 94 Acland Street, St. Kilda, (61-3) 9525-4664,
is a Malaysian restaurant where dishes run from classic nasi
goreng, Malaysian fried bread, and spicy curries to Udang Ria,
succulent king prawns and vegetables in a cilantro, coconut and
lemon grass sauce. Dinner for two with wine, $40. Lunch and dinner
daily.
 &HT;    Bistro 1 Express Bar, 126 Little Collins Street, (61-3)
9654-3343, specializes in good, cheap bistro food like steak and
fries and pumpkin risotto in a cafe on one of the city's hip lanes.
Dinner for two with wine, $40. Serving breakfast, lunch and dinner
Monday to Friday, dinner on Saturday.
 &HT;     (Susan Gough Henly is a freelance writer who lives in
Melbourne.)  
