<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL SPRING: GIVING THE GOOD AND BAD OF TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Read a good guidebook lately?
 &HT;    Chances are that in the crowded and competitive field of travel
guidebook publishing, the book in question was the product of
either Frommer's or Fodor's, the giants in the field.
 &HT;    But it's no coincidence that their mutual success is in large
part due to one man, Michael Spring. The former editorial director
of Fodor's is the current publisher of Macmillan Travel and its
flagship imprint, Frommer's, which claims to be the fastest-growing
travel-guide series in the United States.
 &HT;    Reshaping the two biggest guidebook names in the United States
has made Spring something of an expert on what traveling readers
are looking for.
 &HT;    ``Readers want to feel special,'' Spring says. ``They want to
know about traditional sites but in a fresh way. They want to have
the special moments you usually don't find in guidebooks. It's fine
to tell people about the Louvre and the Eiffel Tower, but the
memories they come home with are private moments. Sitting on a
bench in St. James Park watching a game of bowls or walking along
the Seine at 6:30 in the morning and coming upon Notre Dame. The
real challenge is when you're doing a whole series of guides.''
 &HT;    Spring should know. Before coming to Macmillan in 1994, he spent
seven years as the editorial director of Fodor's Travel
Publications.
 &HT;    Spring's efforts to remake that guidebook series were widely
acclaimed in the industry. Now he's attempting to do the same thing
with Frommer's, offering guidebooks to an increasingly segmented
market.
 &HT;    ``There's no longer a single traveler,'' Spring says. ``There
are different series to satisfy the needs of different travelers.
Frommer's had a reputation for being geriatric, for being safe and
school-marmy. We've rewritten everything for today's more savvy and
curious traveler. We're taking people off the beaten track. There's
a lot of outdoor information, on things like bike trips and sea
kayaking. People want to come home with more than a tan.''
 &HT;    There are 17 distinct series under the Frommer's imprint.
There's ``Frommer's Complete Guides,'' comprehensive guides aimed
at both leisure and business travelers. ``Frommer's Portable
Guides'' are smaller and less-expensive guides for short-term
visitors. There's also ``Frommer's Irreverent Guides.''
 &HT;    ``You had student guides and guides for grownups but nothing for
savvy people in their 20s and 30s who hated guidebooks,'' Spring
says. ``These guides are unabashedly honest. They do knock
things.''
 &HT;    The ``Frommer's $-a-Day Guides'' are for value-oriented
travelers who want bang for their buck.
 &HT;    ``When Arthur Frommer started these guides in 1957 with `Europe
on $5 a Day,''' Spring says, ``his idea was not to travel cheaply
so much as to make travel a process of discovery, of getting inside
a culture. He just felt you could do it best on low budget.''
 &HT;    Arthur Frommer sold his interest in the series years ago, but
his name remains. Spring says that ``We're trying to put back that
sense of adventure and discovery in the books. So that you can have
adventure on whatever budget you have.''
 &HT;    Spring prides Frommer's on publishing exact prices and for
publishing annual editions, which few competitors do.
 &HT;    ``It takes almost a year to put together a guidebook and it's
out there for one year,'' Spring notes. ``That means that the
material is no more than two years out of date. In other guides,
the material is likely to be three or four years out of date. It's
enormously expensive to update, which is why many people only
publish a new edition every three or four years. The information is
incredibly perishable, but it's what people count on us most for.
We provide the details that let you have a worry-free vacation.''
 &HT;    Speaking of vacation, Spring had just returned from China, a
visit he said combined both work and play. His own sense of
adventure leads him to go on wilderness camping trips with his
family, to go dog sledding in Alaska or hiking with his kids at the
Arctic Circle.
 &HT;    He also has a fondness for trips he's done to Iceland, Tuscany,
Provence and Morocco, admitting that there are a lot of places he
hasn't been to yet _ places that he insists his writers live in
before they write about them.
 &HT;    And for anyone who has despaired of good, honest guidebook
writing, they should have a chat with Spring.
 &HT;    ``I love good writing,'' he says. ``I used to be an English
teacher. If someone says to me, `So what if a sentence has mixed
metaphors, it's just a travel guide,' I see purple. Travel writing
can be beautiful. And there's also the matter of honesty. Most
travel writing is the `What can I say that's nice variety.' It's
promotional. But if people want to be sold on destinations they can
get brochures. It's not our job to say nice things. We always
include the good and the bad.''
 &HT;    As for pundits who've predicted the demise of guidebooks because
of the advance of electronic media, Spring strongly disagrees.
 &HT;    ``They're not endangered by the Internet,'' Spring insists.
``When people travel, they want to have a book with them. But for
guidebooks to survive, they need to make people feel privileged.''
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Everett Potter  
