<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-13 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 IN MEETING McVEIGH'S FAMILY, A GRIEVING FATHER FINDS PEACE   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the aftermath of his daughter's death in the
Oklahoma City bombings, Bud Welch wanted nothing less of the
killers than ``to see them fry.'' Had anyone told him then that he
would one day travel almost 2,000 miles to meet the father and
sister of one of the convicted killers, to embrace them and weep
with them, Welch would have thought that person insane.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that is exactly what the 59-year-old Oklahoma City Texaco
station owner did last month. Moved by the pain he said he saw in
Bill McVeigh's face, Welch asked to visit the father of convicted
bomber Timothy McVeigh and McVeigh's 24 year-old sister, Jennifer.
He spent about 90 minutes with them, sitting at their kitchen table
in suburban Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got ready to leave, Jennifer hugged me and then she
just took to sobbing,'' Welch said by phone from Oklahoma City. ``I
put my hands on her cheeks and held her face and said, `Honey, the
three of us are in this together for the rest of our lives. We can
make the most of it if we choose. I don't want your brother to die,
and I'll do what I can to help.'''
</P>
<P>
   Welch's help is showing itself in an advocacy we rarely see from
people who have lost loved ones to violent crimes: He's become a
public opponent of McVeigh's death sentence and the death penalty
in general. So far the work has thrust him before lawyers,
religious groups and college students. He even debated a pro-death
penalty Catholic theologian for part of an Odyssey Channel series
at Notre Dame University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the third-oldest of eight kids, born about 35 miles from
Oklahoma City and raised on a dairy farm,'' Welch said. ``I've run
a service station for 34 years. High school is it for me. But all
of a sudden I got pitched into this public speaking. Hell, you're
not prepared. But I just stand up there and tell people my story.''
</P>
<P>
   That story is one of philosophical death and resurrection. A
Catholic, Welch spent his life talking a good game against capital
punishment. The death of his 23-year-old daughter, Julie Marie
Welch, shattered that tidy, intellectual perspective. A Spanish
translator for the Social Security Administration, Julie was one of
168 people killed in the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal
Building on April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud of her. I bragged on her all the time and it
embarrassed her. But she was such a wonderful kid; she had so much
to offer the world. The rescuers told me that if she'd have just
had another 2 or 3 seconds to get back to her office, she'd have
survived,'' Welch said.
</P>
<P>
   For several months after the bombing, all Welch wanted was to
see the people responsible for Julie's death pay with their own
lives. He was sorry there even had to be a trial: ``I was filled
with so much rage, revenge and hate. Once they were identified and
charged, all I thought was, `Fry 'em.' That was the insanity I went
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, one cold January day, he went to stand by an old American
elm tree that Julie used to try to park her car under on hot days.
Across a parking lot from the Murrah building, it is the only close
object that survived the blast. (Two clones have been grown from
the tree and countless seedlings given to other victims' families.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to think about how miserable I was,'' Welch said.
``I was smoking three packs of cigarettes a day and drinking too
much, and I didn't like myself. I wanted to know: After they
(McVeigh and Terry Nichols) were tried and executed, how was that
going to help me? I struggled with that question for two or three
weeks. And I finally realized, it ain't going to help at all. It
sure won't bring Julie Marie back. Revenge, hatred and rage _
that's why Julie Marie is dead today.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Welch got a call from a Catholic nun who does
prison ministry in Attica in New York. He told her he would like to
meet with Bill McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to tell him to his face that I care about what he's
going through,'' Welch said. ``I first saw him on television; he
was this plain, unassuming-looking man like myself. But I saw the
pain. Maybe it wasn't visible to others, but it was to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the nun put Welch in touch with people from
McVeigh's Catholic parish, and they set up a September meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked that nobody from the media know about it. I wanted it
to be a personal thing,'' Welch said. ``When we drove out there, I
was really hoping we wouldn't find the house. I was so nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Welch asked about McVeigh's garden (he'd been told there was
a substantial one behind the family's modest, frame house), and the
two men spent about a half-hour walking through it and talking
about farming. ``It was kind of common ground, you know?'' Welch
said. Then they went inside and sat at the kitchen table. On a
nearby wall was Timothy McVeigh's high school graduation picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `God, what a good-looking kid,' and this tear came
rolling out of Bill's right eye. I felt so bad for him,'' Welch
said. ``He's worked for General Motors for 36 years. He's just
another slug out there like I am, working for a living. He's six
months younger than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch said he cried for 20 miles as he drove back to town, then
``just bawled for an hour'' when he met up again with the people
who'd arranged the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Mass every week, but I'm not an overly-religious
person,'' he said. ``I'm not a born-again Christian _ I don't even
know what the hell that means. I've done some crap in my life. But
I've somehow felt closer to God than I ever have since I met with
Bill and Jennifer. It was the most satisfying thing I've done in my
life. It brought me so much peace, I can't tell you _ and I'd
recommend it for anybody who's been in a similar situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Except Welch knows most people who have had his experience don't
want his recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's eight or 10 families who are still so filled with
revenge, it's like, `You're not one of us anymore, Bud.' People
still think you can get closure or healing from revenge, but you
can't. I've had a really deep hole in my heart since Julie was
killed. A big chunk of me is just gone forever. But killing Tim
McVeigh isn't going to grow the chunk back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Notre Dame debate with the pro-death penalty theologian,
Welch said he asked the man the same question he asks of every
person who claims to be a Christian in favor of capital punishment:
``I just ask, `Would Jesus pull the switch?' Nobody can say yes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
