<HEADLINE>
THE ASIAN-AMERICAN POWER PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Treasurer Matt Fong's candidacy for
the U.S. Senate seat currently held by Barbara Boxer is one
indicator of the growing desire of Asian Americans for national
political power. Another is a quixotic movement launched in Foster
City last month by a high-profile group of Chinese Americans led by
former University of California at Berkeley Chancellor Chang-lin
Tien and former Delaware Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The movement calls itself the 80/20 Initiative because its lofty
goal is to channel 80 percent of the Chinese-American (and perhaps
Asian-American) vote and political contributions from California,
New York, and New Jersey to the next major party presidential
candidate who will commit to the group's demands. Those demands
include increasing significant policy-making appointments in the
current Democratic administration and, for the majority
congressional Republicans, holding hearings to investigate why
Asian Americans aren't better represented in federal policy-making
positions, as well as in the upper ranks of corporate and academic
life.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate and party that agree to support the 80/20
Initiative will get the Asian-American community's votes and
contributions, the group's leaders say. Otherwise, such support
will be withheld.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, leaders of the 80/20 Initiative want to break the
glass ceiling they say has kept Asian Americans from gaining a fair
share of national power.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 Chinese Americans from all over the country who convened
in the San Francisco area several weeks ago issued a manifesto and
raised more than $50,000 to hire staff to implement their idea,
which is both provocative and pie-in-the-sky. The initiative will
attempt to get grassroots support through e-mail petition and
information campaigns. Woo pointed out that a smaller-scale effort
10 years ago yielded some high-level appointments in the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the 80/20 Initiative, one must recall the history
of political disenfranchisement of the Asian-American population.
Until the end of World War II, most Asian Americans never had full
rights of U.S. citizenship. The population has risen to almost 4
percent of the U.S. population from less than 1 percent 30 years
ago. Asian Americans make up about 12 percent of California's 32
million people and more than a third of San Francisco's population.
</P>
<P>
   Many among the emerging Asian-American immigrant class are well
educated professionals who are perceived to be technically gifted
and economically astute, but not possessed of political leadership
skills. Tien, Woo and the other founders of 80/20 disagree with
that stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Asian Americans account for 3.5 percent of the U.S.
population, we represent less than 1 percent of the top
policy-making officials in the federal government and less than 1
percent of the federal judges,'' the group's statement said. ``Not
coincidentally, Asian Americans have only one-third the
opportunities of other Americans to rise to policy-making positions
in the corporate world, academia, and other private sectors. This
is in spite of the fact that the percentage of Asian Americans
having college degrees is twice the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognizing that Asian Americans are an important part of
America's social fabric and are a significant contributor to the
economy, we believe it is only proper that Asian Americans be able
to participate as equal members in all facets of American life,
including leadership roles in corporations, academia, and
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Tien said the goal is to first unite Chinese Americans, then try
to bring together other Asian Americans. ``As individual
communities, our voices have been ineffective in the political
arena. Together, we shall overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a Sisyphean task, given the disparate political,
economic, cultural, religious and historical perspectives of
Asian-American groups.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Wang, a San Franciscan and vice chairwoman of the
California Democratic Party _ who didn't attend the 80/20
Initiative meeting _ applauded the effort, but raised a caution
flag. ``It's wonderful they are raising the issue (of increasing
political power),'' she said. ``It's a great first step, but we
tend to get stuck on that bottom step.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
