<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE OUTRAGE, GOP MAY HAVE THE EDGE IN ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The vote by the House of Representatives to
conduct an inquiry into possible impeachment was historic because
Bill Clinton joined the short list of presidents so entailed. But
the transparently political nature of this undertaking was
self-evident in the hours of debate preceding the vote and in the
vote itself.
</P>
<P>
   Very much unlike the vote on President Richard Nixon in
Watergate, which was overwhelmingly bipartisan, the one against
Bill Clinton was mostly on party lines. All the Republicans voted
for their more encompassing investigation; all the Democrats, save
31, voted against it. Most Democrats voted for a more defined and
restricted version.
</P>
<P>
   These votes constitute a distinct public service. Now the nation
can deal with the ridiculous charges for consideration of
impeachment, drawn entirely from a consensual sexual relationship,
in the framework and the spirit in which they were contrived:
politics.
</P>
<P>
   More than by the pious lip service in the debate upholding
constitutional integrity in the face of popular preferences for
alternative resolution, this will be settled by how many seats the
Republicans pick up in the mid-term elections Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have used the impeachment discussions to energize
their core supporters, the hard right-wingers who despised Clinton
before Monica Lewinsky. The affair and efforts to cover it up
merely fueled already powerful passions that could not abide that
Clinton was elected despite their wishes twice in a row.
</P>
<P>
   As the elections will go, so will impeachment. If the
Republicans make gains of 10 to 20 in the House (depending on which
Republican politico's figures you accept), then the impeachment
process is expected to result in a House vote, again on strictly
party lines, in favor of articles for Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans do less well, then the possibilities of a
political compromise become more substantial, which means a deal
for some sort of censure or rebuke and the halting of the
impeachment express.
</P>
<P>
   In this political game, the Republicans have the edge going in.
First of all, non-presidential elections tend to produce lower
voter response. As there are more Democrats than Republicans in the
country as whole, that means fewer of Clinton's natural supporters
might show up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans enjoy a major advantage in the November election
because their committed supporters tend to actually show up at the
polls to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the party occupying the White House tends to lose
some seats at the mid-term. Democrats earlier had showed promise of
making gains, because of the low esteem in which the
Republican-controlled Congress was held. But that was before
Clinton's reckless behavior impaired those expectations.
</P>
<P>
   So the issue becomes pretty clear: If matters remain as they
are, the Republicans will gain possibly sufficient numbers to push
impeachment. If Democrats wish to forestall that result, they have
to get out their voters in numbers uncharacteristic for an off-year
poll.
</P>
<P>
   This would be hard, according to conventional wisdom, because
Clinton has disheartened and discouraged Democrats. On the other
hand, the blatant partisanship of the House in the Lewinsky matter
and the persistently overwhelming desire, expressed repeatedly by
the people at large, including nominal Republicans, to get this
mess behind us, provide possibilities for the Democrats to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   However, they have to get started. So far, there are few if any
signs that the Democrats are launching any noticeable efforts.
James Carville, the outspoken former Clinton White House staffer
and campaign director, loudly complained last week that the
Democratic Party in Congress and out is too decorous and diffident
with the Republicans in general and House Speaker Newt Gingrich in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Party worthies worry that the aggressively obnoxious Carville
will hamper the party's attempt to present itself as less partisan
than the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the next days will tell us the likely scenario
that will confront the nation regarding Clinton's fate. In the end,
as in the beginning, it will be a matter of party politics, shaped
by whoever winds up with the perceived mandate from November's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   While the hallowed cliche is that all politics is local, this
year local politics will be seen as turning on Clinton's
presidency. It is in the vicissitudes of political warfare, that
the profoundest implications for future presidencies will be
determined. Just as the Founders and Framers of this nation feared
might happen, impeachment has come down to the exercise of
political muscle to define what constitutes a ``high crime and
misdemeanor.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
