<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHARITY &QL; 
 &UR; Mark Richard (Doubleday, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   The best way to describe these stories is to say that William
Faulkner _ or Flannery O'Connor, or Carson McCullers, with her
affinity for the strange and the outcast _ would have read them and
smiled. Separately, (as they appeared in ``Esquire,'' ``The New
Yorker'' and other magazines), they are vignettes stolen from a
territory of otherworldly isolation. Published together, they take
on an air of macabre suspense, even when the mystery involves
nothing more than a hospitalized boy's Christmas wish to watch
Alfred Hitchcock's film ``The Birds,'' or a child's efforts to come
to terms with the anger of his impoverished father. This is dark
(and sometimes oddly humorous) terrain, yet Richard's characters
are good company and his style is as entertaining as it is ominous
and original. His previous books are ``Fishboy'' and ``The Ice at
the Bottom of the World,'' and he now writes for television's
``Party of Five.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WORK IN PROGRESS &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Eisner (Random House, $27.95)
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Michael Eisner was at a conference in Idaho with
the likes of Bill Gates, Warren Buffett and Tom Brokaw when he felt
pain in his arms and chest. When he got home, he drove from the
airport to a hospital, where he underwent coronary bypass surgery.
As he was being wheeled into the operating room, he gave orders to
his wife, Jane. He wanted to be buried above ground, not below. He
didn't want her to build the new house they'd been considering.
``And,'' he added, ``if it becomes an issue, I think that either
(Michael) Ovitz or (Barry) Diller would be good choices to succeed
me.'' Eisner, chief executive of the Walt Disney Co., had shifted
into his executive mode, he admits, even ``using the leverage of my
imminent surgery to win deathbed agreements from my wife.'' This
memoir is long (430 pages) and pictureless, but it's an interesting
look at Eisner's management style and at the drive and creativity
required to run Disney. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; DON'T KNOW MUCH ABOUT THE BIBLE &QL; 
 &UR; Kenneth C. Davis (Morrow, $25)
</P>
<P>
   The Bible, Davis writes, ``is hard to understand. It's
confusing. It's contradictory. It's boring. In other words, the
Bible perfectly fits Mark Twain's definition of a classic: `a book
which people praise and don't read.' '' Davis thought he had a
working knowledge of the Bible until he researched his previous
book, ``Don't Know Much About Geography,'' and posed a few
questions: Where was the Garden of Eden? What is the world's oldest
city? Did Moses really cross the Red Sea? In answering the last, he
found that Moses and the tribes of Israel never crossed the Red
Sea, but escaped across the Sea of Reeds, which might be one of
several Egyptian lakes or a marshy section of the Nile Delta. In
other words, if he'd been interested in authenticity, C.B. DeMille
would have sent Charlton Heston out across a soggy bog. Among the
questions Davis answers here: What's a ``testament''? Where did
Cain's wife come from? Did Delilah snip more than just hair? Who
really killed Goliath? What happened to Jonah's whale? Davis' other
books are ``Don't Know Much About History'' and ``Don't Know Much
About the Civil War.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE HYPOCHONDRIAC'S GUIDE TO LIFE. AND DEATH &QL; 
 &UR; Gene Weingarten (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $22)
</P>
<P>
   ``Symptom: headache with pain on chewing. Possible diagnosis:
giant cellarteritis. Look for: scalp tenderness. Prognosis: Can
cause blindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symptom: headache with nasal congestion. Possible diagnosis:
primary amebicmeningoencephalitis, spread by polluted water. Look
for: vomiting. Prognosis: quickly fatal _ in all medical history,
only two people have survived it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've dropped this newspaper and are sprinting to your
doctor's office, Weingarten thinks there's still hope for you. If
you're reading this  &UR; in &LR;  your doctor's office, the outlook for
recovery is grim. There is, in fact, only one known cure for
hypochondria: You must contract a life-threatening disease. That's
what Weingarten did in 1991 (we won't spoil the end of his book by
saying more), and his hypochondria disappeared, perhaps because
suddenly he had other things to think about. He may be writing from
memory, but he's no slouch _ this is a funny book, with chapters
such as ``Hiccups Can Mean Cancer,'' ``How Your Doctor Can Kill
You'' and ``Things That Can Take Out An Eye.'' A writer for the
``Washington Post,'' he invites comparison with Dave Barry, who
contributed an introduction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEBDOCTOR &QL; 
 &UR; Vicki F. Sharp and Richard M. Sharp (St. Martin's, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   And here, for you who sit jittery in your doctors' offices, is a
hypochondriac's dream. The Sharps have assembled more than 500
pages of what they consider to be the 1,300 best health-care Web
sites available on the Internet today. They are separated into
categories, so it's easier to find sites devoted to children's
care, mental health, sexuality and fertility, aging and long-term
care, insurance and managed care, plastic surgery, dental care,
diseases and conditions, and many other subjects. Each listing
includes a picture of the Web page and a very brief description _
the authors obviously assume you would rather find the details on
your computer. The book includes a CD with links to all the sites. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
