<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-TRINITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ITS IRISH CLICHES, `TRINITY' HAS PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There's the Irish cop and the Irish priest and
the Irish union mobster and the Irish substance abuser. The bar
they all hang out at is called ``Murphy's.'' The family is the size
of a small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinity'' has more cliches than a Harlequin romance novel. The
funny thing about cliches and stereotypes is, they are sometimes
true.
</P>
<P>
   And among the myriad shows riddled with stereotypes, there are
good ones like ``Trinity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I met about 20 Irish cops and their fathers were cops and
their uncles were cops,'' said Justin Louis, who plays Detective
Bobby McCallister of the NYPD and Clan McCallister. ``I don't see
the stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust us, Justin, they are there. But luckily, the acting and
directing rise above these stereotypes, making ``Trinity'' a
compelling one-hour drama.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is banking heavily on ``Trinity,'' a show from executive
producer John Wells (``ER,'' ``China Beach''), especially since it
is sandwiched between ratings favorite ``Dateline'' and the
critically acclaimed ``Homicide: Life on the Street.'' If you have
seen 30 seconds or more of any NBC show or ballgame in the past few
weeks, odds are you've caught a ``Trinity'' commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Based in New York City's Hells Kitchen, ``Trinity'' (premiering
Friday at 9 p.m. Eastern, check local listings ) focuses on the
individual lives of a diverse McCallister family who still gather
every Sunday at mom and dad's for dinner. The makers promise the
same character twists seen on ``ER,'' where stable characters can
make dumb choices and the miscreants can turn out to be the wise
ones.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great season to be Irish on television. In addition to
``Trinity,'' several other shows built around Irish-American
families will be featured, most notably the one-hour ``To Have &AMP; To
Hold'' on CBS and the sitcom ``Costello'' (yes, it's Irish) on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, CBS will present the mid-season ``Turks,'' the
story of an Irish cop family starring William Devane, who based his
character in part on a relative who served in the Albany Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   What these shows, especially the dramas, have in common besides
ethnicity is a focus on the family rather than the workplace. Wells
said the dynamics of a family especially an Irish-American family
can provide as much drama as, say, a fictional Chicago emergency
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irish families, because of the influence of the church, and a
history and a heritage which requires that you remain close to your
family, is a good place to sort of examine that tension,'' the
producer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Louis, Tate Donovan (last seen in a recurring
role on ``Friends'') stars as the Rev. Kevin McCallister. Both
Donovan and Wells said they don't expect the role to create the
same maelstrom that surrounded the fine but doomed ABC priest show
of last season, ``Nothing Sacred.'' But in the first episode Father
McCallister is presented with a pair of ethical/religious dilemmas
that may make some conservative Catholics queasy.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Clayburgh (``An Unmarried Woman'' and many other films) is
a late addition to the ensemble cast as matriarch Eileen
McCallister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is essentially the family, about how five individual
people living their own lives somehow connect by blood,'' Louis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trinity,'' if true to its initial promise, should connect with
viewers. And they won't even have to be Irish.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
