<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, Oct. 14, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-INSURANCE (Seattle) Teri Lafnitzegger, a 37-year-old
mother of two, was recently diagnosed with a brain tumor and told
by her Group Health doctor that her only chance was a unique
neurosurgical procedure offered by Duke University. She was
referred by her doctor and supposed to get the $100,000 surgery
this week, when Group Health at the last minute refused to cover it
as ``experimental.'' Her doctors at Duke say Group Health is
technically right, but wrong to deny coverage. Most insurers are
paying for this, they say, because it's the only chance for such
tumors. Some patients given months to live have survived for years.
``The clock is ticking on this woman,'' said Dr. Henry Friedman of
Duke. ``What's the problem with this insurance company?'' The Duke
procedure has good data and may be saving lives. PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN (Seattle) Whenever a clerk asks to see my
driver's license, I say: ``OK, but only if you promise not to laugh
at the picture!'' This of course predisposes them to do just that.
Some start giggling even before I reach into my wallet for the
license. Or, they smile when they see the typical police lineup
photo. And they condescendingly say something like: ``Oh, that's
not so bad!''
</P>
<P>
   By Jon Hahn. (story will move in the ``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CORPUS-CHRISTI (New York) Opening of new Terrence McNally
play, ``Corpus Christi,'' which has raised the ire of the Catholic
League because of the gay Christ-like character. Tracks his journey
from Texas to Jerusalem. Play is described as a contemporary
exploration of good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   By Jeffrey Eric Jenkins. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
