<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-INSURANCE-SPI &LR;      10-13 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-INSURANCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN DENIED BEST HOPE FOR TUMOR BY INSURANCE CO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A Kitsap County, Wash., woman suffering from a
fast-growing and highly lethal brain tumor has been denied
insurance coverage for a procedure she believes offers her the only
chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Lafnitzegger, a 37-year-old wife and mother of two in
Olalla, wants Group Health Cooperative to pay for a unique
neurosurgical procedure available only at Duke University Medical
Center in Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Lafnitzegger has glioblastoma, an almost invariably fatal brain
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I have nine months,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking on this woman,'' said Dr. Henry Friedman,
a surgeon at Duke who performs the procedure involving radioactive
antibodies. Surgery for Lafnitzegger had been scheduled for
yesterday, but the operation was canceled when Group Health
officials said they would not pay the $100,000 cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug they use is not FDA-approved . . . and there's not
much published literature on this,'' said Dr. Hugh Straley, an
administrator and oncologist at Group Health in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman truly believes he has the best approach to treating
glioblastomas, Straley said, but the opinion of one doctor or even
one medical center isn't proof enough. Lafnitzegger can appeal the
decision, he said, and because of the medical urgency that appeal
will be expedited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do it in a matter of days,'' Straley said.
</P>
<P>
   The broader question, he said, has to do with who should pay for
unproven therapies.
</P>
<P>
   For Lafnitzegger, the answer is simple. ``It's the only chance I
have,'' she said. ``Even if all they can do is help me live another
year, that's reason enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Lafnitzegger, who with her husband, Eric, has two boys, ages 4
and 6, has perhaps the most aggressive and deadliest of brain
tumors, known as glioblastoma multiforme. She's had brain surgery
to remove some of the tumor and external beam radiation therapy,
but the cancer persists.
</P>
<P>
   When it appeared that there was little more to be done for her
at Group Health, she and her doctor began exploring the unique
neurosurgical procedure at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Lafnitzegger said her physician at Group Health Cooperative in
Tacoma ordered the tests required by Duke's Comprehensive Cancer
Center and her oncologist agreed to refer her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they had to cancel the surgery because Group Health
was refusing to pay,'' Lafnitzegger said. She was stunned, scared
and angry. The cooperative called Duke to cancel the surgery but
didn't call her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Straley said Lafnitzegger was not referred to Duke. Her
physician only agreed to explore this option, Straley said, which
was somehow misconstrued by Duke as a referral and authorization
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of many investigational therapies,'' he said. It
would be irresponsible for Group Health to authorize coverage for
an unproven treatment based on one patient's or one doctor's
assessment, he said. Straley said standard procedure calls for
chemotherapy following surgery and radiation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits that survival rates for patients who receive
standard care is terrible. ``Most patients die of this in 18
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said Group Health's refusal is a knee-jerk response
insurers use when asked to pay for any new therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer they stall, the more likely it is she won't be a
candidate,'' he said. ``The clock favors the insurance company. . .
. She may not have weeks . . . They know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman thinks he can give Lafnitzegger more time, perhaps a
lot more.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina cancer specialists employ a new twist on a
standard approach to treating this form of brain tumor using
radioactive antibodies to target and kill cancer cells. It's
investigational, Friedman acknowledged, but patients are already
surviving much longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patients appear to be beating the odds,'' Friedman said.
One of his first patients was given a year to live _ nearly five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be five years on Dec. 9,'' said Susan Feinglos,
director of the medical library at Duke. She had a relatively large
tumor in her right frontal lobe and was told by her physician
husband not to read the medical literature on glioblastoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one lived,'' Feinglos said. ``It was pretty gloomy.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't claim to be cured, but Feinglos has so far shown no
signs of recurrent cancer. Not all of the patients at Duke do so
well. Many die anyway, but Friedman contended it's worth the
estimated $100,000 even if all they can do is give someone like
Lafnitzegger a year or two longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see my youngest son enter kindergarten,''
Lafnitzegger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke therapy is an improvement on standard therapy, Friedman
said, but he contended it doesn't increase the cost of treating
glioblastoma because they don't charge for the experimental
antibody.
</P>
<P>
   In the procedure, surgeons go in and remove as much of the tumor
as possible. Into the surgically created ``crater'' in the brain,
doctors place a tube. After the crater is tested for leaks using
tracer isotopes, a chamber containing a cancer-killing liquid
iodine solution is connected to the tube.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid contains monoclonal antibodies that have been
manufactured to target specific tumor proteins and that carry
radioactive iodine-131.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use liquid iodine because we figured we'd get a more
homogeneous distribution and less radiation damage to healthy
tissue,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published last June in the Journal of Clinical
Oncology, the Duke team, led by Dr. Darell Bigner, reported on the
increased survival time among patients with glioblastoma treated in
this fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, who works with Bigner, noted that many private
insurers helped pay for the patients in that study. As examples, he
cited Blue Cross and Blue Shield plans, Aetna, Prudential, Cigna,
Travelers and even state Medicaid programs in New York and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a disease is terminal and the patient has no other choice,
many insurers cover it,'' Friedman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
