<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUGGED BY YOUR MUG? LET'S TALK ABOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Whenever a clerk asks to see my driver's license, I
say: ``OK, but only if you promise (begin italics) not (end
italics) to laugh at the picture!''
</P>
<P>
   This of course predisposes them to do just that. Some start
giggling even before I reach into my wallet for the license. Or,
they smile when they see the typical police lineup photo. And they
condescendingly say something like: ``Oh, (begin italics) that's
(end italics) not so bad!''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes they even volunteer: ``You oughta see mine!'' Of
course, very few ever reach into their own wallet or purse to
display their own version of what the Department of Licensing
thinks is a reasonable likeness.
</P>
<P>
   We are, to a person, locked inside our own person. Despite all
the wonders of plastic or corrective surgery, collagen injections,
miracle creams, dietary supplements, artificial tanning and
expensive cosmetics, we are the same guy or gal we came in with.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, we're the spitting image of our parents. I'm not,
which has from the start occasioned whispered conversations about
what our mother might've been doing while my father was out on the
road as a traveling salesman . . . a quirky twist on a standard
joke format.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do I look anything like my twin sister _ something for
which she should be eternally grateful. In fact, although she has
hair on top of her head, neither of us looks anything like our two
older siblings. But the whispers have died down by now and there's
no sense going there.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us, for a variety of mostly vain reasons, affect the
Very Northwest hirsute countenance. And as the ``Wanted'' photo at
the top of this column vividly shows, a beard and/or mustache
cannot truly hide nor much enhance what our genes set in place.
</P>
<P>
   I have, on occasion, come clean by clearcutting the beard and
mustache. And on some of those occasions, the editors bothered to
have the column photo reshot. My late mother, never one to mince
words, saw one of those clean-shaven column photos and told me in
our next telephone conversation: ``You know, you never were a very
handsome guy. I think you should grow it all back.''
</P>
<P>
   She should've lived long enough to read the latest news release
about a University of Louisville plastic surgery researcher who
predicts that complete face transplants might be possible within a
few months.
</P>
<P>
   That gives a whole new meaning, a really scary context to the
driver's license section that declares ``organ donor.'' You don't
get to see someone's liver or kidneys or heart or whatever part you
might be hoping for _ and that's just as well, perhaps. But with
the possibility of complete facial transplants, what you see on the
driver's license photo is what you get.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it . . . do you know (begin italics) anyone (end
italics) whose countenance you might want, based on their driver's
license photo?
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the movie ``Face/Off,'' you knew it was already
possible. I'm not sure what their mothers would've thought, but
then, Nicolas Cage and John Travolta already had their faces
merchandised into millions. And as we movie viewers get older, it's
comforting to see Travolta's face, in particular, become rounder .
. . just like our own.
</P>
<P>
   And Cage's nose seems larger . . . just as my own.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year everyone toys with the idea of renting
or buying a particularly eye-catching (so-to-speak) Halloween mask.
I haven't taken the time to research whether there are any Bill
Clinton ``What, Me Worry?'' masks. Or any Monica Whatzername masks.
And if I were going out to a Halloween party in a Ken Starr mask, I
think I'd wear a Kevlar vest under my cloak and let someone else
start my car.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to belittle the legitimate and downright
wonderful facial reconstruction surgeries done for accident, birth
defect or disease victims. But I think we make too much out of how
we look. We are too quick to assess the book by its cover, even if
it's what we see in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, I used to stand in front of the bathroom mirror
and contort my face into grotesque masks. And that same mother used
to warn: ``If you keep doing that, someday it's going to stay that
way!''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just hate it when it turns out they were right?
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
