<SLUG> BC-COLON-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULAR TESTING SEEN AS CRUCIAL IN BATTLE AGAINST COLON CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Most Americans are unaware that colorectal
cancers are the second leading cause of cancer death and will kill
an estimated 56,500 people this year.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Katie Couric, the co-anchor of the ``Today'' show,
lost her husband, NBC legal commentator Jay Monahan, to colon
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are optimistic that Darryl Strawberry, the Yankee
outfielder, will recover from the disease after surgeons removed a
cancerous tumor from his colon earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they catch it early enough, they can do something about
it,'' said Richard Cartwright of Chatham, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright, 68, considers himself fortunate. A decade ago, he
got a fecal occult blood test, recommended for everyone over 50 on
an annual basis. That test detected something amiss and prompted
doctors to look closer at Cartwright's colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did indeed find a polyp that had cancer cells on it but
had not spread,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery to remove the problem polyp, Cartwright has been
careful about getting screened on a regular basis, especially
because his father also had a history of colon problems.
</P>
<P>
   While physicians recommend that healthy patients with no family
history of colon cancer get a flexible sigmoidoscopy every five
years and a colonoscopy every 10 years, Cartwright has been
following a more rigorous screening schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Every two years, he gets a colonoscopy, a procedure that allows
doctors to examine the inside of the colon with a long, flexible
fiber optic instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Cartwright's vigilance paid off when doctors
found a larger tumor. Though it turned out not to be cancerous,
Cartwright had to have an operation to remove part of his large
intestine.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright has since been able to return to work as a strategic
planner. Today, he feels fine and reminds all of his friends and
relatives to get checked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the least-publicized cancers,'' he said. ``People
don't like talking about that part of their anatomy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what causes colon cancer and there are no clear,
early warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   That underscores why regular screening is so important for men
and women age 50 and older and in younger people with a family
history of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe there may be some genetic predisposition to
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   But most colon cancers can't be linked to genes. Instead,
researchers believe our country's high-fat, low-fiber diet is to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society recommends that people who want to
lower their risk of colon cancer eat more vegetables, fruits and
grains, and limit their consumption of fats and red meat.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright is doing just that. ``Butter is off the table,'' he
said. He is also taking other steps to improve his overall health.
A decade ago, about the time he was first diagnosed with a colon
problem, he quit smoking, breaking a 40-year addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he's developed another habit to stay ahead of colon
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get screened every couple of years,'' he said. ``I
plan to keep doing it as long as I'm on the planet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
