<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE _ JERUSALEM _ At best, the summit between Israeli
and Palestinian leaders starting tomorrow in Maryland, will just be
one step on the long road toward bringing hope to disheartened
Israelis and Palestinians. But, it would be a necessary step before
bigger issues than the land in question can be resolved and a
crisis brewing for next May can be avoided. If the requisite
trappings of summits do materialize _ agreements signed, handshakes
photographed you can expect right wing Israelis to try to topple
the government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and hard-line
Palestinians to try to block progress with terrorist actions.
Having been burned so many times when hoped seemed just around the
corner, people on both sides won't believe peace progress until
they see it. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO _ WASHINGTON _ (DEVELOPING) An 11th-hour deal the
United States brokered with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to avert near-term NATO air strikes and stop the bloodshed in
Kosovo has also put the Serbian province on track for talks leading
to autonomy. The breakthrough, announced Monday night by President
Clinton, came after NATO authorized airstrikes if Milosevic didn't
match his promises with action. Clinton said NATO had agreed to
hold off on airstrikes for four days so international inspectors
could verify that Milosevic has met U.N. Security Council demands
to stop the violence. But U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke said, ``We
hope this will mark a turning point in the right direction. But the
proof ... is in compliance with U.N. resolution 1199 and with
actions on the ground in Kosovo.'' (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS _ ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ How is the
Clinton-Lewinsky scandal playing in the fall races? In Rep. Bob
Etheridge's district, his Republican opponent ran ads accusing him
of having ``Clinton values,'' but recently has been focusing on
more traditional issues. That seems to reflect a national trend in
whcih both parties are content to let the scandal simmer in the
background. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VICTORY _ WASHINGTON _ Some analysts argue that any
Republican gain is a mandate for impeachment, while others say that
if House Democrats do better than lose 29 seats _ the average this
century for an incumbent party's sixth year in the White House _
censure negotiations are likely. What result would be seen as a
victory for President Clinton? (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JONES _ WASHINGTON _ Come Monday, will scandal
aficionados be using the Internet to examine thousands of pages of
potentially embarrassing transcripts from Paula Jones's sexual
harassment lawsuit against President Clinton? The federal judge in
the Arkansas case plans to start releasing evidence that day in the
case, which has been dismissed but is under appeal. Many observers
bet that a settlement will be reached by then, because both sides
have strong incentives to do so. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TECH-GENDER _ WASHINGTON _ A major new gender gap in technology
has developed in American schools, the American Association of
University Women reported today. ``While boys program and
problem-solve with computers, girls use computers for word
processing, the 1990s version of typing,'' said AAUW Executive
Director Janice Weinman. The report said the gap was developing
even as girls close previous gender gaps in math and science
achievement. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
