<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE DOOMED BY A BAGUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every country has its superstitions. So if you don't want your
vacation to be cursed (or have the locals curse you), avoid these
practices, reported by Travel Holiday:
</P>
<P>
   _In France, putting a baguette on a restaurant table with the
flat side up is a sign of doom.
</P>
<P>
   _In Japan, the numbers 4 and 9 are unlucky. Buildings often
don't have floors labeled fourth or ninth, and residents may even
avoid the numbers in conversation. Why? Because the Japanese words
for them sound a lot like their words for ``death'' and ``pain.''
</P>
<P>
   _In Sweden, putting keys on a table is considered bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   _In Russia, shaking hands in a doorway is a no-no. So is
whistling inside a building _ that means you're about to lose
money.
</P>
<P>
   _Ah, but there are good luck practices, too. In Thailand,
sighting the occasional elephant in Bangkok traffic is a positive
sign. Even better, for a small fee you can walk under its belly.
And, the magazine says, if you're a pregnant woman who does so,
that's bonus luck!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  What is the second-largest French-speaking city in
the world? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  The word ``meander'' comes from the Meander River in
Turkey. You would not be surprised to learn that the river
meanders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``Auckland _ last, loneliest, loveliest, exquisite,
apart.'' _ Rudyard Kipling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Good duck, er, luck: &LR;  This could be the month that Boston Duck
Tours gets its millionth passenger, but no one knows for sure _ not
even owner Andrew Wilson. The lucky duck will receive a $500
shopping spree at The Shops at Prudential, free tickets for the
land-and-sea duck tours, and a boatload of ducky merchandise. But
that's hardly all: 1 million pennies will be given in the
passenger's name for his-or-her favorite not-for-profit charity.
(Fortunately, the charity will get a check for $10,000, not the
coins.) Duck Tours operate through Nov. 29; for more information,
call 617-723-DUCK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  Sign in a Tokyo shop: ``Our
nylons cost more than common, but you'll find they are the best in
the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Kiddie business: &LR;  By choice or necessity, more business people are
taking along their children when they travel. So Inter-Continental
Hotels and Resorts has launched ``Kids in Tow,'' a program that
gives youngsters 17 and under a free stay in their parent's guest
room, special meals, complimentary family films, and a lot of other
junior amenities, including treats packed inside a colorful
take-home backpack. For more information, or to get a guidebook of
activities for children and parents in the cities where
Inter-Continental has a hotel, call 800-615-6085 or visit
www.interconti.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Tired travel joke: &LR;  Why do bagpipers march when they play? They're
trying to get away from the noise. (With thanks to the NZ News &AMP;
Features newsletter.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Hurry, hurry: &LR;  You may have read or heard that all hotels in or
near Disney World are sold out for New Year's Eve 1999, but that's
not so. For instance, there is still space at the wonderfully
whimsical Walt Disney World Swan and Dolphin resort, although rooms
are going fast. For more information, call 800-227-1500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag: &LR;  To our discussion of the origin of hamburgers and
frankfurters, Eric Rudd of Falmouth, Mass. adds the wiener, which
is short for wienerwurst, which means Vienna sausage. The
dictionary defines a wiener as a frankfurter, so why names that
honor Frankfurt and Vienna? Here's the answer, according to the
Associated Press: Johann Lahner, the German butcher who concocted
the delicacy, learned his trade in Frankfurt before moving to
Vienna and opening a butcher shop in 1804. A year later, both
cities lent their names to his invention. The name ``hot dog'' and
the bun were American creations, though.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Montreal is the second-largest French-speaking
city in the world. (Paris is first.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
