<HEADLINE>
MONET MAKES AN IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claude Monet has been hailed as one of the supreme landscape
painters of the 19th century. Now through Dec. 27, a monumental
exhibit of works from his later years is on view at the Boston
Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   This spectacular exhibition brings together the late work of the
founder of Impressionism, between 1900 and his death in 1926. Monet
produced an astonishing and innovative body of work that represents
the height of his engagement with color and light. Highlights of
the exhibit include triumphant views of his garden at Giverny, and
a startling re-creation of a water lily exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which is being shown only in Boston, has 80
paintings by Monet, including five monumental Water-Lily panels,
the largest more than 18 feet long. ``Monet in the 20th Century''
displays paintings collected from six countries, including 10
paintings never before exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   Adult admission for the daily showing is $15 weekdays, $17.50
weekends; audio tour admission for adults is $19 weekdays, $21.50
weekends. There are lower prices for students and senior citizens;
children 5-17 are $5 at all times. For information and to charge
tickets, call 617-542-4MFA. For general information, call
617-267-9300. The museum has 38 Monet paintings in its permanent
collection.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to see the exhibit is to obtain a hotel
package that includes tickets good for admission at any time. For
information on 18 hotel packages, call the Greater Boston
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at 888-SEE BOSTON (733-2678).
Information is also available on special Amtrak fares.
</P>
<P>
   Among hotels offering weekend packages with two VIP tickets to
the exhibit are the Swissotel (800-621-9200) at $199, including
breakfast; and The Four Seasons Hotel, Boston (617-338-4400),
beginning at $585, which also includes town car service to the
museum, an exhibit catalog, and an in-room treat.
</P>
<P>
   Monet lovers will not want to miss the dinners offered at the
Hotel Meridien inspired by the cooking journals of Monet. The
five-course meals prepared by executive chef Mark Sapienza feature
recipes from Monet's journals, with each course expertly paired
with Champagne Veuve Clicquot (Monet's favorite) and Bouchard Pere
&AMP; Fils wines. During dinner, a Museum of Fine Arts lecturer will
provide an informal talk. The dinners will be offered Oct. 15, 22,
29, and Nov. 5 and are $95 a person with parking included. Diners
have the option to obtain tickets to the exhibit. For information,
call 617-451-1900, ext. 7120. A truly memorable evening. On Nov.
14, Monet's birthday, the hotel will present a special dinner that
benefits the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Fisheries of Boston is also offering a Monet's Table
luncheon Monday through Friday through Dec. 1. The luncheon is $45
a person and includes a ticket to the exhibit and complimentary
shuttle service to the museum. Reservations must be made three days
in advance. Call 617-424-7425. Taxes are not included with either
meal.
</P>
<P>
   Can't get enough of Monet? Then plan on heading to Montreal Jan.
28 through May 9 when the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts presents
``Monet at Giverny: Masterpieces From the Musee Marmottan.'' The
exhibit features 22 paintings produced between 1903 and 1926 at the
artist's estate at Giverny, outside Paris. The exhibit is on loan
from the Marmottan Museum in Paris, which owns the world's largest
collection of the artist's works.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the exhibit will be a collection of photographs from
Montreal's Gabor Szilasi, who has documented the changing of the
seasons in Monet's garden. The photos will be shown in a
large-scale format to give viewers the illusion they are walking
through the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the exhibit will be available beginning Nov. 1 by
calling 800-678-5440. For other information, call 514-285-1600.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thanksgiving dining
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, why not celebrate Thanksgiving where it all began, in
Plymouth. Beginning Thanksgiving morning, Nov. 26, the Pilgrim
Progress offers a reenactment of the procession of the Pilgrims who
survived the first cold, desolate winter in the New World. The
procession ends at Burial Hill, where a service will be held
Pilgrim-style with prayers and hymns. At Plimoth Plantation, the
replica of the original settlement, one can enjoy a Victorian
Thanksgiving Dinner with all the trimmings known since Abraham
Lincoln made Thanksgiving a national holiday in 1863. There will be
three seatings. Also available will be a Thanksgiving Day Buffet
and an all-day Courtyard Celebration. For reservations, call
508-746-1622, ext. 366.
</P>
<P>
   For a taste of Thanksgiving tradition 200 years after the
Pilgrims, Old Sturbridge Village in Sturbridge is the place to
visit. Here in the 1830s village, visitors can see families
preparing the feast on the hearth. A traditional Thanksgiving feast
will be served in the Bullard Tavern at the village. For
reservations, call 508-347-3362, ext. 325.
</P>
<P>
   For more ideas on Thanksgiving in Massachusetts, call the Office
of Tourism at 800-227-MASS; for a free Getaway Guide, call
800-447-MASS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pirates Week
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The days of swashbuckling pirates on the open seas may be long
gone, but during Pirates Week, the Cayman Islands' annual national
festival, a bit of the past comes to life. Pirates Week kicks off
Oct. 24 with a theme ``Chapter 22: Pages of Our History.'' Despite
the week's title, the real focus of Pirates Week is to celebrate
the Caymans' unique seafaring heritage and variety of natural and
sporting attractions. For information on events, call the Cayman
Islands' tourist office at 800-346-3313.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Key West welcome
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Keys are returning to business following the recent
visit of Hurricane Georges. Reports from the area indicate all
tourism facilities in Key Largo and Islamorada are open and that
the Keys Overseas Highway, with 42 bridges over water, is open from
Miami to Key West. The Dolphin Research Center on Grassy Key
suffered some damage, but the facility's 18 dolphins were unharmed,
and the center reopened Oct. 2. Key West officially began welcoming
visitors back last Friday with air and cruise-ship visits back
again. Fantasy Fest, Key West's annual masking soiree, is still on
schedule for Oct. 23 through Nov. 1. ``By the time Fantasy Fest
gets here, this town will be really ready to party,'' said festival
director Linda O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art and architecture
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 10 and 11, PBS will show a biography on architect Frank
Lloyd Wright produced by film producer Ken Burns (of ``Civil War''
and ``Baseball'' fame). To provide an overview of Wright's legacy,
the Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation in Scottsdale, Ariz., has
produced a special edition of its member magazine, the Frank Lloyd
Wright Quarterly. The quarterly includes rare photographs and a
list of Wright sites open to the public. For a copy, send $6 to
Quarterly, Taliesin West, Scottsdale, AZ 85261.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Cod Museum of Natural History is sponsoring a 12-day
tour of the Iberian Peninsula of Spain from March 29-April 9. For
information on the tour and a Tea and Tapas Party on Nov. 15, call
the museum at 508-896-3867.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Precious as Gold'' at the Smithsonian National Postal
Museum in Washington features items from the 1897-1898 gold rush as
well as the struggles of the US Post Office to ensure that the
Klondike/ &QC; 
Alaskan stampeders could maintain contact with the outside world.
The museum is open daily and admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   A special Picasso Package to the Los Angeles County Museum of
Art's exhibit of more than 115 paintings, drawings, sculptures,
collages, and prints by Pablo Picasso is available at the Four
Seasons Hotel at Beverly Hills. Packages begin at $360 a night and
include VIP admission to the show, an exhibit catalog, a gift, and
tickets to a show at CBS Television City. For information, call
310-273-2222.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, is showing ``A Grand Design:
The Art of the Victoria and Albert Museum'' through Jan. 10. The
exhibit spans 2,000 years of artistic achievement from many of the
world's major cultures. For information, call 713-639-7300.
</P>
</TEXT>
