<HEADLINE>
GROVE PARK INN BOASTS A RELAXING HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CAROL RUST 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ Sitting in a rocking chair at the back of the
Grove Park Inn is like lolling in the generous lap of a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Sundown on the Smoky Mountains, where a steel-blue sky is sliced
with bright-orange waves, is the highlight of every day here at the
appropriately named Sunset Terrace, where rocking chairs are
thoughtfully provided to watch the rhapsodic sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   Inn employees know they aren't personally responsible for the
daily sun finale, but they act like they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried about it earlier in the day, but we
didn't do too badly,'' said one cocktail waitress, lingering with a
customer after she delivered a drink to the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Step inside from the Sunset Terrace and into the Great Lodge,
where firelight plays on the mammoth granite stones that line the
yawning fireplaces and a pianist fills the room with tunes that
waft outside and down the mountain along the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Lodge is the heart of the Grove Park Inn, built in
1913 as the ultimate resort lodge. Literally carved out of the
mountains, some of the boulders that make up its walls were put in
place with the moss and lichens that were growing on them when the
stone was quarried.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-story inn has grown considerably over the years. With two
modern wings, it now has 510 rooms and includes an 18-hole
championship golf course, indoor and outdoor swimming pools, a
comprehensive sports facility, three restaurants, a nightclub, two
ballrooms and 50,000 square feet of meeting space. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Grove Park Inn's guest list reads like a ``Who's Who in
America.'' It is unofficially rumored that Zelda Fitzgerald went
off the wagon at the bar in this very hall; the sanctioned version
has her going off the wagon elsewhere and recuperating here. Or
recuperating elsewhere in Asheville while her husband, F. Scott
Fitzgerald, a giant in Jazz Age literature, stayed here.
</P>
<P>
   Scott visited the city frequently during the 1930s and always
stayed in Room 441. He liked the room because it overlooked the
courtyard and he preferred observing people to mountains. This year
the hotel restored the room to look as it did during his visits,
outfitting it with a vintage telephone and radio and Fitzgerald
memorabilia. The room can be viewed when unoccupied, or you can
stay there for $185 for two during the week, $195 on weekends. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Other famous guests to the Grove Park Inn include eight U.S.
presidents, Thomas Edison, Henry Ford, royalty, movie stars, oil
tycoons _ you name it.
</P>
<P>
   And the guest picture just wouldn't be complete without a ghost.
In Grove Park Inn's case, the Pink Lady roams about, the spirit of
a young woman who jumped to her death from an inner balcony in the
Palm Court atrium around 1920, and wanders the labyrinthine halls
of the sprawling retreat when she pleases.
</P>
<P>
   After years of denying the existence of a ghost, hotel
management finally hired a scientific team in 1996 that specializes
in paranormal occurrences. Step aside, Ghostbusters, these guys
witnessed and photographed sufficient encounters with the Pink Lady
_ all weirdly pleasant _ to fill a movie sequel, not to mention the
first chapter of ``Haunted Asheville'' (Shadowbox Publications,
$14.95). Management, realizing there was no muzzling the Pink Lady,
now touts her as part of its unique panorama of experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Guests checking in will be handed a map of the hotel, and they
would be well advised to hang onto it. Not only is it useful to
find your room in the massive building, but it also serves as a
self-guided history tour.
</P>
<P>
   The halls and courts are set up like a museum, containing
historical tidbits about the guests who've stayed there, a history
of the hotel's construction and remodeling juxtaposed against
clothing, fashions, household items and popular-selling tonics and
foods of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove Park Inn received the American Automobile
Association's prestigious Four Diamond Award for the sixth
consecutive year in 1998 and is listed as a four-star establishment
by Mobile Travel Guide's ``American's Best Hotels and
Restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Rates per night through Dec. 31 are $115 to $125 for value rooms
with limited view and one bed in the historic main inn; $185-$195
for standard rooms; and $205 to $215 for deluxe rooms with views of
either the golf course, mountains or city. Club floor
accommodations cost $325 to $335. Suites start at $525. Special
packages are available.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove Park Inn is located at 290 Macon Ave. For information,
call 800-438-5800 or 800-438-0050. Or access
http://www.groveparkinn.com on the Internet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
