<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL-HOLIDAYS-2TAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No place like home for the holidays?
</P>
<P>
   Humbug.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of tours, celebrations and seasonal bargains lure the
traveler looking for an escape from the chores and crowds that
seemingly go hand-in-hand with the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The key to these getaways is planning early. Cities such as New
York and London fill up quickly. You'll want to secure air
reservations soon, particularly if you plan to use frequent-flier
miles.
</P>
<P>
   With options ranging from cruises to safaris and snorkeling to
snowboarding, a good travel agent can steer you to a holiday that
suits your travel style and budget.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a collection of holiday events, packages and tours to
whet the appetite:
</P>
<P>
   Want to celebrate Christmas in Rome and New Year's Eve in Paris?
Consider Cosmos' ``Europe at Leisure'' tour, a 20-day adventure
designed for the first-time traveler to the continent. The trip,
which departs Dec. 13, also includes stops in London, Amsterdam,
Lucerne, the Alps, Florence and Liechtenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Fares start at $1,148, which covers tourist-class accommodations
(double occupancy), breakfast daily, some dinners, motorcoach
transportation and city tours. Air fare is not included. Call a
travel agent or 800-851-0728, Ext. 7518; or visit the Web site:
http://www.globusandcosmos.com.
</P>
<P>
   Amelia Tours, which specializes in upscale holidays, offers
``Just Sicily.'' The 10-day tour, departing Dec. 23, focuses on the
culinary delights of Sicilian Christmas celebrations. The tour
includes four nights in Palermo, two nights in Agrigento, a night
in Siracuse and three nights in Taormina, where guests will
celebrate New Year's Eve. The $2,700 fare covers deluxe
accommodations (double occupancy), most meals, motorcoach
transportation and more. Trans-Atlantic air fare is not included.
Call a travel agent or 800-742-4591.
</P>
<P>
   Reykjavik in Iceland boasts more than a dozen ``real'' Santas.
You can meet them on an excursion with Icelandair Holidays. The
tour features round-trip air fare to Iceland from Boston, New York
or Baltimore; two nights' lodging with breakfast; Christmas Eve
dinner and special holiday tours. Fares start at $599 per person
(double occupancy). Call 800-223-5500; or visit the Web site:
http://www.icelandair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Camp out in the Kasbahs this Christmas on a walking tour with
Breakaway Adventures. The 14-night trip focuses on the rarely
visited Moroccan region of Jbel Sahro, where visitors will find
exotic wildlife and rugged beauty. The trip departs Dec. 20 and
costs $1,095, including most meals, hotels in Marrakech and a
guide. Air fare is not included. Call 800-567-6286.
</P>
<P>
   See ``The Lion King'' and the Rockettes' Christmas Spectacular
at Radio City Music Hall on a Broadway Blast tour with Travel
Dimensions of San Antonio. Six-night tours, which include deluxe
accommodations and three shows, are offered Nov. 24-30 and Dec.
27-Jan. 2. The double-occupancy fare is $1,695 and does not include
air fare to New York. A five-night tour departs Dec. 6. Call
800-828-6445.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Light up your life &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cities around the country sparkle during the holidays with
special events and festivities. One of the most enchanting is
Celebration in the Oaks in New Orleans' City Park.
</P>
<P>
   Each night from Nov. 27 through Jan. 3, hundreds of cars will
inch their way through a stunning, two-mile driving tour where the
park's centuries-old oak trees are decked with millions of
twinkling lights.
</P>
<P>
   Walkers can stroll through the Botanical Garden, Children's
Storyland theme park and the amusement area, where rides such as
the antique carousel and kiddie coaster await.
</P>
<P>
   Musical entertainment, children's activities and refreshments
are available each evening. Special events include a live Nativity
(Dec. 18-22), Radiofone's Snowland (Dec. 19) with 40 tons of
artificial snow, and fireworks (Dec. 26).
</P>
<P>
   Celebration in the Oaks hours will open 5:30-10:30 p.m. daily.
Driving tour admission is $7 per car; walking tour admission is $3
per person. Call 504-483-9415.
</P>
<P>
   Another greenery-inspired event will take place Nov. 20-Dec. 27
at Callaway Gardens in Pine Mountain, Ga. Fantasy in Lights
features a five-mile drive filled with whimsical presentations of
glittering lights choreographed to holiday music. At the Callaway
Christmas Village, craftsmen, educational exhibits and live
entertainment await visitors _ as do Santa and Mrs. Claus.
</P>
<P>
   As this event often sells out on weekends and holidays, it is
advised to secure your tickets before arriving. Tickets go on sale
Nov. 2. Weekday admission is $8 ($4 for children); weekend and
holiday admission is $10 ($5 for children). A bed-and-breakfast
package starting at $143 per night features accommodations in the
Callaway Gardens Inn, Fantasy in Lights admission, breakfast, a
limited-edition ornament, and daytime admission to the gardens
complex. Call 800-225-5292 about tickets and packages.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Wild Animal Park in southern California promises
``a million watts of fun'' with its Festival of Lights. In addition
to more than 100,000 multicolored lights decorating animal
sculptures, the event will feature musical entertainment, crafts, a
snow-covered hill and the opportunity to feed reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   Festival of Lights will run from 4-9 p.m. Dec. 11-30, with the
exception of Christmas Eve and Christmas Day when the park will be
closed. Evening admission to the park will be $7.95 ($3.95 for
children). Call 760-796-5615; or visit the Web site:
http://www.sandiegozoo.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Magnificent Mile Lights Festival on Nov. 21 kicks off the
holiday season in Chicago. More than 800,000 people are expected to
attend the lighting ceremony, which includes stage shows imported
from Florida's Disney World; a Winter Walk with cookies, hot
chocolate and petting zoo; ice sculptures; and more than 150
decorated trees. Call 312-642-3570.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Away at sea &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All the cruise lines offer holiday sailings _ at a premium
price. So if you're going to pay extra, why not go for something
truly special.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Olympic Cruises offers exotic South American expeditions,
including a 14-day Amazon cruise aboard the 620-passenger Stella
Solaris and a 12-day adventure on Venezuela's Orinoco River aboard
the 840-passenger Olympic Countess.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-day Amazon cruise departs Fort Lauderdale Dec. 21 and
heads to Manaus, Brazil. Stops include Caribbean gems such as St.
Thomas, St. Lucia, Barbados, Grenada and Tobago before beginning a
1,000-mile cruise up the Amazon River, where participants will
celebrate New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   With the line's two-for-one deal, cruise fares start at $1,798
per person (double occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   The Orinico River cruise sails from San Juan on Dec. 23 and
features stops on the islands of Santo Domingo, St. Bart's,
Guadeloupe, Barbados, St. Lucia, Martinique and St. Croix. The
three days on the river reveals a rainforest with tropical birds
and dense foliage. An optional tour involves a flight over the
magnificent Angel Falls, the world's tallest waterfall at 3,212
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise-only fares for the Orinoco trip start at $1,199 per
person (double occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-872-6400 or a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Four-time Emmy nominee Robin Mattson is the guest chef aboard a
December 12 cruise, which originates in Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   Mattson, who portrays Janet Green on ABC's ``All My Children,''
also is a gourmet cook and graduate of the Los Angeles Culinary
Institute. On Radisson Seven Seas' 320-passenger Paul Gauguin,
Mattson will offer cooking instruction based on her book, ``Soap
Opera Cafe: The Skinny on Food from a Daytime Star.'' The book
focuses on dining well and weight control.
</P>
<P>
   The Paul Gauguin caters to active cruisers with its array of
activities, which include scuba, snorkeling, water skiing, wind
surfing and kayaking. Fares for the seven-night Soap Opera Cafe
cruise, which visits Taha'a, Raiatea, Bora Bora and Moorea, start
at $2,944 per person (double occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   Call a travel agent or 800-333-3333; or visit the cruise line's
Web site: http://www.rssc.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a unique cruise experience, consider the steamboats of the
Delta Queen Steamboat Company. Seven-night holidays that include a
two-night stay in New Orleans' romantic French Quarter, a
five-night cruise and round-trip air fare start at $1,398 per
person (double occupancy). Trips on the Delta Queen, Mississippi
Queen and American Queen are available throughout December. Call a
travel agent or 800-543-1949.
</P>
<P>
   Explore the Rhine or the Danube with KD River Cruises of Europe.
Seven-day Christmas and New Year's cruises on the Rhine depart
Cologne on Dec. 20 and 27. Christmas Eve Mass in the Austrian wine
town of Drnstein is one of the highlights of the seven-day Danube
cruise, which begins in Regensburg, Germany on Dec. 20. The New
Year's cruise begins in Vienna on Dec. 27. Fares for all sailings
start at $1,235 per person (double occupancy). Call a travel agent
or 800-346-6525.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Family fun &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discover luminarias, mariachis and traditional tamales when you
visit San Antonio during the holiday season. Trees along the Alamo
City's beloved River Walk are ablaze with twinkling lights and
bridges along the pedestrian path are brilliantly lit. Events kick
off Nov. 13 with an open house at Mission San Jose and reach a
crescendo with a battle of the saxes Dec. 13. Other events include
performances of ``The Nutcracker,'' holiday parade, Peace Market,
Kristkindlmarkt and home tours. Admissions vary. For a list of
seasonal events, contact the San Antonio Convention &AMP; Visitors
Bureau at 800-447-3372; or visit the San Antonio Web site:
http://www.sanantoniocvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Want an old-fashioned Christmas? Look to Colonial Williamsburg
in Virginia, where the clock is turned back to the 1700s. Visitors
will find centuries-old holiday traditions and festivities
throughout the historical area, which includes more than 500
restored or reconstructed buildings. Costumed tradesmen and
townspeople bring history alive. Special musical programs and
holiday feasts also are planned for the season, which kicks off
Nov. 28 and runs through Jan. 3. For a Colonial Williamsburg
holiday planner, call 800-404-3389; or visit the Web site:
http://www.colonialwilliamsburg.org.
</P>
<P>
   A 720-square-foot gingerbread town is a sweet treat for holiday
visitors to the Henry Ford Museum &AMP; Greenfield Village in Dearborn,
Mich. The ``town'' consists of 32 gingerbread buildings and six toy
trains winding through lollipop trees and gumdrop gardens on 500
feet of track. In addition to the gingerbread town, the museum also
is exhibiting classic toys of the 20th century. The museum and
village are open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily, but will be closed on
Thanksgiving and Christmas days. Admission is $12.50 ($7.50 for
children). Call 313-271-1620.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing beats the excitement of a college bowl game. New
Orleans-based Spectacular Sport Specials is offering packages to
the Rose Bowl ($1,255) in Pasadena, Calif., the Orange Bowl ($810)
in Miami, the Sugar Bowl ($845) in New Orleans and the Fiesta Bowl
($785) in Phoenix. All prices are double occupancy and include a
game ticket, three nights' lodging, breakfast daily and transfers
between the airport and game. Single- and triple-occupancy fares
are available. Air fare is not included. Call 900-451-5772.
</P>
<P>
   The folks in Santa Claus, Ind., get a little busy around the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   One group known as Santa's Elves will answer as many as 10,000
children's letters to St. Nicholas this year. And postmaster Sandra
Collignon expects to hand cancel more than 500,000 cards and boxes
this year with the city's special holiday postmark. (Santa Claus'
post office normally processes just 13,000 pieces of mail each
month.)
</P>
<P>
   With all that work, the city of Santa Claus is still taking the
time to celebrate the season. The ``Christmas in Santa Claus''
festival, Dec. 12-13, will focus on an old-fashioned holiday with a
toy fair, craft show and parade. Musical entertainment is planned
and visitors will have the opportunity to be photographed with
Santa.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in Santa Claus, contact the Spencer County
Visitors Bureau at 888-444-9252. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
