<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-13 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS PENDULUM SWUNG AGAINST GOP? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For those following politics who like their
analogies taut, to the point, and oversimplified, here are some
thoughts for the stretch drive of '98:
</P>
<P>
   This is 1996, or possibly 1990. This is not 1994. This is for
the moment a campaign in an atmosphere favoring mildly progressive
ideas whose impact is being blunted by scandal politics for which
President Clinton is ultimately responsible _ 1996 redux, if you
will.
</P>
<P>
   This is, again for the moment, NOT a campaign in which a
volcanic, landscape-altering explosion looms. This could be a
fairly typical off-year election, favoring the party not in the
White House in the congressional contests but more likely by less
than is historically typical. And in the State Houses, this could
be a an election that produces very little overall change, meaning
a continuation of the overall Republican domination (32
incumbents), though many of those Republicans govern more like Bill
Clinton than Newt Gingrich. For a metaphor, the Republicans are
superbly positioned to recapture Florida with a dramatically
moderated Jeb Bush from his '94 incarnation, while the Democrats
lead slightly in an attempted takeaway in California with a rabid
moderate, Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But even this thumbnail sketch may miss a more fundamental
point. Unless one party gets hot nationally, 1999's major paradigm
around here is likely to be the same as this year's: whether it's
impeachment or Social Security, HMOs or public schools, one-party
governance is neither in the cards nor especially desired by the
public. For things of consequence to happen, the hands either reach
across the aisle by the dozens in the House and by 10 or so in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The two most recent, most revealing clues about the atmosphere
going into the final month come from the right. Last week, the
Republican Party began putting out its first big batch of so-called
issue commercials for use, via the outrageous soft money loophole
in election law, in campaigns around the country.
</P>
<P>
   They are warm and fuzzy ads, urging voters to pick Republicans
because they'll protect Social Security and improve education and
because they've done a great job helping to balance the budget, cut
taxes, and reform welfare. There is no Contract with America this
time, no emphasis on vouchers for private schools or huge tax cuts
and government downsizing. They are blurring distinctions far more
than they are making them this year.
</P>
<P>
   And over the weekend, the Republicans in Congress were throwing
their pet, conservative ideas over the side by the crateful in an
effort to meet the president's objections far more than halfway, in
a determined rush to get out of here and go campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all this mush from a party more committed in
recent years to revolution than reason is simple: The always
swinging poll pendulum has swung slightly against them in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In nonpresidential years, the wisest course for the poor citizen
is to pay absolutely no attention to any national polling or
commentary about the election until the final month. This year,
however, it has been hard to ignore because of the Monica Lewinsky
affair and its complete domination of the national and even
regional media.
</P>
<P>
   This has produced two, equally overstated, swings of the
pendulum. In the spring, when the president was still denying
everything, the Democrats really thought the public reaction
against ScandalRama might give them the House of Representatives
back.
</P>
<P>
   They were wrong. The president's confession on Aug. 17 that he
had at least lied to the country about his relationship with
Lewinsky fired up hardcore Republicans everywhere and clearly
dispirited many hardcore Democrats. The talk then was of 1994, and
another House landslide combined with the dream of a
filibuster-proof, 60-vote Senate majority.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again. It's now clear that the Republicans nationally and
here overplayed their hand by releasing the gory details of
prosecutor Kenneth Starr's impeachment referral along with the
videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony to a largely disgusted
country.
</P>
<P>
   So the pendulum moved once again. The largely negative reaction
to the House's initial handling of impeachment has produced an
increasingly mixed view of Congress overall. From 55-36 percent
positive in mid-September by the Gallup people's measurement for
CNN and USA Today, Congress's job approval fell to 48-44 percent
negative last week.
</P>
<P>
   As for the congressional Republicans' handling of the charges
against the president, a mixed verdict in mid-September had turned
sharply negative (58-34 percent) last week and was more sharply so
than it was before Clinton's Aug. 17 confession.
</P>
<P>
   Where the talk last month was of Republican intensity, now it's
angry Democrats who appear to be stirring, while conservatives
grumble about the decision by Newt Gingrich and Trent Lott to
jettison nearly all of their legislative agenda in the closing
hours of the largely unproductive Congress.
</P>
<P>
   That national picture, though, has no lasting validity
necessarily, because it has yet to translate into specific
developments in specific campaigns around the country.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be a weird, gyrating month, Fasten your
seatbelts remains the most useful advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
