</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURES OF SPEECH OFTEN BLUR AS THE CULTURE MOVES ON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Globe's volunteer proofreaders have been especially vigilant
in recent months, judging by the volume of tsk-tsk mail coming in.
Both William Lockeretz and Monica Wing noted the headline that
declared ``Unions try new tact to organize'' _ perhaps written by
someone who thought tact was short for tactic _ when the nautical
tack was the word to use. Bob Kittredge found us broaching no
opposition when we should have been brooking none, mitigating
rather than militating, and calling an ascetic guy aesthetic (not
that he couldn't have been both).
</P>
<P>
   But the complaint that caught my eye was the e-mail from Chip
Hitchcock pointing out our use of ringer for wringer. ``Wringers
were obsolete when I was a child, but I still knew what they
were,'' he said, and so should we. But we blew it againin a recent
Washington story that quoted a White House assistant who was upset
at not having been told about the Lewinsky matter. ``Now my butt's
in a ringer,'' the Globe had him saying.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever that feels like, it's probably better than having it in
a wringer, which was standard equipment on early washing machines
until the spin cycle (mechanical, not political) superseded it in
the middle of the century. A pair of spinning rollers, the wringer
squeezed out excess water before the clothes were hung out to dry
(another expression that gets more figurative than literal use
these days). Think of a pasta machine rolling out dough, and you'll
get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Figures of speech often blur as the culture moves on _ we have
no horses, so free rein becomes free reign _ but it seems too soon
for journalists to be getting wringer wrong. After all, it's
central to one of the most famous quotations in newspaper history:
Attorney General John Mitchell's declaration, in 1973, that if the
Washington Post printed a story about a secret fund controlled by
Nixon's backers, its publisher, Katharine Graham, would ``get her
tit caught in a big fat wringer.'' That was 25 years ago, but I'll
bet the Post's writers and editors still know the difference
between ringer and wringer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
