<HEADER>
A4403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      10-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARVELING AT MONET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIVERNY-ON-HUNTINGTON _ All right, so he was more infatuated _
even obsessed _ with water lilies than Popeye was with spinach, or
George Bush isn't with broccoli. France's Green party would run him
for president if he were around today. And if they were around,
Lily Pons of opera fame and Lillie Langtry, queen of music halls,
would sing his praises for painting the town green, enshrining
their namesakes.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't necessarily make Claude Monet weird. Even though he
celebrated water lilies as Andy Warhol did soup cans, there's a
difference. Monet had talent. Glorious talent. Tremendous talent.
His models, the lilies of the pond in his Japanese garden at
Giverny, not far from Paris, were thriving the last time I looked a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They thrive today with a forever-look on their verdant flat
faces at the Huntington Avenue picture palace in Boston called the
Museum of Fine Arts. Here the bearded Frenchman's fetish for
flowering floaters is being beautifully indulged until Dec. 27 in a
show called ``Monet in the 20th Century.'' Currently, Monet's
Giverny loves are more accessible by MBTA than jet, and the price
is righter, says my friend, Author.
</P>
<P>
   As we wander the rooms glowing with his soothing colors, Author
says she isn't an impressionable person but is ``pretty impressed''
by the great impressionistic stuff this geezer (1840-1926) was
still turning out when he was around the 80 mark. He aged as well
as our local treasures, Fenway Park and Maud Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how he painted the same scene over and over, but
gave each painting new meaning,'' she says. ``As a writer, I'd find
it difficult to do that, keep describing a situation again and
again, yet make it ever fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   So fresh that you feel a couple of resident frogs will suddenly
appear in one of his scenes, croaking amorously, ``Your pad or
mine?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he was kinky for `nympheas' _ that's water lilies in
Greek,'' says Author. ``Lucky for us. Because he was out there
painting at all times of day, in every season. He caught the
reflections of sun and sky in the pond at different hours, and each
painting we see is distinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Giverny, I'm starting to think that Monet improved
on nature, and it didn't even set him back carfare. His walk to
work was never more than a few steps from the pink house he shared
with his wife, Alice. Probably Alice often commanded, ``Take a
hike, Claude. Get out of the house and see what you can do with the
4:45 light.''
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't mean he was a Johnny
One-noteworthy-subject. This isn't only a lily-nilly presentation,
as rewarding as that would be. Monet hit the road, too. His visions
of London and Venice are new to most of us and hauntingly gorgeous.
Maybe he wrecked both towns for MFA gawkers who may visit them. I
mean, how can they live up to his portrayals?
</P>
<P>
   London can't. The landmarks endure, but not the conditions. The
baleful, unhealthy fog that was synonymous with London in his time,
frequently enshrouding the city _ an eerie character in story and
song _ was Monet's pal, his ally. Gazing at his misty canvases of
Parliament and the Waterloo and Charing Cross bridges, you can
almost hear him crooning ``A Foggy Day in London Town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without fog, London would not be a beautiful city,'' he felt.
``Fog gives it its marvelous breadth.'' But almost took away its
breath.
</P>
<P>
   One man's pollution was another man's artistic solution.
Antipollution laws after World War II cleared up and dissolved
Monet's hazy London. But we'll always have his wonderful sunset
over the Parliament House tower in 1904. Through the gauzy fog, the
sun itself and its reflection in the Thames seem orange globes of a
barbell. Parliament will never be the same again.
</P>
<P>
   Marvelous as it is, the genuine Venice pales beside his works of
1908 _ 12. ``Venice has got hold of him,'' wife Alice said. And he
gave the city a stunning brush-off. The Palazzo Ducale is a ghost,
a mirage, and the dirty, greasy Grand Canal sparkles with pinks,
greens, mauves.
</P>
<P>
   Making its public debut is a large canvas of a weeping willow in
his garden. ``Too dark and somber,'' says a viewer. Her friend
agrees. ``Too sad. I can see why it's never been shown.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman named Ruth Stanger says it looks like something a Red
Sox fan would have painted. True enough.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the guards will have to be alert in the next room,
wary of Sox loyalists who may survey the massive canvases of the
pond and lilies that stretch 20 feet and rise six. Poor anguished
souls. Some of them, overpowered by Monet's magic and its promise
of peace, may be tempted to end it all by diving in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
