<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      10-13 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Ledeall: An agreement seems likely
this afternoon on spending bills. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   Should there be such a deal, we plan three others covering
specific areas of the general agreement: census, the environment
and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a least one piece assessing the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-GAYS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court leaves standing a
Cincinnati ban on ``special protection'' against discrimination for
homosexuals, the only municipal ban in the country. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (See also COLO-GAY-BEATING, listed below)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments in the impending
House Judiciary impeachment inquiry. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-RESTORE (Washington) _ The Army Corps of Engineers
unveils an $8 billion, 20-year plan to replumb the Everglades,
calling it the biggest environmental restoration ever attempted. By
John H. Cushman Jr.
</P>
<P>
   VA-EXECUTE (Washington) _ Virginia plans on Wednesday to execute
Dwayne Allen Wright for shooting to death an Ethiopian immigrant
and two other people in a 1989 rampage, shortly after his 17th
birthday. The case has drawn requests for clemency from Amnesty
International, and others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' or
</P>
<P>
   COLO-GAY-BEATING (Denver) _ Colorado State University is
investigating how a scarecrow that mocked homosexuals appeared on a
homecoming parade float while a severely beaten gay man lay dying
in a nearby hospital. Wrapping in more on assailants in death of
Matthew Shepard, a gay University of Wyoming student, who died
Monday in Poudre Valley Hospital from injuries he suffered last
week when he was lured from a Laramie, Wyo., campus hangout, beaten
and lashed to a fence. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CLINTON (Broomfield, Colo.) _ Three weeks before the
election, candidates in tight races around the country avoid the
Clinton scandal, while some long-shots use it to attract attention.
There are signs of backlash against Republicans, but Democrats are
not confident enough of that to use the issue. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CATHOLIC-WOMEN (Undated) _ A committee of U.S. Roman Catholic
bishops issues a statement saying that if women can be promoted in
administrative roles, they should be. This means parishes should
try to make them school principals, for instance. This comes at a
time when another committee of bishops issues a statement giving
the answers to the 10 most asked questions about why only men can
be priests. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFING (Undated) _ The column. By B. Drummond Ayres
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kosovo &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ACCORD (Belgrade) _ U.S. envoy Holbrooke announces a deal
on Kosovo with Yugoslav President Milosevic, averting NATO air
strikes. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels) _ Echoes of Bosnia: Everyone is
crowing, but did Milosevic again get what he wants? How will deal
be enforced? What about the refugees? Bosnian refugees have been
unable to return home. A news analysis by Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Washington reaction to the Kosovo
deal. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   Others as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ATTACK (Jerusalem) _ As the Israeli Cabinet discusses a
peace plan, one Israeli is shot dead and one critically wounded
near Jerusalem in well-planned attack, perhaps timed to the
forthcoming summit talks in the U.S. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Chief arms inspector Butler reports
to the Security Council. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-CUTBACK (New York) _ Merrill Lynch fires 3,400 employees
and cuts 900 full-time consulting positions, and it posts a 75
percent decline in operating earnings and a net loss for the third
quarter. The operating result of 28 cents a share was well below
expectations. Paine Webber's net income fell 27 percent, more than
expected. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette's earnings tumbled 79
percent. Jeffries is also scheduled to post. By Peter Turell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:50 p.m., the Dow industrial average was
down 65 points, the Nasdaq index down 29. Elsewhere, prices fell
2.3 percent in Tokyo and rose 0.2 percent in Hong Kong. They
declined 0.2 percent in Frankfurt, 0.4 percent in London and 0.2
percent in Mexico, but they rose 1.9 percent in Brazil. On the
American debt market, the long bond was up 1 1/32 point at midday,
with the yield at 5.02 percent. The dollar stood at 119.77 yen, up
from 117.63 yen on Monday. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-EON (Tokyo) _ The lower house of Japan's parliament
approves the legislation that will allow the government to spend
more than $400 billion to recapitalize the debt-burdened banking
system. The Cabinet also authorizes a special budget to pay for the
rescue effort. But concern that details of the plan are too vague
helps push down stocks by 2.3 percent. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BANKS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ As the global financial
turmoil continues to take its toll on European financial companies
_ at ING Barings this week, the chairman resigned along with the
two joint heads of emerging markets and high-yield debt and
derivatives _ Europe's central bankers gather to discuss how to
merge financial policies. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-AMERICAN (New York) _ Monsanto and American Home
Products cancel their merger.
</P>
<P>
   GM-EARNINGS (Detroit) _ General Motors posts a loss for the
latest quarter of $809 million, or $1.28 a share, in contrast to a
year-earlier profit and a reflection of two charges: $1.2 billion
for the strikes and $271 million for the sale of Delphi. Excluding
the Delphi charge, the loss was 87 cents a share, better than the
loss of 99 cents a share that analysts had expected. The auto maker
lost $12 million outside North America during the quarter, largely
because of lower sales in Brazil. A cost-cutting campaign helped
make up for the effect of widening price discounts. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Intel will post earnings and is
expected to announce a result of 80 cents a share. Cypress
Semiconductor posts a sharp decline in net, but the result is
better than analysts' expectations, which were for a loss. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-EARNINGS (New York) _ Eastman Kodak's earnings rose in the
third quarter (up 72 percent net to net, up 52 percent excluding a
year-earlier charge, up 45 percent on operations), exceeding
expectations by 1 cent a share, as cost cuts offset a 10 percent
decline in revenue. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-FRIEDRICHSHAFEN (Detroit) _ Ford and Z.F. Friedrichshafen
of Germany form a venture to produce automatic transmissions. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
