<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT INDUSTRY HAS FRIENDS IN HIGH PLACES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Plastic, fantastic as it is, is a major American
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer bankruptcy filings are up 66 percent in the last five
years, to 1.35 million annually, according to the American
Bankruptcy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Could blame lie with the sweet-talking guys at MBNA and
Providian and everyone else pushing easy credit? Could it have to
do with the fact that credit-card solicitations totaled 3 billion
last year?
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School professor Elizabeth Warren thinks so. So do
San Francisco-area bankruptcy lawyers Norma Hammes and Irving
Kornfield, and their colleague, David Ebert of Fort Worth, Texas,
whose grade-school daughters have received applications in the
mail. All four hold the credit avalanche responsible for the
bankruptcy explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-'80s consumer debt became vastly more profitable
than any other kind of lending activity because state usury laws
were effectively overturned,'' Warren said. ``Today, credit card
lending is twice as profitable as all other lending activity, even
when you account for costs and losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid-'80s consumer debt also just took off _ and guess
what? Bankruptcies went right through the roof behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren and the bankruptcy lawyers also are aghast that Congress
_ after being lobbied hard and lavishly by the credit industry _ is
likely to approve sweeping bankruptcy reform legislation that would
make it much more difficult for families who get in over their
heads to wipe the slate clean while protecting critical assets.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative action could force people to repay up to 30
percent of their credit card debts. Estimated savings to the
industry: more than $4 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is special-interest legislation, period,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert called the legislation efforts by creditors ``to empower
the government to collect debts owed to them.''
</P>
<P>
   People like Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Utah Republican, say _
correctly _ that bankruptcy should be a last resort, not a
financial planning tool. But then they cite extreme examples of
abuses under current law, such as the Virginia man who filed under
Chapter 7 but managed to keep his $640,000 race horse. This is
terribly misleading, consumer advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Warren: ``The median income of Chapter 7 filers in 1997 was
$17,652 _ that's momma and daddy and the kid's paper route.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammes, a San Jose lawyer who heads the National Association of
Consumer Bankruptcy Attorneys, said she doesn't believe the many
members of the lawmakers backing the proposed law understand the
damage it would do to hard-working people down on their luck
because of job loss or medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Kornfield, an Oakland lawyer who served as a bankruptcy trustee
in about 10,000 cases between 1969 and 1981, said the frequency of
abusive bankruptcy filings actually is low.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're losing so much money, why did Citicorp pay $3.5
billion to AT&AMP;T to buy the Universal Card?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because when you have friends in high places _ Congress,
namely _ consumer debt is a high-profit narcotic you can push
without concern for the consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1428EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
