<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARSHBARGER-BUSINESS-     10-13 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARSHBARGER-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S THE BETTER CANDIDATE IF ECONOMY TURNS SOUR?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With less than three weeks to go before Massachusetts
voters pick their next governor, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger
last week stood in the heart of Boston's Financial District with
the autumn sun shining on him and a cloud of economic anxiety
hovering overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon Co., the state's largest private employer, had just
announced massive layoffs on the heels of huge cutbacks at nearby
Gillette Co. The stock market was continuing its tumultuous
downward trend, the dollar was sinking, and the threat of a
worldwide recession spread by the Asian economic flu was no longer
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   So here was Harshbarger, the gubernatorial candidate, standing
outside the old Federal Reserve Building with a dozen Democratic
business leaders who pledged their support and who said Harshbarger
is best equipped to run the state should the economy indeed sour.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an argument that's immediately convincing _ nor even
widely heard, given the tiny group of onlookers and reporters who
turned out for the event. And it's one that political analysts say
Harshbarger might not want to stress as voters come to grips with
the likelihood that the next governor will preside during a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Do they want the Democrat, with the willpower to hold up a
safety net no matter how many people get flung from their jobs? Or
the Republican, who never saw a tax cut he didn't like?
</P>
<P>
   ``Research suggests that stock market fluctuations have no
bearing on the election,'' said Darryll West, chairman of the
political science at Brown University. ``The economy matters only
when it starts to affect people's daily lives and they start
getting laid off. And even then, there is a three- to four-month
lag effect. ... So voters will look for someone who is both
reassuring and seen as competent on economic matters.''
</P>
<P>
   West said that benefits Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, not just
because he's a Republican, but because he's the incumbent. ``When
things are in turmoil, people don't want to rock the boat,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Globe poll taken last week shows voters are split along
party lines when asked if it is better to have a Democrat or
Republican governor in office when the legislative majority is
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   But among independent voters _ who could be key to deciding this
election _ 37 percent favored a Republican governor, while just 19
percent of the 400 likely voters surveyed chose a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, when asked ``If the economy were to go into a
recession, who do you think would better manage bad economic
times?'' 41 percent said Cellucci, compared to 30 percent for
Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   Again, independents overwhelmingly sided with Cellucci on that
question, with 49 percent for him, compared to 19 percent for his
Democratic rival.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harshbarger repeatedly says Cellucci takes too much
credit for shaping the state's economy _ the attorney general says
we're riding on a national economic boom _ those polled disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four percent say Cellucci has taken about the right amount
of credit for the state of affairs and 15 percent said he is not
taking enough credit. Only 26 percent said he was taking too much
credit.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe/WBZ-TV poll, conducted by KRC Communications
Tuesday and Wednesday, has a margin of error of plus or minus 5
points. Of the 400 surveyed, 140 were Democrats, 177 independents
and 59 Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Harshbarger continues to plunge ahead like the running
back he was in college, trying to explain why he, and not Cellucci,
should be the steward when leadership is needed most.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger argues:
</P>
<P>
   _Cellucci wants to roll back the income tax rate to 5 percent
while the Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation has said doing so
would ``be difficult to manage beyond 1999.'' Harshbarger would
gradually reduce the income tax rate, employing breaks and triggers
that allow an annual review of the budget.
</P>
<P>
   _The state has the third highest per capita debt in the nation.
Harshbarger says he would rather pay cash for capital projects when
the state can afford it. Cellucci believes vetting projects through
the bonding process keeps costs down.
</P>
<P>
   _Harshbarger says Cellucci has no plan for the economy. The
acting governor says the economy is doing well partly because of
the 28 tax breaks the Weld-Cellucci administration doled out,
including those for the burgeoning financial services and health
care sectors. Cellucci also cites opening the utility industry to
competition, reducing workers' compensation rates and lowering
unemployment insurance rates as steps he and former governor
William F. Weld have taken to encourage growth.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cellucci says, the economy is more diversified,
relying less on the defense industry often targeted for cuts by the
federal government. It was a point he made several times last week
after Raytheon announced 14,000 layoffs, 1,200 of them in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before, Gillette Co. said it was eliminating 4,000
positions, some of which may be local. Another 675 manufacturing
workers will lose their jobs at Intel's Hudson chip-making plant
over the next year, the company said last month.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, Cellucci touted an economic report showing the
state outperforming the nation on unemployment, personal income
(growing at 5 percent a year), median household income, and
inflation, at 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cellucci, wisely, is drawing attention to those things which
have gone well,'' said Roger Porter, a political economist at
Harvard University. ``In the end, this is largely going to be a
referendum on whether or not you are satisfied with the performance
to date, and essentially it has little if anything to do with party
(affiliation).''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, there are other issues Harshbarger is pressing.
</P>
<P>
   _He criticizes Cellucci for vetoing $18 million in job-training
funding last summer, saying the move is symbolic of the acting
governor's disregard for investing in needed projects during good
times to prepare for the bad times. Cellucci defends the veto,
saying the program was unnecessary. He also was looking for ways to
fund a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   _Harshbarger, meanwhile, says he would expand adult education by
$25 million over 5 years, targeting grants for areas with the
highest unemployment rates, such as Fall River, Chelsea and Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   _And while Weld eliminated the Executive Office of Economic
Development as a separate agency to save money by reorganizing
government, Harshbarger would bring back the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing on such ideas, Rob Gray, Cellucci's campaign manager,
said Harshbarger ``will not be a governor who will try to enforce
fiscal discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just about partisan theories on how to get out of
a recession,'' Gray said. ``It's more about keeping the Legislature
in check. In 1991, Bill Weld and Paul Cellucci came into office and
said no, you guys have to take the medicine and make the difficult
decisions to get the economy back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, in endorsing Harshbarger
last week despite earlier concerns the attorney general might lean
too closely to the ``loony left,'' said the Legislature deserved
the credit for healing the economy. Not the corner office.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Finneran said, having a one-party system on Beacon
Hill would not be dangerous because the Democratic party knows
better than to return to ``pursuing an unfettered entitlement
mentality'' and ``trying to be all things to all people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
