<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVENTION-NEWYORK-BO     10-13 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANHATTAN GIULIANI WANTS TO SHOW GOP IS CLEANER AND CHEAPER
</HEADLINE>
 YORK-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He has cut crime, slashed welfare, cleaned up Times
Square, and cracked down on the Mob, but now, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has set out on his most improbable campaign _ convincing
heartland Republicans that New York City is their kind of town.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Giuliani has been pushing for the next
Republican Convention to be held in Manhattan _ a location not only
unprecedented in the party's 144-year history but, to many of its
more conservative members, unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the Republican National Committee's nine-member
site-selection committee has put New York City on its short list of
five, and some say it ranks high among those finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Key to the success so far is that the city Giuliani and his
aides have been selling is not quite the Manhattan that New Yorkers
love and loathe. Instead, they plan to create a cleaner, quieter,
less costly alternative _ what deputy mayor Randy Levine calls ``a
Republican Convention Village'' _ encompassing the mile-and-a-half
stretch from Madison Square Garden to Columbus Circle and all the
watering holes, resting spots, and tourist traps in between.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates worried about traffic? Key streets will be closed off
to the outside world. Security? The nation's most famous police
force will be out in full regalia. Don't like fast, rude taxi
drivers? Shuttle buses will take people to and from the Garden,
hotels, and restaurants, 24 hours a day. Hotels and restaurants too
expensive? Some of the best hotels have agreed to drop their
nightly rates below $200, and ``200 of the finest restaurants,''
Levine said, have agreed to serve delegates dinner for $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   The site-selection committee has visited here three times.
Giuliani personally gave them a bus tour of the city, wined and
dined them at Jean-George, and supplied them with tickets to
Broadway shows.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were plenty impressed,'' said Pat Larimer, the selection
committee's chairwoman, who lives in Wyoming. ``We noticed so many
changes _ clean, safe streets. The mayor has really turned the city
around. I don't think it's any different from any other city. You
didn't get that big-city feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The big pitch, as Giuliani's communications director, Cristyne
Lategano, spelled out, is this: ``New York City is a living,
breathing example of how Republican policies can turn around an
urban center. All of the ideals and policies the mayor has put
forth have been, by and large, Republican ideals. ... The best way
to deliver that message nationally in the year 2000 is to have the
Republican Convention here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's working, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Fitzpatrick, a spokesman for the Republican National
Committee, which will vote on the selection panel's recommendation
in January, echoed the sentiment: ``There's a tremendous success
story that Republicans in New York have to tell. It's a
family-friendly place now.''
</P>
<P>
   Many see another dimension to New York's big push for the
convention. They note that it would showcase not only the
Republican Party, not only New York City, but also the man who led
this transformation, the next (fill in the blank: president, vice
president, attorney general, FBI director, any of the above),
Rudolph William Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his aides deny such ambitions, but it is
universally suspected that Giuliani has his eye on a high-level
national slot. A local term-limit law automatically ends his
mayoralty in 2001, and Giuliani has pointedly refused to promise
that he will finish the term out. He has been very cordial lately
with George W. Bush, the party's front-running presidential
aspirant. And for a man who used to hate leaving New York for even
a night, Giuliani has taken a sudden interest in touring the
remotest reaches of the country, speaking at a dozen out-of-state
Republican fund-raisers since April _ generally to acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Republican governor, George W. Pataki, has also been
making the national rounds, and lately has made no secret of his
ultimate goal, telling the New York Observer, in an interview
published last week, ``If you're governor of New York, you can't
help but think about being president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Giuliani and Pataki both suffer from the fact that they
flunk most of the modern Republican Party's social policy litmus
tests. They may score well on taxes, welfare, and law and order.
But they also favor abortion rights, gay rights, immigrants'
rights, gun control. For the conservative core that generally
chooses the Republican presidential nominee, that puts them beyond
the pale.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the convention in New York would certainly brighten the
spotlight on the mayor and the governor. ``The question,'' said one
Republican consultant, ``is whether the party wants to give a
platform to two guys who go against so much of what they hold
dear.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's New York City itself. No matter how securely the
delegates are contained in their Convention Village, the event
would certainly attract large groups of demonstrators, protesting
the party's stance on abortion, gay rights, and welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a great city to have media attention,'' said one
local business leader with ties to the Giuliani administration, who
asked not to be identified. ``But I'd think the Republican
leadership would want the complete focus to be on the message
they're trying to deliver, as opposed to 10,000 people protesting a
few blocks away. You're guaranteed that situation in New York City.
Maybe in Indianapolis or San Antonio you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are two of the four cities competing with New York for the
prize. The others are New Orleans and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican who is heavily involved in the campaign to bring
the convention here waved off the other cities, especially
Indianapolis and San Antonio, which he has heard are the main
threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do they get from having the convention there?'' he asked.
``They've already got those places won. To win the election, you've
got to move beyond your base. If you have the convention in New
York City, that's moving into the Democrats' heartland. If you make
New York competitive, that puts the Democrats in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged, ``Certain people on the RNC staff'' are
attracted by what those cities have to offer. ``They're seen as
safe places, small towns,'' he said. ``Some Republicans like
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
