<SLUG> BC-VISA-HIGH-TECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO ISSUE MORE HIGH-TECH VISAS NEAR DEAD FOR THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once considered a sure bet to become law,
legislation sought by the high-tech industry to hire more foreign
workers for US computer jobs has all but died for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was politically sensitive because President Clinton and
many other Democrats count on support both from high-tech
companies, who badly want the bill, and from labor groups, who
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and the White House worked out compromise legislation
last month, which the House ratified 288-133. Prospects were
considered high in the Senate, because that chamber had passed a
version of the bill earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, with the congressional session winding down, a small
group of senators blocked a vote on the bill, all but ensuring its
demise for now. Congress plans to adjourn once it passes a federal
budget, which could come as early as tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   One of the opponents, Senator Tom Harkin, Democrat of Iowa, said
he blocked the bill because high-tech companies had exaggerated
their difficulties in finding qualified US workers to take computer
jobs. He said many companies are laying off workers, so there was
no need to allow more foreign workers to take those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But businesses reacted with dismay to the legislation's apparent
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this hurts the ability of American companies to
compete in the global marketplace,'' said Ken Mokler, director of
staffing at EMC Corp. of Hopkinton. ``We're looking at filling
high-level positions, enginering positions, technical-related
positions, where we need to be able to hire the best and the
brightest, and being able to hire them from anywhere is certainly a
big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill have one more opportunity to move the
legislation, if they can persuade lawmakers to include it in a
massive budget bill that sets spending for about one-third of all
government operations for the next year. That bill is sure to be
approved, but congressional aides said chances were slight that the
foreign-worker provision would be attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   Current law allows the government to grant 65,000 so-called H-1B
visas each year for foreigners to work at skilled US jobs ranging
from software writer to nurse, physician, and fashion model. The
visas are valid for six years.
</P>
<P>
   But high-tech companies, including many around Boston, asked
Congress to raise the quota. The current allotment was filled
quickly this year, they said, because the US job market was so
tight that they could not find enough people to take computer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and other workers' groups opposed the new visas,
saying that employers could draw more US workers if they merely
raised wages. The labor groups also said that the alleged shortage
of high-tech workers was overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, employers would have been able to hire
115,000 skilled foreign workers in the fiscal year that began Oct.
1, and 115,000 in the following year. The cap would have dropped to
107,500 in 2001 and returned to 65,000 in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and a group of House members had negotiated
successfully to include &UR;  &LR;  several provisions that they said would
protect US workers from being replaced by foreign workers on H-1B
visas. The bill would have given the Department of Labor broader
authority to investigate companies for abuse of the visas, and it
would have set aside $75 million annually for job training and
scholarships to prepare low-income students for high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to EMC, Massachusetts companies that backed the
increase in visas included Keane Inc., a Boston software consulting
and services firm, and Cognex Inc., a Natick maker of industrial
software.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1446EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIDERITE-KEDS-BOS &LR;      10-13 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEDS, ONCE A BLUE-CHIP BRAND, TRIES TO MAKE COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 RITE-KEDS-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 1987 movie ``Dirty Dancing'' sold a lot of Keds for
the Stride Rite Corp., a company now in the midst of a turnaround.
After female lead Jennifer Grey danced slinky rhumbas while wearing
Keds, the canvas shoes became a teenage fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   The movie ``gave us teen-age girls,'' said the company's
chairman and chief executive, Robert C. Siegel, 61, who is about to
step down and entrust Stride Rite's future to an
as-yet-unidentified successor.
</P>
<P>
   With Keds accounting for about 35 percent of annual sales for
the company, which also makes children's shoes and Sperry
Top-Siders, Lexington-based Stride Rite has been trying to hang on
to those teenage girls ever since _ but with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, grunge was in vogue, and teens swapped their
Keds for Doc Martens. Now there are signs that Keds are cool again,
this time in pricier, reinvented styles that Keds division
president Joanna M. Jacobson debuted last spring.
</P>
<P>
   A top-of-the-line leather model with thicker soles can retail
for almost $50 , a big jump from the $18 canvas Keds most folks are
familiar with. So far, consumers are undaunted by the higher price.
For the quarter that ended Aug. 28, Keds sales were up 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Josephine R.
Esquivel, projects Keds sales of $203 million for fiscal 1998,
which ends in November.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from $362 million when Keds peaked in 1992 and
accounted for 65 percent of Stride Rite's sales, but still better
than the $178 million in Keds sales last year, when most customers
were women over 25.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a Keds comeback, Siegel thinks the company that he was
hired to turn around in 1993 is now on the right track. Still, many
Wall Street investors remain unimpressed. Stride Rite's stock price
has lost much of its value this year, hitting a 52-week low last
week of 6 5/8 on the New York Stock Exchange. Stride Rite shares
fell 1/4 yesterday to close at 7 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Stride Rite may be getting lost in the shuffle, analysts say.
``The whole footwear industry is getting beaten up,'' said Steven
A. Richter, an analyst for Tucker Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Marotta, an analyst with Wasserstein Perella
Securities, asked: ``Does the stock price reflect Stride Rite's
future prospects? The answer is an emphatic `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   If Keds sales are up sharply, growth for Stride Rite's
well-respected brand of childen's shoes is solid, but less
dramatic. Children's shoes delivered about 35 percent of overall
Stride Rite sales last year, but this brand competes &UR;  &LR;  in a
shrinking market &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once boys wore Stride Rite shoes almost until they were 13.
``Now we lose boys at 5 or 6,'' Siegel said. ``They want to wear
Nikes and be like Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with girls. By age 8, many are fed up with
sensible shoes. They want fashion, shoes similar to the ones worn
by teenage sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fickleness of children's tastes _ and how rapidly
young feet grow _ many parents would rather buy cheap footwear at
Wal-Mart than pay a premium for Stride Rite shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to give more fashion options to young consumers and
partly to augment its ``mature'' Keds and Stride Rite brands, the
company recently signed licensing agreements to make shoes under
the brand names of such fashion-minded companies as Tommy Hilfiger,
Nine West, and Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Stride Rite and Levi Strauss opted to discontinue the
Levi's shoe line after its July debut was poorly received. Results
for other licensed lines have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in spring 1997, ``Tommy Hilfiger for Men'' got off to a
great start with many of the shoes having the same silhouette and
look as a basketball sneaker. But then sales for all basketball
sneakers, including those made by Nike, ``hit a wall'' about a year
ago, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   The early line on the ``Tommy Hilfiger for Women'' shoes is a
different story. The recent launch was ``spectacular,'' said
Marotta, the analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Hilfiger and Nine West also are supposed to help Stride Rite
achieve another goal _ stimulate sales all year. Keds and Top-Sider
boat shoes are spring and summer brands. And once children have
been outfitted with Stride Rite shoes at back-to-school time,
company sales go into winter hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to change that, Stride Rite recently aired the first
fall advertising campaign in recent memory. And one priority for
Siegel's successor will be to make an acquisition that rounds out
the company's brand portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As a former president of the Dockers USA division at Levi
Strauss, Siegel thinks trouser fashions help drive shoe trends.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, people wore jeans and complemented them with
Nike sneakers and the chunkier outdoor look of Doc Martens. Now
khakis from the Gap are the king of pants, and Stride Rite, along
with many other companies, makes shoes that go well with khakis. As
a result, Stride Rite is upbeat about 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the company earned $19.8 million on sales of $515.7
million. In a Sept. 25 report, analyst Richter estimated it would
earn $28.4 million on sales of $540.9 million &UR;  &LR; in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But because of uncertainty about Stride Rite's licensed shoe
lines, Richter recently lowered his sales projections and earnings
estimates for fourth-quarter 1998 and for 1999. &UR;  &LR; And he said he may
lower them again following Friday's announcement that Stride Rite
is pulling the plug on the Levi's line.
</P>
<P>
   Because Levi's accounted for 3 percent of Stride Rite's
third-quarter sales, the move is not expected to have much impact.
``The long-term recovery of this company is driven by Keds,''
Richter said. ``And Keds have exceeded our expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   One challenge is improving sales of the Tommy Hilfiger line.
That job may fall to Diane M. Sullivan, head of the company's
licensed brands division, who is mentioned as a possible successor
to Siegel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving Stride Rite more of a fashionable edge,
Siegel has presided over cost-cutting measures that moved shoe
production to factories overseas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he brought in a new management team and helped
solve problems at a distribution center in Louisville, Ky., that
bedeviled the company in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``My great disappointment is a lack of financial success,'' he
said. ``We have not achieved the level of stock performance that
shareholders deserve. But we've completely changed the culture of
the company, and we were in dire need of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
