<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUS-RINGLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-BALANCING RIPPEL BROTHERS GIVE CIRCUS UNUSUAL ACT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you watch the Rippel Bros. perform their act, you can't
wait to give them a hand. But it's certainly not the kind of hand
they give each other.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian brothers, Ferenc, 27, and Viktor, 25, are
hand-balancers, one of the more unusual acts in Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus, the 127th edition of which opens
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; at the FleetCenter and continues through Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Performing in the Bahamas in 1991, the brothers hit upon the
idea of doing their act painted in gold, making them look like
gilded statues that move. Audiences went for it in a big way and
they've been doing it ever since. They refer to themselves as
``living Oscars,'' after the Academy Award statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, from Budapest, perform what is called an
``equilibristic'' act, Ferenc Rippel said over lunch recently,
carefully writing the word out on a napkin. He and his brother had
just finished demonstrating their skill for an appreciative crowd
of noontime strollers in the rotunda of Faneuil Hall Marketplace.
Rippel said the act has also been described as ``a lifestyle, an
extreme sport, slow-motion contortionists, a habit.'' There are
only five or six such performing groups in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since balance is key to their act, the brothers must remain
virtually identical in weight _ 200 pounds each. They watch each
others' diet carefully. They manage their own act and appear to
share equally a desire to excel. Both love the United States, love
performing here, and have many friends here. Ferenc Rippel has been
married for two years. His brother Viktor grins and says he's
``never going to get married.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of their performances, Viktor supports Ferenc's entire
body weight _ with his head. ``If he goes up pounds, it's harder
for me,'' Viktor Rippel said. ``I watch every breadstick he eats.''
</P>
<P>
   The tricks they perform flow seamlessly from one to another.
They balance horizontally on a revolving platform, using their
strength and focused concentration to perform moves that often seem
to defy gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep in shape,'' Viktor Rippel said. ``Every part
of our body is visible. The body is our costume.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, sons of acrobats, began competing at sports
gymnastics, a popular form of acrobatics throughout Europe, at age
4. They attended the renowned Hungarian Artist School from 1982 to
'88. After that, while in Russia, they began working up their
hand-balancing routine. They developed it primarily because they
didn't want to split up and pursue separate, more traditional
careers ``as jugglers, on the high wire or low wire,'' Viktor
Rippel said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, they made mistakes. ``We used to fight a lot
and hold each other in bad places,'' Ferenc said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With perestroika, opportunities in the international world of
the circus opened up. ``We're not self-made millionaires,'' Ferenc
Rippel said. ``We just want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
