<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CORPUS-CHRISTI     10-13 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CORPUS-CHRISTIE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CORPUS CHRISTI' ANYTHING BUT BLASPHEMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In these days of debased civil discourse, blasphemy
is in the eye of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Terrence McNally's controversial new play
``Corpus Christi,'' which opens Tuesday night at Manhattan Theatre
Club's Stage I. For the past five months, the public has been
treated to a media spectacle of protests and demonstrations, both
for and against the production because of its purported content.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the protests have made ``Corpus Christi'' the
hottest ticket in town since ``Cabaret'' opened earlier this year.
Audience members thread past protesters clad in pastel berets who
kneel on the pavement and recite Hail Marys. Entering the theater
building, the security checkpoints create a tension and a sense of
event. Once inside the theater space, though, anxieties dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Loy Arcenas has undermined theatrical artifice by
removing all wings and curtains, leaving a bare wooden playing
space in the center of the stage. Props and costumes are in plain
sight to the rear, the lighting is practical and spartan. The
actors chat comfortably among themselves before one of them
addresses the audience with a gentle warning of what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   What follows, though, is hardly shocking and scarcely
scandalous. Indeed, McNally and director Joe Mantello offer a
delicate and moving alternative to the ``greatest story ever
told.'' The overtones about homosexual relationships in the
apostolic inner circle certainly vary from accepted biblical
scholarship. But McNally clearly states that his point of view is
simply that.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-production rumors that a Christ-like figure named Joshua has
sex with his disciples prove untrue. ``Corpus Christi'' ultimately
is a modern-day allegory about the journey of an outsider from
childhood to manhood. The character of Joshua (Anson Mount) is a
sensitive young man who hears the voice of God telling him, ``This
is my son, in whom I take much delight.'' Born to his virgin mother
in a lowly fleabag hotel in Texas, he grows up a misfit who is
interested in the arts and isn't much good at sports.
</P>
<P>
   Attending Pontius Pilate High School in Corpus Christi, he is
tormented by the other boys for his difference and accused of being
``a queer.'' Rescued by the sexually predatory Judas (Josh Lucas),
Joshua finds a kind of warmth and acceptance in the arms of a man.
But whatever passes between Joshua and Judas _ we see no more than
a brief kiss _ is short-lived as the young seeker goes in search of
his life with God.
</P>
<P>
   Since late spring, the media here and abroad have fed at the
trough of ``obscenity'' and ``blasphemy'' when writing of the
play's subject matter. Although it hasn't quite had the guilty
attractions of the Monica Lewinsky story, the ``Corpus Christi''
imbroglio has drawn the interest of a Catholic civil rights group,
as well as an element of the lunatic fringe.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall hearing that the Manhattan Theatre Club pulled
the production from its schedule last May after receiving anonymous
phone threats to ``exterminate every member of the theater and burn
the place to the ground.'' Before the threats, however, the
Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights already had mounted
a campaign against the play, insisting that McNally excise certain
passages offensive to Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   But no one at the Catholic League had read or seen the play; it
is not unusual for new works to be unavailable before opening. So
the league relied on reports in the New York Times and the (London)
Guardian that referred, respectively, to the play's potentially
offensive and ``flagrantly blasphemous'' content.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the play in previews last weekend, the Catholic
League released a statement calling the play ``a faithful rendition
of the gay stereotype.'' However, the news release quotes the play
inaccurately and insists that Joshua ``has sex with a man (Philip)
at his high school prom.'' Philip is neither present in the scene
mentioned, nor does ``sex'' occur. Also, if the league seriously
believes that ``Corpus Christi'' is meant to represent the actual,
biblical Jesus, then its leaders should remember that the priests
criticized by Jesus were Jewish, not Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The theater's decision in May to yank the production also raised
a firestorm of protest from the artistic community. In support of
McNally, the noted South African playwright Athol Fugard withdrew a
play from the company's season. ``Angels in America'' author Tony
Kushner helped initiate a campaign of support for the production.
Hundreds of theater artists and administrators, including Seattle's
Gordon Edelstein, Mame Hunt, Eddie Levi Lee, Ben Moore, Laura Penn
and Warner Shook, signed a statement supporting the company's right
to free artistic expression.
</P>
<P>
   The production was reinstated, but not before the company
received assurances from the city of New York that its staff and
audiences would be protected. Metal detectors were installed in the
theater's lobby, other security measures were instituted and the
production moved forward.
</P>
<P>
   Attacked as a ``Jew guilty homosexual'' in the threatening phone
messages, McNally, who was raised Catholic, has been publicly
silent except for a note of triumph when he received his fourth
Tony Award in June for ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticized by some in the gay community for his portrayal of gay
men in ``Love! Valour! Compassion!,'' McNally again may find
himself at odds with the same critics in addition to the Catholic
League. During Joshua's temptation in the desert, he meets Satan in
the form of the actor James Dean. Helping Satan in the temptation
of power and privilege, is the character of Judas. Does this imply
that the openly gay character of Judas is the tool of Satan? There
seems no other conclusion to draw. Surely, this is not offensive to
the Catholic League.
</P>
<P>
   Miracles familiar from the New Testament are enacted in ``Corpus
Christi,'' some with a jokey twist. Lazarus is raised from the dead
because Joshua can't stand the mournful wails of his family. A man
possessed by demons hurls profane vitriol, in words we know all too
well, at God and everyone until Joshua releases him from his
torment. An angry male hustler who is HIV-positive is healed,
emotionally and physically, by Joshua's enfolding arms.
</P>
<P>
   In medieval times, the Feast of Corpus Christi was a celebration
of the body of Christ that included theatrical entertainment aimed
at promoting understanding of the mystery of Christ's passion. In
the new play, the sexual content furor has obscured McNally's
sweetly human message advocating universal brotherhood and love for
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, McNally teases Catholic school education here and
there, but is that truly blasphemous or hateful? Are there any
former Catholic school kids who don't make occasional jokes about
the nuns and priests who taught them (and cracked their knuckles
with rulers)?
</P>
<P>
   As histrionic elements of the media and publicity-seeking
watchdogs of morality go in search of the lewd and the profane, one
person's blasphemy may be another person's beauty. For all of the
Catholic League's hyperbole about hate speech, there is nothing
hateful in ``Corpus Christi.''
</P>
<P>
   And if others see it that way, why attack? Why not simply turn
the other cheek?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
