<HEADER>
A4485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DYLAN-CONCERT-BOS &LR;      10-13 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYLAN-CONCERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS DYLAN CONCERT OF 1966 RELEASED COMMERCIALLY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not many pop stars attain the status of icon, not in
their lifetimes anyway, and not in the deepest sense of the word,
which carries connotations of the holy and stirs the faithful
beyond appreciation to a concentrated awe.
</P>
<P>
   If there is an iconic figure still roaming the landscape of
American pop, it's Bob Dylan _ maybe only Dylan, whose mystique in
recent years has grown, deepened, and broadened, even as his
creative output has dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   The proof was on display here last week at the Museum of
Television and Radio, where hundreds gathered to hear a panel
discussion on two old-new Dylan releases _ a double CD of his
famous May 17, 1966, concert in Manchester, England, and an
hourlong film of that concert, called ``Eat the Document,'' that
has not been seen anywhere for 26 years. (The museum, at 25 W. 52d
St., is showing it through Nov. 20.)
</P>
<P>
   The Manchester concert _ long available on pirate LPs but
released commercially by Columbia Tuesday, as ``Live 1966: The
`Royal Albert Hall' Concert'' _ was the penultimate date on Dylan's
first tour with an electric band. The tour with the group, called
the Hawks (later known as the Band), caused a historic uproar.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists waxed philosophic on the implications of this
band, this concert, the songs Dylan was writing and singing, the
transitions he was wrenching himself through, and the transitions
he was reflecting _ and amplifying, so to speak _ in society.
</P>
<P>
   Greil Marcus, the rock critic-historian and author of
``Invisible Republic,'' which links Dylan's work from this era to
an underground tradition of American folk music dating back a
century, laid out the context of the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an unprecedented, self-conscious revolution in all
the arts,'' he reminded the audience at the museum. ``People were
saying, `I can do what's never been done before, win what's never
been won before''' _ a Dylan lyric _ ``and going out and proving
it. There was Jean-Luc Godard's `Weekend,' Roth's `Portnoy's
Complaint.' People were saying, `Can you believe he's doing that?'
And most people were responding, `No, I can't. Give me more.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rosenbaum, the lit-sleuth who has plumbed the depths of
texts from Shakespeare to Pynchon to Hitler, went further, seeing
the mid-'60s Dylan as foraging the dark corners of the
post-Holocaust subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``People often say he stopped doing protest songs at this time,
but I think he was shifting to a more radical protest,'' Rosenbaum
proclaimed. ``He's not protesting political injustice _ that's
taken for granted. He's protesting the very order of the universe,
or lack of it. It's a protest against the laws of gravity _ against
the lack of gravity, in the sense of seriousness and
meaningfulness. I think he's angry that the universe is absurd.''
Many of his songs are about being abandoned by a woman, but this is
metaphor. ``He's feeling that he's living in a universe that's been
abandoned by God.''
</P>
<P>
   All this started to seem a bit over the edge. But then another
panelist, D.A. Pennebaker _ who directed an earlier Dylan
documentary, the classic ``Don't Look Back,'' and served as
cameraman on ``Eat the Document'' _ supplied the coup de theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samuel Beckett, before he died, asked me for a script of
`Don't Look Back,''' Pennebaker revealed. ``Beckett never referred
to Dylan by name. He always called him `The Poet.' He'd say, `Could
you bring me the script of The Poet?'''
</P>
<P>
   If Beckett, the 20th century's bleakest black-humor playwright,
saw a soul mate in Dylan, maybe Rosenbaum was on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum himself added a capper. He interviewed Dylan at great
length in the late 1970s for Playboy. ``At one point,'' he
recalled, ``Dylan kept harping on about how all the troubles of our
world can be traced back to that Time magazine cover in the '60s
that read, `Is God Dead?' Dylan told me, `What if you were God?
What if you saw that cover? You'd be pissed off!'''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Invisible Republic,'' Marcus wrote that Dylan was shifting
to a more elemental, individual, genuinely traditional concept of
folk music than the social-protest songs of the early '60s _ a folk
music, as Dylan once described it, ``based on myth and the Bible
and plague and famine and all kinds of things like that, which are
nothing but mystery.'' It was a concept not incompatible with
electric thunder.
</P>
<P>
   The film and CD confirm the longstanding reports that much of
the audience hated this new sound. The previous summer, at the
Newport Folk Festival, Dylan had famously plugged in an electric
guitar and unleashed howls of rage. (Pete Seeger tried to cut
Dylan's power cords with an ax backstage.) Dylan himself was shaken
by the catcalls, and came back for a reprise strumming his acoustic
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time of the Manchester show, Marcus noted, the hoots
and hollers had become ``a game for Dylan.'' Pennebaker agreed:
``His idea of putting on a show that stunned people _ that's what
made him happy.'' At an earlier concert in France, Dylan came
onstage against the backdrop of a huge American flag _ during the
height of French anti-Americanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dylan was celebrating insolence, as something that artists at
the top of their game sometimes radiate,'' Rosenbaum reflected.
``He knew he was doing something absolutely extraordinary and he
didn't care what people thought of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The degree of anger heard from the audience, on the second disc
of the concert (on the first, he plays solo acoustic to reverential
applause), is Munich-beer-hall frightening. At one point, Dylan
tries to start a song but he's drowned out and disoriented by the
angry masses, stomping their feet off the beat. People yell
``Sellout!'' and worse at every break.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus posited an eyebrow-raising thesis. Dylan's music, he
noted, came as no surprise to this audience. They had heard about
Newport. ``They knew exactly what they were going to be getting,
and they were ready to fight it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were British folk-music clubs all over the UK,'' he went
on, ``and they were run by the Communist Party.'' Even more than in
the States, where folkies tended to be sentimental leftists but not
hardball communists, this faction of the audience saw Dylan as a
traitor to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Another panelist, Betsy Bowden _ a Chaucer professor at Rutgers
University who had just flown in from a conference in Arizona that
compared the concept albums of Dylan and Frank Sinatra _ thought
Marcus was going too far. ``I have a more benign attitude toward
folklorists,'' she shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the protesters' motivations, Dylan and the Band hammer
back by turning out their most riveting rock concert on record _
much fiercer than anything on ``The Basement Tapes'' or their 1974
reunion concert. Even now, long after the sound has been
assimilated, it feels like a gale of fresh air, a joyous fist of
free expression.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan sings that great refrain from ``Ballad of a Thin Man''
(``You know somethin's happenin'/-But you don't know what it is/-Do
you, Mr. Jones?'') with a wonderful, withering sneer. It's not
square suburbia that's Mr. Jones, it's this audience, it's his
former fans! And you can practically feel the shock bouncing off
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the concert, someone cries out ``Judas!'' and
many laugh and applaud. Dylan shouts back, ``I don't believe you''
_ an odd response, until you remember that, a bit earlier, he sang
his 1964 song called ``I Don't Believe You,'' about a girl whose
``skirt swayed as the guitar played/her mouth was watery and wet''
but the next morning ``acts like we never met.'' Again, he's
telling his audience: You're like that girl. You're the turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he turns to guitarist Robbie Robertson, tells him, ``Play
(expletive) loud!'' and launches into a mind-blowingly raucous
rendition of ``Like a Rolling Stone,'' laying into the line that
ends ``... couldn't yoooouuuuuuu!'' with cheery contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan and the Hawks had more than 50 dates scheduled into the
fall. Who knows where they would have taken this music? But then
Dylan had his motorcycle accident, he went into seclusion, the
Hawks moved on to become the Band, the Zeitgeist changed _ the
folk-rock schism, which Dylan had straddled and incited, came down
on rock's side _ and Dylan emerged with a newer sound still (which
culminated in his masterpiece, ``Blood on the Tracks'').
</P>
<P>
   On that night in Manchester, though, the doors of history can
clearly be seen and heard swinging. As Marcus promised the crowd at
the museum, ``You've never heard anything like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTSIN-MEDDLE-NOT-NY     10-13 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-MEDDLE-NOT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE, YELTSIN. DO NOT MEDDLE IN THE NEW GOVERNMENT'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish it as a ``separate
buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _
from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    On Oct. 7 millions of people demonstrated in the streets of
Russian cities. Their protest was responsible, their behavior
moderate, with no sign of extremism.
 &HT;    The demonstrators' main demand was for the resignation of
President Yeltsin and early elections of both the president and the
State Duma. It was a clear verdict on the political regime and the
kind of ``shock'' reforms that the country has had to endure for
the past seven years.
 &HT;    Russia is at a dangerous threshold. The clock shows five minutes
to midnight.
 &HT;    Yet, observers noted, the government of Yevgeny Primakov was
spared the demonstrators' criticism. Primakov, his first deputy
Yuri Maslyukov and the new Central Bank president Viktor
Gerashchenko had not been eager for jobs in the Russian cabinet. In
fact, they took some time before deciding to come on board. That
they finally agreed to carry this burden in the present dire
circumstances is a credit to them. These people are capable of
giving priority to the national interests rather than the narrow
interest of those who have become fabulously and unjustifiably rich
during the years of pseudo-reforms.
 &HT;    The new government, however, has already come under criticism
from extreme free-marketeers in Russia and in the West. Primakov is
being accused of dragging his feet and of lacking a clear economic
program. There is concern that the team may backtrack from market
economics. Much is being made of their past, such as the fact that
Maslyukov was chairman of Gosplan, the Soviet Union's central
planning agency.
 &HT;    I must disagree with this rush to judgment. I know these men,
their views and their character. During the years of perestroika
they were firmly in favor of reforms.
 &HT;    In spring 1990, Maslyukov was ready to resign from Prime
Minister Nikolai Ryzhkov's government, accusing him of stalling on
much-needed change. Other members of the new cabinet have also
shown on many occasions their commitment to socially responsible
market economics and democracy.
 &HT;    It would certainly be too soon to demand that they produce an
elaborate, detailed program or far-reaching decisions on how to
advance reforms at the very moment they have to focus on how to
stabilize the overall situation and avoid total disaster. This
might require measures, some of which could resemble a return to
command economics. But don't rush to label the new government
``anti-reform.''
 &HT;    The steps that may be needed to take the situation in hand do
not mean that reforms are being abandoned. They are the price that
must be paid for the misguided policies of the recent past. If
chaos became total, any reforms would have to be written off and we
would see a very different government, an economic dictatorship.
 &HT;    During the time needed to put the real economy _ the production
of goods and services _ back on track, we shall need aid and loans.
Even more than aid, we shall need direct investment and cooperation
projects. After what happened here, creditors and investors are
understandably doubtful about dealing with Russia. I feel, however,
that Primakov and Gerashchenko will be able to persuade the world
that they are serious people and responsible partners.
 &HT;    So both the West and our own economic radicals would do well not
to push the new team. Do not scare people with the prospect of a
``return to communism.'' Russia has made an irrevocable choice.
Even the communists, the lunatic fringe excepted, are saying that
the clock cannot be turned back. So let us not panic; let us work
with quiet determination.
 &HT;    I am afraid, though, that the government could be dealt a blow
from an unexpected quarter, and where it is least protected. I am
afraid the president might try to meddle in the government's work.
Even worse, he could reshuffle it before it had a chance to make a
difference. I have reason to believe that Yeltsin's entourage is
already intriguing to make this happen.
 &HT;    The president should be reminded that such things have always
turned out badly, for himself as well as for the country. It would
be best for all of us if the president gave the Primakov government
a carte blanche _ and then called for early elections of president
and parliament.
 &HT;    Concerns about the results of early elections are, I believe,
exaggerated. The Russians will not support extremists or
irresponsible populists. Today, much more than before, there is a
good chance for the emergence of a coalition of moderate, centrist
forces capable of winning a majority in the Duma and fielding a
strong candidate for president. Tomorrow, that chance could
disappear.
 &HT;    Who that candidate would be depends in large part on the
``content'' of the presidency. I believe that the constitution
should be amended in order to allocate more power to the parliament
and the cabinet.
 &HT;    With a more reasonable balance of government powers, the
president would no longer be a monarch in democratic clothing, nor
would he be able to usurp power and paralyze the federal
government, as Yeltsin was able to do.
 &HT;    The president would become a true guardian of the constitution
and of the people's rights and freedoms _ the nation's moral and
political leader. Primakov could turn out to be just the right man
for this role.
 &HT;    The Cabinet of Ministers would then become the main body of the
executive branch of government. And, although the mayor of Moscow,
Yuri Luzhkov, has already declared his readiness to run for
president, I think that he is better suited for the role of prime
minister.
 &HT;    I urge our Western partners to analyze the political realignment
now under way in Russia without prejudging it and with a
willingness to help Russia. Objectively, Russia may now have a
chance to begin recovering, and gradually reemerge as a serious and
dependable international player.
 &HT;     (Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko)  
 &HT;     c.1998 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston. He lectures widely
around the world and writes a monthly commentary column for La
Stampa, a newspaper in Turin, Italy.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
