r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GAYKILLING-AZR &LR;      10-13 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROOF GOOD OUTWEIGHS EVIL  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE OCT. 13 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
 KILLING-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - In the contest between good and evil, good often looks
like a sap. The bad guys' deeds get the press. Their actions
command attention that decency and gentleness can't match.
</P>
<P>
   Take what happened in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The two men charged with beating another to death are national
names. They are charged with murderous brutality against a man
because he was a homosexual. That has led to calls for new hate
crimes legislation. It has underlined what some people in Laramie
say is a ``complacency and apathy'' about hostility toward gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Henderson and Aaron McKinney share the spotlight because
of their alleged viciousness. Their capacity for evil.
</P>
<P>
   They are charged with luring Matthew Shepard from a bar and
beating him so savagely that he died five days later. Kristen
Price, McKinney's girlfriend and mother of their 4-month-old son,
told the ``Denver Post'' the two men were embarrassed because
Shepard had made a pass at them. They wanted to get even, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard was pistol-whipped with a .357 Magnum. A bicyclist found
him unconscious and tied to a fence post outside town.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants earned their infamy. The town that spawned them
deserves scrutiny. Charges that Shepard was targeted for violent
assault because of his sexual orientation are like a shrieking
alarm in Laramie, which is called the ``hometown'' of Wyoming _
nicknamed the Equality State because it was the first to let women
vote.
</P>
<P>
   The nation can't ignore the injustice of prejudice directed at
people simply because of their sexual orientation. America can't
ignore the human cost of hating someone so much that the person
ceases to be treated as human.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something else in this sad story that deserves
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The response to Shepard's beating was a flash of decency from
people who refuse to accept such actions.
</P>
<P>
   About a thousand people met for a candlelight vigil Sunday night
near the University of Wyoming campus to support Shepard. There was
another candlelight vigil at the Fort Collins, Colo., hospital
where he lay dying. There was a parade in his honor. So many
flowers arrived at the hospital in his name that staff had to
divert some to other patients. His room was full.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Shepard may not have known of the kindness of these
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation knows.
</P>
<P>
   And in the name of wiping out hate, the nation ought to
celebrate the good that continues to outnumber the evil. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
