<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-LATIN-HNS &LR;      10-13 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-LATIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARMEDIA BANKS ON GROWTH OF INTERNET IN LATIN AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Private investors are betting nearly $100
million that Latin America will be the next front in the
information revolution.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia Inc., a 2-year-old New York-based Internet company
that publishes a multifeature Web site exclusively for Latin
America, announced Monday it had received $80 million in private
funding.
</P>
<P>
   That investment, made by such companies as Warburg, Pincus &AMP;
Co., General Electric Equity Capital Group and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co., brings StarMedia's investor war chest to $96.1
million, gathered since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say this is the largest private investment in a
privately held on-line company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have managed to come up with a pretty big capital raising
at the intersection of two of the most volatile investment themes
in America: the Internet and Latin America,'' said Lanny Baker, an
analyst of on-line media industry for Salomon Smith Barney in San
Francisco. ``That's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constructing a pan-country network for Spanish- and
Portuguese-speaking people,'' said StarMedia's 32-year-old founder,
chairman and chief executive Fernando Espuela. ``This round of
financing will let us continue to become a unifying force across
Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   The StarMedia Web site is fashioned after two well-known Web
success stories: America Online and Yahoo. Like AOL, StarMedia
contains news, free e-mail, classifieds and personal ads, chat
rooms and other content, which is generated by StarMedia staff
located in New York, Miami and eight Latin American countries,
including Brazil, Mexico and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Like Yahoo, StarMedia does not charge a fee for access, instead
relying on advertisements from companies such as Ford and Citibank
to generate revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drew from both models,'' said Espuela, who expects his
company to be profitable by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Espuela said StarMedia was created, in part, to take advantage
of the explosive growth in Latin America Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey conducted by the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi
advertising agency, Latin American computer users will increase
fivefold, to some 34 million, by the turn of the century. U.S.
computer use, by contrast, will increase threefold by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Espuela said the Latin America Internet market is skipping the
development stage and moving right into a full-fledged mass media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that's leapfrogging technologies,'' Espuela
said. ``Latin America isn't going through all this technological
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Espuela, a native of Uruguay, says the idea for StarMedia came
to him while he was sitting on a mountain in Nepal, trying to
decide what to do with his life after reaching the executive ranks
of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling very empty,'' he said. ``I had gotten this
promotion, but I really didn't want it. Then I had a realization,
that the Internet was going to be the biggest thing, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia is just one player in the burgeoning
non-English-speaking Web field, which has been estimated to now
include some 107 million users and counting. According to
Emarketer, a New York-based Internet research group, the number of
Internet users from outside the United States will begin to
outnumber those inside the country by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   And StarMedia isn't playing on an empty field. Latin America's
explosive Internet growth has spawned a number of popular Web
sites, including Brazil's Universo Online and Zaz. Both of these
sites dominate the coveted Brazilian Internet on-line market, in
which an estimated 79 percent of all Internet connections are made
by consumers, according to a recent study by IDC, a Framingham,
Mass., technology research firm. That same study found that Mexico
home users account for only 29 percent of Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet in Latin America is just so new,'' Baker said.
``Although StarMedia has grabbed a huge brand recognition lead in a
very short time, there's going to be a lot of jockeying for
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having that $96 million is going to certainly help
StarBright. No question about that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
