<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-CARDOSO-VICTOR     10-13 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-CARDOSO-VICTORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRAZIL, CARDOSO'S VICTORY IS TOO COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JORGE G. CASTANEDA  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, though by a much smaller margin than foreseen,
Fernando Henrique Cardoso was re-elected president of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   As expected also, his country will receive an aid package of
about $30 billion from the international financial community,
though the difficulties in raising it are also somewhat greater
than forecast.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, finally, Cardoso will have to begin his second
four-year term with a draconian austerity program, though
resistance to it in the Brazilian congress and state governments
will be stronger than anticipated. Why? It is a program that will
worsen unemployment, recession, skyrocketing interest rates and
social inequality.
</P>
<P>
   And by now, for this nation trapped in a self-induced economic
downturn since last October, a moderate devaluation of the currency
is also likely in store.
</P>
<P>
   So what lessons can be drawn?
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso's re-election entailed a heavy cost for Brazil. More
than $30 billion in reserves were spent over the last two months to
prevent a devaluation in Brazil's currency that probably will occur
anyway but that coming sooner would have doomed Cardoso's bid for
another term.
</P>
<P>
   The new currency put in place by Cardoso in 1994, when he was
finance minister, allowed him to control Brazil's hyperinflation
and was sufficiently impressive to lead to his first-term election
as president. In October 1997, when the Asian financial crisis hit,
millions of Brazilians were laid off while the government, seeking
to bolster the real, was forced to cut spending, raise interest
rates and cool down the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, Brazil's interest rates have remained at
stratospheric levels. Without them, the tens of billions of foreign
dollars the country sought to attract would have left, or never
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   There were options to Cardoso's measures. In fact, the most
important costs incurred by Brazil are the very changes a different
president might have implemented:
</P>
<P>
   _ to give up the frozen exchange rate once inflation had been
brought under control;
</P>
<P>
   _ to discourage speculative capital from entering the country
through controls and taxes on entry or early exit.
</P>
<P>
   This, together with a different set of alliances and a much
greater effort to reduce inequality, attain high growth rates and
create millions of stable, decent paying jobs, would have been the
heart of an alternative to Cardoso's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Which points directly to the second lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian left, led for the third time in 10 years by former
metalworker Luiz Ignacio Lula da Silva, must answer a number of
tough questions today that it has avoided for more than a decade.
Some are the typical, superficial charges made against da Silva _
that he represents an insufficiently ``modernized'' left and
opposes many features of the so-called neo-liberal economic reform
program applied in Brazil and elsewhere in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   But let's reach beyond the standard, often senseless criticism
directed at the left for merely being the left.
</P>
<P>
   The key question in Brazil is the same as in Mexico, Chile, El
Salvador and Argentina _ all countries where a strong left will be
contending for the presidency between now and the year 2000. It is
whether the left should contend on its principles alone, without
compromising its stances, even if that foretells defeat, or instead
support centrist candidates and programs able to win, but
inevitably less committed to social change.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the left wing of da Silva's Workers' Party forced him
to be their standard bearer for the third time in order to avoid
supporting a more centrist, appealing candidate, the former
governor and finance minister, Ciro Gomes. Had the party adopted
Gomes as their candidate from the outset, they might have been able
to take better advantage of a theoretically ideal situation: an
incumbent running on his economic program at the precise moment it
collapses.
</P>
<P>
   As the young, competent, professional opposition candidate
running amid an intensifying economic and social crisis, with
rising unemployment and recession, Gomes might have attracted a
combination of the party's strong labor, peasant and student
constituency with a ready middle-class electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Workers' Party machinery refused to risk a
reduced presence in Brazil's congress and statehouses in exchange
for a definite shot at the presidency. They forced da Silva to run,
largely against his will. The result was the re-election of
Cardoso, who could have been beat _ and indeed, even da Silva did
substantially better than last-minute polls suggested.
</P>
<P>
   There is a case to be made for standing on principle and losing.
But in a region where the left has been banned from power for so
many years yet, at the same time, remains on-target in so many of
its analyses and criticisms of the status quo, there is probably a
better case to be made for compromise and victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine and Chilean left seem to have reached this
conclusion; the Salvadorean and Mexican left, not quite yet. The
example of what just happened in Brazil might serve them all in
good stead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1540EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
