AIRLINE PASSENGERS LIVING IN THE `ZONE' 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The term ``peanut fares'' may soon take on new meaning in the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation has notified U.S. airlines of
its position that peanut-free ``buffer zones'' should be created
aboard airplanes upon advance request by passengers with medically
documented severe allergies to peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   These zones would consist, at the minimum, of the passengers'
row and the rows immediately in front and behind.
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it: No offense to thousands of Americans said to be
bothered by peanuts, but your immediate reaction _ like mine _ was
to laugh, right? I can just envision an already-beleaguered flight
attendant patrolling the aisle prior to takeoff, asking, ``Is your
seat belt fastened? Your briefcase all the way beneath your seat?
All peanuts locked in your purse?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A peanut tax? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will those passengers still requesting peanuts _ the only
``cuisine'' served on some flights these days _ pay a higher
tariff? Perhaps a peanut tax? And will there be separate seating
sections for those preferring their peanuts salted, honey-roasted
or mixed with cashews and almonds?
</P>
<P>
   But, then, I got to thinking that the DOT may be onto something
here. Modern-day computer systems are so advanced that, utilizing
sophisticated passenger profiles, these peanut-free zones can be
established _ and adjusted _ within seconds for individual flights.
</P>
<P>
   So why stop with peanuts? Welcome to Air Shattuck, where we
really organize cabin interiors.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start with ``no-conversation'' buffer zones. Have you ever
plopped into a middle seat dog-tired and ready for a catnap only to
be verbally accosted by the guy on the aisle determined to
embellish every detail about his job, his car, his family or _ my
predicament on one recent flight _ his gallbladder surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we'll still encourage courtesy how-do-you-do's throughout
the aircraft. But if you intend to babble on incessantly at 35,000
feet, you'll be assigned elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also be required to let us know in advance if you plan to
use a laptop or if you intend to make more than one call on the
airphone at your seat. And for overnight flights, we'll separate
those who wish to read and those who prefer to sleep _ with an
additional distinction among the second group for snorers and
nonsnorers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who disdain cologne or perfume, or worse, deodorant _
another allergy, I presume _ will be grouped, too. Maybe with the
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   We'll require a medical certificate attesting to bladder size
and function. No stepping on innocent toes in a frantic rush aboard
Air Shattuck; passengers with weak bladders will automatically get
an aisle seat near the lavatory.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rest easy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We'll also keep recliners and nonrecliners apart. Isn't it
amazing how, just as you release the food tray _ in the
peanuts-allowed section, that is _ the passenger in the row ahead
adjusts his seat so that his hair is in your lap? Be thankful at
least that he isn't Dennis Rodman. But we'll solve that problem.
With our passenger profile system, all reclining passengers will
sit together.
</P>
<P>
   I was going to create a ``kid zone,'' too. But Israel's El Air
Airlines beat me to it. El Air's new 15-row, 150-seat section on
some Boeing 747 jets caters specifically to families with small
children; passengers receive a kit with diapers, formula and a
pacifier, and only G-rated videos are shown on movie screens in the
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, shame on you for requesting X-rated movies in the
``adults-only'' sections.
</P>
<P>
   Those kiddie zones give me an idea, though. If we put enough
tiny tots together in one section of the plane, we can squeeze more
seats into those rows. That will allow us _ without affecting
revenues _ to establish separate ``wide-bodied sections.'' (Hey,
it's my airline!)
</P>
<P>
   Or with passenger profiles, maybe we'll just require an advance
listing of waist sizes _ I'm already shamed enough to begin
weight-reduction program No. 4,621 _ and make certain a stringbean
sits between every two heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   I won't get into religious preferences. Or politics. Well, with
these exceptions: Republicans will be seated near the right wing,
Democrats beside the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing: Avid Starr backers and Clinton
supporters will all be assigned to the no-conversation zone. With
G-rated videos.
</P>
<P>
   Time to stop. I've got to purchase popcorn for folks in the
peanut-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone allergic to melted butter? &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
