<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREUD-CORRECT-WHEN-NY     10-13 2516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREUD-CORRECT-WHEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT FREUD GOT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By KEN ADELMAN  
 FROM: Washingtonian Magazine  
 &HT;    The 20th century opened with Sigmund Freud publishing ``The
Interpretation of Dreams'' and closes with Freud so controversial
that not long ago the Library of Congress postponed an exhibit on
him. In October the library again hopes to display its large
collection of original Freud works.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, psychiatrists such as Sandra Gail Hershberg practice
Freud's craft and use his techniques.
 &HT;    Born and raised in the Bronx, N.Y., Dr. Hershberg graduated from
New York University and Yale Medical School. After an internship in
pediatrics at the University Hospitals of Cleveland and a residency
in general psychiatry at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York, she
completed a fellowship in child and adolescent psychiatry. She is a
graduate of the Washington Psychoanalytic Institute.
 &HT;    Hershberg specializes in child and adolescent psychiatry, the
psychology of female development, and the psychological dimensions
of medical illness. She lives in Bethesda with her husband, a
physician, and their two adolescent daughters. She enjoys reading
fiction, antiquing, watching old movies and biking.
 &HT;    In her office, lined with Freud's complete works and featuring a
couch, we discussed what she's learned.
 -0 
 &HT;    KEN ADELMAN: What makes Freud so incendiary a century after he
started writing?
 &HT;    DR. SANDRA GAIL HERSHBERG: Three things come to mind. People
today often view psychoanalysis negatively _ as a luxury treatment
that takes a long time and is very expensive. So it's thought that
Freud's method doesn't work any longer. At least, that it's been
surpassed by medication, group therapy, family counseling, or other
techniques. I've found that's wrong.
 &HT;    The psychoanalytic method is alive and well. To me it's an
exciting and meaningful treatment. But it's no quick fix. People
now seek to do everything faster and faster. Western Union's been
replaced by the Internet. So many people no longer have the
patience for psychoanalysis they once did.
 &HT;    Second is this big category summarized as comprising ``women.''
The way Freud viewed women _ as having inferior superegos and penis
envy and all that _ opened him to harsh criticism. I'm with the
critics here. I don't agree with Freud much on this score. Some of
what he said on women has some relevance. But there are much more
complex and productive ways of looking at women and gender than
what he presented.
 &HT;    Third is Freud's treatment of sexual seduction and abuse as a
type of fantasy. He initially did think there was real sexual
abuse, but then switched when he attributed patient accounts to
subconscious fantasies.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What did Freud get right?
 &HT;    A: When considering Freud in his own times _ he was a pioneer,
there was no one before him; he used his cases and his
self-analysis as data _ I'm impressed at how much Freud got right.
Every brilliant individual who makes discoveries makes errors along
the way. Freud made many important contributions.
 &HT;    First and foremost was the nature of the inner life, the
significance and meaning of the unconscious. Freud pioneered the
use of free association. Through his analyses of others and
self-analysis, Freud delineated the concept of psychosexual
development, the child's progression through various developmental
stages.
 &HT;    Unconscious motivation was and is an enormous discovery. It
permeates our lives and culture. Fantasy and creativity are central
to modern life. The fact that we never fully know our less rational
motivation is a staggering insight. Freud developed all that.
 &HT;    Moreover, Freud showed greatness in his willingness to revise
his theories based on new clinical information. He was thus
open-minded in an honest, scientific way. Freud got carried away by
his ideas and his narcissism in deciding to psychoanalyze his
daughter Anna. His putting his daughter on the couch and hearing
her innermost thoughts and fantasies in that way breached an
important boundary.
 &HT;    Clearly Anna Freud identified with her father through her
trailblazing work with children and her defining contributions in
the field of child development and child psychoanalysis.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Was Freud an attack on free will?
 &HT;    A: I don't see it that way. Not at all. Because of unconscious
factors, we make choices on the basis of more than rational free
will. That's true. But Freud's thrust makes one freer, not less
free. For people truly suffering _ as his patients did, as many of
my patients do, and as all of us do from time to time throughout
our lives _ Freud showed us a technique to better understand and
treat conflicts that result in feelings of shame, disgust, guilt,
etc.
 &HT;    Freud frees us by enabling us to be aware of inner connections
and see deeper motivations. That's at least been my experience with
patients. Once they're able to peer into their innermost feelings,
memories, fantasies, they can then make real choices. Freud knew
psychology and biology went together. As a trained neurologist, he
always searched for the biological basis of psychology. The concept
of mind versus brain interested him deeply.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Why should someone choose psychoanalysis over drugs, a
family-systems approach, group therapy or yoga?
 &HT;    A: Pharmacotherapy helps with symptom relief. Drugs can
accompany psychoanalysis or another therapy for someone who's
extremely depressed or with a manic-depressive disorder.
Psychoanalysis works best with patients who suffer from traumas or
other early experiences they haven't integrated well.
 &HT;    It opens up an opportunity to be in a safe situation with
someone committed to exploring such experiences in depth. This
enables the patient to transform internal representations and thus
to act and feel better. They can be freer.
 &HT;    Granted, other therapies do that too. But to me psychoanalysis
provides that help in a deeper and broader way than the other
approaches. It opens a greater sense of meaning and knowing one's
internal motivations.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Do you still use a couch?
 &HT;    A: Yes. I usually sit behind the patient, out of view _ like
Freud. The patient's usually lying down.
 &HT;    Q: What's your average length of treating one patient?
 &HT;    A: More than two years and up to 10 or 12 years _ or more. It
really depends.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How did you feel as a patient?
 &HT;    A: Undergoing psychoanalysis was an essential part of my
professional training. It had a very important, even dramatic,
impact upon my life and it made me more aware of what the process
is like for the patient. That made me a better analyst because I
both knew myself better and knew what this process was like on the
other side of the couch.
 &HT;    Psychoanalysis made me much more aware of who I am as a person _
what interests me, how I pursue creative interests, act as a
parent, and what I carry from my own childhood which then gets
aroused in me as an adult. Knowing all this, and these responses,
makes me freer to act _ more of being my own person.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Being a parent, I wonder if Freud really blamed neuroses
almost entirely on the mother.
 &HT;    A: Mothers do have a tough time and a tough job. By emphasizing
the importance of early childhood experiences, Freud did put
mothers at the center of traumas and such early episodes. But
remember that in cases like little Hans, Freud focused on the
father as well. I don't see it as being hard on mothers so much as
trying to understand the nature of the conflict in front of him.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Which groups get maddest at Freud?
 &HT;    A: We've all gotten mad at Freud. But too many have treated
Freud as the last word. They expect too much of him. No one gets it
all right. Certainly Freud didn't. By focusing on so many
cornerstones of the theory of the mind, development, and
psychopathology, Freud opened the door for others to modify and
change the theory. I think that even he would embrace that view. He
did change his theories when shown contrary evidence.
 &HT;    Remember, Freud was a man of his time. He was limited by the
milieu and context in which he worked. The field was brand new
then. There wasn't much to go on. Some of Freud's blind spots
reflect that. Many times he went beyond these constraints and made
enduring insights. And that's why he's still prized, and praised.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've lectured on creativity?
 &HT;    A: Freud wrote a lot on the subject. His office was full of art
pieces, mostly antiquities. Freud read constantly on art and had
many artistic friends. In a paper analyzing Dostoyevski, Freud
said, ``Before the problem of the creative artist, an analyst must
alas lay down his arms. '' Freud thus recognized that he was at a
loss when analyzing creativity. But then, as on most topics, he
proceed to say a lot on the topic.
 &HT;    Freud writes beautifully. I hope the Library of Congress exhibit
and the resulting conferences will prompt more people to read what
Freud actually wrote, rather than what other people have written
about Freud. Works like ``The Psychopathology of Everyday Life,''
``The Interpretation of Dreams'' and ``Civilization and Its
Discontents'' are accessible to the average person.
 &HT;    One of my favorite essays of Freud's was ``Creative Writers and
Daydreaming. '' There he says, ``The child's best loved and most
intense occupation is with his play or games. Might we not say that
every child at play behaves like a creative writer in that he
creates a world of his own, or rather rearranges the thing of his
world in a new way which pleases him?''
 &HT;    While a child takes play seriously, Freud pointed out that he
``distinguishes it quite well from reality.'' Freud concludes:
``The creative writer does the same as the child's play. He creates
a world of fantasy which he takes very seriously _ that which he
invests with large amounts of emotion, while separating it sharply
from reality.''
 &HT;    Freud goes on in this vein of comparing play and creative
writing. It's a very lovely essay.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What makes creativity?
 &HT;    A: Many artists had an early appreciation of the sensual world.
Sometimes even an early trauma. Edgar Allen Poe's mother died when
he was quite young. Poe saw her body then in all its horror. That
description appears in some of his later stories. Magritte's mother
jumped off a bridge and drowned. You can see that sense of time
standing still and unreal nature in his work.
 &HT;    Many creative people were ill or had a lot of time to
themselves. They then became more aware of their own thinking and
fantasies _ their inner workings. For those of us less gifted, we
must find a way to bring out the creativity within us. I see
psychoanalysis as a very creative act. In that space between me and
a patient, something exceptional happens.
 &HT;    I take in a vast range of images, fantasies and feelings from an
analysis, and I respond on a similar level. It's a most exciting
and creative endeavor. I'm very privileged to be able to help
people in need, to free them from symptomatic behavior.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How can we increase our creativity?
 &HT;    A: Give yourself time every day when you're not busy with
something else. Allow your thoughts then to flow out. When Freud
was very young, he'd place a blank sheet of paper in front of
himself every day, just to see what would come up. That was a way
to expand his creativity.
 &HT;    You can see how he was always interested in learning about
himself. This led him into the unconscious, being able to connect
with inner thoughts and emotions. That's what creativity's all
about and what psychoanalysis is about.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've also lectured on eating disorders. Is that an
upper-class, female adolescent disease?
 &HT;    A: Basically. It's not only teen-agers but young adult women as
well. I've treated so many that it appears to me like a societal
disease.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What causes it?
 &HT;    A: It involves a girl coming to terms with her body, with sexual
feelings, and relationships with each of her parents, particularly
with her mother. She must develop a sense of herself with
confidence _ just who she is in the world. While this sounds like
the adolescent struggle in general, some women are of a
perfectionist bent and more preoccupied with their bodies. They
have more eating disorders than others. But adolescent boys
body-build and strut around. They too fixate on their bodies.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: So why don't they have eating disorders?
 &HT;    A: The incidence of eating disorders in boys is on the rise;
however, our culture emphasizes beauty mostly in the female body.
Look at our advertisements. Girls must look a certain way, wear
makeup, watch every ounce of fat. There's a different emphasis on
the female body for the girl, and for her mother and father, which
is generally less pronounced in boys.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: You've studied women who have careers. Give us lessons
learned there.
 &HT;    A: The opportunities to be fulfilled by one's work are ever
increasing in our society. That's so wonderful. Not that women get
compensated equally for their work _ they don't yet _ but they can
fulfill such ambitions more easily nowadays. That's important. For
working mothers, it's essential to keep open all lines of
communication.
 &HT;    From professional experience I've learned that sometimes my kids
need more of me. Sometimes they need less of me. Occasionally they
don't need me at all, for a while.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is the incidence of mothers with careers increasing?
 &HT;    A: Yes, but we should look at how the whole family functions in
that household. The real problem arises when one parent becomes so
absorbed that he or she doesn't realize what's missing in the
family.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What have you learned from Freud?
 &HT;    A: The main thing is the primacy of one's inner life. That
determines so much of how we think and behave. As an analyst, I'm
very grateful to Freud for his methodology, which is very much a
part of my way of working and helping others.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What are the main lessons of life?
 &HT;    A: Psychological health is based on the capacities to love, to
work, and to play, as Freud indicated. To be able to maintain a
balance of those abilities makes for a satisfying and fulfilling
life.
 &HT;     c.1998 Washingtonian Magazine  
