<SLUG> BC-BOOKSTORE-BANKRUPTCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER BOOK CHAIN RESTYLES ITSELF TO COMPETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANNE JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILDERLAND, N.Y. _ Lauriat's, the East Coast chain of
bookstores that filed for bankruptcy protection earlier this year,
is beginning a new chapter, the privately-held company's new chief
executive says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to compete head-on with cash-rich superstores,
Lauriat's will go back to a smaller and humbler profile that
emphasizes personal service and a more streamlined inventory, says
Matthew C. Harrison, Jr., a business-turnaround specialist brought
in to head the chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had four problems,'' Harrison said in an interview Monday
at the Crossgates Mall near Albany. ``We had too many unprofitable
locations, too much overhead. We had lost focus with some stores
competing directly with superstores.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, the chain was undercapitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said the chain, which operates stores under the
Lauriat's, Encore and Royal names in the Northeast and
Mid-Atlantic, has now worked through many operational problems.
</P>
<P>
   First, the chain shut down 37 unprofitable stores, bringing the
number of locations to 75. And the chain fired some staff at its
Canton, Mass., headquarters, bringing employment there from 60 to
40.
</P>
<P>
   Some locations _ including the one at the Crossgates Mall _
stayed open, but needed special attention to become more viable.
</P>
<P>
   The store had too much floor space for its level of sales. So
Lauriat's downsized the store from 12,441 square feet to 8,624
square feet. The move eliminated the sales of recorded music and
relocated the children's department within the core of the store.
The store also managed to renegotiate its lease to get cheaper
rent, Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The trimmed-down store, selling books, calendars, stationery and
some gifts, should be more profitable and generate more sales per
square foot, Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned store will carry 30,000 to 40,000 titles, said
Patrick White, store manager at Crossgates. Superstore booksellers,
by contrast, carry some 150,000 titles and occupy 65,000 square
feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
