<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-IN-BAKU-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL RUSH IN BAKU 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JEFFREY GOLDBERG &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; FROM: The New York Times Magazine &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan is a former Soviet republic located in a disagreeable
spot just south of Russia and just north of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   It is known for nothing except oil, and the smell of that oil is
inescapable, even inside the cabin of an arthritic helicopter
desperately trying to gain altitude for a trip across the Caspian
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter, a rusting Soviet Mi-8, seems unable to move
forward, which is problematic, because we are already hovering 25
feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Our destination, an offshore pumping complex known as Oily
Rocks, sits 15 miles away. Azerbaijan Airlines inherited the
helicopter from Aeroflot but did not, apparently, inherit spare
parts.
</P>
<P>
   One of these helicopters recently crashed into an oil platform,
initially prompting the president of Azerbaijan's state oil company
to turn down my request for a lift. ``It would be very embarrassing
if foreigners were killed on the way to Oily Rocks,'' Natig Aliev
told me.
</P>
<P>
   But I told Aliev I couldn't leave Azerbaijan without seeing Oily
Rocks, one of the world's largest offshore oil complexes, a place
that would certainly rank as Azerbaijan's greatest tourist
attraction if Azerbaijan had tourists. And so the accommodating
Aliev lifted the ban, for an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After hanging in the air for two minutes, the pilot sets the
helicopter back down. Big yellow rings of sweat stain his shirt. He
tosses off the last man to climb aboard, and returns to his seat.
This time we're off, a single 150-pound oil worker making all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   As we gain altitude, the Apsheron Peninsula spreads out before
us. The ground below is brown and cracked dry in the heat. Crippled
oil pumps dot the landscape all the way back to the capital city,
Baku, which is built on vast reservoirs of oil and gas and is
crowded with ornate buildings that date back to the first great oil
rush here, more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   We fly out over the pale blue Caspian, which is spidered with
mean black slicks of oil. Which makes me think of ... caviar. Just
how safe can Caspian beluga be, if the sturgeon swim in light
crude?
</P>
<P>
   And then, there it is: Oily Rocks, a Stalinist fabulation of
broken-down oil platforms and causeways that stretch past the
horizon. Crosshatched streets, 125 miles of them, rest on pylons
sunk into the seabed.
</P>
<P>
   We touch down on a weedy landing pad and are met by a school bus
that will carry us down the causeways that link one platform to
another. The state oil company has sent a senior executive, Baba
Musayev, to be my official minder. He is a man of about 50,
rough-hewed, with rotting teeth and arms tanned the color of plums.
There is no place like Oily Rocks in the entire world, he says, and
this is true: In the West, oil platforms are built freestanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the Soviet Union,'' Musayev says, ``steel was cheap and
there was a lot of it, so the Soviet mentality said that everything
should be linked by road.''
</P>
<P>
   Oily Rocks is crumbling. Truck-size chunks of it are falling
into the sea, and everything is orange with rust. One-third of the
600 wells are inoperative, and miles and miles of causeway have
broken apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Caspian is rising, and water now laps the second stories of
many buildings, even those that house oil workers. These
eight-story apartment buildings are a remarkable sight. Only the
Soviet Union could build slum housing in the middle of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that we couldn't sustain this when the market
economy came along,'' Musayev tells me, curling his lip when he
says ``market economy.''
</P>
<P>
   We are eating lunch in the cafeteria, fresh greens, white cheese
and boiled chicken, served by dour, henna-haired women. A
photograph of Azerbaijan's president, Heydar Aliyev, watches us
from the wall. It is impossible to avoid Aliyev's image _ or his
influence _ anywhere in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capitalism is only interested in revenue, not in
engineering,'' Musayev continues. And yet he wants to join the
market economy he so distrusts. He has already applied for jobs
with four Western oil companies. He earns $80 a month, and knows
that even drivers for Amoco and Unocal make three or four times
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are already aboard Oily Rocks, in a limited way.
We drive past a yellow-painted facility that shines in the
hammering sun. It is a gas-compression facility just built by
Pennzoil. ``No smoking around here,'' Musayev says, tossing his
cigarette. ``American rules.''
</P>
<P>
   American rules may soon apply to all of Oily Rocks. The complex,
like everything in Azerbaijan, is for sale. The government is
looking for a partner, a Western oil company, that will modernize
this mess. It will surely find one, because Baku is overflowing
with oilmen. The city stands at the center of the first great oil
rush of the 21st century, an oil rush of great consequence for
Washington and Moscow, and for a dozen capitals in between.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars who believe that history ended with the collapse of
communism should visit Baku, because in Baku, nothing is settled.
Who could predict the future of a country that many in Moscow _
volatile, feverish Moscow _ believe shouldn't be a country at all,
but instead a province of a reanimated Russian empire?
</P>
<P>
   In Teheran, Azerbaijan is seen as an unforgivable contradiction:
a secular Shiite state, a country ripe for Islamization. In 10
years' time, Azerbaijan could be an Islamic state, or a
neo-Communist state, or a capitalist democracy, or a capitalist
autocracy, or even part of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan gained its freedom in 1991, but soon lost 15 percent
of its territory to Armenia, which humiliated it in a vicious war.
Azerbaijanis were killing each other too; the country seemed
ungovernable, a failed-state-in-the-making of warlords and
gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993, Aliyev came back to Baku. He was the former
Communist Party boss of Azerbaijan who had gone into self-imposed
rural exile, but returned to Baku and exploited the chaos there.
His bloodless coup brought a temporary stability.
</P>
<P>
   He also brought with him an idea that ensured his country's
independence. There has always been oil in Azerbaijan. Centuries
ago, the Zoroastrians built their fire temples in the hills of
Baku, worshiping the flames that burst from the gas-filled earth.
More than 100 years ago, the Nobel brothers and the Rothschilds
built fortunes on Baku oil. Then the Soviets came, and closed off
Azerbaijan's oil reserves to the West.
</P>
<P>
   It took an ex-KGB general and former Politburo member to open
them up again. For Aliyev, oil wasn't only a commodity; it was
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil is our strategy, it is our defense, it is our
independence,'' Aliyev's foreign-policy adviser, Vafa Gulizade,
told me. ``Iran is dreaming dreams of Azerbaijan, and if the
Russians were strong, they would colonize Azerbaijan. But they
can't because Aliyev invited the whole world in to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, the world's major oil companies, with Aliyev's
encouragement, were busy developing Azerbaijan's neglected oil
wealth. Aliyev's theory was that flag follows trade, and the theory
is proving correct. Aliyev has become Washington's man, and
Azerbaijan's oil has become an issue of great strategic importance
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan sits atop as much as 20 billion barrels of oil, which
makes its reserves smaller than Kuwait's but about the same size as
Nigeria's, from which the United States imports nearly 5 percent of
its oil. Azerbaijan may also become the conduit for even more oil
and natural gas that will flow from Turkmenistan and Kazakhstan, on
the east side of the Caspian.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Caspian region could be the source of as much as
200 billion barrels of oil. For America, the stakes are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Caspian region will hopefully save us from total
dependence on Middle East oil,'' says Bill Richardson, the
secretary of energy and the administration's point man on the
Caspian oil rush. For the oil companies, the opening of the Caspian
means access to tens of billions of dollars of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Western companies have signed oil contracts totaling
$40 billion in Azerbaijan. More than 1,000 American oilmen are
making Baku their base, part of an expatriate community numbering
at least 4,000. Profits at this early stage, though, are still
theoretical, and some companies are having a lousy time of it. A
consortium including Pennzoil, for instance, recently spent a great
deal of money drilling in the Caspian and came up with no oil.
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev has ladled out much of his oil already, entering his
state company into 12 development projects with foreign oil
companies, but there is still plenty of oil left to be found. In
the race to capture it, the Americans hold the early lead, with the
British close behind and the French, Germans, Norwegians, Japanese
and Italians all trailing. Even the Russian oil company Lukoil has
a presence.
</P>
<P>
   Baku is a United Nations of oil, and the jockeying for the most
lucrative oil fields is intense. But no more intense than the
jockeying between Russia and America, which find themselves in a
subterranean and unacknowledged war for primacy in an especially
dangerous corner of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have difficulty convincing the Russians that we're not
trying to edge them out,'' Richardson says. ``They see the area as
their sovereign, virgin territory.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Americans might have difficulty convincing the
Russians that they're not being edged out is because they are being
edged out. Aliyev has already cut favorable deals with American oil
companies at the expense of Russian ones. Which is why the Russians
don't like it when the Americans start talking about pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   The next best thing to controlling the source of the oil is
controlling its flow. Some of Azerbaijan's oil already flows north
to Russia through a small pipeline. Another small pipeline is being
built to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But an international consortium of oil companies is scheduled to
recommend a route for a main export pipeline in October that could
eventually move one million barrels of oil daily.
</P>
<P>
   Russia wants the pipeline to run through its territory but the
United States wants it to run west, through Georgia and into
Turkey, a NATO ally. Iran too would like to have a pipeline, but
that won't happen as long as the United States says it won't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The competition for all this oil means that Baku is filled with
intrigue and the fear of instability. Last month, Aliyev's police
and opposition demonstrators fought street skirmishes in advance of
the mid-October national election.
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev has been the object of three, or four, or five
assassination attempts in the last several years (his intelligence
chief counted six for me, though two sounded more like wishful
thinking than executable plots), and his ally to the west,
Georgia's Eduard Shevardnadze, is also a semiregular target of
assassins.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed throughout the Caucasus that the assassins are
dispatched by Russian nationalists who have not accepted the death
of their empire. Russia's current meltdown has only heightened the
fear in Baku and Tbilisi, Georgia's capital, that Russian
hard-liners will be trying even more enthusiastically to pull
Azerbaijan and Georgia back into Moscow's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Assassins are only occasional visitors to Baku, but the city is
rampant with ham-handed Russian spies, as well as Turkish
gangsters, Chechen revolutionaries, American diplomats, Iranian
terrorists and financial speculators of various nationalities,
drawn to Baku because it is a frontier of global capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Before I left for Baku, I was inundated with propaganda from the
oil companies and from Azerbaijan's lobbyists in Washington,
assuring me that Azerbaijan is a lighthouse of stability, a
pro-American redoubt and a place ready to do business in the
community of Western nations. Most of all, they said, it is a place
whose shining future, under the leadership of Aliyev, is assured.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not that's true, Baku is a fine place to watch the
future of capitalism unfold. The Caspian oil rush is a reminder
that not all commerce in the future will be carried out
antiseptically over the Internet, that the ethereal talk of
globalization means little to men who have to drill for oil and
then physically move that oil across dangerous territory.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the old verities apply. At least in this corner of the
globe, 21st-century capitalism looks very much like 19th-century
capitalism. Baku is a city of the bribe and the shakedown, of
florid corruption and baroque greed.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of high-tech capitalism _ in this place America hopes
will help solve its Persian Gulf oil problem _ the fragility of the
oil business is apparent. Success depends on the cooperation, or at
least the acquiescence, of Russians and Chechens, Iranians and
Armenians, as well as the fortunes of Azerbaijani politics.
</P>
<P>
   The future may be not nearly as hopeful as Aliyev believes it
will be, and not nearly as secure as the oil companies _ and
Washington _ need it to be.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeffrey Goldberg is a contributing writer to The New York
Times Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
