<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BELOVED-THRILLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAP THRILLS IN THE MAINSTREAM CINEMA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DIANE CARDWELL  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Early on in Jonathan Demme's movie ``Beloved,'' a character
named Paul D (Danny Glover) literally walks a gantlet of memories,
moving slowly down a hallway while bloody images of the past are
flashed before him, the work of an invisible and extremely hostile
young ghost.
 &HT;    He shields his eyes _ who wouldn't? _ trying not to look but
having to as he moves toward a room free of these visions.
 &HT;    It's an unsettling sequence, certainly, but one that evokes the
familiar: He could just as easily be a viewer cringing from any one
of a number of recent and soon-to-be released movies and television
shows that traffic in graphic violence, difficult sex and plain old
nastiness.
 &HT;    Things on-screen have been getting increasingly explicit for
years now, but what is striking about these new works is their
hyperrealism: They are all serious creative undertakings intended
to slam home a particular reality, as opposed to offering up
gross-outs merely to shock or entertain, as in ``Urban Legends'' or
``Very Bad Things.''
 &HT;    Stylistically diverse and divergent in scale, they are united in
their use of hard-to-watch images in the service of a larger social
or political message.
 &HT;    Take, for example, ``American History X,'' which opens this
month and tells the story of Derek Vineyard (Edward Norton), a
racist skinhead consumed by virulent hatred, and the younger
brother (Edward Furlong) who idolizes him. Norton recently told a
reporter from George magazine that he and the creative team
realized they ``had the potential to touch the nerve of a very
potent reality in contemporary American life ...'' and that the
inspiration for a few of the movie's more horrific scenes _ a
murder, a rampage in a grocery store _ ``was all material straight
out of news clippings.''
 &HT;    The heart of the movie's viscera is perhaps the death by curbing
of a young black man at Vineyard's hands _ well, foot, to be
precise. (Curbing, a particularly vicious practice in which a
victim's open mouth is placed on a curb and the head is stomped,
breaking at least the jaw if not the neck, is known among skinheads
and other assorted sociopaths.)
 &HT;    Similarly, Oprah Winfrey, who co-produced and stars in
``Beloved,'' has said that she ``wanted to do with a movie what
Toni Morrison had done with a book. She allowed us to see what
slavery felt like and ... allowed you to go into the interior of a
person's spirit, to understand what slavery did to their soul.''
 &HT;    In one sequence, as Sethe (Winfrey) narrates the disturbing
events of the night she escaped a plantation, a pastiche of
bondage, sexual brutality and punishment plays out in grainy,
washed-out color.
 &HT;    Even Steven Spielberg, an emotionally but not visually
promiscuous filmmaker, delved headlong into gory territory with his
famously explicit combat scenes in ``Saving Private Ryan,''
recreating the mayhem of battle so effectively that his movie
becomes an antiwar message.
 &HT;    But the trend isn't limited to violence or film. Todd Solondz's
``Happiness'' depicts the intense dysfunction that afflicts
relationships, showcasing not only a faintly sympathetic pedophile
but also a good deal of masturbation and, jarringly, its aftermath.
 &HT;    On television there's the HBO series ``Oz,'' a stylish drama
that examines the social and spiritual bankruptcy of men in prison
and the lives that led them there. Last year's final episode
featured gruesome revenge for a season's worth of sexual slavery,
and this season opened with an imprisoned child abuser being nailed
to the floor by fellow inmates. (Significantly, both horrors took
place in the gym, that everyday temple of masculinity, here gone
haywire.)
 &HT;    It has often been the justification for this sort of show-me
culture that the benefits of seeing the truth far outweigh its
unpleasantness, that we cannot know (and therefore be moved to
eradicate) the ugliness of life without being subjected to it (an
argument that oddly puts Kenneth Starr and gangsta rappers in the
same camp as reporters of reality).
 &HT;    And as a society we seem to have a taste for it. Witness the
proliferation of documentary programming on television _ shows such
as ``Cops'' or ``Justice Files,'' which take you into the world of
crime, or even ``The Operation,'' which takes you inside the human
body. The net effect has been to ratchet up our tolerance for what
we can watch. Now for a film to distinguish itself as portraying a
real pathology, it has to go even further.
 &HT;    There's nothing inherently wrong with using harsh images to
shock audiences out of their complacency, to dramatize the ways in
which our society has gone around the bend. Indeed, real-life
hideousness _ juvenile crime, family abuse, racial hatred,
inner-city despair _ worsens every day. The problem is that there
seems to be no end on the horizon; we are progressing toward a
point where nothing will be left unseen.
 &HT;    And when everything is laid bare, as viewers we will have no way
to engage, no way to use our own experiences and ideas to interpret
what we take in. This, it seems, robs art of its most animating
function: the exchange of imagination between creator and consumer.
 &HT;    In fact, one reason that the images in ``Beloved'' are powerful
is precisely because they don't last too long; they insinuate
themselves on the psyche, leaving an imprint that lingers and
recurs. Though there is much to admire in fictions such as
``American History X'' and ``Oz,'' they ultimately suffer from a
fascination with their own authenticity, from their obsessive need
to keep it realer than real.
 &HT;    And the more the urge to show is indulged, the more we'll all be
like Paul D, turning one squinty eye to the visions before us as we
try to endure them and reach safer ground.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Diane Cardwell is an editor at The New York Times Magazine.) &LR;  &QC;
