<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KINGSOLVER-BOOK-PROFI     10-13 2719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGSOLVER-BOOK-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA KINGSOLVER AT THE BARRICADES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SARAH KERR  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Barbara Kingsolver has been hospitable beyond the call of duty
ever since I accidentally arrived early at her house in Tucson and
surprised her padding barefoot in a sundress and sipping a beer.
 &HT;    She's been solicitous about jet lag. She has gone out into her
woolly desert garden, plucked giant cucumbers and bright purple
eggplants and cooked up a delicious meal.
 &HT;    But when I ask about her childhood, she says, ``I'm not crazy
about myself,'' and emits a low, edgy chuckle.
 &HT;    Kingsolver, you see, doesn't want to be just another
late-20th-century image for sale. She's no performer, and the
history of her psyche is not in the public domain.
 &HT;    When I suggest that Dickens, Twain and Wilde all happily
embraced fame, she counters: ``Well, they weren't raising kids. And
Oscar Wilde was never shoved onto the noontime news in Denver and a
mike clipped to his lapel and asked, 'In 58 seconds, because that's
what we have, what did you mean when you wrote ``The Importance of
Being Earnest?'' '
 &HT;    What she does want is to be an engaged writer, a responsible
citizen, a positive moral force. Her novels have always been
indirectly political.
 &HT;    ``The Bean Trees,'' ``Animal Dreams'' and ``Pigs in Heaven''
touched, respectively, on the Sanctuary movement to shelter Central
American refugees in Tucson; on idealistic young Americans who went
to work with the Sandinista government and on laws concerning the
adoption of Indian children. But her latest novel moves politics to
the front burner.
 &HT;    ``The Poisonwood Bible'' is set in the Congo in the late 1950s
and early 1960s, just as that republic is winning independence from
Belgium. The novel is Kingsolver's first in five years, and it is a
quantum-leap breakthrough.
 &HT;    Where her earlier books tended to be simple and sweet, the new
one is learned, tragicomic and sprawling. It is also more truly the
work of an activist _ critical, especially, of American involvement
in the assassination of Prime Minister Patrice Lumumba and the
installation of the dictator Mobutu.
 &HT;    Not that the politics are always right there on the surface:
``If I were to write a nonfiction book about the brief blossoming
and destruction of the independence of the Congo, and what the CIA
had to do with it, then probably all 85 people who are interested
in the subject would read it. Instead I can write a novel that's
ostensibly about family and culture and an exotic locale. And it's
entertaining, I hope.''
 &HT;    It's not your typical literary chat, this frank admission by
Kingsolver that she deliberately set out to hook people with a good
story, then smuggled in a political lesson. But Kingsolver is
pretty much indifferent to your typical literary chat.
 &HT;    Shy she may be, but she's also an iconoclast. She believes that
much of America's literary elite (``the gatekeepers, the inner
circle,'' she calls them, almost certainly overestimating their
influence) is squeamish and snobby. She believes critics made a
fatal mistake in the 1950s by caving in to McCarthyism and allowing
a gulf to divide art from politics. With some justification, she
points to great writers from George Bernard Shaw to Solzhenitsyn
who weren't afraid to mix literature and advocacy.
 &HT;    And when Kingsolver believes something, she tends to act on it.
With the advance from ``The Poisonwood Bible'' (estimated at close
to $1 million), she is endowing a new literary prize, the
Bellwether, which will award $25,000 to the writer of an
unpublished novel that addresses issues of ``social change.''
 &HT;    The prize, which will be handed out in the spring (on May Day,
to be exact), is, for all its idealism, also stunningly pragmatic _
and this is key to understanding Kingsolver. The typical literary
award entails a backbreaking amount of slogging through
manuscripts, but Kingsolver streamlined the process by asking 25
literary agents to submit one entry each.
 &HT;    Another shrewd idea: She'll team up each year with a different
publisher, who will guarantee a minimum run of 10,000 copies. So
the Bellwether winner won't be just another ``worthy'' book; it
will be a worthy book with a publisher behind it.
 &HT;    ``As much as she wants to encourage younger writers, she wants
publishers scrambling to publish these books,'' Frances Goldin,
Kingsolver's longtime agent, says of her client's aspirations. In
short, Kingsolver wants to change the world _ her way. She wants to
bring politics back into literature. She wants progress, not a chic
cocktail-party discussion of progress.
 &HT;    But she's realistic about what she can do, and careful not to
overextend. Hers is a pared-down radicalism _ a radicalism of
lowered expectations, aware of its limits and selectively
strategic. Kingsolver may object to the commodification of American
life. But in her own way, she's as wily as an entrepreneur.
 &HT;    In private, she considers herself just an average ``working
mom.'' And indeed, dinner with Kingsolver and her husband, Steven
Hopp, an ornithologist, is the same stop-and-go chaos as dinner in
any household with a toddler.
 &HT;    Two-year-old Lily hasn't been fed since lunch and is gearing up
for a protest. Barbara and Steven desperately hunt for the special
``sippy cup'' she likes to drink from, but it's too late. Lily
frets. She starts to cry. And while Lily is unhappy, Kingsolver is
unable to focus on anything else.
 &HT;    In several essays, Kingsolver has agonized about what lessons to
teach her daughters. (Besides Lily, there is Camille, who is 11 and
the child of a previous marriage.) Kingsolver tells me she worries
constantly about her performance as a mother. In fact, she seems to
approach motherhood with such specific ideas _ frequent walks in
the woods to learn about nature; don't outlaw TV but set an example
by curling up on the couch with a good book _ that you wonder if
she is trying to replicate her experience as a little girl or make
up for shortcomings.
 &HT;    For instance: Camille has been allotted a space in the garden
behind the house, where she's expected to grow a crop. When Lily's
a little older, she'll get one too. This, it turns out, was exactly
the practice in a certain household in Carlisle, Ky., the backwater
``one valley away from Appalachia'' where Kingsolver grew up.
 &HT;    Kingsolver sounds nervous when talking about her parents, who
are still alive _ admiring but defensive. She tells me that her
father was a physician who could have made a pile of money
practicing in the city but stayed behind to deliver babies to women
in need; her mother was a homemaker with exceptional strength of
character.
 &HT;    She speaks with gratitude about the sense of responsibility they
instilled in her, the way they gently guided her toward an
appreciation of nature and books. But as soon as she can change the
subject, she does, moving toward some general statement about the
world.
 &HT;    ``My parents always gave me to know I could make a difference _
and I'd better make one.'' Pause, then the move-out: ``In some
sense, I realize it's a luxury to feel the way I do. I know there
are plenty of people who are completely overwhelmed just by
survival.''
 &HT;    It is impossible to know whether Kingsolver is (quite
understandably) trying to protect her parents' feelings or whether
her own feelings about her childhood are simply unresolved. What's
true is that in her fiction, the subject of parents is a loaded
one.
 &HT;    ``Animal Dreams'' told the story of a young woman who feels like
an outsider in her small home town and who struggles in a
relationship with her distant father _ like Kingsolver's own, a
physician.
 &HT;    The parental issue becomes even more awkward when you consider
``The Poisonwood Bible.'' The new novel is told in the voice of
five females _ the wife and four daughters of a Christian
missionary who moves his family to the Congo and sacrifices their
health and safety in order to further his arrogant dream of
``civilizing'' Africans.
 &HT;    The year 1963 happens to be the same one when the Kingsolver
family moved to the Congo. Kingsolver seems to have relatively
carefree memories of her time there _ a child's memories of
learning songs in a new language and playing in a strange, lush
forest.
 &HT;    ``The Congo sent an electric shock through my brain. It was so
interesting to live in a place with no electricity, no radio, no
running water, no plumbing. There were just worlds of people living
perfectly satisfying lives, without needing some of the stuff I'd
assumed was necessary. I looked around and thought: 'Wow! I don't
know the half of it.'''
 &HT;    Kingsolver is infuriated when readers and journalists ask her to
elaborate on the parallels between her novels and her life.
 &HT;    ``She gets very upset when she has to do interviews,'' Frances
Goldin says. ``She's fearful of saying something about her family
that will upset them. People are sometimes not sensitive. They're
going to ask her why her father went to Africa, but it's got
nothing to do with her family. They conclude it must be
autobiographical, and she can't get them off their insistence.''
Goldin sounds protective, and upset. ``She's the most polite person
I've ever met. She lives her life by her principles. She gives so
much back. So I hate to see her wounded.''
 &HT;    Still, the fact remains that the fraught theme of most of her
fiction is the same theme that comes up when she talks about her
childhood. Kingsolver assumes that people want to draw vulgar
diagrams of her work _ to find out what real person X and Y
represent.
 &HT;    But she may be underestimating readers who don't want to pry (or
vilify her parents, who sound as if they were extraordinarily
loving and conscientious) so much as they want to know more about
her experience of responsibility: its possibility for good, its
burdens, its danger when carried too far.
 &HT;    There's a palpable fragility about Kingsolver. A mistrust, even.
When we go to a friendly local restaurant, she requests a booth
seat, back against the wall, so as not to be exposed to the rest of
the room.
 &HT;    As we drive out of Tucson one afternoon, across a parched plain
studded with gnarly mesquite, she points out dozens of ostentatious
mansions that rich escapees from California are building high in
the hills. Why would anyone want to live there, she wonders,
exposed for all the world to see? Her own sleek, ecologically
responsible adobe ranch house is built into the side of a hill
outside of Tucson, screened by the trees from the scrutiny of
passers-by.
 &HT;    When she bought it three years ago, Kingsolver was daunted by
its magazine-ready glamour, so with her typical _ modesty?
practical-mindedness? guilt? _ she roughed it up a little to make
it more homey.
 &HT;    She gets much, much happier when the conversation moves from her
personal life to her political views. They seem quite deeply felt,
if occasionally dewy-eyed. She thinks the United States could learn
a thing or two from Denmark's generous social programs. She was
enraged this summer when America bombed the Sudan. She believes
that Mumia Abu Jamal, a former radio journalist and black activist
convicted of killing a policeman in Philadelphia, is being held as
a political prisoner.
 &HT;    (She sent Abu Jamal a draft of ``The Poisonwood Bible,'' and he
wrote back with extensive, helpful comments ``from the point of
view of an African-American,'' she tells me.)
 &HT;    Her capacity for outrage and hope makes me nostalgic for the
thrill I felt as a college freshman discovering the outside world _
and it turns out this is precisely the giddy age at which many of
Kingsolver's views took shape.
 &HT;    In the early 70's she entered DePauw University. She had zoomed
through high school, studying Kant and Hume for a correspondence
course in philosophy, but she had yet to learn the judgmental pop
language of American youth. The adjustment was painful. ``It was
very scary when I first got there, because there were all these
kids who looked alike and they had these clothes and these hairdos.
There was a veneer of knowing things before you know them that I
didn't have.''
 &HT;    She gradually lost her Southern accent because ``they'd hear me
say 'Hi' and they'd think how cute it was that I was wearing shoes
and it wasn't even Sunday.''
 &HT;    Soon she found a comfortable role as a campus activist, reading
``The Feminine Mystique'' (``a book that changed my life'') and
Karl Marx (``the scales fell from my eyes'') and joining sit-ins in
front of the ROTC building. This was the tail end of the Nixon era,
remember.
 &HT;    Before she went to DePauw, Kingsolver says all she knew about
Vietnam was that Kentucky boys were coming home in body bags.
``When I got to college, bang, I saw the rest of the story. Like
everything else in the world, it was rich people somehow protecting
their interests. And I got right out in the streets and protested
against that war. And the war ended, and I felt very empowered. I
felt like I had something to do with it. Whether or not I did is
not the point, you know. I felt like I did.''
 &HT;    I was struck by the thematic resemblance in ``Poisonwood'' to
two books that came out last spring: Jane Smiley's ``The All-True
Travels and Adventures of Lidie Newton'' and Russell Banks'
``Cloudsplitter.'' All three novels revisit the actions of white
people living side by side with blacks at a critical period in
history. All three are long, dense and mournful over white
arrogance of the past.
 &HT;    I called Banks to see if he thought these novels constituted a
trend _ a mildly guilt-ridden white sequel to multiculturalism.
Call it the literature of re-examination, if you will.
 &HT;    ``It's inevitable as we come to the end of the century,'' he
answered. ``Fiction writers are going to reflect the culture's
desire to take its own measure. I look around, I see Don DeLillo
doing this, Thomas Pynchon, Jane Smiley. ... these are all books
that are kind of stepping back a little in time and distance to
re-examine what it is to be American. We sort of know what it means
to be on the left side of the hyphen: Italo-American,
Native-American, African-American _ but we don't know much about
what it means to be on the right side.
 &HT;    ``Part of it is the millennial swing, that sense of rhythm or
tide that pulls you. The other part of it is cultural history. When
Americans have been least sure of what it was to be American have
been periods when historical fiction has been most engaged.''
 &HT;    Banks raises an interesting point about uncertainty and the
cyclical nature of fiction. Kingsolver tells me, ``Everything I do,
from writing to raising my kids, is about preparing for the
future.''
 &HT;    Like many novelists right now, Kingsolver is preparing for that
future by atoning for the past. But one could argue, in a way, that
this retrospective mood actually confines her writing to the
present tense. Kingsolver has tended her career like a patient
gardener, weeding out nuisances and watching for predators, making
sure the seeds she's sowing take firm hold.
 &HT;    The question remains: Will the kind of political writing she
hopes to nurture flourish, and if so, for how long? Or does it
represent a corrective moment, a look back as the millennium
approaches _ an anxious pause while the world gets ready for
something new?
 &HT;     c.1998 Sarah Kerr  
