<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-STRIKES-1014-C     10-13 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-STRIKES-1014-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOSNIAN SERBS DEFIANT IN FACE OF POSSIBLE NATO AIR STRIKES
 &HT;    With US-KOSOVO-1014.
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRCKO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ As they prepared to evacuate the
Serbian-controlled area of Bosnia Monday, international officials
worried that NATO airstrikes in Kosovo might derail the stumbling
peace process in this part of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   As they talked about returning their jobs Tuesday, having heard
that airstrikes probably were not going to happen, they worried
that the whole Kosovo conflict had already done a lot of damage
here.
</P>
<P>
   For over a week, politicians both in Yugoslavia and in Bosnia
have been calling on all ethnic Serbs, wherever they might be, to
prepare to retaliate against Westerners if NATO bombs Yugoslavia.
Some have suggested that a NATO airstrike could lead to armed
conflicts in Bosnia, and even mean the end of the Dayton Peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the International Police Task Force, the United
Nations agency charged with reforming and monitoring Bosnia's
civilian police force, felt the heat immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``IPTF has nothing to do with NATO, but sure, we're part of the
international community here,'' said Stefo Lehmann, spokesman for
the Brcko (pronounced ``Burch-Ko'') IPTF office. ``One of our
officers, a guy came up to him and said, 'You boom-boom Belgrade.
We boom-boom you.'''
</P>
<P>
   With warnings like that in mind, the U.S. State Department
issued the order Monday morning for all Americans to evacuate the
Serbian-controlled area, before Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic agreed to NATO demands Monday night apparently
forestalling an airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   A political advisor for an international agency sat in his Brcko
office Monday morning, his suitcase packed, fielding calls from
other members of the international community wondering if he had
heard anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Status quo here. Sphincter muscles are tight,'' he told one
caller.
</P>
<P>
   Asking that his name not be used, he said he figured NATO
airstrikes would cripple the U.S. effort in the Serbian area of
Bosnia by further radicalizing the people who are already
suspicious of Western efforts here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does this set us back? Sure. Absolutely. The elections set us
back months. And this is worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the September elections, the Serb Radical Party, an
anti-Western party based in Belgrade and operating in both Bosnia
and Yugoslavia won several important seats, including the
presidency of the Serb state within Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Peace accords which ended the ethnic war here three
years ago divided Bosnia into two states -- a Serbian Republic and
a Croat/Muslim Federation -- each with its own president, prime
minister and military. Since the peace accords were signed in
December 1995, officials in the Serbian Republic have resisted the
ethnic reintegration of Bosnia called for in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that resistance, the Serbian Republic has maintained
close ties to Yugoslavia, sharing things like a telephone system,
currency and political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb Radical Party chairman, Vojislav Seselj, is deputy
prime minister in Yugoslavia. Before the elections, he said the
Serb Republic should secede from Bosnia and abandon Dayton. For the
past week, he has been urging all Serbs, in Yugoslavia and
elsewhere, to get ready to retaliate against Western officials,
foreign and local journalists and local civic activists. He has
labeled all of the above spies and warned that they might be taken
hostage in the event of an airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   And Seselj isn't the only one urging vengeance. Last week, the
Office of the High Representative, the international supervisor of
Bosnia, removed a member of the Serbian Republic parliament from
office because of similar statements.
</P>
<P>
   One of the groups Seselj has said might be attacked is the
Helsinki Committee for Human Rights. Branko Todorovic, president of
the Serbian Republic chapter of the Helsinki Committee, has
received death threats in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a dangerous political mafia which is equally active
both in Yugoslavia and in the Serbian Republic,'' he said. ``It is
a pity that a lot of our politicians go to Belgrade to get advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seselj has complete control over the Serbian Republic,'' he
added. ``The politicians on both sides of the border (between
Yugoslavia and Bosnia) are using the Kosovo issue to drum up
support.''
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, the hard-line message had been heard and was
being repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like your country too much,'' said Aleksic Danko, a
19-year-old forestry student. ``A lot of our policeman and soldiers
were killed in Kosovo, but the world doesn't want to see that. But
when our soldiers kill a few terrorists, the whole world knows
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not scared of NATO,'' he said defiantly. ``There are a
lot of Serbs in a lot of places.''
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, the threat of a NATO airstrike seemed to
be receding, at least in the cafes of Sarajevo, where evacuated
international officials gathered to exchange theories. One theory:
Even if NATO takes no action, the damage has been done in the
Serbian Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's so worked up over this, it will take a long time
for them to calm down, to forget that they hate us,'' said a
contractor working for the U.N. ``I mean . . . I'll go to work, and
I'll try to talk to the same people I spoke with last week. But
they know . . . I had to leave because my country was threatening
to bomb their brethren in Yugoslavia. Doesn't make for a good
working relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
