r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRICITY-DEREGULAT     10-13 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICITY-DEREGULATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE REVISITED OVER DEREGULATION IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By George Raine  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the end of August 1996, a legislative
committee, ringed by lobbyists, worked without much sleep for some
200 hours to wrap up a two-year effort to deregulate the
electricity industry in California.
</P>
<P>
   The final stretch was appropriately called ``the Steve Peace
death march,'' after the committee co-chairman, a Senate Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the shrill debate today over who has actually
benefited from deregulation, the death march seems like the good
old days.
</P>
<P>
   The law that broke the century-old grip of utility monopolies on
power generation and allowed customers to choose their own
electricity provider has been excoriated by consumer advocates as
corporate welfare for utilities.
</P>
<P>
   A group of these critics gathered sufficient petition signatures
to place on the Nov. 3 ballot Proposition 9, which would undo
elements of the law Santa Monica activist Harvey Rosenfield calls
``the greatest single con job I have seen in 20 years as an
advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield, who led the consumers' effort on behalf of auto
insurance reform _ Proposition 103 _ 11 years ago, is the co-author
of Proposition 9. It would prohibit the utilities from passing on
to rate payers the costs of repaying $6 billion in bonds the
utilities issued to finance a 10 percent rate cut for those same
customers.
</P>
<P>
   It would also eliminate utility charges for operating
unprofitable nuclear power plants and promises a 20 percent rate
cut for residential and small business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, some of Proposition 9's biggest proponents either
supported or did not oppose the original deregulation law when it
passed the Legislature _ unanimously and amid much fanfare _ in
1996. The state's leading consumer group, The Utility Reform
Network (TURN), participated in the lobbying and writing process
and in the end said it was neutral.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Quentin Kopp, a San Francisco independent, voted in
favor of the bill but is now supporting the Yes on Proposition 9
effort. ``There was a mantra that deregulation is good, regulation
is bad, and everyone was swept into the mantra. Including me,'' he
said. ``The more I thought about it I was repulsed by the notion of
lending the utilities money to pay their debt.'' But to overturn
the past, Kopp and others have found, is a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is driving out of the rear view mirror,'' said
Commissioner Gregory Conlon of the California Public Utilities
Commission. ``After (deregulation) passes they say, `Look how bad
this thing is.' It's a little late, guys.''
</P>
<P>
   For the measure's proponents, one problem is an enormous money
gap: As of Sept. 30, the No on 9 Coalition had collected $30.1
million and spent $22.7 million, according to the Secretary of
State's office.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money is being spent on television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Yes on 9, on the other hand, had collected $1,229,866 and spent
$1,247,971. Representatives of the group say it has no advertising
budget and is endeavoring to tell its story through the news media
and volunteers knocking on doors.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities, Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co., San Diego Gas &AMP;
Electric and Southern California Edison, are the principal donors
to the No on 9 Coalition. Opponents of the measure include both
major political parties and their gubernatorial candidates,
Democrat Gray Davis and Republican Dan Lungren; major trade
associations representing large power users who have already
benefited from deregulation; and labor and hundreds of other
business and local government groups that say Proposition 9 could
lead to higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based Consumers Union, which publishes
Consumer Report, found in state filings that several people
associated with groups that signed ballot pamphlet arguments
against Proposition 9 have received contributions from the
utilities and No on 9 Coalition. They include a former TV consumer
reporter David Horowitz, paid $106,000 as a consultant, and Gerald
Meral, executive director of the Planning and Conservation League,
who was paid $70,000. Meral heads a committee called ``Yes on 7 (a
clean air measure), No on 9.''
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz did not return a telephone call and Meral said he was
not influenced to oppose Proposition 9 by a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty about the outcome of Proposition 9 brought
Houston-based Enron Corp., one of the world's largest integrated
natural gas and electricity companies, into the fold of the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to improve electric restructuring and make it
more competitive is through the regulatory and legislative process,
while a proposition will stop the clock and probably set it back
quite a bit through legal challenges that would tie it up in courts
for years,'' said Enron spokesman Gary Foster. ``Proposition 9
could throw the entire deregulation law into jeopardy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Enron has signed contracts with major California customers,
including Pacific Bell and the University of California and
California State University systems, but it said in April that it
found no opportunity for profit in competing for smaller customers,
because the current deregulation rules favor the existing
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield is undaunted by the odds. ``Every once in a while an
initiative comes along that exposes the corruption in cash register
politics in this state, and Proposition 9 is one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   He alleges California's investor-owned utilities had their way
with a legislature more concerned with the art of the deal than
with consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Proposition 9 passes, a blizzard of lawsuits is likely. The
proponents themselves recognize a flaw in the initiative's bond
section: The contract clause of the U.S. Constitution says neither
the federal government nor any state may impair a contract, like
the one existing between the utilities and bondholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at that proposition and see a legal nightmare,'' said
Bill Dombrowski, president of the Sacramento-based California
Retailers Association, representing some 9,000 department,
specialty, grocery and chain drug stores in California.
</P>
<P>
   The association is one of many representing large energy users
that have benefited from electric deregulation since it took effect
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be four years before residential and small business
users see meaningful competition and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the electric restructuring law that Proposition
9 attacks created a four-year transition period, giving utilities
an opportunity to pay down perhaps as much as $20 billion in
``stranded costs.'' These costs include some $5 billion in nuclear
plants, other generating facilities and power contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Peace said he was offended by his opponents' tactics and use of
the initiative process to undo deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly have never seen more irresponsible and deceitful
conduct in 16 years of public life,'' he said. ``They have total
disregard for truth. I was very aggressive about trying to make
sure everybody had the opportunity to participate in the process.
But the pro-Proposition 9 people demonstrate precisely the
irresponsible, childish behavior that ultimately leads to people
not believing in the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
