<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COMPUTERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS FACE `DIGITAL DIVIDE' OVER COMPUTER USAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to computer skills in the classroom,
there's a troubling ``digital divide'' between higher-income
students who have computers at home and lower-income students who
don't, according to a survey of educators released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the survey found that computers in schools help
students at all achievement levels to perform better but the
respondents urged better training of teachers on how to teach
computer skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that should concern all of us,'' said Paul
Houston, executive director of American Association of School
Administrators, which co-sponsored the study along with Lightspan
Partnership Inc., a San Diego-based educational software firm. He
spoke at a news conference unveiling the survey of teachers,
principals and superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   While 86 percent of those surveyed said home computers help get
parents involved in their childrens' education, only 8 percent who
work in low-income schools reported the majority of their students
have computers, Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   The divide appears more pronounced in rural and urban areas,
compared with suburban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Among rural educators, 74 percent said less than half their
students have home computers. For urban educators, the figure was
73 percent. But among suburban educators, 46 percent said less than
half their students have home computers.
</P>
<P>
   At least one school district reported it is taking steps to
close the ``digital divide.'' With $800,000 in federal and state
grants, the school system in Wichita, Kansas, gave simple computers
to students for home use in three high-poverty schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Carol Holmes, a Wichita elementary school principal, told
the news conference that the lowest-achieving students in those
schools did nearly 50 percent better in reading and math than
comparable students in schools without the home computers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, of 811 teachers, principals and superintendents
surveyed, 78 percent said computers and educational software had
yielded solid gains in student achievement. And 30 percent said
computers had helped low-performing students achieve higher test
scores, with 42 percent saying they had enabled these students to
master the content of a particular school subject.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent reported increased motivation among low-achieving
students, many of them from poverty-stricken areas, and 28 percent
reported decreased behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the survey results, we concluded that educational
technology is working for students and working for teachers, and
that it does help student performance especially in low-performing
schools,'' said John Kernan, chairman and CEO of the Lightspan
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The survey contrasts with a separate study released two weeks
ago by the New Jersey-based Educational Testing Service, which
administers the college entrance exams. That survey of 14,000
fourth and eighth graders showed that students who spent more time
on computers actually did not do as well on math exams as students
who spent less time.
</P>
<P>
   The ETS study said computers can be beneficial but only when
students use them to learn real-life applications of math concepts,
instead of for repetitive drills. It also noted that success with
computers depends in large measure on the teachers' own computer
skills.
</P>
<P>
   That concern was reflected in the survey released Tuesday. Among
superintendents and principals who make budget decisions, 84
percent reported that computer purchases got the lion's share of
their schools' overall technology budget. Only 26 percent reported
that teacher training in computers and software got such high
priority.
</P>
<P>
   When asked the most effective way to help students get the most
out of computers in the future, 42 percent said provide additional
instruction to teachers on the use of educational software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are behind the curve,'' said Houston. Compared to computer
hardware purchases, computer training for teachers is ``a much
tougher sell.''
</P>
<P>
   When schools purchase computers, ``It's easy to say `this is
what your money bought.' You put money into staff development, it's
real hard to trot that out. Yet we know that's a real part of it
... There is a gap there.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made computers in schools a centerpiece of
his educational policy, setting a goal of wiring all schools to the
Internet by the year 2000. The administration is spending $425
million this year in technology grants to schools, part of an
overall effort projected at $2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
