<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ANTIQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES DEALERS KEEP A WATCHFUL EYE ON WHAT THEY BUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, N.Y. _ When the middle-aged stranger walked into
Townhouse Antiques about a week ago looking to sell some
merchandise, owner George Jurgsatis was immediately interested.
</P>
<P>
   The man told Jurgsatis he was the owner of an antiques shop in
the Catskills that was closing. He wanted to unload some items.
Outside, in the back seat of his car, were a number of items,
including a $150 Empire mirror that was easily worth twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Jurgsatis liked the mirror. He was ready to pay for it. But he
didn't. There was simply no way to know if that mirror was stolen
or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel comfortable buying it,'' he said. ``I just
didn't know him.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the genteel surface of antiques is a darker side that
many dealers would prefer to not discuss.
</P>
<P>
   The case of multiple killer and antiques thief Gary Evans
exposed another side to this genteel world of gilded frames and
elegant Windsor chairs. Evans, who confessed to killing five
people, specialized in stealing rare and valuable antiques. He
killed himself after escaping from the U.S. Marshals Service and
jumped off a bridge in Troy, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But dealers say thieves are the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Most fine arts and antiques stolen in the United States are
taken by someone who has no idea of its value _ and then hocked to
a dealer who, most likely, does not know what he's buying is
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be in this business, you're going to end up
with something stolen,'' said R. William Vollbrecht, owner of an
antiques store here.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers say they have to exercise caution when purchasing
antiques and books. Most dealers say they'd rather pass up on a
good deal then get stuck with something hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risk enough,'' Jurgsatis said. ``Plus, it's not good for
your reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, the sale of stolen antiques and fine arts
makes up the fourth-largest black-market trade, after drugs,
money-laundering and weapons, according to Interpol, the
international police agency. It's estimated that the illegal
trading of stolen antiques runs between $2 billion and $6 billion
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, for example, the theft of art, antiques and
collectibles is more costly than automobile thefts. In prisons
there, one of the most popular television programs is ``Antiques
Roadshow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're stealing items for the same reason they're stealing
your car,'' said Anna Kisluk, New York director of the Art Loss
Registry. ``For the money.''
</P>
<P>
   The registry is a London-based organization that keeps a
worldwide database of stolen ``items of culture.'' Their list
contains more than 100,000 items, everything from Tiffany lamps to
an Aston-Martin automobile. The list is used not only by crime
victims but by buyers who want to check on the authenticity of an
item they're about to purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who once nabbed an $80,000 Audubon book from a library,
wasn't the only one dealing with rare items. Earlier this year,
Daniel Spiegelman of Yonkers, N.Y., was sentenced to 5 years in
prison and fined $314,150 for stealing rare books from a Columbia
University library. The rare items included a letter from George
Washington, hundreds of hand-painted maps cut from an extremely
rare 1667 German atlas and a number of medieval works.
</P>
<P>
   Spiegelman was caught in 1995 after trying to pass the items off
to a dealer in the Netherlands who recognized the items from a list
of stolen material.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, most antiques journals include a report of
stolen items, with photos and a contact number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
