<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE: ZABACO PINOT NOIR 1995, RUSSIAN RIVER, SONOMA COUNTY, CALIF.
ABOUT $11. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The label on this most attractive pinot noir would have you
believe it was made by a winery called Zabaco in Healdsburg, Calif.
That is true up to a point; there is a Zabaco Winery, but it is
also known as E.&AMP; J. Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Zabaco is one of a number of labels the Gallos use for the
lower-priced wines made in their new Sonoma County winery. They
also make pinot noir under the Indigo Hills and Anapamu labels, the
first with a North Coast appellation and the second with a Monterey
County appellation. All three sell at about the same price.
</P>
<P>
   The Zabaco is a full, fruity pinot noir, typical of the 1995
vintage in California. It is a wine to drink young and is the equal
of some pinot noirs costing $18 to $20.
</P>
</TEXT>
