<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-SMITH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Within Cowboys' secondary, Smith's play primary concern
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an otherwise positive season for the Dallas
Cowboys, cornerback Kevin Smith continues to be missing in action
at crucial moments.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider Smith the only weak link in a secondary that ranks
among the best in the NFL. As long as Deion Sanders continues to
line up on one side of the field, Smith will be targeted by
opposing offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys improved to 4-2 after Sunday's 27-20 victory over
Carolina, but concerns about Smith's breakdowns run rampant. The
Panthers took an early lead when Raghib Ismail blazed past Smith
for a long scoring pass.
</P>
<P>
   That was the latest in a long line of busted coverages for
Smith, a seven-year pro who remains immensely popular in the
Cowboys locker room. Yet his inability to stay with opposing
receivers is a problem the Cowboys have addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everybody and their brothers want to jump on
Kevin's case,'' said Coach Chan Gailey, who has no plans of
removing Smith from the lineup. ``Is he playing as aggressively as
I'd like? At times he is and at times he isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Smith is a good player who _ fairly or not _
gets the bulk of work in the Cowboys secondary. It is not unusual
for opponents to throw exclusively to Smith's side of the field, as
long as Sanders is on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is not to give up and just don't give up any
touchdowns,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas secondary had its worst game of the season Sunday
against Carolina. Panthers backup quarterback Steve Beuerlein threw
for 286 yards and three touchdowns. Among the Cowboys he burned on
deep passes were Smith and strong safety Darren Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, however, said beating the Panthers should outweigh
whatever mistakes the Cowboys made. He admitted being frustrated in
the close contest, but softened his tone later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the happiest guy in the locker room (after the
game),'' Gailey said. ``I need to put in perspective that we won
the game. I don't want the players to feel bad about winning a
game. I told the team some things I wish I could take back. The
object is to win. Were we perfect? No. Do I wish we had played
better? Yes. But we won. And if the rest of the games go like this
one, that'll suit me just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey reported no major injuries Monday. Emmitt Smith and
receiver Billy Davis will be limited in practice this week because
of a hip bruise and foot sprain, respectively, but both will play
Sunday at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey also said he is ``99 percent certain'' that injured
quarterback Troy Aikman will not return until the Nov. 2 game at
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
