<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK14-COX     10-13 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mandatory withdrawals might prove to be painless
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here's good news for retirees who must make mandatory
withdrawals from retirement accounts such as IRAs and 401(k)s:
</P>
<P>
   You don't necessarily have to sell your stocks or other assets
and make the withdrawals in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including some professional financial advisers,
have assumed transfers out of those tax-deferred accounts must be
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   That left both retirees and advisers groping for the best move
in a sinking stock market. Is a retiree compelled to sell some
stock, even if it means he or she must take a loss? Is there a way
to dodge into another investment, or to limit the amount they must
sell? Is there a way to avoid the problem in future years?
</P>
<P>
   Ellen O. Keller, a certified financial planner in Roswell,
provided the basic answer: In many plans, the problem just doesn't
exist. If you don't want to sell a stock, just tell your account
manager to transfer the stock from your IRA to a brokerage account.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a perfect solution. ``You'll have to declare the value
of the stock as taxable income,'' Keller said. ``You have to come
up with money for the taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it universally available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legal, but it is not a required option,'' said Randall W.
Eidson, a group vice president at SunTrust Securities. In a 401(k),
the employer who sets up the plan can decide whether to allow
``in-kind'' rather than cash withdrawals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has helped numerous small businesses set up their 401(k)s,
and those typically authorize withdrawals of securities. But you'll
have to check with the corporate office that administers your plan
to be sure, he added.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a self-directed plan _ an IRA, for example _ you
still need to check the rules. ``Then it's a question of whether
your service provider _ SunTrust or Fidelity or whoever _ will
allow you to do it,'' Eidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandatory withdrawals are an element of most tax-deferred
retirement plans, with the exception of Roth IRAs. The requirement
kicks in shortly after the owner of the account passes the age of
70 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   There are several methods for establishing how much you must
withdraw each year. Each of them is based on standard tables of
life expectancy for the owner and the beneficiary of the plan, said
Bob Bordett, a certified financial planner in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He worked out an example, using the most commonly selected
method for establishing a minimum withdrawal: Suppose the owner of
an IRA is 71 and the beneficiary is 67. Their combined life
expectancy comes to 21.7 years. If they have $50,000 in the
account, they would be required to withdraw a minimum of $2,305
this year, Bordett said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount must be recalculated each year to account for the
couple's increasing age. Next year, this hypothetical couple would
have to take out at least $2,404.
</P>
<P>
   If another couple of the same ages had $650,000 in an IRA, the
first-year withdrawal would have to be $29,954.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking ahead to next year, Bordett recommends
putting a portion of your retirement account into money market
funds or other cash equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   For those who intend to pass some of their retirement plan
investments along to children or grandchildren, certified financial
planner Steve McConihay recommends stashing some assets in a
separate IRA with the child named as the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   That changes the calculation, since the beneficiary's age will
be much less than, say, a spouse's age. When calculating a minimum
withdrawal, the Internal Revenue Service allows a maximum spread of
10 years between the ages of the owner and the beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Is any of this worth messing with? It depends on how big a
withdrawal you have to make and how much of a loss you might have
to take by selling stocks. In Bordett's second example, with nearly
$30,000 at stake, it would certainly be worth checking out your
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail:hezelll(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
