<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Seeing Paris through the eyes of
Texas
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOE MURRAY
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ I'm picking up the tab for an oyster dinner but, still,
Kyle Jarrard is paying a price.
</P>
<P>
   This is the night that French TV shows ``Star Trek.'' Kyle, an
old friend and a Texan to boot, says he'd rather have dinner with
me.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle, a novelist, says a lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   In his recently completed novel, his third in the last several
years, Kyle says what he actually thinks of France, where he has
lived and written since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Roundabouts _ what my people call traffic circles _ feature
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``Bastille Day Weekend,'' centers on a village in
France (not unlike the one where the family of Kyle's French wife
owns a country home) and symbolizes ``everything that's wrong with
France,'' the author says.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it has become the village of the dammed, ever
since a government project diverted the river and, as a result of
the dam, polluted its waters.
</P>
<P>
   As for the roundabout, the book version of the village never had
need for so much as one traffic circle. Now, thanks to corrupt
politics and payoffs by contractors to local officials, dozens
surround the little town.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the book's plot is a terrorist plan to dynamite
the dam during Bastille Day weekend, though this French legion of
inept anarchists is more humorous than murderous.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the basis of the story. Such, for its author, is the
basis of his problem with publishers.
</P>
<P>
   His French agent's initial reaction was that of ``Perplexed.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle, almost immediately, felt the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perplexed?'' he pondered. ``Is that bad?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering,'' she wondered aloud, ``if the French people
will be insulted.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a political correctioness thing with a French twist.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: Can a foreigner write a book about France without
offending the French?
</P>
<P>
   Kyle, who is in his early 40s and an editor at the International
Herald Tribune, thinks he has paid his French dues, and then some,
over the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   He is married to a French woman. Their children are growing up
more French than American. They are even in the process of
investing in a home.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about French dues. Talk about Paris real estate.
</P>
<P>
   A three bedroom, one bath home in a subdivision of lots closer
to the size of burial plots costs in the neighborhood of $350,000.
And it's not even that good of a neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have muddy little yards, and some of the walls even touch
each other at the property lines,'' Kyle muttered.
</P>
<P>
   So it is, in fact, that he and his family find themselves
thinking more and more of Texas where there's plenty of wide open
spaces, though about the same density of closed minds.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle's first novel, ``Over There,'' which takes place in Paris,
Texas, (though not Paris, Texas) and Mexico was a puzzlement for
more than a few critics.
</P>
<P>
   Some found it incomprehensible, and I liked it a lot.
</P>
<P>
   His second novel, ``Down In There,'' mostly about Mexico, is
being shopped around by Kyle's agents, so far without success.
</P>
<P>
   One must wonder:
</P>
<P>
   Can a Texan living in Paris write a novel about Mexico without
offending the island nation of Seychelles in the Indian Ocean?
</P>
<P>
   It's a marketing thing. You wouldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. We'll always have Paris. And right now I think I'll
have another plate of oysters, Paris style.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of The Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
