<SLUG> BC-NY-HATECRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE LEADER OPPOSES LAW ON HATE CRIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Despite the brutal murder of a gay man in Wyoming
and increasing pressure to enact bias-crime legislation, the leader
of New York's Senate has grave reservations about joining the 41
states that impose tougher penalties on perpetrators of so-called
hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, who has blocked legislation
in the past that would increase penalties for attacks stemming from
prejudice based on race, religion, gender, sexual orientation,
ethnicity or disability, said he favors tough sentences for any
violent criminal, regardless of the motivation, and is leery of
creating a special class of victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone deserves an extra five years for a crime, they
ought to get an extra five years whether they committed it against
you, me, a straight person, or anybody, not just for somebody who
is considered gay or senior or Jewish,'' Bruno, a Republican, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno has for several years shut the door on hate-crime
legislation, despite bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George Pataki has twice proposed bias-crime
legislation and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat from
Manhattan, has repeatedly passed his own version in the lower
house. Attorney General Dennis Vacco is a strong proponent of a
hate-crime bill. But without Bruno's say-so, the measure is
probably doomed in New York, and Bruno remains cool to the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, which emerges annually and relatively quietly, takes
on heightened visibility in the wake of the death Monday of Matthew
Shepard. Shepard, 21, a University of Wyoming student, was savagely
beaten, pistol-whipped and lashed to a fence post. The Police said
that robbery was the main motive but that Shepard apparently was
chosen in part because he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   New York state Sen. Neil Breslin, a Democrat from Delmar and
proponent of bias-crime legislation, has never had an opportunity
to vote on such a law because the Republican majority led by Bruno
will not let the bill out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   Breslin on Monday expressed hope that Shepard's death would
provide the impetus to bring a hate-crime bill to the floor of the
Senate in the next session. Bruno said he is open to discussions on
any initiative that might deter crime, but said the Shepard
incident alone did not affect his views on hate crime, although it
did reinforce his belief that violent criminals should be subjected
to the severest penalties allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that crime that was committed (in Wyoming) was about
as hateful and disturbing as anything could be,'' Bruno said. ``My
feeling is, and has always been, you have to punish people who
commit crimes like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruno suggested hate-crime legislation is unnecessary, and
possibly unwise. The majority leader said the state already has a
statute that allows judges to increase sentences when there are
aggravating circumstances, and questions whether it is appropriate
for the state to declare crimes against members of certain groups
as more serious than offenses against other individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco argues that an assault on an individual motivated by
hatred toward a particular group _ minorities, gays, Catholics and
others _ is essentially an attack designed to intimidate and
instill fear in an entire class of citizenry and should be punished
accordingly, said spokesman Mike Zabel. The attorney general has
supported Pataki's bias crime initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, however, claims that Pataki has shown no leadership on
the issue and made no effort to nudge his allies in the Senate,
such as Bruno, to consider the bill, according to spokeswoman
Patricia Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, spokesman for the governor, noted that Pataki
proposed bias crime legislation in 1997 and 1998 and remains
committed to the concept. He said Silver, who has refused to
consider many of the governor's criminal justice initiatives, has
``no credibility'' on issues of crime and punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statistics indicate that hate crimes in New York jumped
7.4 percent from 1995 to 1996 _ and in 1995, New York law
enforcement agencies reported the second highest number of
hate-crime incidents in the nation, 845. California led with 1,751.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
