<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-ASIA-$ADV18-COX     10-13 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ASIA-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS CHINA ROARS INTO CAR MARKET, WORLD OIL PRICES MAY GO ALONG
FOR THE RIDE
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    With OIL-EMBARGO-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Oil barons around the world, take heart: China's leap
toward prosperity has caused nearly 1 million families to switch
from bicycles to cars.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the coming of the car culture to China isn't going to
shock the world's oil markets, as did the Arab oil embargo of
1973-74.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Chinese private car phenomenon should gain momentum
in the next few years just when the rest of Asia is soaring back
from its current economic crisis, the combined impact on world oil
prices could be dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The simple mechanism of supply-and-demand could slowly crimp the
world oil market in much the same way as members of OPEC did in the
oil cartel's heyday, when they agreed to cut production quotas --
and then stuck to the rules. Gradually, oil would become less
available and the price would go up.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the number of private cars in China has jumped from
virtually zero five years ago to at least 699,000, according to a
report by the China Automobile Market Survey and Research Society.
China's auto makers are now increasing the production of passenger
sedans by 15 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the year 2000, there will be at least 1 million privately
owned vehicles in China's cities,'' the research society declared.
``In major municipalities and provincial capitals, the ownership
rate among families will reach five(CQ) percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, since 1996 China has ``trimmed'' the production of
bicycles, the China Light Industry News reported last month. It
attributed the fall-off to ``shrinking market demand'' and
``accelerated development of the automobile industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Though affluence is on the rise in China, the rest of Asia is in
a deep recession. This has flattened Asia's spectacular 5
percent-a-year growth in oil consumption that generally kept world
prices above $24 a barrel throughout the 1980s. When Asia's energy
demand sagged last year, world oil prices slid by this summer to
below $11 a barrel, their lowest level (on an inflation-adjusted
basis) since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, almost every expert believes that Asian oil demand will
start to rebound fairly soon. When that happens, it will probably
spell the end of cheap gasoline around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Writing this March in the American journal ``Foreign Affairs,''
world oil experts Daniel Yergin, Dennis Eklof and Jefferson Edwards
predicted that overall Asian energy consumption ``will again rise
sharply in two or three years'' -- once Japan and its neighbors
solve their internal economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in the lowest trough of the Asian economic doldrums,
Asian countries consume about 19 million barrels of oil a day.
That's just over one-fourth of the oil that is used worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Oil fields in Asia produce just 8 million barrels for Asia's
daily needs; the remaining 11 million barrels a day must be
imported. Three-fourths of Asia's imported petroleum comes from the
Persian Gulf, with Saudi Arabia by far the largest supplier.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sum, the prospects for Asia's oil supply look decidedly
grim,'' wrote Yergin, Eklof and Edwards. ``By 2010, (Asian)
productive capacity will have declined 6 percent from its 2005
peak, with new oil field developments unable to compensate for
maturing Indonesian, Malaysian and Australian fields. So regardless
of exploration, Asia is destined to import more than 20 million
barrels of oil per day by 2010, compared with approximately 11
million today.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   China is the newest and fastest-growing customer for Middle East
oil. Until five years ago, China was proud of its status as an
``energy-independent'' oil exporter. But thanks to its own meteoric
economic growth, China now imports 25 percent of its oil, amounting
to 1 million barrels a day. So far, most is for industrial uses and
only a small fraction for private cars.
</P>
<P>
   China derives another 3 million barrels a day of oil from
domestic oil wells while obtaining the balance of its energy from
massive reliance on coal, and hydro-electric and a few nuclear
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of China's imported oil now comes from Saudi Arabia, Iran
and the United Arab Emirates. Determined to diversify its oil
sources beyond the Persian Gulf, China's national petroleum
corporation last year outbid some of the biggest Western oil
companies for the right to help develop some of the choicest
Caspian Sea Basin oil properties in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, China's steep increases in oil imports worries some
Chinese energy experts. Early last year retired scientists Yang
Jike, the former vice president of China's national environmental
protection committee, published a warning that it was better to
rely
</P>
<P>
   on coal than imported oil.
</P>
<P>
   If China allowed its oil imports to increase, ``China will get
entangled in Middle East politics, like the United States,'' Yang
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
