<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-LATAM-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIKE IT OR NOT, U.S. AND LATIN NEIGHBORS TIGHTEN BONDS WHEN IT
COMES TO OIL
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With OIL-EMBARGO-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS AND SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When the price of crude oil falls, it's happy days
for American consumers and the U.S. economy. But those same price
cuts strike fear in the hearts of Mexicans and Venezuelans, now
critical exporters of oil to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil dominates the economies of Latin America's biggest
producers. And every time prices fall, big cuts in federal spending
and economic crisis are sure to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The ties that bind the U.S. and its Latin American suppliers
have grown strong since the Arab oil embargo of the 1970s, part of
a promise by the U.S. to diversify and avoid oil dependence on one
region.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, for example, is expected to supply the U.S. with 13.4
percent of its imported oil in 1998. That's up from 1.2 percent in
1975. In 1985 Mexico's share of U.S. oil imports hit a high of more
than 16 percent, then dropped a bit before rising again this year.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   The growth of mutual dependency between the United States and
Mexico is ironic, given how jealously Mexico guards its national
resources. In Mexico, the day that oil was nationalized in 1938 is
still celebrated as a moment of civic pride, and suggestions that
privatizing the nation's oil industry to make it more efficient
always prompts a flurry of angry denunciations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, not all of Mexico's oil was sold to the United
States,'' said John Lichtbleu, an analyst with Pira Energy Group in
New York. ``There was a time when they didn't want to sell more
than 50 percent of exports to the U.S. because of a fear of
domination. Now 85 to 90 percent of Mexican exported oil goes to
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   While the northward flow helps stabilize the Mexican economy, it
also means demand and price fluctuations have a greater impact on
average Mexicans. About 33 percent of the country's federal revenue
comes from Petroleos de Mexico -- Pemex -- the government's oil
company.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim ends here.)
</P>
<P>
   That's a dependency Mexico has tried hard to shake. A decade
ago, oil money made up 45 percent of the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   And oil used to be Mexico's number one export, drawing three out
of every four dollars worth of foreign capital flowing into the
country. Today, as Mexico has built up its manufacturing base, oil
accounts for only 5.4 percent of the foreign revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the economy and the national budget are highly vulnerable
to the ups and downs of international oil prices. Three times this
year Mexican government officials made emergency budget spending
cuts to make up for oil revenue shortfalls. More cuts are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico will have to operate next year with an austere budget
and somehow depend less on oil revenues,'' said Jonathan Heath, a
Mexico City-based economist. ``That will be tough for a country
like Mexico, where public needs are so great today.''
</P>
<P>
   The bust-and-boom oil price cycles have been even rougher on
Venezuela, who's main crude producer, Petroleos de Venezuela, is
the world's second largest.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela puts out 3 million barrels of crude each day, and
relies on oil to generate 60 percent of its government budget
revenue and 80 percent of its foreign income.
</P>
<P>
   The result: recession and political instability this year as the
price for Venezuelan crude hit a 12-year low; oil revenue is off by
a third; the government has slashed spending by $4 billion; and
bank-loan interest rates have soared to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The chaos has opened the door for protectionist politicians like
Hugo Chavez, a former military leader who headed a failed coup in
1992 against then-president Carlos Andres Perez. Chavez is the
front-runner in the race for presidency, which culminates in a
December vote.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has promised to revisit Venezuela's open-door policy on
outside investments in the nation's oil business -- a move that
could crimp the revenues of dozens of foreign companies that
operate in Venezuela. He's even hinted at cutting back on exports
to rich nations, like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez is really the big unknown and he's got investors
scared,'' said Don Bowles, Latin America director for the Economist
Intelligence Unit, a research firm in London. ``Whether he wins,
and what he decides to do if he does, will shape the country's
economic future and could affect the oil industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
