r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-RUSSIA-$ADV18-COX     10-13 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-RUSSIA-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FINDING THE OIL IS EASY, GETTING IT IS TOUGH
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With OIL-EMBARGO-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Think of the world's major oil powers and the first
images likely to come to mind are of Persian Gulf sheikdoms or the
sun-baked Texas plains.
</P>
<P>
   Think vodka and snow, too.
</P>
<P>
   A sizable portion of the world's future oil and natural gas
supplies will come from Russia and other former Soviet republics,
if Western oil companies can get to it.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the Soviet Union seven years ago sparked the
last great oil boom of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Oil giants like Exxon, Amoco, Mobil, Shell, Texaco and British
Petroleum are investing billions of dollars across the continent to
tap oil and gas fields from the Siberian tundra of Russia to the
arid Central Asian plains of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be here and ready with this kind money if it
wasn't worth it,'' said Alexander Ordjonikidze of the Sakhalin
Energy Investment Company, a consortium of Shell, Marathon and
several Japanese partners that is set to begin offshore production
next year off Russia's far east coast.
</P>
<P>
   Worthwhile maybe, but it is far from easy.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is the world's second largest energy supplier; it
produces more natural gas than any country in the world and is
third behind Saudi Arabia and the United States in quantities of
oil.
</P>
<P>
   But its teetering economy and aging production facilities have
left its status as an oil and gas giant in a sorry state, pumping
about half the levels it did a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Western oil companies have touted themselves as the solution to
Russia's problem -- with partnerships to help Russia extract its
oil and get it to market.
</P>
<P>
   Yet frustrated oil companies have run up against a snarl of
bureaucracy, unfavorable tax conditions and changing terms of the
production deals by Russian partners who want a bigger stake. With
Russia's economy now in crisis and its market reformers on the
political outs, conditions are not expected to improve soon.
</P>
<P>
   Flat world oil prices and a threat of global recession have
further eliminated the urgency and eagerness to push ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Caspian Sea on Russia's southern fringe, billions of
dollars in deals are going forward in a region with the largest new
oil finds in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   It is hailed as the next great Middle East, and the Caspian Sea
basin -- including the former Soviet republics of Kazakhstan,
Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan and the breakaway Russian republic
Chechnya -- could be just that.
</P>
<P>
   The region combines the lucrative and dangerous elements of oil,
political unrest and geopolitical implications as the United
States, Russia and Iran vie for influence there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cliche about the former Soviet Union is it is a place with
lots of problems and lots of opportunities. The problems may now
look bigger than they did two or three years ago, but the oil is
still here,'' said Stephen O'Sullivan, an oil and gas industry
analyst in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the Caspian prizes is the Tengiz oil field in
Kazakhstan. Tengiz potentially could produce more than 1 million
barrels a day -- more than the current yield of Alaska's Prudhoe
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But how to get the oil from the Caspian basin to market has been
a source of diplomatic frustration and intrigue. Russia, Iran and
the United States have differing alternatives for pipelines to the
West.
</P>
<P>
   In the far east, an estimated 2.5 billion barrels of oil and 400
billion cubic meters of natural gas lie under the waters around
Sakhalin Island.
</P>
<P>
   The Sakhalin consortium so far has spent $1 billion and is
prepared to spend ten times that to fully develop its offshore
fields. But it is stalled by the Russian parliament's refusal to
approve legislation on a production-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma, the lower house of parliament, is dominated by
Communists and die-hard nationalist parties suspicious of the West
and reluctant to share Russia's resources with big oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the allure of Russia is fading. Countries in Latin America
and Asia, whose economies also need foreign investment, have begun
to woo the oil companies. Even Saudi Arabia, which nationalized its
oil interests in the 1970s, is making overtures to Western
companies to buy a stake there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Western oil companies take a very long view in
Russia, but they've begun to direct their attentions elsewhere,''
said O'Sullivan. ``They won't leave completely. But they may be
content to allow the oil to stay in the ground another five, 10 or
20 years longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
