<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-CENTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS GET THEIR OWN PIECE OF SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GERALD D. ADAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The late real estate developer Ben Swig would be
appalled at the idea: setting aside an entire block of downtown San
Francisco just for children.
</P>
<P>
   Swig, owner of the Fairmont Hotel, proposed in 1954 that Yerba
Buena Center's 87 acres be reserved for a sports arena, multilevel
parking garages and a convention center _ uses that would be good
for business.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, surrounded by some of San Francisco's most
high-priced turf, nearly 10 acres of real estate atop the Moscone
Convention Center was opened for children.
</P>
<P>
   For a downtown devoted almost exclusively to grown-ups and
commerce the new Rooftop at Yerba Buena Gardens is an anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   The $60 million project, originally called the Children's
Center, is a modern playground for children of all ages. It
includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A permanent ice skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 12-lane bowling alley.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Zeum, an upside-down cone where kids can learn creative
arts using the latest in computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gardens where they can learn to cultivate vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ An amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   _ A 95-year-old carousel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fantastic thing,'' attorney John Sanger, a Zeum
board member, said of the Rooftop complex.
</P>
<P>
   Considering political and financial problems, the children's
center also is a political miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to fight. This was always the stepchild,''
environmental lawyer Sue Hestor said. ``There was this fantasy that
everything (built at Yerba Buena) be huge revenue generators
instead of for residents of the city and their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the struggle to claim a block for children has taken at
least two decades of politicking and the lobbying of four mayors,
several Redevelopment Agency executive directors and dozens of
redevelopment commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of perseverance, hard work, politics and
badgering,'' said Douglas Engmann, a member of the late Mayor
George Moscone's original Select Committee on Yerba Buena. That
committee's consensus in the late 1970s revived what had been a
moribund redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   As to badgering, the chief self-described ``badger'' through two
decades was Supervisor Sue Bierman, who championed the idea of
restoring the Playland carousel at Yerba Buena through her 16-year
career as a planning commissioner before joining the Board of
Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of all the time I spent in those meetings,
glaring like a mother superior ...'' Bierman laughingly recalled.
``But we got it, especially the carousel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierman credits architect Richard Gryziec with conceiving of the
idea of a children's block during the 1970s when he persistently
submitted potential sketches to the Redevelopment Agency.
</P>
<P>
   One major effort centered on restoring the antique carousel. The
merry-go-round was decaying at a Long Beach shopping center until
Bierman and the carousel owner, Marianne Stevens of Rosewell, N.M.,
managed to get it back to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   First installed in 1906 at a park in Seattle, the Playland
carousel is a child's fantasy of mirrored walls, poles of brass and
reflecting jewels, together with horses, giraffes, rams, camels and
chariots, all hand-crafted by craftsman Charles I.D. Looff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success in recovering the carousel and setting aside
the block for children, an additional problem threatened the
children's center: the lack of money to construct it.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Bob Gamble, the former chief fiscal officer for the
Redevelopment Agency, who suggested using the city's sacrosanct
hotel tax fund _ rather than Redevelopment Agency revenues _ to
finance a major portion of the children's block.
</P>
<P>
   ``That met with less than overwhelming enthusiasm from some
quarters,'' Gamble recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism industry representatives ``have always viewed hotel tax
revenues as their province, directly related to filling hotel
rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Untouchable as that treasury was, his proposal caught on. With
grassroots enthusiasm for the children's project rising, and key
support from Redevelopment Commissioner Leroy King, ``That helped
us to overcome any potential opposition,'' Gamble said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $60 million cost of the children's block is financed
by bonds backed by the city's 14 percent hotel tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
