<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-1014-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELIS, PALESTINIANS SKEPTICAL OF PEACE TALKS' POSSIBLE
OUTCOMES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 700 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The murder of an Israeli Tuesday in what police here
called a terrorist attack sent tremors through the preparations for
peace talks in Maryland this week.
</P>
<P>
   Two Israelis were shot while swimming in a spring near
Jerusalem, one died. The assailants fled in the victims' car,
apparently toward a Palestinian-controlled area.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the office of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
said that, in light of the shooting, ``there is no chance of an
agreement being signed at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the terse statement may be just a reiteration of
Netanyahu's consistent push for the Palestinians to fight terror
before Israel will hand over any more land under the Oslo peace
process. It might not preclude a success this weekend at the summit
hosted by President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rule anything out,'' said Israeli government
spokesman Moshe Fogel. ``There is no reason why we shouldn't reach
an agreement if the Palestinians fill in the details with regard to
fighting terror.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal that will be under discussion at the Middle East summit
meeting starting on Thursday would be a small, but needed, step in
softening the disappointment Palestinians and Israelis feel for the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen months of deadlock have hardened their deep distrust in
each other and their leaders. Israelis and Palestinians alike, say
they are tired of pointless meetings and handshakes disguised as
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The talks center on an American proposal -- initially agreed to
months ago by the Palestinians -- in which Israel would pull its
army out of more land in the West Bank territory it captured in
1967. In exchange, Palestinians would have to crack down on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu Tuesday met with his Cabinet, and some right-wing
allies threatened to topple his government if he gives away too
much in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis are divided over whether an agreement hammered out in
the United States would be good or bad for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a small step forward,'' said Yaron Meir, a retired
Israeli laborer who sipped coffee this week at a Jerusalem mall.
``I know you can't trust Arabs. The main thing is that no more
blood is shed.''
</P>
<P>
   At a table nearby sat Meir Uhamkin, 30, in a black skullcap. He
is a member of the large Lubavitch Orthodox Jewish group, which
teaches that Israel should give away none of its biblical land. He
hopes the summit ends in deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope nothing will come of it,'' said Uhamkin, who inspects
the Kosher practices at a restaurant in the mall's food court. ``My
position is according to (Jewish law), that you cannot give an
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, meanwhile, are still surrounded by Israeli
checkpoints and Jewish settlements. They will take what they can
get, but do not expect much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not achieving anything, just promises and promises,''
Fathi El-Hawari, a 52-year-old Palestinian electrician who often
has to sneak around Israeli soldiers to travel from his home in the
West Bank city of Ramallah to jobs in Jerusalem. ``The people are
so sick and tired of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to his anxiety is the widely-held belief among
Palestinians that the United States favors its ally, Israel in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Oslo peace process, begun in 1993, set out a schedule of
unspecified Israeli army pull- backs from the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip. These Palestinian areas were captured in the 1967
war.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Gaza Strip is now controlled by Yasser Arafat's
Palestinian National Authority. About three percent of the West
Bank -- including its eight largest cities -- are under PNA
control, and another 24 percent is controlled by Arafat in civil
matters but still patrolled by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian-controlled areas remain divided into more than
150 pockets surrounded by Israeli areas and Jewish settlements, the
latter neighborhoods now house more than 160,000 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   No land has been handed over since January 1997. The pull-backs
were supposed to lead to negotiations over the toughest issues,
including settlements and Jerusalem, at final talks. The process
expires May 4, when Arafat says he will declare Palestinian
statehood over Israeli objections.
</P>
<P>
   The American proposal would have Israel turn over another 13
percent of West Bank land. The hand-over could be broken into
stages, with the Palestinians required to take security steps along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The deal could also include requirements, sought by the
Palestinians, that Israel stop expanding the West Bank settlements
and allow the opening of an airport and an industrial center in the
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American negotiators are asking Arafat to accept a
schedule of 50 specific anti-terrorist actions. Also, there will be
work on an agreement on security procedures, brokered by the CIA,
that the Palestinians have accepted and the Israelis have not.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said three ``major gaps''
exist between the two sides, including whether Israel will: Agree
to crack down on Jewish extremists who have threatened
Palestinians, stop settlement expansion and withdraw troops
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis shift the burden to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu spokesman David Bar-Illan said Israel still insists
that the leadership of the PLO, the international Palestinian
organization also headed by Arafat, convene and amend the
anti-Israel portions of its charter. Arafat once convened the PLO
to begin the revision process, but it was not completed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
