r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-Y2K-HNS &LR;      10-13 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL HOSPITAL ISN'T TAKING MILLENNIUM BUG FOR GRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEGUIN, Texas _ At midnight on Dec. 31, 1999, a health care
worker will be stationed at the bed of every patient in the
Guadalupe Valley Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The workers all will be holding flashlights _ just in case the
millennium bug bites.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that computers and other electronic
equipment originally programmed to recognize only the last two
digits of a year will fail or malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the
machines will assume it is 1900. This is known various as the
millennium bug, the year 2000 problem or YK2 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, like this rural South Texas facility of fewer than
100 beds, aren't immune.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Don Richey, the hospital administrator, got a
call from a supplier who told him all four of the hospital's
anesthesia machines would quit working on Jan. 1, 2000, and must be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each machine costs $40,000,'' Richey said. ``I told them, `We
may need to replace them, but we won't buy the replacement machines
from you.' Then a miracle happened. Two days later he called back
and told me the machines could be fixed for $1,000 each.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's just four machines in a hospital with literally
thousands of pieces of equipment with embedded microchips that
could malfunction when the calender and its electronic counterparts
turn to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While all businesses have to deal with the potential problems of
the year 2000 problem, hospitals depend on equipment to keep people
alive. Consequently, they have a bigger stake in ensuring the
transition to 2000 goes smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Making sure Guadalupe Valley Hospital makes the transition
without problems is the job of the associate administrator, Robert
Haynes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not spending long, sleepless nights worrying about it, but
I am working long days so we can have a clue what will happen,''
Haynes said. ``We will do what we can to make sure everything is
Y2K compliant, but we will have contingencies built in to have a
backup ready if anything fails.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K compliant'' is a phrase that may edge out ``Happy New
Year'' by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Guadalupe Valley Hospital is making an inventory of
every piece of equipment that has a computer chip in it and working
closely with the hospital's vendors about potential Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slow process.
</P>
<P>
   The operating room, for example, has 87 pieces of equipment, 70
of which are considered critical to patient care. Hospital
officials don't know yet if a single piece of that equipment will
malfunction after 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be ready,'' Haynes said. `I am not going to be 100
percent confident about anything, but I'm going to try to be as
sure as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the Y2K bug is not cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Richey said the cost for his small hospital would be ``in the
hundreds of thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital recently replaced its entire phone system for
$200,000. Richey said the system was old and needed to be replaced
within the next few years anyway. But the fact it was not Y2K
compliant sped its replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking this Y2K situation and using it to upgrade our
equipment over a three-year period,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
