<HEADLINE>
N.Y. FOOD NOTES: BABY KIWIS; MANSION FOR CATERING; WILLIAMS-SONOMA
CATALOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They Look Like Olives and Taste Like Big Kiwis
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They're called baby kiwis because inside, these
inch-long specimens look and taste exactly like regular kiwis. But
they have no fuzz. ``We like to say we have a contract with
Remington,'' said Mark Hurst, the owner of Hurst's Berry Farm in
Sheridan, Ore., a grower of baby kiwis, which are available
nationally through the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their name, baby kiwis are actually mature fruit, a
variety developed in Russia at least 50 years ago. (All kiwis
originated in China. They were introduced as Chinese gooseberries
in New Zealand in 1906. After New Zealand developed an
international market for the fruit in the 1950s, the name was
changed to kiwi.)
</P>
<P>
   The babies have thin, smooth, gray-green skins, sometimes with a
bit of blush, and they look something like olives. When ripe, they
yield slightly, like a nectarine. The best part is they can be
eaten skin and all, making them convenient for salads or for
children's lunch boxes. Each baby kiwi has four or five calories.
Like regular kiwis, they are rich in vitamin C.
</P>
<P>
   Many Food Emporium and Waldbaum's supermarkets sell them for
$2.50 for a six-ounce basket, about 30 kiwis. They are also
available at Agata &AMP; Valentina, 1505 First Ave. (79th Street), for
$2.98 a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Off to Dobbs Ferry
</P>
<P>
   On the bus taking party guests from Manhattan to Westchester
County, servers pop the corks on bottles of champagne and pass hors
d'oeuvres. It's just the beginning for a catered event at
Estherwood, a turn-of-the-century mansion in Dobbs Ferry that is
available to rent.
</P>
<P>
   The house was built by James Jennings McComb and his wife,
Esther Wood McComb, in 1895. It is now on the grounds of the
Masters School, which once used it as a dormitory. For 16 years,
Jensina Olson catered parties at Estherwood, doing the cooking
herself. Two years ago, she teamed up with Remy Gautier, the chef
who owns Cuisine de France, a Manhattan catering company, to
provide the food for parties.
</P>
<P>
   The house can accommodate up to 225 people for a cocktail
reception, and buses from Manhattan can be arranged. Costs for
catered events vary, depending on the menu. In addition, the school
charges $250 an hour for the use of the house on weekdays and
$1,400 plus $10 a person on weekends. Information: (914) 693-3322.
</P>
<P>
   From Williams-Sonoma
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma has introduced a catalog devoted entirely to
foods _ both shelf-stable goods like condiments and perishables
like lamb chops and croissants.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog may come in handy for people who do not have ready
access to retail shops that sell fresh rabbit or imported
prosciutto, but they will pay high prices for the convenience. And
they cannot expect last-minute service. Perishable items like meats
and seafood have to be ordered more than a week in advance, with
very little flexibility in the delivery date. The fastest delivery
for nonperishable foods is two days, with a $10 surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   A look through the catalog shows that the collection has been
gathered from generally high-quality domestic and imported sources.
The catalog gives precise information about shelf life, storage and
serving.
</P>
<P>
   The food catalog (800-699-2297) will be published twice a year;
the company's regular catalog will continue to carry some food
items as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
