<P>
   RUDOLPH _ David Mosley, a Nashville ammunition dealer, and his
wife appeared before a federal grand jury Tuesday to testify that
they sold Eric Rudolph the smokeless gun powder tests show is the
same as that in the Olympic park bomb. Mosley said he remembers
Rudolph because it was his biggest sale since he went into business
in 1993 - one of the bills was $622. Rudolph used the name Bob
Randolph and paid with checks, although Rudolph has reportedly told
friends he doesn't trust or use banks. Mosley said he made three
sales of powder and, in one case, 20,000 rounds of ammunition to
Rudolph. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDDIE _ BATON ROUGE, La._Is Fast Eddie down for the count?
Former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards has survived decades of
allegations, indictments and even one trial. But now his friends
are testifying against him in a lingering casino payoff scandal. A
profile of Edwards' ups and downs and what his cronies and enemies
are saying about his latest troubles. (Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN _ What exactly did the Virgin Mary reveal to Nancy
Fowler? Were there record crowds? A look at the big day in Conyers.
(Scott/Anderson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-ABUSE-REPORT _ A district judge was so emotionally moved
by the child abuse death of an infant last year that he has spent
months working on a special report that presents in painful detail
all the problems with Texas' child protective services system.
Judge Scott McCown took it upon himself to become a one-member
blue-ribbon taskforce to try to help abused and neglected children
in Texas. His unprecedented report _ to be sent to the Governor and
Legislature today _ shows a system spinning out of control and show
how Texas is at the bottom of the barrel compared to other states
in helping abused and neglected children and finding adoptive
parents. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   w/ABUSE-BOX _ Highlights from the report. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ABUSE-JUDGE _ Scott McCown once was headed for partner in one of
the country's most prestigious law firms. Then, he gave it all up
for public service. He has made his mark in Texas by working as an
assistant AG on the prison reform lawsuit and the mental
retardation institution lawsuit. Then, he became a judge and forced
Texas to adopt a more equitble funding formula for public schools.
But his heart is with the children. His most important issue these
days is child abuse and neglect and he is leaving his trademark
handprint on another major Texas issue. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED-MEAT _ ATLANTA _ More meat was recalled from a Georgia
meat plant. Meanwhile, some metro Atlanta students were served the
undercooked, possibly salmonella-tainted meat patties on Monday.
School officials say they weren't notified of the recall. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
