<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE DOG WON'T SING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two potential eyewitnesses to HankyPankygate, neither
of whom has testified before the grand jury, given a deposition or
even been offered $3 million to appear on Roseanne's new talk show.
</P>
<P>
   I am speaking, of course, of Socks the cat and Buddy the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Socks and Buddy have, quite wisely, kept a very low profile
throughout this whole unpleasantness, a strategy that may have
diverted the attention of Ken Starr and company to other sources of
information.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody had taken the trouble to ask Socks or Buddy what they
knew or when they knew it, this whole unfortunate matter might well
be behind us by now and we, the American people, could get on with
more important business such as dreading Christmas shopping or
waiting for the ``Lost in Space'' sequel to come out.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, if not likely, that Socks and Buddy were asleep
or busy elsewhere during those many times that Bill and Monica were
alone together in the Oval Office, ordering pizza.
</P>
<P>
   From my experience, dogs are particularly unreliable witnesses
and often have trouble keeping track of what's happening right
under their nose, let alone in some distant, pepperoni-scented
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   My pug dog, Buster, for example, sleeps an average of 21 hours a
day, and it's during those times that his mental faculties are at
their most alert.
</P>
<P>
   It's during those rare moments of consciousness that his brain
leaves his body and is replaced by a stale biscuit or, possibly, a
sunflower seed.
</P>
<P>
   Since I have very little else going on in my life, much of my
fun comes from watching Buster ``chase'' bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   Before you animal rights nuts mail me a pipe bomb, be advised
that no bunnies are harmed in any way during this game, unless,
perhaps, they pull a muscle in their side from laughing so hard.
</P>
<P>
   Buster and I will be out in the yard, doing our business, and I
will see a bunny grazing contentedly on my yard weeds, say, 30 feet
away. Buster, his keen canine senses at full alert, sees nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buster!'' I shout, pointing at the bunny. ``Bunny! Get the
bunny!''
</P>
<P>
   This is Buster's signal to turn in the exact opposite direction
from wherever I'm pointing and charge off at full speed, usually
into a tree or a fence.
</P>
<P>
   The bunnies that eat my yard learned long ago that they are more
in danger from falling asteroids than they are from Buster, and
often invite their friends over to watch the ``chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there will be three or four bunnies in the yard
watching Buster tear around in frantic circles just a few feet from
where they're grazing. You would think by sheer, dumb luck he would
bump into one by accident, but so far that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I will pick Buster up and throw him in the direction
of the bunnies, in order to better his odds. This has had no
effect, either, other than to cause me some lower-back pain.
</P>
<P>
   But the game is not a total loss. Buster and I both get exercise
and for the bunnies it's like an evening at a comedy club, only
cheaper and without all the annoying cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
   All of which I mention simply to make the point that President
Clinton probably has nothing to fear from any testimony Buddy may
give, because if he is anything like Buster, he wouldn't have
noticed Monica's visits if she had steamed in on the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of Socks the cat, though ... well, that's an
entirely different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA
</P>
</TEXT>
