<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT INCARNATION OF A GOOD COAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Oct. 20)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two wool coats have been my good friends. Though slightly
worn, they are still serviceable, the linings intact, the pockets
not poked through and free of old movie stubs and gum wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   Both coats have been around a while and were not of the highest
quality to begin with. But they've still got some life in them and
would suit someone just fine for a California winter.
</P>
<P>
   The right person could give the coats her own personal signature
and they, in turn, provide warmth and a lift. One is wine red and
short, with impressive shoulders, the other a long charcoal tweed,
two opposites on the fashion spectrum, two different personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The first night I wore the red coat I was exactly where I wanted
to be, out on the town with my husband and friends in an European
city, walking fast on cold icy streets and hurrying into warm loud
taverns.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is red and has outstanding shoulders, you can see it
in the fog and it looks pretty with a dusting of snow on it.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it came from a German department store, was marked
as a European size 40 instead of an American size 12 and was bought
with marks and not dollars impressed me, as if its foreign origins
gave it, and therefore me, bonus panache.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been hanging on a rack at an American mall I might have
walked right past it. I think my intent that day was to buy
something warm and neutral which otherwise would have translated to
brown or black but this coat forced itself on me. It looked like
something from the 1940s and demanded to be worn with lipstick just
as red. It had swagger, that coat.
</P>
<P>
   It went everywhere I did for a while and then started to turn. I
put it on one day a winter ago and one of my resident fashion
critics frowned and said the coat was losing its dazzle. The color
was slightly faded and it looked tired. Not wanting to appear the
same, I hung it back in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I gave it up grudgingly. It would have been nice to keep
it around just for the memories but it needs to be worn by someone
who this winter requires a red wool coat.
</P>
<P>
   The tweed was bought on a whim and a lunch break and it worked
for many years. I took it to New York on a winter vacation with my
daughter and it looked as stylish shopping on Fifth Avenue as it
did ice skating in Central Park. Of course, I froze in it since it
was absolutely insufficient for a New York winter, being a
California coat made of light wool and a thin lining and worthless
any place where the temperature gets below freezing and stays
there.
</P>
<P>
   But it made me feel long and tall and urban. It hung straight
and ended at mid-calf. For most of its years I wore it open, loose
and casual as if I had just grabbed it running out the door. The
truth is that I couldn't button it without it bunching in bad
places, which would have given it a definite frump factor which
this coat does not deserve.
</P>
<P>
   But, like the red one, it has miles to go before it sleeps.
Besides, you can't throw a coat away just because its time with one
person is over.
</P>
<P>
   You can turn a T-shirt into a cleaning cloth, hoard the jeans
until stovepipe legs come back and toss the baggy pantyhose without
any guilt at all. But a coat has many lives.
</P>
<P>
   If they were Beanie Babies I could give them names and adopt
them out. But they're just coats that need to move on.
</P>
<P>
   I learned coat recycling long before we did it with bottles and
cans. My mother gave all coats to the church for its rummage sale
and then worked the rummage sale so she could put the lowest price
on them for the neediest candidate. I pass mine on to Goodwill or
Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill truck was open that day and the attendant said,
``You sure you want to give these up? You could be needing them in
another month.''
</P>
<P>
   No, I said, explaining I was buying a new coat and I'd feel
better about it if someone else gets these. Then I worried that I
sounded kind of spoiled or like I was looking for a blessing for my
incredible generosity. I drove off, hoping he could tell by my car
I was one of the common folk and not some Lady Bountiful off to
Neiman Marcus to invest in this year's fur.
</P>
<P>
   Someone is going to love these coats and they will be loved
back. Soon they'll be in another closet, wearing someone else's
perfume, taking on a new personality, making someone smile at
herself as she catches her reflection walking down the street.
</P>
<P>
   And I and my balanced karma will be in our new gray silk trench
coat with a detachable fleece lining. Gray is in this year, I hear,
and this fabric is treated with something that allows you to wad it
up in a ball and shake out to full elegance.
</P>
<P>
   I imagine arriving by train into a foreign port. I uncoil from
its gray silkiness, fluff out my hair, put on my dark glasses and
emerge from the compartment looking cool and confident, though
vaguely mysterious. It is my next life and my coat's first.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
