<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4964 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-ALTAVISTA-HN     10-13 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ALTAVISTA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ ADDING FEATURES TO ALTAVISTA WEB SITE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Compaq Computer Corp. and its Alta Vista Web site, the
search is the thing.
</P>
<P>
   While other Internet search engines have chosen to downplay
their services' search functions, Compaq has decided to beef up the
capabilities of AltaVista, the popular site acquired in the $9
billion purchase of Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention is to make AltaVista synonymous with search on
the Internet,'' said Rod Schrock, senior vice president of Compaq's
consumer division. ``Searching is the No. 1 thing people do on the
Internet. While every other company is deinvesting in this arena,
we believe there are substantial customer needs yet to be met.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Compaq has added a slew of new features to
AltaVista, including the ability to handle plain-English questions
and filter objectionable content out of searches.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy is distinctly different from that of competing
search sites such as Excite, Lycos and HotBot, which are relying on
glitzy content and topic-based directories to attract visitors,
rather than purely on search.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista, located at www.altavis-ta.com, was something of a
poor stepchild under its previous owner, Digital. It began as a
research project and was nearly spun off as a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq placed AltaVista under its consumer division and spruced
up the site. A deal with ABC News provides journalistic content,
while a partnership with a company called LookSmart gives AltaVista
a Yahoo-style site directory.
</P>
<P>
   The features include:
</P>
<P>
   Ask AltaVista, which lets users ask simple English questions,
such as ``Where can I buy a car online?'' or ``How do I care for a
puppy?'' Schrock said the feature relies on a database of 7 million
commonly asked questions that were gathered by a team of
researchers. It was developed in conjunction with a company called
Ask Jeeves, which has its own site at www.aj.com.
</P>
<P>
   AV Family Filter prevents potentially offensive sites from
popping up on a search. Louis Monier, technical director at
AltaVista, said the filter can distinguish between medical
information and ``actual smut,'' so that a search on the word
``breast'' won't prevent a user from learning about breast cancer.
This feature was created in conjunction with SurfWatch, which makes
filtering software for PCs.
</P>
<P>
   AV Photo Finder, developed in partnership with Virage, lets
users search a database of 10 million images scattered across the
Web. A search returns a thumbnail picture of the image, which can
be enlarged with a click.
</P>
<P>
   AV Full View Searching combines different types of searching _ a
raw search of AltaVista's 140-million-page Web index, directory
searching a la Yahoo and plain-English questions _ into a single
process.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista will now spell check a query, recommending correct
spellings of words. For example, if a user misspells ``bottle'' as
``botle,'' the results page includes the words, ``Did you mean
bottle?''
</P>
<P>
   AV On Target is new technology that results in placing more
relevant sites near the top of the results list. Schrock called
this feature the ``secret sauce'' of AltaVista, saying it makes
searches more useful than those of other search engines.
</P>
<P>
   AV Recommends will highlight specific sites that the AltaVista
software believes will most satisfy a user's search for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Parr, director of electronic commerce research at
Framingham, Mass.-based International Data Corp., said AltaVista
already enjoyed a reputation as one of the best search engines on
the Web, and these new features will enhance that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Search is very much a commodity, and despite the fact that
AltaVista is the best, most consumers don't necessarily know the
difference,'' Parr said. ``Ultimately, the question is whether
there is room in the marketplace for a site that is strictly a
search engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, search sites have been bidding to become the
start-up page for users' Web browsers as portals to the rest of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the heap is Yahoo (www.yahoo.com), which is built
around a catalog of Web sites that is maintained by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Other search engines, such as AltaVista, use automation to comb
the Web for new sites to add to a database. When users search for a
site, the database is examined and relevant sites presented in a
page or pages of results.
</P>
<P>
   Those result pages often can return thousands and even millions
of target sites, or hits, per search. The improvements at AltaVista
are an attempt to help sort through that glut of information.
</P>
<P>
   Parr said AltaVista was ``one of the two most-missed
opportunities on the Internet, with the first being the Netscape
home page.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Netscape Communications did little with its home
page, the default start-up page found on its Navigator Web browser.
Netscape recently has begun beefing up the content there, turning
it into an Internet portal and selling advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq is beginning to realize the promise of AltaVista, Parr
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a marketing problem, and that's a problem Compaq
knows how to solve,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4968 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MANAGEMENT-KAN &LR;      10-13 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MANAGEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Managerial exercise strikes right chord for health sciences
faculty  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mozart met management Monday morning on the
Folly Theater stage.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six members of the Kansas City Symphony bowed and blew
their way through sections of a Mozart symphony, sitting among
about 100 faculty and department heads of the University of Health
Sciences College of Osteopathic Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians played.
</P>
<P>
   The managers listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Music Paradigm'' unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Conductor Roger Nierenberg used his baton and commentary to
weave leadership lessons into a $15,000 management seminar that
Karen Pletz, University of Health Sciences president, hopes will
pay long-term dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my goodness. This was money well spent,'' Pletz raved after
the two-hour seminar. ``The musicians illustrated management
principles you hear about and read about all the time, but I'll
never forget the way they were illustrated here.''
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, university managers will go on a planning retreat.
That, Pletz said, will be a good time to see in action the
principles demonstrated Monday _ teamwork, communication and
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pletz said she learned from her own turn at sharing
Nierenberg's baton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw all the potential out there and had an overwhelming
sense of responsibility, knowing that all those people were relying
on you to help them develop their potential,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg, a New York-based musician, developed ``The Music
Paradigm'' as a ``real-time teaching tool that has no lag between
behavior and the results produced from that behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   He contracts with orchestra members around the country to help
him emphasize good management principles. He has worked with
representatives of such companies as Bristol-Myers Squibb; Lever
Brothers; Lockheed Martin; and Sears, Roebuck and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Ray, the university's director of communications, saw a
piece on CNN about Nierenberg and urged Pletz to hire him for a
management training exercise.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during his Folly Theater appearance, Nierenberg led
a lackluster playing of the second movement. Technically it was
proficient, but even untrained ears could hear there were no
dynamics and no emotion in the playing. The musicians complained
when asked for their response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, a leader can command and control,'' Nierenberg said.
``But I reduced the artists to functionaries, to typists. Through
my desire to be good at my job, to lead, I controlled...but they
didn't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's micromanagement!'' laughed Geoffrey Decker, corporate
recruiter for DST Systems, one of the Business Symphony Partner
companies invited to send participants to the training event.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Nierenberg encouraged the musicians to play as
masterfully as each could. Some virtuoso individual work resulted,
but musicians and managers alike agreed the sum was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the magic was gone because everyone was trying to
dominate,'' observed Kristi Olsen, training and staff development
specialist for the university.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg used the moment to illustrate ``hard skills'' _
technical mastery of the specific job _ and ``soft skills'' _ which
include the ability to work together.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the conductor said, ``We see everything from the
chairs in which we sit. That's our perspective, our reality. We
don't always see the big picture....But when asked to play to make
the orchestra sound absolutely great _ rather than the individual _
the results change.''
</P>
<P>
   To teach other big-picture lessons, Nierenberg plucked members
of the faculty from the stage chairs to join him at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell us what you saw,'' Nierenberg coached William Morris,
assistant professor of osteopathic principles and practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see everyone,'' Morris responded. ``And they can see
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How does that make you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those sitting in the chairs have no idea of the anxiety felt
by their leaders,'' Nierenberg summarized. ``They just feel the
effects of their leaders' actions...
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stand at the podium, you see a different reality. We
all need to supersede those boxes we're in and try to see the
bigger picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris perceived something else: ``It was powerful to watch the
music flowing this way. (The musicians) were glancing up here
frequently for guidance. That's something I couldn't see from where
I was sitting at the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Thomas, a professor of anatomy, also had an opportunity
to help direct. It was, she admitted later, nerve-racking, and it
taxed her more than lecturing to 240 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't loosen up,'' she said. Yet she did perceive a
``flowing feeling _ not like we were ordering it _ but the response
was immediate, the orchestra was already there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg said seminar participants everywhere had the same
reactions, even when they came from dysfunctional workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   It's also common, he said, for the juxtaposition of musicians
and management tips to quickly win over skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   At the session Monday, some of the back-row doubters, who
initially sat with arms crossed or heads down, or wearing slight
smirks _ body language that said they weren't buying into it _
appeared engaged within half an hour of Nierenberg's introduction.
Their bobbing heads and smiles spoke for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skills of these professional musicians are the fundamental
building blocks of the organization,'' Nierenberg reminded the
participants. ``The `hard skill' of playing their instruments is
the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not enough to have the skills if they can't play to
fit in. They must play as a team. They must play as one.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizational leaders have the extra burden of providing vision
and direction, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``A leader must not just give orders. A leader must trust people
to do their jobs, not stifle them by command and control,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Nierenberg said, just as every member of a symphony
must play so listeners hear the most pleasing product, strong
organizations must have a customer focus ``so that everyone thinks
about their own jobs as they relate to the end product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
