<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     10-13 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COOKOFF WITH A TASTE FOR OPENERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I enjoyed a new culinary experience over the weekend.
I judged a chili cookoff.
</P>
<P>
   So what, you're thinking. And it's true _ as a known and devoted
glutton, I've judged plenty of cookoffs before. But this was
different.
</P>
<P>
   This was (begin ital) canned (end ital) chili.
</P>
<P>
   Just the words put you in mind of a reddish gelatinous goo that
slides out of the can with a THWOCK!, tastes like warmed-up sweat
socks and contains beans with the same texture as water chestnuts.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't what I tasted at the Third Annual Kaiser Bill
Memorial Canned Chili Cookoff, a benefit for the St. Vincent de
Paul Food Bank held in the scenic parking lot behind the Texaz
Grill, in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the canned chili was just the base _ cooks could
add whatever ingredients they wanted to the mix (with the exception
of better meat) _ so what we judges ended up tasting bore the same
relation to the canned chili you buy at the supermarket as filet
mignon has to Spam.
</P>
<P>
   Stagg and Wolf were the most popular brands. Rumors of secret
ingredients abounded, some more appetizing than others. A stuffed
armadillo adorned the table used by the ArtPharts _ a great chili
team name if ever there was one (they were from the Phoenix Art
Group).
</P>
<P>
   And he was missing some of his tail.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, one team member said. We didn't use the tail. We
used a paw. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Counting paws &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hey, wait _ didn't that violate the no-extra-meat rule, in
addition to violating my own policy of not eating meat from animals
that look like they are wearing medieval suits of mail?
</P>
<P>
   ``No meat,'' he said. ``Just claw.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he was kidding. I hope. And the armadillo still had
all four feet.
</P>
<P>
   We judged by passing around cups of chili and rating each. It's
a quick process, and the first few chilies go by quickly. Which is
dangerous, because by the sixth or seventh taste, all that chili
catches up to you and you suddenly feel as if you've swallowed an
anvil. Whole.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the gastronomic effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nose is running, and I don't know which one caused it,''
former Arizona Gov. Rose Mofford, another judge, sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   When the judging was done, E.D. Baptist stood alone at the top,
despite someone taping a handmade sign to his table that said
``fried booger stew.'' He took second place last year, so you might
guess that he took that recipe and improved upon it. Perhaps a
year's worth of experimentation, tasting and honing until he found
just the right combination?
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life of me, I couldn't tell you what was in it,''
Baptist said. ``A little of this and a little of that. Onions,
peppers, a whole clove of garlic, all kinds of spices. Just a
little bit of everything.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Burned entry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last place, and the plastic garbage can that accompanies that
honor, went to Dr. Chompers, who in real life is Carol Ford, a
dentist, and members of her office. What they lacked in cooking
ability, they more than made up for in good spirits. And intentions
_ they included a dollop of fluoride in their chili. Hope none of
the judges were John Birchers.
</P>
<P>
   Their chili suffered from a scorched taste, blamed upon smoked
chipotle peppers or too much cooking, depending on whom you asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a method,'' Sandy Perkins, a dental assistant, said.
``We didn't just throw in (ingredients) carelessly. Tequila, chili,
peppers, onions. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``And then we burned it,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Their table sat between members of the Phoenix and Gilbert,
Ariz., fire departments, and they had a nice little rivalry going.
Neither fire department won anything; after one of the firefighters
dumped a bucket of water on me (and except for my belly, I wasn't
even on fire), I can't say I was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the difference between a fireman and a puppy?'' Ford
asked. ``Puppies stop whining after six months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just get their first names,'' a firefighter shot back,
``because they've all got the same last name _ ``Losers''!
</P>
<P>
   But there were no losers, really. Unless you count my digestive
system. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
