<SLUG> BC-COURT-PHONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TAKES UP COMPETITION IN THE LOCAL PHONE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration urged the Supreme Court
Tuesday to reinstate federal rules designed to break up monopolies
in the $100 billion local phone industry.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman told the justices that the rules,
which would be administered by the Federal Communications
Commission, would allow free competition in the local phone market
to grow ``rapidly and throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Diane Munns, representing state utility regulators, argued
that the rules would take away the right of state governments to
oversee communication companies operating within their borders.
</P>
<P>
   She maintained that ``the FCC doesn't have a role with respect
to pricing unless the state fails to act.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Justice Antonin Scalia said that if her contention is
correct, ``you could have 50 different states having 50 different
regulations ... until they were all litigated out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the early days of the telephone, state governments have
controlled intrastate communications while the federal government _
primarily through the FCC _ has had jurisdiction over interstate
and foreign communications.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996 Congress passed the Telecommunications Act, which
was designed to break up local telephone monopolies and to open
those markets to free competition.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve these goals, the act authorized the FCC to set
regulations that would allow an outside competitor to get into the
local phone business by building its own network, leasing parts of
existing local phone networks or by buying a local service and
reselling it to customers. That would offer Americans, for the
first time, a choice in local service.
</P>
<P>
   Existing local phone companies and state utility commissions
objected, saying that the FCC had no right to meddle in state
telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the 8th U.S. Court of Appeals in St. Louis agreed,
striking down the regulations. It ruled that the states _ not the
federal government _ have the power to regulate local phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also invalidated several FCC rules that
required existing local phone companies to sell parts or all of
their service networks to outside competitors for no profit.
</P>
<P>
   In his argument Tuesday Waxman said the federal regulations were
needed to foster competition in the local phone industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said that some federal control over the local phone industry
was needed because the line between interstate and intrastate
communications was becoming ``blurred.'' Waxman said local phone
companies now provide services such as long distance and Internet
access that extend beyond state lines.
</P>
<P>
   He said that under the FCC rules, state governments would retain
the right to oversee and, at times, to set the price that outside
firms would pay for leasing local phone networks from existing
companies _ although those prices would be within guidelines set by
the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   But Munns said the authority to set price guidelines and other
rules must be reserved to the states. ``Since 1934, that power has
been given to the states,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Clinton administration hope that competition in
the local phone market would have the same impact on local phones
rates that the 1984 breakup of the Bell system had on the
long-distance phone rates, which have dropped by more than 70
percent since then.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme court also heard arguments Tuesday from lawyers for
existing local phone companies. They objected to the 1996 law's
provisions that would allow outside companies to lease parts or all
of an existing phone company's network at wholesale rates.
</P>
<P>
   William Barr, representing several local phone carriers, said
the act would ``destroy'' any competitive edge that his clients
possessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For existing phone companies, any system or process that they
develop which would help them beat their competitors would
immediately be available at cost to those same competitors,'' he
said. ``It's ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr suggested the act be changed so that outside companies,
such as AT&AMP;T and MCI, could lease only the parts of a local phone
network that they could not build or buy on their own, such as
underground phone wires. ``New entrants to the market should be
allowed to buy what they need, not what they want from existing
phone companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Carpenter, lawyer for the FCC, said the agency would
monitor the local markets to make sure that outside firms did not
take advantage of existing phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to issue a decision by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
