<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED-TURTLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORTS TO PROTECT SEA TURTLES SUFFERS SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A campaign to protect endangered sea turtles
suffered a key setback when the World Trade Organization ruled that
the United States cannot force other countries to equip their
shrimp boats with devices that enable turtles to escape shrimp
nets.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-page decision, the WTO said Monday that the United
States cannot impose its environmental standards on other
countries, even if those standards were established to save species
from extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Steiner, executive director of Earth Island Institute's Sea
Turtle Restoration Institute, said the decision ``begins a downward
spiral which will dismantle many U.S. environmental laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort to protect the endangered sea turtles was initiated
by the San Francisco-based Earth Island Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the decision is to ``allow our standards to be
reduced to the lowest common denominator of any of our trading
partners. This is absurd and not acceptable,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law requires all shrimpers to use nets with ``turtle
exclusion devices'' _ trap doors in trawl nets that enable turtles
to escape after they've been scooped up with the shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   The law also forbids the importation of shrimp caught in nets
that do not have those devices, but it was not enforced until 1995,
when Earth Island Institute sued the State Department and won.
</P>
<P>
   The Earth Island Institute estimates that 150,000 sea turtles
drown annually because they are caught in shrimp nets.
</P>
<P>
   India, Malaysia, Pakistan and Thailand challenged the U.S.
embargo against their shrimp catches before the WTO in April and
won. The United States appealed _ and lost.
</P>
<P>
   The United States now has two choices: either allow shrimp
imports without restrictions or continue to enforce the law and
face trade sanctions from the four countries, said Martin Wanger,
international programs director for the Earth Justice Legal Defense
Fund in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the State Department was ``a reluctant defender'' of
the requirement that all shrimping nations use nets that protect
turtles, Wagner said he doubted the United States would continue to
enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky insisted that the
ruling would not affect its efforts to protect endangered sea
turtles. But Steiner said ``the spin she's putting on the ruling is
nothing but fantasy and wishful thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
