<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CONGRESS14-COX     10-13 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CONGRESS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH INDUSTRY PUSHES TO SAVE INTERNET TAX BAN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ E-commerce advocates are pressing Congress to save
a bill banning new Internet taxes, amid a flurry of last-minute
lobbying that may result in one of the most productive legislative
sessions yet for the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists were scrambling late Tuesday to shore up support among
Republican House members for the Internet Tax Freedom Act, which
cleared the Senate with overwhelming support last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership has signaled its intent to put
portions of the bill into the massive omnibus spending bill now
making its way through the Congress. ``It's impossible to imagine
this being left on the cutting room floor,'' said Rep. Christopher
Cox , R-Calif., who sponsored the House version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still unclear how this is going to get done,'' said Jill
Lesser, a lobbyist for America Online Inc. ``But we're optimistic
that we'll end up with an Internet tax bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would bar taxes for three years on Internet
access fees, such as the monthly connection charge by AOL, as well
as new taxes that apply solely to electronic commerce. However, the
bill would allow existing local Internet taxes to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators were also weighing what other parts of the Senate
bill to include in the omnibus spending measure. The Senate bill
includes provisions that would protect children's privacy on line,
recognize digital signatures as authentic, require Internet service
providers to make filtering software available, and restrict
on-line speech deemed ``harmful to minors.''
</P>
<P>
   If lobbyists are successful in pushing the Internet tax bill
through, this week's last-minute lobbying will have resulted in a
stunning string of victories for the nation's high-tech community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have accomplished most of our legislative agenda,''
said Ira C. Magaziner, President Clinton's senior policy adviser
for Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   The major victories include a measure to more than double the
number of visas for foreign-born high-tech workers, which also will
be tucked into the overall spending bill. Under the compromise, the
visa ceiling would rise to 115,000 over the next two years from
65,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   A measure to protect online copyrights that passed the House
late Monday likely also will become law.
</P>
<P>
   The Digital Millennium Copyright Act updates the U.S. copyright
laws to protect products such as software, musical recordings and
software. It also protects Internet service providers from
liability if their customers infringe on copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   But lobbyists aren't popping the champagne yet. ``We're not
going to celebrate until President Clinton signs this into law,''
said Jon Englund, senior vice president of the Information
Technology Association of America, which represents the software
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
