<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Oct. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A potent jet stream disturbance will sweep toward the Northeast
Coast preceded by a broken area of showers. As additional moisture
is drawn into the system, briefly heavy showers and some rumbles of
thunder will occur near a front from the Hudson River valley to the
New England coast. As the front slows later Wednesday, a steady
rain may develop across northern and eastern New England. In the
wake of the front, gusty winds from the northwest will import
chilly air from eastern Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will have abundant sunshine with a
comfortably warm afternoon as high pressure moves east from the
Mississippi Valley. Isolated showers will erupt in the more humid
air mass over southern and eastern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Warm air will spread north from the southern Plains as breezes
from the south increase. As the warmth encounters a cooler air mass
in place over the northern parts of the Plains and Mississippi
Valley, clouds and a few showers will develop, especially near the
Missouri River. Meanwhile, sunshine will be plentiful in the warm
air from Kansas to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A complex storm system will initially have limited moisture as
it begins to develop over the Rockies. Cool air will spread south
through the northern Rockies accompanied by a few light showers.
Wednesday night and Thursday, more widespread showers and mountain
snow will develop as the storm strengthens. In the Pacific
Northwest, onshore winds will promote showers and some snow in the
Cascades above 5000 feet. Meanwhile, the Southwest will be warm and
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Change of Pace
</P>
<P>
   Autumn weather is a marked change of pace. Afternoon
temperatures in the balmy 60s and 70s in the Rockies early this
week will yield to the locally heavy mountain snow by Thursday.
Weather moves about twice as fast at this time of year compared to
the summer season. During the autumn, the deepening Arctic chill
advances southward from Canada as tropical warmth clings to the
southernmost United States. This temperature contrast is the fuel
for the jet stream winds which steer the parade of weather systems
that march to an ever-quickening drum beat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
