<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-BAD-ART-2TAKES     10-13 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-BAD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS IN AMERICA: ART SO BAD A MUSEUM IN BOSTON RELISHES IT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Gak!'' is one expression likely to burst from a
visitor. Also ``Agh!' and ``Yew!'' Or here and there, a more
articulate ``Hoo boy! Is that bad!''
</P>
<P>
   Beautifully bad. Mind-bogglingly bad. As bad as this: a
pointillist rendering of a footless, corpulent man seated on a
toilet in only his undershorts and titled ``Sunday on the Pot with
George.'' Or a portrait of a frowning, slack-busted old woman
sitting in an office chair in a field of flowers against a yellow
sky. Or a shrunken, mud-colored papier-mache pirate's head
protruding from an aqua seascape canvas, a truly astonishing,
bowling-ball-size excrescence.
</P>
<P>
   So bad that the paintings become _ well, not good, but at least
somehow worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   For though the Museum of Bad Art might seem at first to be
nothing but a joke, an elaborate sendup of the snooty pretension
and dictated taste of the professional art world, it also has a
positive point, its founders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say we're celebrating the right to fail,'' said Scott
Wilson, an antiques dealer who is the museum's curator, which means
he decides which paintings are too good to enter the collection.
</P>
<P>
   The works accepted by the museum, said Marie Jackson, its
director of esthetic interpretation, ``are done with enthusiasm,
with sincerity of purpose, with exuberance, with everything going
for them _ except that something's gone horribly awry.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of the collection, said Jerry Reilly, its executive
director, as the equivalent of songs sung by people in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are millions and millions of people who paint but have
no aspirations to be the next Monet,'' he said. ``Just as someone
singing in the shower is not singing to be the next Frank Sinatra.
They just sing because they love it. These are paintings from
people who just paint because they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Art connoisseurs could never love the results. The museum, which
charges no entrance fee and is housed in the locker-room-like
basement of the community theater in the Boston suburb of Dedham,
even sells T-shirts that read, ``In our museum, it's not the
artists that are tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   But funnily enough, for all that it is based on failure, the
museum is an ever more resounding success.
</P>
<P>
   Its beginnings could hardly have been more humble. In 1993,
Wilson rescued the portrait of the old woman against the yellow sky
(since named ``Lucy in the Field with Flowers'') from some trash.
He was interested in its gilded frame, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, his friend Reilly, a computer programmer
with a penchant for elaborate pranks and celebrations, laid eyes on
it. And, said Wilson with the mock pomposity common among the
museum's tongue-in-cheek crowd: ``There was a feeling that
something bigger than all of us was happening. Jerry asked me, `Is
there anything else like this out there?' And I said, `Oh, yeah, I
see it all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The museum began to take form in the basement of Reilly and Ms.
Jackson's house. Five years later, the Museum of Bad Art has a book
out under its name subtitled ``Art too bad to be ignored'' (1996,
Andrews and McMeel, Kansas City) and a CD-ROM (distributed by
Backyard Computing of Needham, Mass.), and is well visited at its
Web site (http://www.glyphs.com/moba/). Thousands receive the
museum's newsletter, the most active volunteers have been awarded
highfalutin titles and nearly 3,000 patrons have become ``Friends
of MOBA.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks the museum has sent out traveling
exhibitions to Calgary, Canada, and to Arlington, Va. The paintings
are accompanied by texts like this one for a blurry ``Madonna and
Child'': ``A work of undisputed tenderness that places the
spiritual above the physical through careful disregard for details
of the human form.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit of about 70 pieces of bad art at the Ellipse Art
Center in Arlington has proved so popular that visitors have been
dragging their co-workers in to enjoy it, said Trudi Van Dyke, the
gallery's curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going right through the gallery and laughing out
loud,'' she said. ``We've never had anything like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was relatively simple to put on, she said, because she
did not have to worry about insurance for the artworks or fancy
transport arrangements. ``They just sort of boxed it up and threw
it on a Mayflower,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Bad Art has a policy of never paying more than
$6.50 for a work of art, its founders say, and, in fact, it almost
never has to pay anything, so eager are bad-art owners around the
country to unload their anti-treasures. It also has a hard-and-fast
policy of never sending back art that has been submitted.
</P>
<P>
   But it actually accepts into its permanent collection only about
one of every 10 works it is given; it rejects all reproductions,
works on black velvet and other cliched kitsch, obvious student
exercises and bad art that was deliberately made badly rather than
just turning out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Still, submitting a piece to the museum is always a win-win
proposition, Ms. Jackson said. All the museum's known artists have
been happy to be exhibited: ``If you get in, you can say you've got
a piece in a museum,'' she said. ``And if your work's rejected,
you're officially not bad: you're certified not bad by the world's
leading authority on bad art.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To some, the museum's picky criteria and the gusto with which
its founders explain them amount to a sort of long-running
performance art parodying traditional museum selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found this just fascinating, that they basically take the
model of a museum of fine arts and apply the same kind of criteria
to acceptance for bad work,'' said Dean Nimmer, a painter and
longtime professor at the Massachusetts College of Art, in Boston.
Rules like the one against black velvet, he said, ``are very
similar to a gallery or museum that says, `Well, our area is really
installation art or realist paintings or neo-postmodern
abstractions.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, said Nimmer, whose affiliation with the museum
affords him the lofty but little-used title of ``executive director
of good taste,'' it is heartening to see a place created for the
kind of artist who has no hope of being shown in a mainstream
museum or gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a comedian who winds up making very poignant
social commentary without intending to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's founders emphasize that they are not in any way
anti-art or anti-artist _ quite the opposite. ``There are people
who have frowned on us and said we're taking these poor innocent
people's work and twisting it,'' Wilson said, ``and that's not what
we're about. We're celebrating the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders say they are also giving viewers a direct
connection to a painting, circumventing the usual priesthood of
curators and critics, and allowing comments in full voice instead
of the hush of typical museums and openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regularly,'' Reilly recounted, ``people say: `There's nothing
wrong with that! I think that's a good painting!' Everyone feels
completely at ease; people don't kowtow to the central process.''
</P>
<P>
   So what now for the world-renowned Museum of Bad Art? Its
founders are toying with an exhibition called ``Art in the Gutter''
that would involve hanging bad paintings in a bowling alley.
Previous exhibitions have included the ``I Just Can't Stop'' show,
which focused on certain artists' tendencies to produce a great
many similar bad works.
</P>
<P>
   Nimmer said he hoped the museum would branch out into truly bad
needlepoint, crocheting and long-fiber fabric work _ for example,
an artistic '70s-style shag carpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piece I have, the fibers are two inches long and it's a
squirrel with a nut, and the nut looks like it's oozing, everything
is melting in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson ``liked it,'' Nimmer said, ``but I don't think he's ready
for shag.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEFORE-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     10-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEFORE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIKE NEVER BEFORE': THE LINE BETWEEN LOVING AND CURSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: publication notes are at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a moment in Ehud Havazelet's new book, ``Like Never
Before,'' that incarnates the distilled bitterness, the melancholy
sting, of this quietly powerful collection of stories. Max
Birnbaum, the distracted and ineffectual son of a famous rabbi from
Cracow and the father of two disappointing children, is in his
living room in Queens speaking to his wife, Esther, who is dying of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them,'' he says abruptly, speaking of his children,
David and Rachel, whose estrangement from their parents exemplifies
Havazelet's view of human relations as battles nearly to the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them that,'' Esther replies. And then:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell them,'' he sneers. ``That I never will understand them,
how they live?'' Max thinks about his long-dead brother, killed by
the Nazis, and he has Job-like thoughts of God: ``That every
morning I curse him for a traitor and I curse them for the
unhappiness they bring.'' His hands make a gesture of futility.
``You too,'' he says, ``for tricking me like this, for leaving.
Every morning I curse you all, and then I curse myself. I should
tell them that?''
</P>
<P>
   Havazelet, who got respectful attention for ``What Is It Then
Between Us?,'' his first collection of stories, proves himself
again an impressively talented writer in ``Like Never Before,'' a
book that lives on the precarious edge between loving and cursing.
A series of independent but related stories, the new book consists
of intense, often searing scenes from three generations of a
spiritually wounded Polish Jewish family living in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Havazelet writes with a kind of anatomical precision, his
scalpel slicing at his characters to expose the dark reality
beneath. He has a sharp, almost grotesque wit, a fine ear for the
eccentric cadences of lower-middle-class New York Jews and an
unsentimental compassion for the scars they bear.
</P>
<P>
   The first story, ``Six Days,'' sets the scene, etching in the
relationship between Birnbaum and his son that will emerge as the
central conflict of Havazelet's collection of vignettes. Birnbaum
teaches in a Hebrew day school, living in the shadow of his father,
the rabbi of an Orthodox Brooklyn congregation. One Yom Kippur, in
his father's synagogue, prayers are interrupted when David and a
friend, playing ball outside (already a sacrilege), break a
synagogue window with a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy saw his father's eyes, the look in them. He's going to
kill me, he thought. Birnbaum leaned over, grunting words he didn't
recognize. He tried to reach with his fists, but he couldn't, so he
began using his feet on the red-faced creature scuttling away from
him on its back near the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Light of This World,'' which describes a day in the life of
three truants from the Hebrew Day School, it becomes clear that
there is a cruelty in David that goes beyond the normal cruelty of
children. Havazelet provides a flashback in the next story,
``Lyon,'' where Birnbaum, then 16 and known as Maxim Birnboym, and
his older brother, Rachmil, both refugees from Cracow, collect
money to pay for Jews to be smuggled across the border into
Switzerland. This brief excursion into Birnbaum's past is all the
more powerful because it is so brief, and only once more referred
to _ in Birnbaum's acrid comment to his dying wife.
</P>
<P>
   The brief incident, written with a kind of verbal suddenness
reminiscent of Isaac Babel, tells almost all one needs to know
about the troubled fate of the Birnbaum family. It is not only the
sins of the fathers that are visited upon the sons, Havazelet seems
to be saying. It is more importantly the wounds that have been
inflicted upon them and that they struggle without success to keep
to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The most brilliantly executed piece in the collection may be
``Leah,'' which is the story of Rachel, David's sister, told
through her relationship with a female cousin exactly her age, a
kind of inverse doppelganger. While Rachel shares David's
rebelliousness, she is more lost than vengeful. David, whose look
is one of ``quiet outrage, detachment, the aloof expectation of
pain,'' is a disturbed and disturbing figure, shown by Havazelet in
an almost luridly bright and unforgiving light.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Leah'' we see him as a 17-year-old full of mockery,
contempt and self-punishment, a boy who spreads a dark shadow
around him. We later glimpse his marriage to a non-Jewish woman
named Maura, who fails to evoke a sympathetic response in her
husband when a neighbor is murdered. David by now has become an
architect, intelligent and ambitious, but he is so damaged and
self-punishing as to be unwitting in his cruelty. He falls in love
with a young woman at work, comes home late one night and wakes
Maura to tell her the news. ``What was happening to him was
unusual,'' he thinks in his solipsistic way; ``if it happened to
you once in your life you were lucky. Could she try and see that?''
</P>
<P>
   Havazelet tells these stories with a remarkable economy and
stylistic precision, the characters emerging in just a few quick
strokes. ``His mouth, through his thick ungainly beard, was a wet
red hole glistening with teeth,'' he writes of an early suitor of
Rachel's cousin Leah. When Birnbaum is introduced to David's second
non-Jewish wife, he takes it as ``one more signal that his life, so
meagerly lit, was about to get darker still.''
</P>
<P>
   There is very little in the way of redemption in Havazelet's
vision of subtly but irrevocably afflicted lives, only a small
flicker of possible understanding between David and Rachel near the
end. When Birnbaum, his wife dead, goes to Seattle to try to settle
his accounts with David, living there with his wife and two young
children, even the effort of the two men to embrace is a failure.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of reading Havazelet's stories is one well on the
dark side of poignancy, but it is also one of pleasure at the
realization of a striking talent.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LIKE NEVER BEFORE'
</P>
<P>
   By Ehud Havazelet
</P>
<P>
   268 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
