<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS MILOSEVIC: BRING PEACE TO KOSOVO PROVINCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Keeping pressure on Yugoslavia, President Clinton
warned President Slobodan Milosevic on Tuesday that he must
demonstrate by deeds, not words, his intentions to bring peace to
Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic agreed on Monday to a series of concessions, including
the pullback of armed forces that have attacked ethnic Albanian
civilians and the arrival of 2,000 international inspectors to
verify his compliance. NATO gave Milosevic 96 hours to comply or
face an airstrike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commitments he has made could lead _ and I emphasize the
word `could' _ to the peaceful resolution of a crisis that
threatens the stability of the Balkans, and the lives of tens of
thousands of refugees, many of them homeless,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for that to happen, we must see progress as President
Milosevic turns his commitments into concrete realities,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not rely on what President Milosevic says, but on what
he does for the whole world to see. To that end, a key component of
the commitments he has made is an intrusive, on-the-ground and
in-the-air verification system,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Milosevic, leader of the ethnic Serb majority
in the former Communist nation, sent in the Yugoslav army and
police to put down a rebellion by ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Since
then, hundreds of Kosovar Albanians have been killed and 300,000
left homeless by Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Yugoslavian capital, Milosevic appeared on
television to announce the agreement. He said the accord will
``avert the danger of a military intervention against our country.
Our task is to accelerate the political process and economic
recovery of our country as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came after marathon negotiations by U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke and after an international military response
seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke also cautioned that the emergency was not over yet and
that Milosevic must abide by the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot stress too highly how deeply concerned we are about
what happened in the past few months in Kosovo ... the unnecessary
horror of it,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Just prior to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization action,
Milosevic agreed to continue an 11-day cease-fire, withdraw new
troops sent to Kosovo and garrison the rest, permit full access by
international monitors and allow humanitarian relief agencies to
provide services to the thousands of homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Americans will be among the 2,000 international inspectors who
will be sent to the region to verify that Milosevic is in
compliance. Administration officials could not say how many
Americans would be involved in the mission being formed by the
55-nation Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE).
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, Clinton's national security adviser,
said the 2,000 inspectors will have authority to ``establish
permanent presences at any location in Kosovo,'' as well as to
accompany Serb police and troops, coordinate relief efforts, return
refugees to their homes, supervise elections, establish
institutions and local police and demand removal or punishment of
those people violating compliance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO will provide air surveillance, with
participation by United States forces, to verify compliance as
well. Navy Capt. Mike Doubleday, a Pentagon spokesman, said NATO
also expected to station a ``rapid reaction'' military force near
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday said the U.S. military would not likely be apart of
the rapid reaction team. However, U.S. spy planes would be
available for reconnaissance missions and U.S. war planes could be
a part of a protection force for unarmed NATO planes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said NATO planes would have unrestricted access to Kosovo
air space and Milosevic will remove or store away air defense
systems.
</P>
<P>
   He said the verification mission will remain in Kosovo ``so long
as it's necessary'' and ``certainly months'' will be required.
Berger said that within the four-day deadline set by NATO, ``we
have to see serious progress'' by Milosevic toward meeting his
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called verification the key to peace.
</P>
<P>
   The president referred to the international inspectors as
``watchdogs'' who will ensure the cease-fire holds and that Serb
forces withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community prefers compliance to conflict.
But in voting to give our military commanders the authority to
carry out airstrikes against Serbia, NATO sent a clear message to
President Milosevic _ NATO is ready to act,'' Clinton said. ``It is
now up to the president of Serbia to follow through on his
commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans have been in turmoil since the collapse of
Communist-ruled Yugoslavia led to internal battles between ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 nations of NATO authorized the use of force Monday night
to enforce a United Nations resolution aimed at forcing Milosevic
to stop the attacks on Kosovar Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the 2 million people
living in Kosovo. The agreement calls for Milosevic to allow
elections next year for an autonomous, but not independent, Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time NATO authorized the use of force and
the first involving the internal affairs of a nation.
</P>
<P>
   NATO previously authorized airstrikes in Bosnia where the Serb
minority backed by Milosevic waged war against Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke helped fashion the peace accord in Bosnia which led
the the partitioning of that country into a Serb Republic and the
Muslim-Croat Federation. U.S. ground troops have been in Bosnia
since the 1995 peace accord. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
