<SLUG> BC-TSAI-SF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CANDIDATE TAKES AIM AT MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCSICO _ In a city where the dominant political
establishment revolves in tight orbit around one man, Board of
Supervisors candidate Rose Tsai is a runaway meteor.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai's bid for office takes aim at the man at the center, Mayor
Willie Brown, and her election would upset a City Hall where
loyalty to the mayor rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many issues that Rose and I agree and disagree on,''
said Angela Alioto, the former Board of Supervisors president and
two-time mayoral candidate. ``One thing about Rose is she is her
own conscience, and that is so important these days _ that she is
nobody's puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto, along with state Sen. Quentin Kopp and Supervisor Leland
Yee, are three prominent figures and Brown detractors who are
supporting Tsai's anti-Brown campaign for the board.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is not the only candidate being pitched to voters as
an independent voice in the Nov. 3 election for five seats on the
Board of Supervisors, Tsai stands apart in two regards:
</P>
<P>
   _ She is the lone challenger entered in the race with a solid
base of neighborhood support.
</P>
<P>
   _ Her candidacy, more than any other, gives the electorate a way
to vote against the mayor and what Tsai contends is Brown's
imperial way of governing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to call it a pro-democracy campaign,'' Tsai said,
whose views are slightly more conservative than many politicians in
this liberal city.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign street signs make the message perfectly clear:
``She'll Stand Up To Willie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsai, 44, was born in Hong Kong and emigrated to New York at age
7. She moved to San Francisco in 1982 to attend Hastings College of
the Law.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai emerged publicly as a political force during the 1995
mayoral campaign when she helped pack a school auditorium with
opponents of a set of proposed, preservationist-inspired limits on
remodeling and expanding single-family homes.
</P>
<P>
   All five candidates for mayor, including Brown, left that
evening pledging to kill construction restrictions if elected.
</P>
<P>
   The homeowners, members of a group called the San Francisco
Neighbors Association, also became the core radio audience of a
Chinese language public affairs call-in show hosted by Tsai and
Julie Lee. Tsai and Lee, co-leaders of association, used the
program to inspire political activism and excoriate their foes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Tsai, Lee, and the Neighbors Association, then about
4,000-members strong, gathered signatures for a ballot measure to
retrofit and partially rebuild the elevated Central Freeway. The
measure, Proposition H, appalled the city's environmentally minded
activists and was resisted by the mayor and the county Democratic
Party apparatus. It won easily with 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know that Rose has been active for years,''
said David Lee, director of the Chinese American Voter Education
Committee. ``Certainly planning commissioners did. But the Central
Freeway marked a turning point toward electoral politics as her
remedy of choice for problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The question for Tsai is whether the west- and south-side voters
who put Proposition H over the top _ voters in neighborhoods with
large or growing Chinese-American populations _ will turn out for
her Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai said she learned from the Central Freeway issue to ignore
people when they say, ```Forget it, throw in the towel.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I proved them wrong,'' she said. ``I believe that if you are
right and truly you believe what you are doing is right, then you
should do everything possible to promote it. That is how we can
improve on society.''
</P>
<P>
   Her ideas include eliminating rent control on owner-occupied
buildings with four or fewer units, a proposal trounced at the
polls in June, and easing other city regulations on rental-property
owners and builders.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai also is at odds with legislation requiring city contractors
to provide benefits for registered domestic partners on a par with
those given to spouses of employees. She doesn't propose repealing
the ordinance, but said the city went too far in not exempting
social service agencies, like the Salvation Army, with religious
objections to the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To promote gay rights, do you have to shut down those
services, or can there be a compromise and things worked out?'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tsai's stances have won her the support of the county Republican
Party and the city's major restaurant and real estate associations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
