<HEADLINE>
DOING PENANCE AFTER A FLOP  
 FRACTURED FUNNY BONE 
ASCENDING ABC  
 A CALL FOR DECENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Bylines follow notebook items.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC got some punishing news for its first big movie project of
the season, an adaptation of the Dostoyevsky classic ``Crime and
Punishment,'' which drew ratings so frigid that the network may
send several of the other literary works on its development list to
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was crushed on Sunday night, finishing last among
programs on four networks. It fared particularly poorly against the
CBS movie ``Marriage of Convenience.'' That movie, about a couple
who marry to be parents for a dead sister's son, more than doubled
the NBC rating for ``Crime and Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime and Punishment'' had a 6.1 rating, while ``Marriage of
Convenience'' was a 14.5. Each rating point represents 994,000
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very disappointing morning around here,'' said Lindy
DeKoven, the executive in charge of NBC's movies. ``We knew it was
a particularly difficult classic for television. But I think the
audience was clearly sending us a message. The audience said they
prefer the CBS movie, which was really a far more traditional kind
of television movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeKoven had led the effort at NBC to bring literary classics
to television and turn them, though big-name casting and aggressive
promotion, into events. The strategy worked brilliantly with such
fare as ``The Odyssey'' ``Gulliver's Travels'' and the legend of
Camelot packaged in ``Merlin.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of Sunday's lugubrious results, Ms. DeKoven
said, ``We probably will re-evaluate some of the literary projects
we have in development here.'' She did not specify which projects
might be affected but said they would not include several other
classic-type movies in the works for this season, like ``Alice in
Wonderland'' and ``Noah's Ark.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for a reason why ``Crime and Punishment'' fell so short
of NBC's hopes, Ms. DeKoven said she believed the national mood was
not right for a movie with a setting or theme so serious and heavy.
``We commit to these two years out,'' she said. ``Now we have the
collapse of the Russian economy in the news. The realism in the
movie was obviously very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   FRACTURED FUNNY BONE
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is laughing at the Fox network _ both on the air and in
its office suites. Four of the five live-action comedies on Fox's
schedule drew anemic ratings and Fox's patience ran out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The network has taken a meat ax to its comedy lineup, knocking
the four comedies off the air. Tuesday, ``Holding the Baby'' was
the latest to make the hit list (that's hit as the Mafia, not
Nielsen, defines it). On Monday, Fox dropped both its Friday
comedies, ``Living in Captivity'' and ``Getting Personal.'' Last
week ``Costello'' was the first show on any network canceled this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Personal'' is the only one of the three comedies
bounced this week to get an official cancellation notice. The other
two will stay in production, though Fox had no idea when they would
return. No other network has removed shows from its schedule this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The moves leave only ``That 70's Show'' in the crop of
live-action comedies on Fox's schedule as it heads into the
November sweep month in just a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will replace the Friday comedies by rearranging its plans
for a drama series called ``Brimstone,'' originally set for Tuesday
nights at 9. Fox will now run the show on Friday nights at 8,
starting on Oct. 23. The network has ordered new episodes of its
summer series ``Guinness Book of World Records'' to fill the spot
on Tuesday nights at 9.
</P>
<P>
   Fox will count on football overruns and perhaps some double
episodes of its Sunday series ``World's Funniest'' to fill the gap
left on Sunday by the shelving of ``Holding the Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   ASCENDING ABC
</P>
<P>
   At least one network had something to smile about in the weekly
ratings: ABC saw some promise in its improvement in many areas from
a week earlier and the network has moved into a solid second place
behind NBC in the category of viewers between ages 18 and 49 that
ABC considers its measuring stick.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly ABC is pleased that it has patched up what had been
disastrous nights on Thursday and Saturday and has gotten solid
performances out of such holdover series as ``Home Improvement,''
``Spin City'' and ``The Practice,'' while hoping some new shows
like ``The Hughleys'' and ``Sports Night'' will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really upbeat about the first three weeks,'' said Stu
Bloomberg, chairman of ABC Entertainment. ``We were so close to NBC
in the 18-to-49 group last week.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC had a 5.9 rating among that age group last week compared
with a 5.5 for ABC. CBS had a 3.9 and Fox a 3.5. (Each rating point
represents 994,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   ABC was extremely pleased to be well ahead of Fox, which has
beaten ABC in that category two years in a row, leading to much
teeth gnashing at ABC and its parent, the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, Bloomberg predicted that ABC would
improve its overall ratings after several seasons of steep
declines. So far, ABC is down, not up, for the season, though in
half of the hours on the schedule it has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think our new shows are better this year,'' Bloomberg
said. ``I still think we have a good chance to improve overall by
the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A CALL FOR DECENCY
</P>
<P>
   Is television leading children down a moral sewer? Steve Allen
thinks so, and his name and photograph have appeared in full-page
newspaper advertisements _ one ran Tuesday in The New York Times _
asking people to send money to a conservative media advocacy group
that is urging advertisers ``to stop sponsoring sex, filth,
violence and sleaze.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you fed up with steamy unmarried sex situations, filthy
jokes, perversion, vulgarity, foul language, violence, killings,
etc.?'' the ad asks. It also argues that television violence causes
real violence and that television sex encourages teen-agers to have
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the comedian and former television talk show host, has
joined actress Shirley Jones as a co-chairman of the Parents
Television Council, the Los Angeles arm of the Media Research
Council, which is based in Alexandria, Va., and whose chairman is
L. Brent Bozell III.
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Allen asks people to send in a coupon so that the
council can tell advertisers how many people want them to ``bring
back family-safe TV,'' and to contribute money for more ads.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign began with $500,000 donated by a retired
advertising executive who wishes to remain anonymous, said Mark
Honig, executive director of the Parents Television Council. Ads
have appeared in about 50 newspapers, and the group has placed
orders with a total of 119.
</P>
<P>
   But advertisers are more concerned about reaching a particular
age group than with placing their ads in specific shows, said
Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of the Media Access Project
in Washington. ``Sponsors want a certain demographic and they leave
it to the ad agencies' computer models to pick where their ads
go,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, head of the Motion Picture Association of America
and an architect of the year-old television content ratings system,
applauded Allen's concern but criticized his contention that
television shows cause criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide rates and crime generally have been going down for
the last three or four years, especially in big cities,'' he said.
``Should television get the credit for that, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was on a plane Tuesday afternoon and could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
