<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: My mistake was pointing out his mistake
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My dog Kazan has been house-broken almost as long as I can
remember. But the other morning, he fell from grace.
</P>
<P>
   When I went downstairs to let him out, I saw it wasn't soon
enough. He had made a puddle in the living room. I shouted, I
scolded, I upbraided and berated. A soon as I opened the door, he
was gone. He dashed out into the darkness and didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   When I had finished with the mop and made my first cup of
coffee, I began to regret my hasty tirade. After all, he is an old
dog and generally well-behaved. He sleeps on a bathmat at the foot
of my bed, and when I move around the house and yard, he's my
shadow, taking every step I take. Most of the time he asks to go
out and he asks to come in, and when I talk to him, he sits still
and listens, which is more than my own children are famous for.
</P>
<P>
   If Pavarotti were a dog, he would sound like Kazan. A voice of
such range, such volume. It's said that he has an Eskimo in his
background. The dog, not the tenor. (I never question the lineage
of anybody, man or beast, that I'm fond of.)
</P>
<P>
   But he does lift his muzzle and howl on occasion, and it is pure
Jack London and the frozen north.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of all this as I waited for his return. Finally, when
there was no summons to the back door, I took the flashlight and
set out to look. The sun was still missing from our sky; the birds
were still silent.
</P>
<P>
   I heard a neighbor's dog in the distance, but I didn't hear
Kazan. I called. (He doesn't always answer. I think his hearing is
impaired.) I flashed the light under shrubs and down the driveway.
He is very fond of my daughter and her children, and if I'm not at
home on a stormy day, he seeks refuge from thunder in their house
next door. So I visited them, flashing my light under their front
steps where he has been known to sleep on a hot afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   No Kazan. I went back in the house and got another cup of coffee
and repented of my nasty temper.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who would scold such a fine friend doesn't deserve his
bright-eyed attention, his big paw on her knee, his false but
impressive effort to repel all suspicious visitors. My coffee
didn't taste like anything. I put the cup in the sink and picked up
the flashlight again.
</P>
<P>
   This time I tried the dirt road in front of the cabin. He was
run over there once, and I think he doesn't spend time on the road
any more unless one of us takes him walking. But I flashed my light
and called. He came out of the bushes, his big plum tail at full
mast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kazan, come on home,'' I pleaded. ``I'm sorry I scolded you.
You are a good dog.''
</P>
<P>
   He acted as if he didn't hear me. He trotted to the other side
of the yard out of range of my light. But then he turned, and when
I opened the screened door to the porch he deigned to enter. He did
not, however, have any interest in my apologies.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a good day. I groveled. Kazan pouted. I fed him and
refilled his water bowl. He wasn't grateful.
</P>
<P>
   Only when my granddaughter Betsy came over and rubbed his ears
and scratched his back and discussed the life of a dog and a little
girl in comparable terms did his long doggish face lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, when I settled in the swing with a book, he
came and lay down nearby, sighing heavily. I think I'm forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
