<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home furnishings take on latest accent
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think exotic getaways are only for the rich and famous,
think again.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture manufacturers are designing pieces inspired by places
they hope will take you, vicariously, around the world. And they're
hoping to make the trip more enticing by attaching celebrity names
to their products _ a trend among the thousands of manufacturers
that show their newest pieces each spring and fall at the world's
largest furniture trade exposition in High Point, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the essence of world travel ... as a big
influence on home furnishings with a blend of exotic and tropical
themes and motifs,'' said Mark McMenamin, merchandising and
business editor for Home Accents Today, a trade publication. ``What
that looks like is a setting in which the traveler has kept all his
prized possessions from his travels.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Ernest Hemingway. When the weeklong fall market opens
Thursday, Thomasville Furniture Industries and other manufacturers
will introduce a collection of 96 pieces inspired by places where
the famed author lived or worked _ Kenya, Key West, Ketchum and
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Think merry old England. Artist Thomas Kinkade has teamed with
La-Z-Boy to create a line of furnishings with images of his
landscape paintings emblazoned on everything from lampshades to
upholstery. ``One thing we'll see at this market is a resurgence of
the English country cottage look,'' McMenamin said.
</P>
<P>
   Think golf outings. The Professional Golfers Association and
Vanguard Furniture, in one of the more unusual licensing
agreements, will present PGA Tour, a collection inspired by ``the
casually elegant decor of upscale resorts and the finest old
country clubs,'' its promotions claim.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the lines introduced this fall (and expected in stores
by spring) reflect the increasingly popular strategy of
``branding'' _ linking a famous name or trademark to a product to
give it a sense of value.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mackie, the Hollywood costume designer, will unveil a
collection of Louis XV-style furnishings for Ladd Furniture Co.
Manufacturer John Widdicomb will be showing reproductions of pieces
in London's famed Victoria and Albert Museum. Even trends guru
Faith Popcorn, who coined the term ``cocooning'' in the '80s and
will speak at Thursday's press breakfast, is about to launch the
Faith Popcorn Cocooning collection with BarcaLounger. It will
include a recliner with features for nursing mothers and
aromatherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many heroes today, as the millennium
approaches,'' Marla Metzner, who created the Hemingway brand, told
The New York Times. ``We're going back to the great icons of the
century, as heroic brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Hang onto your luggage, furniture buyers. It could be quite a
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
