<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HALLOWEEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HALLOWEEN IS HAUNTINGLY ENTICING AS THE CITY BY THE SEA GOES
SPECTRAL
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 18: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. AUGUSTINE, Fla._A persistent early evening drizzle enshrouds
the nation's oldest city. Menacing gray clouds hang heavily above.
Rain-drenched sidewalks, glistening under the soft glow of
streetlights, are all but empty. Attractions and shops that lure
tourists by day are locked for the night.
</P>
<P>
   All is quiet near the City Gate _ built in 1739 as the only
entrance to the then-walled settlement _ except for the sound of a
bluesy guitar at the Milltops, a tavern upstairs at the Old Grist
Mill with its landmark water wheel. Nearby, a few brave souls
huddle under umbrellas, waiting for the ``Ghostly Experience''
walking tour to commence. Dampened by the rain, we follow our
guide, Stephanie Kent, into the night.
</P>
<P>
   We splash across St. George Street, dodging puddles as we head
toward the shadowy Catholic Tolomato Cemetery on Cordova Street.
It's an eerily appropriate spot to begin with a chilling tale.
</P>
<P>
   A young wife who had died of a severe illness was being carried
to her grave _ sitting upright in a chair, as was the custom of the
time, her head nodding back and forth from the motion. Suddenly,
the story goes, she was cut in the temple by a thorny branch and
began to ... bleed. When a friend thought he saw her blink, she was
returned home where she recovered and lived six more years. When
she died again, her husband warned the pallbearers to steer clear
of the offending tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a zillion stories in St. Augustine,'' says native
Sandy Craig, who ought to know. A descendent of one of the city's
oldest families, the Solanas, she started the ``Ghostly
Experience'' tours in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of the supernatural take our imaginations on phantasmic
flights from the sturdy coquina fortress of Castillo de San Marcos
downtown to the black-and-white striped lighthouse across Matanzas
Bay on Anastasia Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stories are true stories,'' says the harmonica-playing
guide Tommy Ray Bledsoe as he begins another tour through the dark
streets, lantern in hand. ``But even though they're all true
doesn't mean they're all factual.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe 'em or not, the legends make for great entertainment.
And the visitor in search of haunted history can get an earful _ if
not an eyeful. On a recent visit, we collected ghost tales like
souvenirs, but left without encountering a single spirit of the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the restless ones are waiting around to make their grand
re-appearances during the Halloween celebration Oct. 30-31. The
family-friendly party has been dubbed ``Old Haunts in the Old
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything old is revered here: There's the Old Market at the
Plaza, the Oldest House, the Oldest Wooden School House, the Oldest
Drugstore, the Oldest Store Museum, the Authentic Old Jail.
Overnight guests can stay at the Old City House Inn. Oh, and don't
forget the Ancient City Baptist Church and the Ancient Cab Co.
</P>
<P>
   Just what you'd expect to find in the oldest permanently
occupied European settlement in the United States, founded by
Spanish explorer Pedro Menendez de Aviles in 1565 on land occupied
by the Timucuan Indians. In more than four centuries, the city has
weathered periods of Spanish, English and U.S. rule, flourishing in
the late 1800s when oil millionaire Henry Flager built elegant
hotels and churches to create what he envisioned as an American
Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable what this town has been through,'' says Tony
Kuykendall of Louisville, Ky., as he examines a patinated bronze
cannon on the gun deck of the Castillo de San Marco. ``It's not
surprising there'd be a few ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   A few, indeed. Every building in town, it seems, has a resident
ghost (or ghosts). And almost everyone you meet has a spooky story.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Aikens, who runs the Gatekeeper gift shop, recalls an
unsettling experience when she was tour guide at the DeMesa-Sanchez
House, built about 1760 and now furnished to reflect the
comfortable lifestyle of a St. Augustine family in the American
Territorial Period (1821-1845).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one who locked up,'' she recalls, ``and I made sure
everything was in its place. The next morning when I came in, a
little tea set had been moved.'' Another time, she and an
accompanying group of tourists heard a piano playing _ but no else
was in the house.
</P>
<P>
   One theory about the ghost suggests it could be a Native
American boy whose grave was disturbed when the house was built.
But Aikens thinks the spirit is probably a daughter of the Loring
family that lived there in the 1830s. The child drowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was quite interesting and curious,'' Aikens says.
``That set me to find out more about that house. That's the fun of
St. Augustine _ there's so much history to explore and research.
The things I've heard over the years have made me believe these
stories are authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the dark tales give this historic town an appeal
that's at once magical and romantic. Maybe that's why even the
dearly departed simply refuse to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
