<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cronkite and Glenn team up again for live space coverage
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Glenn isn't the only object of nostalgia associated with
NASA's Oct. 29 space mission, when the first man in space becomes,
at 77, the oldest man in space.
</P>
<P>
   CNN viewers will experience another deja vu when Walter
Cronkite, 81, co-anchors the cable news network's live coverage,
with Miles O'Brien, from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
Cronkite was virtually the voice America's space heyday, including
Glenn's 1962 Earth orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first opportunity to do a live broadcast in many
years,'' says Cronkite, who last called a launch in 1991. ``It's
exciting to all of us (at CNN), and to the public as well. (It
will) remind the public that we're still in space. The flights of
the shuttle have become so routine, we've really almost lost track.
This is a good opportunity to remind the public and educate a new
generation about what we're doing in space.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite spoke to reporters on Tuesday from New York about the
coverage of Glenn and his mission. Here are some excerpts:
</P>
<P>
   -- On the recent death of CNN correspondent John Holliman, who
was scheduled to co-anchor with Cronkite, and to whom CNN is
dedicating its coverage: ``I was seriously affected by the death of
John Holliman. I had many meetings with him by telephone, and then
I met him the Wednesday before the Saturday he was so tragically
taken from us. I understood at that meeting why he was so beloved
at CNN. He was an extrordinary personality.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On covering the launch for CNN instead of CBS, for whom he
has worked for 49 years: ``Since (CNN newsgroup chairman) Tom
Johnson came to me with the proposition, I asked CBS whether they
had plans to cover the mission live. I thought they did not (CBS
will cover the 2 p.m. launch live from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m.) and they
released me to do this with CNN. Since CNN was the only operation
going live with a full day's broadcasting, this was obviously a
great place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On whether he's sorry he's not the one being sent into space:
``Of course. I'm delighted (Glenn) is getting the flight _ he's the
qualified one. But as I told him in a phone call, I told him it's
most unfair. I'm older than he is, and if they want to test old age
in space, I'm the one to send up there.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On whether he views Glenn's launch as a publicity stunt by
NASA: ``I reject (that). NASA obviously is excited with the
publicity. But they took this suggestion after two years of study
... and certified it as a legitimate mission. An astronaut ... at
the age of 77, who would be willing to go through all this rigorous
training _ it's not child's play. This is not a vacation trip by
John Glenn in any manner. I don't see how it can be called a
publicity stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On his impressions of Glenn when he first met him in the '50s
and '60s: ``John always seemed more serious about the mission than
the other (early astronauts). It was the way he tackled everything
in life. There was a little bit of a feeling among the rest that
John was kind of a boy scout about the thing; he chastised them
when he thought they weren't taking it seriously enough.''
</P>
<P>
   -- His impressions of Glenn now: ``Nothing's changed.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman doing fine
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Atlanta TV anchor Monica Kaufman has received the best
possible news following her breast cancer lumpectomy Friday at
Emory University Hospital. Kaufman told WSB-TV that her doctors
have said the tumor was extremely small, that it had not spread,
and that radiation will not be necessary. ``This excellent result
came from the power of prayer,'' Kaufman was quoted as saying in a
memo posted at WSB, thanking the staff for their prayers.
</P>
<P>
   WSB general manager Greg Stone said Kaufman will probably return
to her anchor seat next week, tentatively on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Everything basic with MTV show
</P>
<P>
   MTV's new ``Revue'' (10:30 EDT tonight) is basically an artist
talking to a camera.
</P>
<P>
   No interviewer. No studio audience. Not interested? Well, the
first artist is rapper/singer Lauryn Hill, arguably the most
talented member of rap act The Fugees, so this simple program's
debut registers higher than your basic TV fare.
</P>
<P>
   Since its release six weeks ago, Hill's solo debut ``The
Miseducation of Lauryn Hill'' has held Top 10 positions on
Billboards's R&AMP;B and pop album charts. She's been on the cover of
seemingly every magazine but because Hill released her album way
into her pregnancy, she's been avoiding TV.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. ``Revue'' shoots from the waist up as the
25-year-old weaves bits of her life story around selections from
``Miseducation.'' The music is the much better part.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a response to her long-rumored troubles with fellow
Fugees Wyclef Jean and Pras, we get what it was like when they
first met. (``(Pras) was very suave for high school.. . . Clef was
whoo!''). While the single Hill talks about her first child Zion,
she relates nothing about his father. And even when it seems like
she just might open up _ ``I was going in a direction that wasn't
healthy for me,'' she says of her life before children _ there are
no details about that ``direction.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no follow-up question. After all, there's no
interviewer. Makes you miss Kurt Loder a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
