<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-EELS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Rice eel' may threaten Everglades soon, biologists say
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Walking catfish, take a hike. A
yard-long, sex-changing, air-breathing eel may take the crown as
the weirdest foreign fish ever to invade South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian swamp eel also may pose one of the greatest threats
ever to the Everglades, federal biologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Geological Survey estimates that tens of thousands of
the nocturnal carnivores are lurking in canals along the border of
Broward and Miami-Dade counties.
</P>
<P>
   Though nobody has found the eels in the Everglades, scientists
say they see little to stop them from spreading through the
region's maze of canals.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, they could drive out native species while devouring
the crawfish, frogs and small fish that wading birds need for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida has a lot of exotic fishes,'' USGS biologist Leo Nico
said. ``But unfortunately, I think this is one of the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the walking catfish, the eel can breathe air. It can
migrate over land, slithering as fast as a snake between waterways
hundreds of yards apart, Nico said.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike most of South Florida's foreign fish, which mostly
stick to canals, this one likes marshes, said Jim Williams, a
researcher at the agency's Florida Caribbean Science Center in
Gainesville. In its native Asia it thrives in rice paddies, giving
it the nickname ``rice eel.''
</P>
<P>
   It also tolerates cold weather and has been spotted as far north
as Atlanta. It's versatile, too, often starting out life as female
before swapping genders.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Shafland, an administrator at a state exotic-fish lab
in Boca Raton, cautioned against panic. He said the walking catfish
spawned all sorts of spurious rumors after it arrived here from
Thailand in the 1960s, including news reports claiming that it
climbed trees and attacked dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned,'' said Shafland, a biological administrator
for the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission. But he said
scientists don't know yet whether the eel will prove a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   For the record: Scientists have no reports of the eels attacking
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've handled several hundred eels, and they never show
aggression to humans,'' Nico said. Instead, they use their slimy
bodies to slither away.
</P>
<P>
   The eel joins an estimated 28 foreign fish species thriving in
South Florida _ including various catfish, tilapias, gouramies, the
pike killifish, cichlids, guppies and carps. Even piranhas have
turned up from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   The eel appeared in late 1997 in two spots across the state:
south of Tampa Bay and in the Snake Creek Canal near Pro Player
Stadium. Since then, the USGS has found the eels in the canal from
east of Interstate 95 to as far west as U.S. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists suspect that people who own aquariums dumped the eels
in the wild. Now, they may be here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   One solution to other foreign fish problems _ using chemical
poisons against sea lampreys in the Great Lakes _ is unlikely in
canals that help supply South Florida's drinking water, Nico said.
</P>
<P>
   He said scientists have used a boat equipped with electrodes to
shock the water, stunning the eels before scooping them with a net.
But that method can't catch them all, and the inches-long babies
can be small enough to slip through the mesh.
</P>
<P>
   Alligators, birds and water snakes probably will eat the eels,
Nico said. But the eels might prove too elusive to catch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible solution: plain old human appetite.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Roche of Fort Lauderdale, an activist with the Native Fish
Conservancy, has posted a recipe on the Internet for Asian swamp
eel _ marinated and fried. He says it can be ``served over cold
pasta and garnished with fresh chopped tomato and a sprig of
rosemary.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
