<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SOFTMONEY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most of Florida's political soft money comes from capital
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ The state capital is not among Florida's largest
cities, but it is easily the most generous to politicians looking
for money.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in every nine dollars given to either Democratic or
Republican parties _ so-called soft-money, because there are no
limits on how much can be given _ comes from just three of the
state's 1,500 zip codes: downtown Tallahassee, home to a couple of
thousand legislative and executive branch lobbyists, according to a
Palm Beach Post analysis of contribution records.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't surprise me at all,'' said Sally Spener,
executive director of Common Cause of Florida, a group that has
long pushed more stringent limits on campaign contributions. ``The
lobbyists, the special interests, are in Tallahassee.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $29.8 million taken in by the two parties as of Sept. 24,
almost $3.4 million, or 11 percent, comes from the three
Tallahassee zip codes surrounding the state Capitol: 32301, 32302
and 32399.
</P>
<P>
   The three codes ranked one, two and three as Democratic donors
and one, two and five for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, donations to the two candidates for governor _
which are limited to $500 per individual or corporation _ from the
three zip codes are much more in line with those of other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay received $82,940 from the 32302
area code in the capital, his best territory for fund raising but
only about $30,000 more than what he raised in Miami's 33131 zip
code, his next highest contributor base.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Jeb Bush, a Miami developer, raised $47,963 from
Tallahassee's 32301, but that zip code ranked 18th on Bush's list.
First for Bush was 33134 in Coconut Grove, which raised $136,801.
Miami's 33131 also came in second for Bush, which gave him $132,290
_ more than 2 1/2 times what it gave MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two candidates, Tallahassee's downtown zip codes
account for only 1.8 percent of the $9.9 million the two men have
raised.
</P>
<P>
   It is the unregulated, ``soft-money'' donations to the parties
that show the abuse of the system, critics like Spener believe,
especially since lobbyists are expected to make campaign
contributions just as they are expected to pay their phone bills or
rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a cost of doing business,'' Spener said, adding that
although donations are not tax deductible business expenses,
ultimately it is the clients who pay for the donations through the
lobbyists' fees.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most generous lobbyists, Aventura's Ron Book, said he
gives money because, as with any job, he has grown closest to those
people he must deal with every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call it a cost of doing business, call it anything you want,''
said Book, who counts Wayne Huizenga and many south Florida cities
among his clients. ``To me it's helping your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this election cycle, Book has contributed $107,240 to
various campaigns. That includes $44,490 to the state Republican
Party and $6,000 to the state Democratic Party. His wife, Patricia,
has donated another $46,750, according to state Division of
Election records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time you can help people the most is during their
campaigns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While businesses donate indirectly through their lobbyists, they
also can donate directly through their executives and the
corporation itself _ sometimes creating interesting contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   The 33440 zip code in Clewiston, for instance, is not generally
regarded as a well-to-do area. But it is the corporate home to U.S.
Sugar, which put the zip code in the No. 16 spot for Republican
Party donations statewide with $145,410. That ranked above 34103 in
Naples, 33426 in Boynton Beach and 33133 in Coconut Grove.
</P>
<P>
   The Clewiston zip code also gave $19,735 directly to Bush and
$31,130 to the Democratic Party. In contrast, MacKay, a staunch
supporter of a failed constitutional amendment to tax sugar to pay
for Everglades restoration, received but $75.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
