<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-ENROLLMENT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT student enrollment again highest in nation
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sitting in a state that's big on being big, the
University of Texas is the nation's biggest university for the
second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   With 48,917 full- and part-time students this fall, UT has more
student bodies than its closest rival, Ohio State University, which
counted 48,169 last Friday. Head counts at both schools will change
before they become final later this month, but Ohio State officials
said Monday they won't fluctuate nearly enough to close a
748-student gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're safe in saying UT is the largest,'' said Gail
Stephenoff, an assistant in the office of enrollment management.
</P>
<P>
   UT officials aren't crowing, however. They had hoped to fall
below last year's enrollment of 48,857 and get closer to their
ideal head count: 48,000, said James Vick, vice president for
student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love-hate relationship,'' Vick said. ``It's nice to
have something where you're No. 1, . . . but when you're recruiting
students, often they may have resistance to a large school.''
</P>
<P>
   UT officials said the campus was coping well with the influx.
Many services are now computerized, eliminating long lines for such
things as financial aid and schedule changes.
</P>
<P>
   But lots of students still mean big classes, and high
student-faculty ratios have caused UT to suffer in quality
rankings. Most big schools around the nation said they have taken
pains to shrink.
</P>
<P>
   UT had as many as 50,245 students in 1989 and brought the
numbers down to 47,905 in 1995. They crept back up, however,
propelling UT to its No. 1 status last fall. Ohio State last year
had 48,278 students.
</P>
<P>
   Although UT hoped to enroll a much smaller freshman class this
year, it ended up with 6,744, just 341 fewer than last fall.
</P>
<P>
   It will take time to get smaller, Vick said, adding, ``It's a
little bit like turning a battleship around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
