<HEADER>
A5070 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      10-13 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Oct. 14. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ACCORD (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The U.S. special envoy
Richard Holbrooke announces an agreement that averts the immediate
threat of NATO air strikes against Serbia and addresses measures
that could lead to a form of autonomy in Kosovo Province. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ Through forceful if belated
diplomacy, the Clinton administration has won enormous concessions
from the Yugoslav President, Slobodan Milosevic. But the agreement
on Kosovo seems fraught with the dangers that have long bedevilled
the West in Bosnia. A news analysis by Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-IMF (Washington) _ The Treasury Department and
congressional Republicans hammer out final details of compromise
legislation to provide $18 billion to the International Monetary
Fund in exchange for new restrictions on its ability to lend to
foreign governments. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CLINTON (Broomfield, Colo.) _ While the election in
three weeks has been portrayed in Washington as a referendum on
whether President Clinton should be impeached, the scandal has not
become a central part of the discourse _ or the candidates'
strategies _ in the closest House and Senate contests in the
country. By Richard L. Berke. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILER-GIRL (Dixon, Ill.) _ Watching classmates strut past in
designer clothes, Wendy Williams sat silently on the yellow school
bus, wearing a cheap belt and rummage-sale slacks. One boy stopped
and yanked his thumb, demanding her seat. ``Move it, trailer
girl,'' he sneered. It has never been easy to live on the wrong
side of the tracks. But in the economically robust 1990s, with
sprawling new houses and three-car garages sprouting like
cornstalks on the Midwestern prairie, the sting that comes with
scarcity gets rubbed with an extra bit of salt. By Dirk Johnson.
With photos. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-INDUSTRIAL-PARK (Gaza City, Gaza Strip) _ The grandly named
Gaza Industrial Estate, hailed by all sides as the first tangible
achievement of the current phase of the tortuous
Israeli-Palestinian negotiating process, is expected to be
operating before the end of the year. It will employ up to a
thousand Palestinians in several small-scale manufacturing
ventures. It is a measure of the Gaza Strip's isolation and
economic desperation that this tentative, modest project looms so
large for Palestinian planners. By William A. Orme Jr. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-CUTBACK (New York) _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the first big
American financial firm to announce cutbacks in response to the
world's troubled financial markets, says it will eliminate about
3,400 jobs, or just more than 5 percent of its work force. By Peter
Truell. With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
