LANDLORD JAILED (Phoenix) - Slumord Sherwin Seyrafi is arrested and
jailed without bail on charges of obstructing justice by allegedly
trying to intimidate a witness who is also a tenant. He and County
Attorney Richard Romley hold press conferences. Seyrafi announces
he wants to give his properties to charity. By BILL HERMANN. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONGRESS-LIMBO (Washington) - Arizona's congressional delegation is
awaiting word on the fate of a half-dozen or so measures hanging in
limbo as the White House and Congressional Republicans try to reach
agreement on vital spending measures before adjourning for the
year. Two border- crossing issues - an entry-exit system (Section
110) and border-crossing cards (Section 104) - are under intense
discussion in the budget talks. A high-profile identity theft bill
and two water projects are held up by other states' senators who
have placed holds on them until they get legislation that they want
passed. By ADRIANNE FLYNN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COCKFIGHT (Dewey, Ariz.) - Dale Dunivin got a little misty-eyed as
he remembered the first time he hauled his fighting cock, Ol' Blue,
to the pits in Quartzsite three years ago. Seems that Ol' Blue was
paying way too much attention to loving and not enough to fighting,
when a rather effeminate-looking ``henny cock'' took to the center
of the ring. ``He thought he had himself a new girlfriend,''
Dunivin said. ``But that other cock got on top of him and cut down
through his back, cutting his ribs loose. ``We thought we were
going to lose him.'' But Ol' Blue rallied, put some moves on his
foe, and managed to dig his spurs into the heart of the other fowl.
It was all over but the shouting as the bleeding bird slumped to
the ground. Then, as usual, Ol' Blue pecked off the downed cock's
head. With PHOTOS and COCKPROP.
</P>
<P>
   By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COCKFIGHT-PROP (Undated) - Trailing in the polls, Arizona
cockfighters are huddling behind a ``Mt. Rushmore defense'' against
a proposed ban on their sport. Presidents Washington, Jefferson,
Jackson and Lincoln all were cockfighters, David Harris says in a
publicity pamphlet for the Nov. 3 general election. Proposition 201
would be a slap in the face of the nation's founders, Harris, a
cockfighter, claims. A check with historical agencies in the home
states of all four presidents found no chicken blood in the
background of Jefferson or Lincoln. But Washington and Jackson were
another matter. Washington's correspondence mentions that the
future president attended a cockfight when he was 19. And
cockfighting was only the least scurrilous of the accusations
hurled against Jackson in the 1828 presidential campaign. In his
defense, Jackson scrawled in a handwritten message that he had not
been to a match ``for the last 13 years.'' By MIKE MCCLOY. Story
will move in the ``A'' category.{ &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SNOWBIRDS-ARIZONA (Undated) - This time of year, Joe Stofsick, 76,
and his bridge pals at Leisure World in Mesa can usually count on
having 10 or 11 tables of bridge players as the Canadians start
rolling in for the season. The annual welcome back party for
thenortherners is planned for Oct. 19, but Joe and his neighbors
areconcerned that most the seats reserved for the Canadians will be
empty. The Canadian dollar, now worth just under 64 U.S. cents, is
causing some Canadians to cancel or shorten their U.S. winter
visits. The number of winter visitors in Arizona declined 6 percent
last season_ the first drop since the recession of the early 1990s.
Arizona rankssecond only to Florida as a winter destination for
retirees. Other forces may be at work besides Canadian exchange
rate and health policy. Arizona's strong economy, for example, is
attracting young workers who are renting every available apartment,
mobile home and RV space, leaving few vacancies for part-year
tenants. With PHOTO. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
