<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP WATCHING NORTH CAROLINA RACE FOR CLUES ON 'CLINTON FACTOR'
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. With CLINTON-VICTORY.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ The ``mess in Washington'' is an unwelcome
guest in this year's congressional elections, even for a Republican
like Dan Page, who has spurned the advice of national GOP leaders
and has turned his campaign into a referendum on impeaching
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Political strategists have been watching Page's race since
August, when he became the first Republican to run TV ads tying his
Democratic opponent to Clinton's moral failings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Applauding Clinton's values, not ours,'' trumpeted the ad,
which featured a photo of the president and incumbent Rep. Bob
Etheridge standing together. Etheridge was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   But Page has maintained an almost daily drumbeat of baiting
Etheridge to act ``responsibly'' and join him in demanding
Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three weeks before a general election which may decide
the fate of Clinton's presidency, few Republicans elsewhere seem to
be following Page's example.
</P>
<P>
   Only 11 Republicans and 4 Democrats have made any reference to
Clinton's troubles in their advertising since Page's in August,
according to calculations by The Hotline, an electronic political
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks ago, Clinton's troubles seemed likely to drag
Democrats to large House losses and below 40 seats in the Senate,
sapping their power to filibuster bills they oppose. But now,
analysts wonder if an anti-impeachment backlash is rising.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington Post poll published Monday found that the
Republican-held Congress has lost support among likely voters since
last week's largely partisan vote in the House to begin a formal
impeachment investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, the proportion of likely voters who say
they intend to vote for the Republican House candidate dropped from
47 percent to 42 percent during the past two weeks. Democratic
support increased from 47 to 51 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   With such a volatile electorate, the analysts say, candidates in
close races are largely avoiding the impeachment topic, although
some who trail badly are using it to draw attention to their
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders are continuing to advise candidates to let the
scandal simmer on its own without stirring it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our folks out there have a great story to tell the American
people,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, citing
the party's role in balancing the federal budget, cutting taxes and
reforming welfare.
</P>
<P>
   In such uncertain times, both parties have reverted to what they
know best: Democrats are promoting Social Security and education,
and Republicans are advocating tax cuts and smaller government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what people perceive you are best at,'' said Mike
Davis, a longtime Democratic political consultant in Raleigh, the
state capital, who is advising the Etheridge campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, however, that on the day after the Nov. 3 election,
the Republican leadership of Congress will dissect the results in
the Page-Etheridge race before deciding how far to proceed in their
inquiry on whether to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a district that is going to send a message to the
president and to the Republican Party,'' said Jack Hawke, a veteran
of Republican political wars in the South going back to Barry
Goldwater's presidential campaign in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Hawke said Republicans intend to express their anger not only
with Clinton's extramarital relationship with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky, but also their disappointment in the GOP
congressional leadership for ``not doing enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis insisted the election is still issue-driven, which should
benefit Democrats. ``But if Bob Etheridge loses by 10 or 15 points,
the president is in serious trouble,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's 2nd Congressional District, which includes
parts of Raleigh and nine small farming and manufacturing towns
like this one in the northeastern part of the state, is a swing
district. In 1994, it elected a conservative Republican, David
Funderburk. In 1996, it was carried by Etheridge and Democratic
Gov. Jim Hunt, but ticket-splitters also favored Republican Sen.
Jesse Helms, and 52 percent of its vote went to the GOP
presidential candidate, Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Smith, a retiree and longtime resident of Rocky Mount, is
typical of the district's voters. She identifies herself as a
Democrat, but admits voting Republican occasionally. And like so
many others here, she is fed up with ``that mess in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president did was repulsive,'' she said. ``But what
the Republicans are doing is repulsive, too. The president didn't
hurt the government. He hurt his family. But the Republicans won't
get on with what's important to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke, a former state GOP chairman who is an unofficial adviser
to Page's campaign, acknowledged that the Clinton scandal, once a
clear advantage to the GOP, has shifted enough that Republicans
throughout the country are fearful of a voter backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House strategists are brilliant,'' said Hawke.
``They've made it look like people are fed up with it and
Republicans are going too far. So nobody wants to get involved.
Republicans are always complaining that the White House pays too
much attention to polls. But I think that maybe the Republican
leadership is paying too much attention to polls right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican pollster Bill McInturff predicted that polls are
going to ``snap back in a Republican direction'' in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And Democrats, who earlier this year entertained the prospect of
reclaiming the House from the GOP, are fanning backlash sentiments
just to hold their own.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
