<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN IMPEACHMENT CONTEXT, WHAT IS ELECTORAL VICTORY OR DEFEAT?
 &HT;    With CLINTON-POLITICS.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Measuring victory or loss for President Clinton in
the upcoming general election is no mere matter of tallying up the
number of elected and defeated Democrats. It's more a matter of
exceeding or falling below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   New York Times columnist William Safire tried to ``lowball''
Clinton this week in a column suggesting that any increase of
Republican seats in the House would be a mandate for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But that ignores historic trends that work against all incumbent
presidents. In this century, the party that controls the White
House has lost an average of 29 House seats in elections taking
place during their sixth year of control.
</P>
<P>
   Some have predicted that if the Democrats can do better than
this historical average, Republicans will feel pressure to
negotiate a Clinton punishment of censure or another sanction
rather than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if House Democrats gain 11 seats, they will control
the new Congress in January. But hardly anyone expects that result.
</P>
<P>
   In an uncertain political climate, some Democrats are boldly
predicting they'll gain a few seats, while some Republicans foresee
picking up scores.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., chairman of the National Republican
Campaign Committee, said recently that the GOP could add 10 to 15
seats to its current majority.
</P>
<P>
   Any Republican gain of less than this level would be viewed by
some political analysts _ and certainly by the White House _ as a
Republican loss that could slow the momentum toward impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
