<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAY-ISSUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT CALIFORNIA LEADER MAY HAVE TO GRAPPLE WITH GAY MARRIAGE
ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Although Republican Dan Lungren and
Democrat Gray Davis don't talk about it unless asked, gay marriages
will be one of the issues facing the next governor.
</P>
<P>
   The state may soon be forced to decide if marriage licenses
issued to gay couples in Hawaii should be legal in California, too.
And supporters of an initiative to outlaw gay marriages have
submitted signatures to qualify for the June 2000 ballot _ ensuring
a divisive debate during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond marriages, the next governor must make important
decisions on a variety of issues the gay community cares about _
issues such as financing a $52 million AIDS-drug program, allowing
gays to adopt children and legalizing domestic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The gay-rights community is universally supporting Davis, the
current lieutenant governor, over Lungren, the state's attorney
general. But many had supported financier Al Checchi and Rep. Jane
Harman in the Democratic primary, mainly because they were viewed
as taking more committed gay-friendly stands. Davis, who supports
domestic partnerships and civil rights protections, said he
wouldn't sign a gay-marriage bill ``because I don't think America
is yet ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren is staunchly opposed to gay marriages, even citing the
Seventh Commandment on adultery in one legal argument. And he went
out of his way to support a Colorado initiative barring local
anti-discrimination laws for gays. But he supports expanding
public-private partnerships to house AIDS patients, and he opposed
an effort to ban gays from public classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Gay-rights and conservative groups believe the Nov. 3 election
is crucial, particularly if the Legislature remains controlled by
the Democrats. A poll released Monday by the Public Policy
Institute of California showed Davis favored by 49 percent of those
surveyed compared with 41 percent for Lungren and 9 percent
undecided. The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 2
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups say 16 years of Republican governors have
helped stop the ``homosexual agenda.'' Gov. Pete Wilson, who cannot
seek re-election, vetoed every domestic partnership and gay civil
rights measure sent to him last year, saying existing
anti-discrimination laws were adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Gay-rights groups say a Democratic governor would improve the
civil rights laws and expand benefits for gay families.
</P>
<P>
   Davis as governor ``would be a challenge,'' said Lou Sheldon
with the Anaheim-based Traditional Values Coalition. ``I'm not
going to brush that one off. We'd have to prepare ourselves for a
huge onslaught.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago this month, California became the first state to
sanction inter-racial marriages. Activists say California faces
another historic moment soon, depending on how its leaders act on a
pending Hawaii Supreme Court case regarding two men fighting for a
marriage license there.
</P>
<P>
   A 1977 California law defines marriages as ``a personal relation
... between a man and a woman.'' But the U.S. Constitution requires
states to give ``full faith and credit'' to the laws of other
states, just as California accepts marriages between cousins in
some Southern states. The Hawaii decision could mean thousands of
gay California couples getting married on the islands, and
returning with a license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
