<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-1014-COX     10-13 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-1014-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR STRIKES AVERTED - FOR NOW, PROBLEMS REMAIN IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    With BOSNIA-STRIKES-1014.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. pilots, diplomats and military observers will
begin moving this week into positions to help monitor a Serb
military pullback in Kosovo, but President Clinton warned TUESDAY
that the threat of NATO air strikes will hang over Belgrade until
Serbs have ended their campaign of repression and terror against
Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   While pledges by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic have
averted NATO airstrikes for now, Clinton stressed that the United
States and its allies would rely on an ''intrusive'' verification
regime -- some 2,000 observers on the ground supported by military
surveillance aircraft in the skies -- to determine whether the
Serbs live up to their word.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be facts, facts on the ground, which will tell us
whether or not the compliance is there,'' Clinton told reporters on
the South Lawn of the White House. ''I certainly would hope that
this NATO position will, in effect, be maintained until all the
conditions are fully met, and I expect that it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization, or NATO, has given
Milosevic until Friday night to comply with a Monday agreement
concerning Kosovo or face the prospect of air strikes carried out
by a massive, U.S.-led force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments made clear that he favors retaining the
threat of NATO force for the foreseeable future, as the
verification team moves into place to monitor Serb actions on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the verification regime were still being hammered out
as of late Tuesday, the day after Milosevic agreed to pare back
military and other security forces in the southern province of
Kosovo and enter into talks centered on Kosovar autonomy in
exchange for a reprieve from a threatened NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the United States and three dozen other
members of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) will provide some 2,000 observers who will go unarmed into
Kosovo and fan out across the province to verify Serb compliance
with Monday's accord. It wasn't known how many of the observers
would be Americans, though several administration sources suggested
it would be at least several dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also agreed to enter into negotiations -- by early
next month -- over a path toward autonomy for Kosovo. Nine in ten
residents of the province, part of Yugoslavia, are ethnic
Albanians. Since 1989, however, the province has been governed by
ethnic Serbs, under a series of decrees and legislation ushered
through by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke brokered Monday's accord with an
eye toward three basic goals:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  end Serb violence that has led to the deaths of hundreds of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ensure the safety of an estimated 300,000 Albanians that have
fled their homes so that they might return before winter takes a
grisly humanitarian toll;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and set up negotiations between the government of Serb
nationalist Milosevic and the Kosovars aimed at returning to the
Albanian majority some measure of control over the institutions of
provincial government -- chiefly, the police, judiciary, schools
and local administrative organs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea here is you have a verification mission in place to
provide confidence and security to the people of Kosovo that they
can get the food they need, they will not be subject to police
intimidation, that they can come back to their homes ... pending a
political settlement,'' said U.S. State Department spokesman James
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Fully staffing and deploying the observer mission could take
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, however, were expected to begin moving within
days, likely beginning with a doubling and reactivation of the much
smaller Kosovo Diplomatic Observers Mission, or KDOM, that had been
operating in Kosovo under the auspices of NATO and the OSCE. The
KDOM team, roughly 50 observers, had recently moved out of Kosovo
due to escalating violence and the prospect of a possible NATO
attack, but was expected to return within days.
</P>
<P>
   Observers on the ground will be assisted by NATO aircraft,
including U.S. planes, flying over Kosovo on surveillance missions.
No NATO warplanes are envisioned for the mission, though the
Pentagon suggested that combat aircraft would be available to
support the reconnaissance planes if they came under threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll leave it to NATO to figure out whether they want to
disclose how they're going to handle the protection of those
flights,'' Pentagon spokesman Cpt. Michael Doubleday told
reporters. ''There are plenty of aircraft to take any steps that
NATO commanders feel are necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the risk to NATO pilots, air defense systems operated
by the Yugoslav military will be moved out of Kosovo or placed
under the observation of international monitors. In addition,
Yugoslav combat aircraft will not be permitted to fly in the
vicinity of NATO surveillance aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday said NATO would have ''unrestricted access'' to the
airspace above Kosovo, but would file advance flight plans with
Yugoslav officials ''up to several days in advance,'' of NATO
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ''But if it becomes necessary, because of weather or other
considerations, to set up one of these flights on a very rapid
basis, it could be done with as little as an hour's notice,''
Doubleday told reporters during a Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to point out potential flaws in Monday's
accord and the plans for verifying Serb compliance with it.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, while Monday's agreement calls for Milosevic to
pull back thousands of troops and police, some backed with armor
and heavy artillery, from Kosovo, it allows him to maintain
thousands more who were already in the area before he unleashed an
aggressive campaign of terror last February upon the ethnic
Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're still going to be at the mercy of Serbian force,''
said Kurt Bassuener, associate director of the Balkan Action
Council, a non-profit research outfit here.
</P>
<P>
   Bassuener also fears that unarmed observers on the ground in
Kosovo might be used as human shields by Serbs should NATO threaten
future strikes. Similar concerns were an impediment to NATO strikes
against Serbs during three and a half years of fighting in
neighboring Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people,'' in Kosovo, ''could have the same effect,''
Bassuener said.
</P>
<P>
   To anticipate that problem, NATO will set up a rapid reaction
force just outside of Kosovo -- possibly in nearby Macedonia, where
a U.S. military observer mission has been stationed for several
years -- that would have the capability to conduct combat rescue
missions on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   And, while U.S. officials declined to publicly discuss the
prospect of observers being used as human shields, one White House
official said privately that ''It would be a gross
miscalculation,'' for Serbs to threaten observers, adding that
''any punitive response would be decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
