<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5092 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDY-GARLAND-MUSIC-$A     10-13 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDY-GARLAND-MUSIC-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDY GARLAND: A BUNDLE OF EMOTION FROM ``MISS SHOW BUSINESS'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Oct. 18) 
(JT) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pure feeling. Judy Garland didn't just deliver it when she sang,
she embodied it, no matter how ragged her voice or how histrionic
her delivery. The sound of that much emotion so densely
concentrated wasn't always easy to take. Like no other American
singer, Garland erased the line between laughter and tears,
suggesting a barely suppressed hysteria with each gasp and
choked-up cry.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Piaf, who was seven years Garland's senior, also delivered
pure feeling, but it was harsher, even sadder, and more
animalistic. Even so, Garland, who conveyed the same mixture of
wracked fragility and resilience, was America's answer to the
Parisian legend. Both women were tiny, explosive and
self-destructive, dying at 47 yet paradoxically coming to symbolize
survival over terrible odds.
</P>
<P>
   Until the release of ``Judy'' (32 Records), a four-CD career
retrospective that comes with an excellent video showing highlights
from her 1963-64 television variety show, Garland's recorded legacy
was scattered among several different labels. This set, produced by
Joel Dorn and his son, Adam, with the Garland archivist Scott
Schechter, encompasses the breadth of Garland's recording career,
from an early 1929 recording of the 7-year-old vaudevillian through
a stunning, stripped-to-the-bone 1969 concert performance of ``Over
the Rainbow,'' recorded in London five months before her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy'' goes out of its way to intersperse familiar songs with
fascinating esoterica and previously unheard concert performances.
Her version of ``Over the Rainbow'' in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' for
instance, is prefaced with a dramatic re-creation made for radio of
the composer Harold Arlen ``teaching'' Garland the song, which he
sings in a sweet cantorial tenor.
</P>
<P>
   By 1946, Garland's wistful lost-little-girl sound had ripened
into a brassier post-vaudevillian trumpet. The set includes many
crucial movie songs, the most wrenching being ``The Man That Got
Away'' from ``A Star Is Born.'' The selections from Garland's years
at Capitol include two swinging Nelson Riddle-arranged performances
and two dark-night-of-the-soul selections from her Gordon Jenkins
album, ``Alone'' as well as are high points from her landmark 1961
concert album, ``Judy At Carnegie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Disks three and four concentrate almost entirely on excerpts (in
mono) from Garland's television show and include her first
television duet with Liza Minnelli as well as duets with Tony
Bennett (Garland's favorite male singer), Bobby Darin and Barbra
Streisand (their famous medley of ``Get Happy!'' and ``Happy Days
Are Here Again''). Also here are her rousing post-Kennedy
assassination version of ``The Battle Hymn of the Republic'' and a
heart-stopping rendition of her favorite song, ``Through the
Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at its most disturbing, it's powerful stuff. A performer
who always gave her all, Garland more than lived up to her nickname
(and title of her first Capitol album) ``Miss Show Business.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-FARMERS14-COX     10-13 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-FARMERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COURT PUSHES FOR SETTLEMENT IN BLACK FARMERS LAWSUIT
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge on Tuesday heavily pressed black
farmers and the Department of Agriculture to reach a settlement in
a nationwide discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing to discuss the status of the class-action case,
U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman upheld a planned February trial
date and said if the USDA is serious about remedying past
discrimination against farmers, all efforts should be made to reach
an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said a settlement is even more appropriate since both
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and President Clinton have
acknowledged some farmers have a legitimate case against the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the secretary of agriculture is saying these things in good
faith . . . then why can't it get done?'' Friedman asked. ``Trials
aren't necessarily the best way to solve systemic problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Although USDA lawyers declined to discuss details of settlement
negotiations in court, spokesman John Sparks said the department
has submitted an offer that seems appealing to farmers . He said
that although the two sides are growing closer to agreement,
several issues still need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more than just throwing money at the issue,'' said
Sparks, who works in the agency's office of civil rights. ``What we
really want to do is afford redress to those deserving of it and
get as many farmers who want to farm back to farming. There are a
lot of details that need to be worked out to achieve the goal we
all want to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks said solutions may include giving farmers access to
lending programs or returning land that was foreclosed on.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 billion lawsuit filed by more than 400 farmers contends
that, since 1983, the USDA denied or delayed their bids for
government farm loans because of their race. It also claims the
agency ignored or unfairly rejected their discrimination
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Friedman certified the farmers as a class, meaning they
can sue the government as a group rather than have to pursue cases
individually.
</P>
<P>
   In the event negotiations fail, USDA lawyers said Tuesday they
doubted whether they will be prepared for a Feb. 1 trial. However,
farmer representatives said they are ready to go to court as
scheduled, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government is just buying time,'' said J. L.
Chestnut, a lawyer representing the farmers. ``It is in the
government's best interest to delay this. . . . We don't have
one-tenth of the resources available to the government. These poor
farmers are ready for trial.''
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, department lawyers also questioned whether
the court has a right to hear cases that fall under the agency's
jurisdiction. They said the court may need to remand the cases of
the 12 initial plaintiffs back to the agency for further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, Friedman said the department already has had the
opportunity to investigate the farmers' claims, and in many cases
either ignored them or lost their files. He said the court will not
remand the cases, and unless there is a settlement, ``we're going
to have a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
