<SLUG> BC-COURT-PHONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS IN MAJOR TELECOMMUNICATIONS CASE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
Houston Chronicle Washington Bureau 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal regulators squared off against local
telephone companies at the Supreme Court on Tuesday, with the
future of local telephone service potentially hanging in the
balance of this bitter fight.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether Congress, in a 1996 law, gave the Federal
Communications Commission broad authority to require that existing
local telephone companies, such as Bell Atlantic, give new firms
access to phone lines in an effort to increase competition for
local service. The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals sided with
state agencies and local telephone companies in ruling that the FCC
lacked such a broad mandate, prompting a Supreme Court appeal from
the federal government and firms seeking to provide local service.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, pressing FCC's case, said the
agency has been regulating telephone service for 65 years and,
since the breakup of AT&AMP;T, ensuring competition in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Established companies ``have never embraced competition,'' said
Waxman, the Clinton administration's chief spokesman before the
justices. ``This act was not designed to protect AT&AMP;T.''
</P>
<P>
   However, attorney William Barr, representing local telephone
companies Ameritech Corp. and GTE, countered that the FCC violated
its limited authority under the 1996 Telecommunications Act by
requiring existing companies to grant fledgling competitors wide
access to phone lines at wholesale prices. The law says FCC can
grant new local companies access only to those lines needed to
begin service, but the agency has misinterpreted the statute by
allowing these firms access to all the lines they want, Barr
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrants sometimes want what they don't need,'' the Washington
lawyer said, adding that the FCC rule gives these new companies
``the most promiscuous right to access you can imagine.'' As a
result, start-up local firms get instant, inexpensive access to
phone lines and technology that the established companies have
spent a fortune to install, Barr told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, reflecting the enormity of an issue that has
prompted eight separate appeals to the justices, took the unusual
step of scheduling two hours of oral arguments in the matter _
twice the amount of time the court usually gives attorneys. During
the session, the justices peppered government attorneys and lawyers
for existing and fledgling local phone companies with questions
addressing whether Congress gave the FCC authority to regulate
local service and order companies to provide access to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist asked Waxman how the agency
can regulate competitive access for local service when the law
limits federal jurisdiction to interstate and foreign commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Waxman said that telephone lines do not distinguish
between local and interstate service. The same lines that handle
calls down the street also connect telephones across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission has unquestioned jurisdiction'' over interstate
commerce, Waxman said. ``Congress recognized that the use of
(telephone) network elements is inextricably entwined with both''
interstate and local service, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer, noting Barr's criticism of the FCC
regulations, asked the attorney if he could suggest a more fair
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Barr responded that the agency should address individual
requests for access from companies seeking to provide local service
rather than establish a national rule that fails to consider the
particular relationship each established company has with its new
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia was especially critical in questioning
attorneys on both sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He assailed a lawyer for companies seeking to enter the local
market, Bruce Ennis Jr. of Washington, for arguing that state
agencies retain their authority to regulate phone service _ so long
as the FCC agrees with the state's decision. In that case, state
agencies could regulate only at ``the grace of the FCC,'' Scalia
said in a comment Ennis did not contest.
</P>
<P>
   The justice, however, also derided the argument of Diane Munns,
the Iowa Commerce Department's general counsel, who said state
agencies have sole authority to set rates, without fear of FCC
oversight. ``You can (then) have 50 states with 50 different sets
of regulations,'' Scalia said incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy was even more critical of Munns'
argument, saying it ``doesn't make sense'' that California could
have one set of telephone access rules while New York could have
another.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Munns said FCC can regulate local telephone service
only if Congress expressly states that it can. She added that the
1996 act provides FCC with no local regulatory authority.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University law Professor Laurence Tribe, pressing the
case of established local phone companies, said the
telecommunications law states with ``great precision'' that local
commissions can set rates and makes no reference to FCC regulation
in that area. However, some justices seemed unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation has great precision?'' Scalia said with
surprise, noting the sharp difference of opinion regarding FCC
authority under the controversial law. Breyer asked whether the
court is presented with an option of ``all or none'' in which the
FCC has either pre-eminent authority over rates or no authority
whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   Tribe responded that any authority FCC would have under the law
would be as a ``backstop'' to ensure state agencies comply with
federal procedural guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   However, attorney David Carpenter, representing companies that
want to provide local phone service, said Congress intended FCC to
have wide discretion to require that established telecommunications
firms grant access to their existing phone lines. ``The non-AT&AMP;Ts
of the world cannot build alternative facilities,'' the Chicago
lawyer told the justices.
</P>
<P>
   The high court is expected to render its decision by July. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
