<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION SPENDING, IMF DISPUTES DELAYING BUDGET DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Disputes over education spending and the
International Monetary Fund kept White House and Republican
negotiators from a budget deal Tuesday, raising the possibility
that Congress may have to approve a fourth stopgap funding measure
today to keep the government from shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from an afternoon meeting with White House Chief of
Staff Erskine Bowles and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said the prospects for a final 1999
spending agreement did not look good, given the deep divisions over
education and other policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having very difficult negotiations about very serious
principles, whether Washington controls everything or local
citizens have an impact on their own lives,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am much less optimistic than I was this morning because I am
beginning to realize how far apart we are,'' the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich had predicted on Monday that an agreement would be
reached by Tuesday night and that the House and Senate would vote
on it today. But instead of voting on a final package of spending
items for the new fiscal year, which began Oct. 1, members may have
to approve yet another interim funding measure to keep government
departments running past midnight when a stopgap bill passed Monday
will expire.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have said they are willing to continue funding
federal agencies with short-term spending authorizations to avoid a
repeat of the 1995 budget disaster when the public largely blamed
them for two partial government shutdowns. Clinton has said that he
would continue to sign the authorizations. But with the Nov. 3
election now less than three weeks away, most members are eager to
get on with their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Chairman Bob Livingston, R-N.Y., said he
was telling members not to lose heart, that negotiations are ``95
percent done.'' But he acknowledged that negotiators are stuck on
issues such as education, financial support and reform questions
for the IMF, family planning and abortion language in the foreign
aid provisions, and how to conduct the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton and Republican leaders have agreed on only five
of 13 major appropriations bills needed to fund all government
departments and agencies. They hope to roll the remaining eight
into one catch-all bill that would finish out the appropriations
process for the 1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the remaining disputes is Clinton's request for
$18 billion for the IMF. House Republicans have agreed to the
funding, but are insisting that the IMF undertake some strict
reforms like shortening the amount of time it gives countries to
repay loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There remain some issues that Treasury and the Congress are
trying to work out, but we've made a lot of progress,'' White House
Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a tentative agreement worked out late Monday, the
Clinton administration will require loan periods be reduced from
three years to no more than 2 1/2 years, according to Republican
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF also would be forced to halt its practice of making
loans at below-market rates, which House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Irving, repeatedly has complained about.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also are pushing for greater openness at the IMF by
requiring it to provide written summaries of board meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department, meanwhile, would be required to oppose
future IMF loan payments to South Korea, unless federal officials
can certify that IMF funds are not being used to subsidize Korean
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The additional funding would be used by the IMF to replenish
coffers depleted during its 1 {- year battle against a world
economic crisis that has hit economies from Thailand to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is one of 182 member countries with financial
stakes in the IMF. But as the fund's largest shareholder, with an
18 percent share in the entity, Washington's concerns carry great
weight.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the IMF issues, Republicans are balking at
Clinton's request for nearly $4 billion more in education money
that he wants earmarked for helping some of the nation's most needy
communities build new schools and hire more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have agreed to provide more money, but they want it
disbursed to the states in the form of block grants so that local
officials can decide how to use it. Clinton and the Democrats,
however, have refused to give in to that demand, saying the block
grants would end up being used for administrative costs or other
programs that would not achieve the ultimate goal of reducing class
size.
</P>
<P>
   They say a big portion of the money under the GOP block grant
proposal would end up going to school districts that are wealthy
enough to provide more teachers and build more schools without the
input of ``federal seed money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The net result of a block grant would be a significant shift
of federal funds from poor schools and communities to wealthier
ones,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Texas Democrats in Congress share that view. On
Tuesday, Texas Reps. Sheila Jackson Lee, Gene Green and Ken Bentsen
joined with Reps. Lloyd Doggett of Austin and Ciro Rodriguez of San
Antonio, Texas, to endorse the Clinton plan.
</P>
<P>
   The five lawmakers expressed concern that Texas could end up
losing $17 million in education money under the block grant
proposal. They said the only way the money would end up in the
neediest communities would be for the federal government to dictate
how it could be used and where it would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to earmark to make sure it goes to the classroom,''
said Rodriguez, summing up the position of his colleagues. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
