<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALHOUSE-ANNIVERSA     10-13 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALHOUSE-ANNIVERSARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DECADES LATER, FRAT-HOUSE EPIC IS STILL HIGH-WATER MARK IN LOW
COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, the quintessential frat-house comedy
``National Lampoon's Animal House'' was released, and it signaled a
sea change in major motion-picture comedies. It also coincided with
my father's ascension to his status as Coolest Dad in the History
of Dads.
</P>
<P>
   Pops was living in Denver, recently divorced, and my younger
brother (then 9) and I (11) were visiting him. We had all seen a
``family'' movie together and were leaving the theater when we saw
the poster for ``Animal House,'' an intricate illustration of the
Delta House. Sundry characters poked their heads out of the
frat-house windows, displaying a sense of joie de vivre I had not
known since my dodge-ball days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, what's this movie?'' I asked. ``Looks kinda crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   My father stared at the poster for a long time. He smiled in an
... unfatherly manner. He spoke slowly. ``Well, it's a very, very
funny movie. But it's not for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Then something in him snapped. Somehow, the movie's anarchic
sensibility formed itself into a ray of energy that literally shot
forth from the poster and stunned my father, causing the incredibly
irresponsible parental act that ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, why not? Go in, boys, and grab a seat. I'll get the
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when He Who Had Previously Been a Poseur became cool. It
didn't matter that I didn't get many of the jokes. (I had no idea
what a ``frat'' was, didn't even know what a ``zit'' was _ a
crucial bit of knowledge to fully appreciate the famous
Belushi/mashed potatoes gag.) It was still one of the most
indelible moviegoing experiences I've had, and not just because of
the movie's adult dress code. It's because ``Animal House'' was the
perfect slob comedy _ a deft mix of music, lovemaking, friendship
and stupidity that typified the things Americans want to believe
their college experiences were all about.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible I remember the movie so fondly because of the
good-parenting mishap that led to my first viewing of it. (I've
seen the movie, in its entirety, more than 50 times since.) Film
critic Leonard Maltin, for example, says that ``National Lampoon's
Vacation'' was a funnier movie than ``Animal House,'' which he
calls ``sporadically funny.''
</P>
<P>
   About that, consider two things: 1) Leonard's name is
``Leonard''; 2) He's wrong. It's sporadically hysterical. And its
sporadicism is part of the film's charm. It explores other things
that are important to anyone caught in that purgatory between
childhood and adulthood, the age when you are, to quote a country
music lyric, old enough to know better and still too young to care.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sexual awakening (Pinto's attempts to lose his
virginity); class hatred (the rich Omegas vs. the
lower-middle-class Deltas); the cracks that form in longtime
relationships (the love triangle among Boone, Katie and her
professor); and, of course, toga parties (''to-ga, to-ga'').
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the film's many imitators thought ``Animal
House'' was successful ``only'' because of its vulgarity. They
missed elements that made it as much a social commentary as an
exploration of collegiate excess. The film really takes hold when
the Delta House's energy is aimed at conquering the authoritarian
restrictions placed on it by Faber College's Dean Wormer. He
represents the one thing most imitators forget to include: a figure
or institution against which to rebel. The film's sexual subplots
were mindful of this. Although there's plenty of appropriately
gratuitous nudity, the sex scenes weren't just thrown in to undress
the most shockingly proportioned actresses on-set, as ``Porky's''
and its ilk did. Pinto doesn't just find love _ he finds it with
the dean's underage daughter. (Proving you can laugh at something
that, in everyday life, you don't chuckle too often at.) Otter
finds it with the dean's ``wife,'' Mrs. Wormer. Vegetable shopping
was never the same for me.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was movie-watching, at least comedy-watching. ``Animal
House'' still feels fresh, less dated than more ``respectable''
films from the '70s, certainly more so than the tripe we're forced
to sit through these days. ``(BASEketball,'' anyone?) In fact, I
think I'll rent it this weekend. Maybe invite Dad over. I will,
though, make sure my daughter is out of the room. I mean, have you
seen this movie? It ain't for kids.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
