</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN ARE UNDONE, AND DONE IN, BY UNDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new entry in the Modern Library series has ``New York Novels''
as its collective title. The novels are Edith Wharton's, and they
are ``The House of Mirth,'' ``The Custom of the Country'' and ``The
Age of Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   In the recent notorious list of the 20th century's 100 ``best''
novels as chosen by Modern Library board members, both the
unmirthful ``House of Mirth'' and the not-so-innocent ``Age of
Innocence'' were recognized, and Wharton's ``Ethan Frome'' should
have been. (The tepid explanation that ``Frome'' was ``too short''
doesn't satisfy; it's longer than George Orwell's ``Animal Farm,''
which made the cut.)
</P>
<P>
   So what of ``The Custom of the Country,'' possibly a surprise
companion to Wharton's best-known novels in the omnibus volume? I'm
delighted by its inclusion, because it's my favorite Wharton, and
not mine only.
</P>
<P>
   I do not vote a straight Edith Wharton ticket. Among her two
dozen or so novels and novellas are several gems but as many
clunkers. If she never fails in her depiction of a society, she
often misses in the matter of its individual members. Lily Bart in
``The House of Mirth'' and Ellen Olenska in ``The Age of
Innocence'' are fully realized somber heroines, and the three
tormented principal characters in ``Ethan Frome'' are masterfully
drawn. But that's almost it.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I tried reading all of Edith Wharton all at once, and
it was heavy going. I couldn't care enough about so many of her
people. The most shining exception was and is a woman by the
unusual name of Undine Spragg, the heroine or anti-heroine of ``The
Custom of the Country.''
</P>
<P>
   Revival of interest in Wharton's fiction began in earnest, I
believe, with R.W.B. Lewis' much-honored 1975 biography of her. In
conversation with Lewis around that time, I learned that he also
rated ``The Custom of the Country'' as Wharton's strongest work. He
reasoned that the title itself was weak, less alluring than, say,
``The Age of Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier biographer, Cynthia Wolff, reported that ``The Custom
of the Country,'' ``... superbly polished and utterly
uncompromising, has now come to be regarded by many critics as
Wharton's best work.''
</P>
<P>
   So why its comparable obscurity? The answer may lie not only in
its title but in its timing. ``The Custom of the Country'' arrived
in 1913, nine years after ``The House of Mirth'' and seven years
before ``The Age of Innocence.'' Bad-girl protagonists were not yet
in literary fashion; but the mercurial Undine Spragg anticipates
Scarlett O'Hara by almost a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Undine, too, is selfish and self-centered, using her dazzling
beauty to manipulate men as steppingstones to power. What she wants
is anything that would be denied her. Undine is born without
pedigree but not without cunning. She marries four times (twice to
one man) without experiencing love. One husband is her passport to
New York society; another gives her claim to a French title; and
she casually discards a husband when she becomes bored by him.
</P>
<P>
   There's a shade of difference. One believes Margaret Mitchell
finally admired born-survivor Scarlett, but one is fairly certain
that Edith Wharton detested Undine, whom she projected as a symbol
of the grasping materialism that appeared to have consumed the
world in which Wharton came of age.
</P>
<P>
   In his foreword to the $27.95 Modern Library package, Louis
Auchincloss _ himself novelist of later blueblood generations _
notes a ``distinct implication'' in the novel that Undine, for all
her beauty, is sexually cold. She is ``... the triumphant Genghis
Khan of American commercial society: the sexless female who knows
nothing and believes in nothing but holds the world strictly
accountable for her eternal disappointments.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't necessary to love or like Undine Spragg to enjoy her.
After all, fascination with a ``femme fatale'' is a custom of our
country.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Forth Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
