<HEADLINE>
MOTHER SUES GUN MAKER OVER TEEN'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACOB H. FRIES  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lynn Dix recently had a dream about the future:
She was taking a grandchild to a museum and pointed to one of the
exhibits, saying, ``See, they used to sell guns that allowed anyone
to shoot them, even children. That was when gun manufacturers
refused to make them safer, back when your uncle was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   That uncle, Kenzo Dix of Berkeley, died at age 15 when a friend
thought his father's unlocked handgun was empty and accidentally
killed Kenzo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lynn Dix is suing Beretta USA Corp., the maker of the 9mm
pistol that killed Kenzo, claiming the company's failure to install
an internal lock on its guns makes it liable for her son's death.
If she wins the case, her lawsuit may accomplish what years of
political lobbying could not: a climate in which gun makers must
install safety devices in their products or pay the price when
someone dies in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach is very similar to how people took on the
tobacco industry,'' said Nancy Hersh, a lawyer representing Dix.
``This is our checks and balances at work. The courts correct where
legislators fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Dix is certainly not the first person to sue a gun manufacturer.
Cases claiming that guns are inherently dangerous and thus imply
liability for the companies that make them, have been rejected by
courts over the past two decades. Another case pending in New York
makes an even broader claim: that manufacturers ``oversupply'' the
legal gun market, so guns inevitably end up in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   This case, however, is being closely watched by gun
manufacturers nationwide because it makes a very narrow and
specific claim: that built-in trigger locks were available and
known to be effective when Beretta made its pistol, so not
installing the locks is akin to selling a car without a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case could have huge implications,'' said Eric Gorovitz,
legal director of The Trauma Foundation in San Francisco, another
lawyer in the case. ``If it is successful, there will probably be a
flood of lawsuits against gun manufacturers. All it takes is for
one to survive, and more will pop up.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 people a year die in accidental shootings, according
to a 1991 report by General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress. Of those, the GAO estimated that a third could
have been prevented had the guns been equipped with internal locks
or indicators that the chambers were loaded with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Dix's case hinges on product-liability law, Hersh said. Under
that law, a manufacturer is liable for injuries resulting from its
product's design _ unless it can show that the benefits of the
design outweigh its risks, she said. When Beretta made the
1992-model pistol that killed Kenzo, the manufacturer had the
ability to ``personalize'' the gun so that only the owner could
discharge the weapon after punching in a code on a miniature
built-in lock, Dix's lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple case of manufacturers designing an unsafe
product, knowing how to make them better and not doing it,'' Hersh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gebhardt, lead lawyer for Beretta, declined to comment
directly on the case, saying he did not want to influence potential
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   But court motions filed by Beretta outline their case. Beretta
argues that the design of the gun ``was not the legal cause of the
plaintiff's injuries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
