<P>
   MICROSOFT-JUSTICE (Washington) Outlining its strategy for
defending its corporate practices in court, Microsoft yesterday
asserted that it is not a monopoly, blamed the Netscape
Communications Corp. for its own problems, and offered detailed
defenses of its relationships with Apple, Intel, Intuit and
Netscape. The defenses came in an unusual 40-page document offered
not in the courtroom but in a paper faxed, e-mailed and
hand-delivered to reporters and posted on the Internet. The
company's decision to offer a detailed, non-legalistic defense
illustrates the importance of public relations to the Redmond-based
software giant, which is the defendant in a much-anticipated
antitrust trial scheduled to begin here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-STOCK (Seattle) Boeing enterprises didn't work because
the company's stock prices were so low, the ousted head of the
division said in an interview Tuesday. For now, he says, you will
see that effort pull back until the stock prices return. Larry
Clarkson also shared some thoughts about Alan Mulullay, whom he
sees as very focuses on the inside workings of the company... a
``Mr. Inside,'' compared to his predecessor. Clarkson, whose civic
activities have included presiding over the Seattle Opera Board,
says he hopes to stay in the area.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SATELLITE (Seattle) Sea Launch, the satellite launch
venture led by Boeing Co., has delayed its first commercial launch
until sometime after March 1999, company officials said. Instead
the project's initial launch in March will be a demonstration
payload with the same size and weight as a Hughes Space and
Communications HS 702 satellite, Sea Launch President Allen Ashby
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
