<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JONES14-COX     10-13 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PAULA JONES CASE MAY NOT GO QUIETLY INTO THE NIGHT
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the clock ticking toward their next court
date, pressure is mounting on both President Clinton and Paula
Jones to settle the sexual harassment lawsuit that spawned
Clinton's impeachment problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both political parties have urged Clinton to
resolve the matter. Meanwhile, the cash-strapped Jones and her
husband, Steve, continued Tuesday to mull over an unusual set of
options, including a $700,000 offer from the president and $1
million volunteered by Abe Hirschfeld, a 79-year-old New York
parking lot tycoon who said he just wants the lawsuit to go away.
</P>
<P>
   But will it go away? Legal experts are raising questions about
whether the case will leave a trail of problems behind.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, a settlement would end prospects of a public trial
at which he would have to answer Jones's charges that he made a
lewd proposition in 1991, when she was an Arkansas state worker and
he was governor.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring in Arkansas, U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright
threw out the case. The two sides are scheduled to appear in
federal appeals court Tuesday to argue over whether the trial
should go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Still uncertain is whether a settlement could stop the next
installment of the saga of sexual allegations against Clinton.
Wright has said that documents in the Jones case, now under court
seal, would be made public on the Internet beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new material includes allegations of Clinton's extramarital
involvement with several women _ identified only as ``Jane Does'' _
during his years in Arkansas and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But it may add little to the tawdry sexual detail revealed
earlier in the impeachment referral sent to Congress by Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr, said John Whitehead, whose Rutherford
Institute has sponsored Jones's legal team. ``There's nothing even
approaching the (Monica) Lewinsky stuff,'' he said of the
descriptions of the president's relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the materials include a deposition in which Clinton
denied under oath that he had a sexual relationship with Lewinsky
and also sat by as his lawyer, Robert Bennett, adamantly denied
that there had been any sexual contact whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   That could put Clinton in legal peril, said Jonathan Turley, a
law professor at George Washington University. ``The settlement of
the Jones case does not necessarily mean that the president could
not be held in contempt of court,'' he said. ``Not only did the
president lie in the deposition, but he is an officer of the court,
which places him under particularly high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more damaging, said Turley, could be the videotape of the
Clinton deposition, which would show whether Clinton was looking
attentive when his lawyer categorically dismissed all sexual
contact with the former intern.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to settle the case, especially after the president
won in the lower court, could also leave the public impression of
admitting that he sexually harassed Jones. That's the
``conventional wisdom,'' said federal prosecutor Bruce Yannett, who
added that defendants who are not at fault sometimes make payments
simply to avoid the time and expense of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   However, Yannett said that in this case, the guilt question may
have already been settled in the public's view. ``From the polls,
it seems the public already believes something happened with Paula
Jones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead, who recalled that few people believed Jones's story a
year ago, said that shift in public perception was a victory in
itself. Although he said he had taken a ``reality check'' and given
up on extracting a presidential apology, he would consider
Clinton's payment as a symbol of accountability, even if it comes
from a legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
   However, Whitehead ruled out the Hirschfeld cash, even if Jones
took it, as being part of the official settlement of the case.
``It's the president who should pay it, for the simple reason that
it is a settlement with the president. It isn't a settlement with
any third party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hirschfeld donation would almost certainly create a new flap
in the Clinton sexual saga. ``It certainly falls within a gray area
and raises obvious ethical concerns,'' Turley said, predicting that
there would be a ``chorus'' of objections that a private
businessman had, in effect, given the president the gift.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Klayman, founder of Judicial Watch, has already served
notice that his group would challenge such a transaction in court
as an illegal gratuity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
