<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL TELLS PALESTINIANS: NO AGREEMENT UNTIL SECURITY COMMITMENTS
ARE FULFILLED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel on Tuesday issued a bleak forecast for
success at this week's summit with the Palestinians after two Arab
assailants killed an Israeli man and escaped to a Palestinian-ruled
area of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no agreement unless the Palestinians fulfill all
of their security commitments and in light of this depressing
picture, there is no chance at an agreement being signed at this
time,'' said a statement by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's office.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was issued hours after the police reported that
two Palestinian gunmen drove by and opened fire on two Israeli men
swimming in a pond five miles west of Jerusalem, killing one of the
swimmers. The other man was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants, driving a car with blue license plates issued to
Arab residents of the West Bank, escaped to a village near
Bethlehem, authorities said. Some reports said they later fled to
Palestinian-ruled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, on the eve of the summit scheduled in the
Washington, D.C., area, underscored Israeli demands that
Palestinians do more to reign in their militant opposition and put
pressure on Yasser Arafat's security forces to move quickly to
catch the killers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials had hoped that the summit would end an 18-month
impasse by clinching a deal on Israeli troop withdrawal from a
portion of the West Bank and other outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the two sides could launch negotiations on a final peace
deal and avoid the danger of violence that looms over a May 4,
1999, target date. On that day interim peace agreements expire and
most Palestinians expect Arafat to declare independence.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
there was ``no policy change'' because of the killing but that it
did not bode well for Israeli expectations of improved Palestinian
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very positive thing that these guys can commit a
murder and then escape to Gaza or the West Bank without being
arrested,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Netanyahu has been demanding that the Palestinians
share more intelligence, reduce their police force, confiscate
illegal weapons and allow extradition of fugitives wanted by
Israel,according to U.S. officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Netanyahu's Cabinet gave the go-ahead to pull back
from 13 percent of West Bank territory if Palestinians fulfill
their commitments and acquiesce to Israel's demands for greater
cooperation on security issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli leader will go to Washington with two security
hawks, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon and Trade Minister Natan
Sharansky. Both ministers are known for their close links with
organizations that favor greater settlement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli leader still must maneuver to please his
pro-settlement coalition partner, the National Religious Party, and
to placate hard-liners in his own Likud party. Many have threatened
to desert him in the next election if he makes what they consider a
bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any one _ even one _ of the 160 settlements is damaged
because of the agreement, we cannot participate in the
government,'' said Transportation Minister Shaul Yahalom, a settler
and leader of the National Religious Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 160 settlements have to be safe, have to have safe roads
(leading to them) and have territory so they can develop in the
future,`` Yahalom said.
</P>
<P>
   Following Tuesday's murder, the third in two months, some of the
most hard-line members of Netanyahu's coalition called on the prime
minister to forego the Washington-area summit.
</P>
<P>
   In August, an elderly rabbi was killed in Hebron, and just last
week, a 19-year-old female soldier was stabbed to death outside a
West Bank settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians said they suspected Netanyahu's government was
using Tuesday's killing as a pretext for inaction. They said the
Cabinet go-ahead for a troop withdrawal was carefully worded to put
the onus for the summit's success _ and blame for its failure _ on
the Palestinians, when in fact Cabinet members have no intention of
turning over more West Bank land.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are pretexts that they invent for one simple reason:
they don't want to go ahead with the peace agreement,'' said Marwan
Kanafani, an advisor to Arafat and member of the Palestinian
legislative council, or parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu is never pleased,'' Kanafani said. ``He thinks he
can always find a way to say that the Palestinians are not doing
their part.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say their security forces are acting against
militants even, if the sentiment in the street is any judge, to the
extent that they are becoming unpopular among their own people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
