<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-800     10-13 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS FASHION: PROOF THE NEW LOOK IS OLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The only vision more disturbing than the Goth panorama
that Olivier Theyskens displayed in his spectacular show Monday was
the suggestion of the return of wasp waists and full skirts a la
Dior. And where else were backward-looking fashions like these
shown? In the Dior salon on the Avenue Montaigne, of course, in
blazing yellow suits with skirts held girlishly aloft by horse-hair
linings.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, for the first time since he took over the reins at
Dior two years ago, John Galliano presented the collection there.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thought the appearance of full skirts, in the very
place where Dior championed them, would make for a poignant moment
was disappointed. But one thing is clear: Galliano, to his
everlasting credit, has totally made his bed in Dior's house and
given it his own strong imprint.
</P>
<P>
   And if these suits were the oddest expression in a discordant
show, it is because the New Look looks old.
</P>
<P>
   One can hardly imagine them on the two older,
distinguished-looking women dressed in furs watching the show, who
thanks to some obvious help looked as if they are the same age now
as they were when Dior introduced the New Look in 1947. Nor can one
imagine them on new young Dior clients like Gwyneth Paltrow _ who
attended the show with Ben Affleck _ dressed in a pretty Dior
seafoam turtleneck and long, hip-hugging skirt.
</P>
<P>
   What was significant was the abundance of day clothes. Among the
best were familiar swashbuckling black jackets over black lacquered
knit tube skirts and olive knit tops and dresses. There were
water-washed chiffon gowns with Cubist prints, like the art of
Sonia Delauney. Galliano, who has often been criticized for his
lack of day clothes for Dior, was making amends.
</P>
<P>
   But every artist who strains under the yoke of constriction
eventually rebels. Surely that was the point of the dissonant
interlude of barefoot blond nymphets in plain white dresses. If
fashion really wants another pedestrian designer, Galliano seemed
to be saying facetiously that he can do it easily.
</P>
<P>
   Polls say that most Americans, particularly women and members of
minority groups, support President Clinton because they fear the
alternative of the radical right. And the rise of religion and
religious conservatism is evident in fashion's dalliance with the
1950s. But designers ought to fear from submersion in the '50s,
which began last season with a penchant for gray, for knee-length
skirts, for sweater sets and for smiling, sun-kissed fashion
advertisements. The ultimate regression would be the New Look, a
reminder of a repressive time socially and an artless moment in
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope, however. Not everyone in Paris was invoking Dior.
Most optimistically, Marc Jacobs, who was once a flag bearer for
the conservatism trend, banished it from his show for Louis
Vuitton. His presentation Monday was the first important show of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Having proved he can design a skirt and sweater set, Jacobs
reminded his audience with this Vuitton collection that he is also
a world-class talent. The assured, easy hand at work in the show
appeared in limpid hooded ponchos worn high in the front and low in
the back, over hot pants styled like trousers. Jacobs added
sophisticated details to every piece: a double-face wool jacket
with zippered bracelet sleeves, a cotton and cashmere sweater with
slit pockets like a flat kangaroo pouch, and blouses curved over
the shoulder with tiny darts.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs possesses all the ingredients to be among the handful of
American designers who years from now will replace Ralph Lauren and
those of his generation. Jacobs has already proved he can set
trends. He has design talent; a stylist's eye; commercial savvy;
innovative ideas; a strong right arm and protector in his business
partner, Robert Duffy, and at last a deep-pocketed French backer.
And besides, Jacobs, who once posed nearly naked in Vanity Fair, is
handsome.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that practically invented the word ``image,''
it's surprising how infrequently people publicly acknowledge the
vitalness of a designer's image to his success.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, within a breath of mentioning Theyskens' walloping
designs, the audience's chit-chat turned to how appealing the
long-haired Theyskens looked as he walked down the runway for the
traditional bow.
</P>
<P>
   Theyskens has Madonna to thank for introducing him to the world
even before he had a business. The singer and actress wore his
sweeping Gothic jacket to the Academy Award ceremonies in March.
Like Madonna that night, or perhaps more like Bette Davis in ``Hush
. . . Hush, Sweet Charlotte,'' there is something weirdly
mesmerizing about Theyskens' collection. Arianna Phillips, the
stylist who introduced his clothes to Madonna and who was also at
the Versace show last week dressing Courtney Love, was in the front
row at the show.
</P>
<P>
   In this, his first season of selling to the public, Theyskens
offered not only an ode to Dior, with full-cut dresses and coats,
but a paean to macabre women, with tight pink leather leggings and
the sharpest of high heels. Then came black leather skirts over
leather leggings, with leather shrugs that encased the shoulders
and bared the breasts.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Belgium, Theyskens is of a school of new designers,
including Raf Simons, who see the world as a dark Gothic place.
Their references are more the knife-point shoulders and harsh view
of early Alexander McQueen than the populist romanticism of
Galliano.
</P>
<P>
   Within 10 minutes of the ending of Theysken's show, executives
from Barneys New York, not known to be the most populist of stores,
raced backstage to tie up the collection exclusively for New York
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Theyskens presented his collection with the sense of theater
that McQueen and Galliano usually bring to their shows. In a less
complicated way, Dries van Noten used the art of presentation to
add dimension to his simple collection. He turned Salle Wagram, a
popular space for Paris shows, into a dimly lighted cavern dotted
with ominous black trees and foliage. Every chair _ there were
hundreds _ was painted an austere black, as if a giant oil slick
had rolled through the room.
</P>
<P>
   Against this starkness, there were pure and innocent cotton slip
dresses, some with ruche bodices, others with buttons down the
front or gentle folds and drapes adorning the hips. The innocence
gave way to black slips and jackets, some with dangling belts that
resembled glistening fishermen's nets with mollusc shells.
</P>
<P>
   Would van Noten's collection have been any less without its
artistic setting? And would Galliano's have been any more had he
followed his custom and set his clothes within a play? Designers
who go to great trouble to create a set for their clothes are
acknowledging the connection between art and fashion. There is a
lot of discussion about that link here in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly the magazine I.D. is running a feature this month on
the Biennale di Firenze, which explored the link between fashion
and cinema. Curated by Terry Jones, the magazine's editor, the
exhibition, which is running in Florence through Nov. 22, allowed
22 designers to place their clothes in an artistic setting of their
choice related to movies.
</P>
<P>
   Designers continually seek to show fashion's links to art, when
what many really want to do is to show how fashion is itself an art
form and can stand alone. It is this approach that was at the heart
of Ennio Capasa's winning collection for Costume National. The
white zippered skirts and jackets were a continuation on themes he
had started with last season. His low-slung pants and skirts are
now looser and have a sexy belt that sits just above the hipbone as
if an attached belt had become separated from the skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bergere's nod to the Gothic resulted in one of his most
decisive collections. The reference to religion and church was in
the elegant models whose heads were draped with scarfs like
mantillas. There were also loose caftans and light coats inspired
by clerics' robes.
</P>
<P>
   There seems no question that the Hermes-Martin Margiela new
alliance was crazy like a fox. Margiela's collections for the house
make for shows that are short on drama, but they do make plenty of
sense for a house with a reputation for innovative luxury. The
tunic jacket, without buttons, from last season has become a white
shirt and a jacket in light linen and supple suede. The sleeveless
jacket, a Margiela signature, looks at home at Hermes, and Margiela
offers tubular trousers as well as impeccable seamed ones in white
linen. While it did not make for one of the most scintillating
moments in fashion, Margiela and Hermes are at least truly looking
for a new look. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
