<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EDUCATION (Washington) _ With the budget battle between
the White House and Congress in the final phase, President Clinton
visits overcrowded classrooms to dramatize his insistence that the
1999 federal budget include money to hire new teachers. Republican
leaders on Capitol Hill, however, say the $1.1 billion sought by
Clinton for new teachers should instead be funneled directly to
local school districts. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PHONES (Washington) _ The Clinton administration asks the
Supreme Court to reinstate federal rules designed to break up
monopolies in the $100 billion local phone industry. By MARK HELM.
(Also filed in ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Members of the Congressional
Hispanic Caucus outline their top legislative priorities as the
105th Congress inches toward an expected close at the end of this
week. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-COMPUTERS (Washington) _ When it comes to computer
skills in the classroom, there's a troubling ``digital divide''
between higher-income students who have computers at home and
lower-income students who don't, according to a survey of
educators. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ Republican leaders in Congress
say they are confident they are zeroing in on a budget agreement
that is palatable to the White House. By GREG McDONALD. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-KOSOVO (Washington) _ President Clinton voices support for
using 2,000 international monitors to make certain that Serbian
leader Slobodan Milosevic withdraws his forces and allows
humanitarian aid to the region. While Clinton reiterates his
skepticism about Milosevic's intentions, he says NATO can now hold
him accountable. By NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-NASA (Undated) _ NASA managers are huddling to formally
set the launch date for a shuttle mission that will include Sen.
John Glenn, the Ohio Democrat who last flew in space 36 years ago
in a Mercury capsule. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Israel issues a bleak forecast
for success at this week's summit with the Palestinians after an
assailant killed an Israeli man and, authorities said, escaped to a
Palestinian-ruled area of the West Bank. By DEBORAH HORAN. (Already
filed.)
