<SLUG> BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NASA A-OKs OCT. 29 LAUNCH OF DISCOVERY WITH ASTRONAUT GLENN 
 
By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA managers on Tuesday formally agreed to proceed with the
launch of the shuttle Discovery, with Mercury astronaut John Glenn
among its crew members, on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery is scheduled to blast off on its nine-day research
mission at 1 p.m., CST.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, now 77, is returning to space 36 years after he became
the first American to orbit the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   He joins an international crew of seven commanded by Curt Brown,
pilot Steve Lindsey and payload commander Steve Robinson. Their
crew mates include flight engineer Scott Parazynski, Japanese
astronaut Chiaki Mukai, European Space Agency astronaut Pedro Duque
of Spain and Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Named to the shuttle crew in January, Glenn has combined his
legislative duties in the U.S. Senate with training at the Johnson
Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He will serve primarily as a subject in a range of medical
experiments designed to identify similarities between the stresses
of space flight on the human body and the natural aging processes.
More than 80 experiments are planned all told.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's countdown will get under way on Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA announced its Advanced X-ray Astrophysics
Facility will not be ready for its scheduled launching on Jan. 21,
1999, aboard the shuttle Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second delay of the flight, which had been planned
for August.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the agency's Marshall Space Flight Center said the
large X-ray telescope will remain with its manufacturer, the TRW
Space and Electronics Group for the replacement of an electronics
component and more testing.
</P>
<P>
   A new launching date will not be announced in mid-January. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
