<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      10-13 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: KOSOVO PACT MAY HAVE BOSNIA-STYLE PITFALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-ACCORD and KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(bl) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Through forceful if belated diplomacy, the
Clinton administration has won enormous concessions from Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. But the agreement announced Tuesday
on Kosovo, the embattled province in southern Serbia, seems fraught
with the dangers that have long bedeviled the West in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   For a Serbian leader to accept NATO jet fighters patrolling over
the sacred ground of Kosovo is an unusual act of pragmatism over
principle.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the United States seems to have secured a
temporary end to the fighting between Serbs and separatist Albanian
forces, with the promised withdrawal of troops and police from
Kosovo. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Tuesday, ``Mr.
Milosevic has taken some big steps back.''
</P>
<P>
   But once again, as in the Croatian war of 1991 and the 1992-95
Bosnian war, Milosevic has retreated only after advancing his aims
a very long way _ in this case, through the eviction of more than
200,000 ethnic Albanians from their homes _ before apparently
trying to lock in his gains by accepting the deployment of
international monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Once again a concerted international intervention is only coming
after violence has gone so far that attainment of a lasting peace
is certain to be difficult. The Kosovo Liberation Army guerrilla
movement Tuesday rejected the accord, saying, ``All solutions but
independence are not acceptable to the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, as with the large United Nations force in Bosnia and
Herzegovina, thousands of European observers will be placed with
scant means, if any, to defend themselves while U.S. NATO pilots
patrol overhead and attempt, in the words of NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea, ``to put some spine into the mission of the monitors.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bosnia proved, that particular configuration, in an area
where no peace settlement exists, has drawbacks. It undermines the
deterrent force of air power by placing potential international
hostages and victims beneath the planes. It can easily lead to
divergent U.S. and European views of the conflict. And it tends to
ensure that the buck stops in mid-air.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief visit to NATO headquarters Monday, Richard
Holbrooke, who negotiated the agreement, insisted that the 2,000
monitors to be deployed in Kosovo under the auspices of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe be of the
highest quality.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said Holbrooke suggested that some could be
soldiers in civilian clothes, and many others could be drawn from
police forces in NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that the security organization is an
unwieldy group that sprawls across countries of vastly different
cultures, and it will find itself in the middle of a conflict for
which no resolution is in sight. Corruption and indiscipline may
prove to be persistent problems.
</P>
<P>
   The onus of verifying Milosevic's compliance with a commitment
to withdrawal his troops and special police forces thus seems
likely to fall on NATO, which is already stretched by its Bosnian
commitments. As in Bosnia, Kosovo could well become a long-term
Western protectorate, expensive and treacherous to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   For despite Milosevic's pledge to restore the Albanian autonomy
he quashed a decade ago when he was president of Serbia, and
despite U.S. ideas to make that autonomy sweeping and genuine, no
long-term vision of how Kosovo can be made lastingly peaceful
exists. That is the painful void behind Holbrooke's
patched-together truce.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, like all NATO governments, considers
independence for Kosovo _ changing a European border _
unacceptable. Even Turkey, always a strong supporter of the Bosnian
Muslims, is muted about the independence claims of Kosovo's Muslim
Albanians because its sympathy for fellow Muslims is outweighed by
concern over setting a precedent for the Kurds in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said in Brussels last
week, ``We have made it clear to Milosevic and Kosovars that we do
not support independence for Kosovo, that we want Serbia out of
Kosovo, not Kosovo out of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   This tortuous formulation reflects a difficult reality: If
Kosovo is not ``out of Serbia,'' Serbia will inevitably be present
in one form or another in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And in a province whose population is 90 percent ethnic
Albanian, after the violence of the past six months it appears at
best uncertain that such a presence would be tolerated for long _
unless Serbian rule is one day maintained again, as Tuesday, at
gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   As one NATO official put it: ``A serious problem is that the
legitimacy of any form of Serbian rule in Kosovo is shrinking fast.
After the terrorizing of the population on this scale, it is pretty
clear that intense international verification is needed to sustain
any settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, as in Bosnia, the cycle of violence and revenge
may have gone too far to allow any peace _ other than Kosovo
independence _ to be self-sustaining without international
monitors.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 7,000 U.S. troops already in Bosnia on a mission
that now looks open-ended, that prospect is scarcely appealing to
the Clinton administration or to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was precisely to the avoidance of another Bosnia that
Ms. Albright committed the United States six months ago. But in the
interim, NATO moved with a painful slowness, as many alliance
officials acknowledged Tuesday, and scars similar to those that
make Bosnia so unstable seem to have been inflicted on Kosovo.
Moreover, once again, the United States has chosen to work with
Milosevic rather than defeat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us too long,'' said one NATO official. ``But we are 16
democracies, and consensus is hard to forge.''
</P>
<P>
   The most optimistic scenario is that the international presence
backed by the threat of force will restore Albanian self-rule in
Kosovo, allowing the more strident and violent supporters of
independence to be marginalized until a more lasting settlement is
negotiated three years from now.
</P>
<P>
   But the humiliations of the past decade and the violence of the
past six months have raised the ambitions of even moderate ethnic
Albanians well beyond autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 President George Bush told Milosevic that Washington
drew the line at Kosovo. U.S. soldiers were dispatched to
Macedonia, a former Yugoslav republic that borders Kosovo and has a
population that is one-third ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the U.S. soldiers represented an attempt at
preventive diplomacy. It worked for a while, but when the trouble
started in Kosovo, those soldiers did not move from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   And so, six years later, another U.S. administration finds
itself engaged in reactive diplomacy in the Balkans, an effort that
may have come too late to salvage a sustainable peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
