<HEADLINE>
AT LEASDT 10 DIE IN EXPLOSION AT MEXICO FIREWORKS FACTORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULTEPEC, Mexico _ An explosion in a house that doubled as a
fireworks factory carved a crater two blocks long in this nation's
self-proclaimed pyrotechnics capital Tuesday, killing 10 people and
trapping dozens under layers of concrete and rubble.
</P>
<P>
   What set this blast apart from previous gas-line explosions in
Mexico was the reaction of residents in this congested town near
Mexico City, who are fearful of losing jobs in its dominant
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of defensive residents tried to stop police and rescue
officials from entering their homes to inspect the damage. The
homes sometimes serve as illegal storehouses for gunpowder and
sulfur used in fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, with the choking stench of sulphur and gunpowder
prevading the air, insisted that the highly flammable stocks did
not help spread the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fireworks is our way of life and many of us don't know how to
do anything else,'' said Cristobal Salas de Castillo, a 47-
year-old resident who works in a nearby factory.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which injured at least 27 people and damaged or
destroyed more than 150 homes, also is bound to raise questions
about regulation in the industry, which is overseen by Mexico's
defense department.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the explosion was still unclear as of Tuesday
night, authorites said. Local police said a natural gas leak may
have been the cause but neighbors and other investigators said that
illegally stored fireworks were probably also to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Tultepec, a city of 50,000 people about 20 miles north of Mexico
City, has specialized in fireworks for generations. A large yellow
sign that hangs over the city's main avenue reads ``Welcome to
Tultepec, capital of pyrotechnics.''
</P>
<P>
   As residents huddled on street corners near the center of the
blast three large bulldozers clawed through the rubble and rescue
workers searched for more survivors. As far as a half-mile from the
site dirt roads were littered with shards of glass from broken
windows and shreds of fireworks casings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the population here is dedicated to the fireworks
industry,'' said Felipe Medina Santos, director general of Mexico's
civil defense. ``We're not sure if this work shop was legal or
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican army troops were deployed to the area to help restore
order and to investigate. The council's National Defense department
administers the fireworks industry, selling it gunpowder and
setting out safety standards, such as prohibiting factories from
heavily populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   But as competition here has intensified over the last several
years, officials acknowledge that scores of illegal and hazardous
workshops have sprouted in many of Tultepec's residential
neighborhoods. In June 1997, another fireworks-related blast in one
home here killed three people. A 1988 blast spread from a Mexico
City marketplace selling illegal fireworks, killing 65 people.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, on a lush stretch of land about 5 miles north of the
Tultepec blast, dozens of authorized fireworks factories sit in
carefully partitioned rows. On one of those plots, Juan Flores
Fiesco, 57, delicately lifted crates of freshly made firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a permit and our methods are constantly reviewed by
the government,'' Flores said as he walked around the factory that
his family has owned for three generations. His own home lies just
one block from the explosion site.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the devastated Tultepec neighborhood, Manuel Martinez, a
28-year-old mechanical engineer, quietly watched the rescue crews.
He said one of those killed Tuesday was one of the town's fireworks
leaders _ and something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I've lost my closest friend,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Globe researcher Lorena Zarate contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
