<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDLORD-JAILED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX SLUMLORD JAILED OVER ALLEGED INTIMIDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM HERMANN and PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The day went from bad to worse to completely lousy for
notorious Valley landlord Sherwin Seyrafi.
</P>
<P>
   _ After being convicted in court of six misdemeanor counts, he
was arrested on a felony charge of obstruction of justice and
booked into jail.
</P>
<P>
   _ During a somber jailhouse interview in which he apologized to
``the people of Arizona and to anyone else,'' he offered to give
his remaining properties to charity.
</P>
<P>
   _ An hour later, in a Madison Street Jail courtroom, Seyrafi was
told he's ``unbondable'' and would stay in jail for weeks, if not
months.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest and most dramatic chapter in Seyrafi's
long-running battle with Phoenix and Maricopa County officials, who
have branded him a ``slumlord'' and sought repeatedly to penalize
him for operating substandard properties and refusing to heed
tenants' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   His real-estate companies have accumulated about 400 maintenance
complaints at their Phoenix rentals since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Seyrafi began Tuesday in an east Phoenix justice court. He faced
six misdemeanor counts alleging environmental health violations in
apartments he owned in the 4900 block of East Holly Street in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He was found guilty on all counts, but the state requested that
the sentencing be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Seyrafi was outside the court standing in a
circle of journalists when a Maricopa County Attorney's Office
investigator leaned in, whispered to Seyrafi that he was under
arrest and snapped handcuffs on his wrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding me!'' the astonished landlord gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Seyrafi's arrest stemmed from his alleged efforts to intimidate
a tenant at the Holly Street apartments who had made housing code
complaints against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Seyrafi tried to intimidate Lori Utter into not helping
investigators,'' County Attorney Rick Romley said Tuesday. ``You
cannot intimidate witnesses from coming forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The alleged intimidation apparently happened several times from
May through October.
</P>
<P>
   In a jailhouse news conference Tuesday afternoon, Seyrafi said
he had not intentionally intimidated Utter. The formerly defiant
landlord appeared penitent: ``I'm sitting in front of you very
humble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hurt anyone of my present or past tenants, I apologize,''
he said. ``I apologize to everybody, including Ms. Utter.''
</P>
<P>
   Seyrafi said that though he was unsure exactly how much property
he still owned, he would be glad to discuss with the city turning
the property over to a charity.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped that ``my properties can benefit the people of
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the day, Seyrafi's attorney had said his client
was indigent, and that of the 28 properties Seyrafi once owned, he
now was down to four _ all in various stages of foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Seyrafi probably won't own anything by the end of the
year,'' Richard Coffinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Coffinger also said he found the obstruction of justice charge
``very scary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman in question was still his tenant,'' he said, ``and
it is very difficult to have a continuing relationship with someone
and not do something that the tenant might not like.''
</P>
<P>
   A court document filed by Romley's office noted that Utter had
repeatedly reported housing code violations at the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``In May 1998, Mr. Seyrafi accused Ms. Utter of being the
troublemaker and problem in the apartment complex,'' the document
says.
</P>
<P>
   Utter verified that Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that he wanted me out 'cause I was causing too many
problems,'' she said. ``I was a real pain for him, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Seyrafi raised Utter's rent in August and again in September,
according to the court document.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 30, Seyrafi was sentenced to spend 30 days in an
apartment in his Holly Street complex; he appealed the sentence
Friday and thus has not moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the Sept. 30 sentencing, Seyrafi drove to the
apartments and spoke to Utter. She reported that he told her he was
raising her rent and that he wanted her out of the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents say that on Oct. 7, Seyrafi accused Utter of
`'talking with a representative of `The Arizona Republic.' '' Then
he said, ``Never mind, I'm not going to argue with you, I'm just
going to get you out of here. I want you out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction of justice charge is a Class 5 felony, and could
result in a fine or prison time, Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Seyrafi was convicted in Phoenix Municipal Court of
numerous violations of the neighborhood preservation ordinance and
was sentenced to 60 days in jail. He served 13 days, then was
released pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a county grand jury indicted Seyrafi on seven felony
counts for allegedly defrauding tenants out of security deposits.
If convicted at trial this fall, he could face 12{ years in prison
on each count.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the investigation into Seyrafi's dealings, and
those of other landlords, Romley and Phoenix City Councilman Phil
Gordon formed a Slumlord Task Force that soon will propose
legislation to strengthen Arizona's rental laws. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
William Hermann can be reached at william.hermann(at)pni.com via
e-mail. Pat Kossan can be reached at pat.kossan(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
