<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5224 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ACCORD-ART-1     10-13 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ACCORD-ART-1,260(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO ACCORD ANNOUNCED; THREAT OF NATO AIR STRIKES IS AVERTED
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-ASSESS, KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The American special envoy Richard
Holbrooke announced an agreement here on Tuesday that averted the
immediate threat of NATO air strikes against Serbia and could lead
to a form of autonomy in Kosovo Province.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the accord with President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia calls for 2,000 international observers and NATO
reconnaissance flights to monitor troop and police withdrawals in
Kosovo, where Serbian forces have mounted a crackdown against the
mainly ethnic Albanian population. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The composition of an observer force had been a stumbling block
in the nine days of talks because Milosevic would not allow foreign
troops to be stationed on his territory. How the unarmed civilian
force will be deployed and how it will actually verify the status
of Milosevic's military forces remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that as part of the accord Milosevic had also
committed himself to elections in Kosovo and amnesty for those
accused of taking part in the fighting on behalf of the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the accord, both sides in the standoff _
Milosevic on one side and Washington and NATO on the other _ could
claim victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a rare television appearance here, Milosevic said he had
preserved his country's dignity and territorial integrity, an
allusion to his insistence that foreign troops not be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, NATO officials stressed that it was only the
approval Monday night of a so-called activation order authorizing
NATO air strikes against Serbia that had forced Milosevic to
finalize the negotiations. But at a news conference on Tuesday,
Holbrooke said that the agreement had been reached Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke outlined what is essentially a three-part agreement
intended to meet conditions laid out in a Security Council
resolution on Sept. 23: verification, from the ground and the air,
of the withdrawal of military forces, and the setting up of a
political process for Kosovo's future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ground verification agreement is to be signed by the Serbian
authorities and Bronislaw Geremek, the chairman of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which will organize the
verification team. The accord on verification from the air is to be
signed by the secretary general of NATO, Javier Solana, and the
commander of NATO Forces, Gen. Wesley Clark, and Yugoslav
officials, Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke held out particular hope for the pledges by the
Serbian authorities Tuesday night on a political process for
Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs about nine to one.
``We hope that it will mark a turning point in the tortured and
tragic relationships between the peoples _ Albanian, Serb, others _
in Kosovo,'' he said. But he indicated details still needed to be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be specific about how many soldiers or police
officers Milosevic was required to withdraw from Kosovo, where the
Yugoslav army and the Serbian police have been waging a brutal
campaign against the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army and its
civilian supporters. He said the withdrawals by the Serbs had to be
in compliance with the U.N. resolution, which mentions only general
pre-crisis levels but is not precise about numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have been fighting for the independence of the
province, which had its autonomy within Yugoslavia revoked by
Milosevic nine years ago. The West does not back independence for
the province but has been seeking some kind of middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   Barduhl Mahmuti, a KLA spokesman in Switzerland, reiterated the
separatists' stance for independence but added: ``We agree to a
three-year transition period that would lead to self-determination.
If Mr. Milosevic accepts that we are satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke acknowledged that he had failed to persuade Milosevic
to comply with a U.N. resolution calling for him to allow the
international war crimes tribunal in The Hague to have jurisdiction
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's only concession on future operations of the tribunal
in Kosovo was to allow freedom of access and a doubling of its
operations there. The tribunal has a representative office in
Belgrade staffed by one or two people, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of jurisdiction of the tribunal is particularly
sensitive to Milosevic because of two widely publicized massacres
of ethnic Albanians, apparently by Serbian forces, on Sept. 26,
three days after the U.N. resolution demanded Milosevic adopt a
cease-fire and withdraw his forces.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how quickly the 2,000 observers, whom Holbrooke
specifically defined as ``verifiers,'' could be assembled. They
will be drawn from among diplomats, former military personnel and
non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The observers are to have a number of roles: verifying
Milosevic's troop levels, assisting relief groups to help in the
return of about 250,000 ethnic Albanian refugees to their homes and
monitoring elections.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-member team is to operate under the auspices of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, a group of
nations based in Vienna that includes the United States and Russia
as members.
</P>
<P>
   Known for its monitoring of elections, arms control agreements
and human rights, the organization has never tried anything on the
scale called for in the Kosovo agreement. Its biggest long-term
mission so far has been of 300 monitors in Bosnia. The observers
are to be present in Kosovo for one year with the possibility of
renewal if both sides agree, an official of the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that Geremek, who is the foreign minister of
Poland, was somewhat taken aback by the size and potential expense
of the role devised for the OSCE in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Geremek met Holbrooke Monday night in Brussels to review the
agreement and is expected to come to Belgrade on Friday for a
signing ceremony with the Serbian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Solana and Clark, the two top NATO officials, will come to
Belgrade to sign the reconnaissance agreement with the Yugoslav
authorities and are ``enthusiastically preparing'' for the trip,
Holbrooke said. But Solana's office in Brussels said it was not
clear where the signing would take place.
</P>
<P>
   For the longer-term future of Kosovo, the president of Serbia,
Milan Milutinovic, announced on television tonight an 11-point
political agenda and a seemingly ambitious timetable.
</P>
<P>
   The document said there would be a restoration of
self-government to be achieved through elections for a Kosovo
parliament within nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The agenda said that local police forces would be created based
on ``proportion of population.'' This would mean that the police in
towns and villages would be almost entirely ethnic Albanian, a
radical change from the various kinds of present-day police forces,
which are almost totally Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading home to New York, Holbrooke was asked if
Milosevic could be trusted to fulfill the agreement worked out over
nine days of sessions that often ended after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The question of trust and Milosevic is a favorite theme of
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. She has repeatedly said he
cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke was less definitive. ``Our issue is to deal with the
realities and do the best we can,'' Holbrooke said. On the question
of trust he said, ``There's no value in going down that route
today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agreement was particularly welcome news for the
approximately 250,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who have been forced
in the last five months to abandon their villages after methodical
attacks by Serb forces. Tens of thousands of these refugees are
still camped in the open in makeshift shelters, waiting for the
Serbian police to disappear from the perimeters of their villages
before they go home.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees are clustered in four main areas where the fighting
was heaviest: the Drenica region in central Kosovo around the towns
of Glogovac, Klina and Srbica; around the towns of Pec and Prizren
in western Kosovo; north of the capital of Pristina around the
towns of Podujevo and Mitrovica, and in the southern region around
Suva Reka where the Serbian offensive wound up 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements were also good news to the international relief
agencies, which will carry the burden of helping restore the broken
lives of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret O'Keefe, the director of the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees office in Belgrade, said that more than
20 foreign staff members had left Serbia by Monday night, leaving
only three behind. The biggest concern had been that workers from
NATO countries might be targets of Serbian extremists, she said.
But the staff was beginning to return on Tuesday and two truck
convoys will head for Kosovo on Wednesday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the American diplomats who left Belgrade by car for
Hungary on Monday returned to Belgrade on Tuesday afternoon. Their
departure in a convoy of cars and the partial closure of the U.S.
Embassy _ documents were shredded and computer hard drives
destroyed _ was intended to increase the pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the 40 American and European Union diplomatic monitors who
have been driving around Kosovo for the last several months and
sending reports to their capitals on the fighting were unlikely to
return to Kosovo until next week, at least.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
