<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-ETHICS-NYT &LR;      10-13 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-ETHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE'S U.N. NOMINATION STILL ON HOLD AMID ETHICS PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The diplomatic career of Richard Holbrooke, who
brokered the agreement on Kosovo, remains in the hands of Justice
Department lawyers who are trying to determine if he violated
federal ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials say the investigation, which
has sidetracked Holbrooke's nomination as the next chief U.S.
representative at the United Nations, is expected to last several
more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry is trying to determine if Holbrooke had improper
contacts with former State Department colleagues while working as
an investment banker in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, a former ambassador to Germany and the architect of
the 1995 settlement that ended the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina, left
the State Department two years ago for a Wall Street career.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been formally nominated for the United Nations
position. Thus, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee says, it
will not be able to address the issue this year.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's lawyer, Richard Beattie, said in an interview that
Holbrooke's apparently successful negotiations this week with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic offered new evidence of how
valuable he would be at the United Nations. ``This just stresses
the importance of getting this investigation completed and
Holbrooke nominated,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which was prompted by an anonymous letter
last summer, is being overseen by the public integrity section of
Justice Department and by the State Department inspector general.
``This matter is still pending, and we can't comment on how far
along it is,'' said Bert Brandenburg, the Justice Department's
chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say investigators at the Justice
Department are trying to determine if Holbrooke had improper
contacts with State Department officials while pursuing business
deals for his investment banking firm, Credit Suisse First Boston.
Federal ethics laws bar former government officials from lobbying
their former colleagues for a year after they leave the government.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the investigators had requested records from U.S.
embassies across Europe of contacts between embassy officials and
Holbrooke, and of any assistance he may have sought in securing
interviews with foreign leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Holbrooke say it was impossible for him to avoid
contacts with his former State Department colleagues in 1996 and
1997 because he had remained an unpaid adviser to the
administration on the Balkans and traveled widely in Europe. They
say he was careful to separate his work for Credit Suisse from his
work on behalf of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke would replace Bill Richardson, who stepped down from
the U.N. job to become energy secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
