<HEADER>
A5228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIAN-POLASYLUM14-     10-13 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIAN-POLASYLUM14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Albanian girl denied US visit after brother seeks asylum
 &HT;    By Cathy Mong
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was the photograph with the barbed wire
faintly showing in the distance that cinched Cheryl Schafer's
decision to host the girl posing with her brother, mother and
father.
</P>
<P>
   The cold symbol of imprisonment was the opposite of the freedom
Schafer felt on her 80-acre farm, surrounded by fields of corn,
soybeans and the gentle mooing of dairy heifers.
</P>
<P>
   All the efforts in the world, however _ calls to embassies,
telephone and Internet conversations _ could not have completed
this match. Unbeknownst to Schafer, the girl, Aelsa Sulaj, had a
brother, Genti Sulaj, who has sought political asylum just 50 miles
away in Miamisburg.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter from The Dayton Daily News called Aelsa in Tirana,
Albania, but the girl was reticent to say anything on the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The saga began in March, when Schafer told Bill Bayman, Ohio
manager of Council Educational Travel U.S.A. student exchange
program, that Aelsa was her family's choice, and the two families
began chatting on the Internet, on the phone and through letters.
</P>
<P>
   But after several months, Schafer heard that Aelsa didn't
receive her student visa, ostensibly because her English didn't
meet standards.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer thought that odd since she had no trouble speaking with
Aelsa, and her written English was beautiful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She talked with the U.S. Embassy in Tirana and was told Aelsa's
brother hadn't returned to Albania. Bombings of U.S. embassies Aug.
7 in Tanzania and Kenya forced the closing of the embassy in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 3, Schafer said, everything made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to read a story about an Albanian with Aelsa's
last name seeking political asylum in the United States, in
Miamisburg, Ohio,'' Schafer said. ``Then I read Aelsa's application
and there was his name, her brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Sulaj, who was returning to Albania after finishing his school
year in Idaho, got off his plane May 22 in Cincinnati and didn't
get back on for the rest of the trip. He took a bus to Dayton and
after three weeks in shelters, moved in with Frances and Charles
Holloway and applied for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaj claims his parents are on the wrong side of the political
fence in his native country, and he would be in danger if he
returned. And the youth also fears he has closed the door on his
sister's chances of leaving the troubled country.
</P>
<P>
   Bayman said that's probably a fair assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have a relative who didn't return, she wouldn't get
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he pledged to bring as many students from Albania as
possible because of the region's turmoil. Currently, he is hosting
Evisa Quku, 17, also from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer said her family is hosting Ksenia ``Ksusha'' Kalinina,
16, from Eastern Siberia, but she holds on to the hope to see Aelsa
one day.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't blame Genti Sulaj for seeking asylum. ``I really
feel for the Albanian kids. If Aelsa were here now, to put her on
the plane home now would break my heart, knowing what they're doing
to the people over there.''
</P>
<P>
   For information on how to host an Albanian student, call Bayman
at (877) CETUSA3 after 3:30 p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Mong writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
