<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-CHARGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MUM ON OTHER AREAS OF HIS INVESTIGATION OF CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth W. Starr's investigations into the
Whitewater land venture, the possible abuse of FBI files, and the
dismissal of the White House travel office staff appear to be
ending with neither a bang nor a whimper, but rather in silence.
Administration officials say this silence is a cheap attempt by
Starr to further damage President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and their Democratic allies are becoming
increasingly critical of the independent counsel's decision not to
conclude his grand jury investigations and provide them some form
of exoneration. While Starr has said his inquiries may yet lead to
further allegations of impeachable acts, many Democrats contend the
independent counsel is trying to taint Clinton with innuendo
because he cannot criminally implicate him with fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unconscionable that he just does not terminate those
investigations and make those announcements so this matter can be
brought to closure,'' said Representative William Delahunt,
(D-Mass.) a former prosecutor, and a member of the House Judiciary
Committee. ``There have to be reasonable boundaries in terms of
time frames.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's allies said Starr has no evidence of any further
possible impeachable offenses committed by Clinton or Hillary
Rodham Clinton. It is a belief supported by Starr's decision not to
ask a single question during Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony
related to Whitewater, the FBI files, or the travel office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us believe he hasn't been able to find anything to
implicate the president or the first lady,'' said Harold Ickes, an
informal Clinton adviser and former deputy White House chief of
staff. ``There's a frustration that he hasn't issued a report to
the court. But that's his modus operandi. He lets it hang out there
and hang out there. Right now, it's up in the air, and no one can
say he has made a finding.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr concedes no such point, and said that all his
investigations, while nearing a conclusion, are not over, and that
any determination of more charges cannot yet be made. In his
referral to the House, Starr listed 11 possible grounds for
Congress to impeach Clinton, although all of those were tied to the
president's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot foreclose the possibility of providing the House of
Representatives with additional substantial and credible
information arising from those investigations that President
William Jefferson Clinton committed acts that may constitute
grounds for an impeachment,'' Starr wrote last week to members of
the House Judiciary Comittee, replying to their request for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office has not publicly commented on the status of his
investigations, although one published report indicates that he has
concluded that the FBI files represented little more than a
bureaucratic mishap within the White House.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Starr has several options. He may still seek indictments
against people involved in any of the investigations, he may make
another referral to the House if he concludes that there are
further grounds for impeachment, and he must, by law, issue a
report to the three-judge panel in Washington to conclude his
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That report would contain the inherent message that he has found
no further impeachable offenses, but he is under no time
restrictions to reach that conclusion, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said Starr is simply following the letter of
the law and bundling all his investigations together before issuing
a report to the court. He is also known to be actively
investigating accusations made by former White House volunteer
Kathleen Willey that Clinton groped her in a study outside the Oval
Office _ allegations that could still result in a charge of perjury
or obstruction of justice. The grand jury that investigated the
Lewinsky portion of the probe is still convened and met twice last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might be waiting for other testimony to come before he
makes a report to the court,'' said Joseph diGenova, a former
independent counsel. ``There are all sorts of acceptable reasons
why he wouldn't have filed anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said it is a fact of life in criminal investigations that
the subjects of any probe rarely receive sweeping and definite
exoneration.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the unfortunate things about being the target of a
criminal investigation is that there is typically no formal process
for closure,'' said Robert Luskin, a criminal defense attorney in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the independent counsel statute, he added, ``there is a
report back to the court, but in an ordinary case, you don't ever
get anything back from a grand jury or a prosecutor, like a letter.
What happens is you just never hear from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats and White House officials, however, say Starr has
decided not to conclude the portions of his investigation relating
to Whitewater, the FBI files, and the travel office because he
wants the specter of future charges to haunt Clinton as the House
determines whether to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Republican leadership hinted last week that
they may seek to expand the Lewinsky inquiry into areas of
Whitewater and the travel office dismissals, angering their
Democratic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a prosecutor trying to make a move on a defendant,
you leverage every bit of power you have,'' Representative James A.
Traficant Jr., a Democrat from Ohio, said in a telephone interview.
``It's the unfair atmosphere that I don't like. They say he did one
thing, but the scuttlebutt is that they have more.''
</P>
<P>
   Traficant has proposed that the House compel Starr to submit any
evidence of wrongdoing by Clinton in any of the other probes, so
lawmakers may weigh the range of allegations in an impeachment
proceeding and not harbor suspicions of future charges. But the
proposal has little support among members of the Republican
majority.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitewater inquiry initially began under special prosecutor
Robert B. Fiske in January 1994, and was intended to focus on
Clinton's real estate investments in Arkansas that were tied to a
failed savings and loan association.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Starr, who replaced Fiske, received permission from the
appellate court judges to investigate why seven members of the
White House travel office were dismissed and whether Mrs. Clinton
concealed her involvement. Later in 1996, Starr added to his
portfolio an investigation into whether the White House abused the
secret FBI files on more than 400 Republicans in prior
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   This past January Starr took on the last piece of his probe:
allegations that Clinton lied under oath in the Paula Jones
sexual-harassment lawsuit when he denied having a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more benign explanation is he might just not be finished
with those investigations,'' said Paul Rothstein, a professor at
the Georgetown University Law Center. ``It does seem to be a
stretch that at this time, he isn't in a position to draw some type
of conclusion. There comes a time when you have to either fish or
cut bait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
