<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 18,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE STORY
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-THEATER (Undated) _ Like book publishing before it _
until the last decade, a quaint holdout against the forces of media
consolidation _ the theater is now becoming ``content'' suitable
for synergistic annexation and exploitation by our new
entertainment conglomerates. By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   BELOVED-FILM (Undated) _ What is most impressive about the film
version of ``Beloved'' is not that it simplifies Toni Morrison's
difficult esthetic to attract a wider audience and become a
blockbuster in the process, but that it takes an opposite tack: It
stubbornly reinforces a literary way of looking at things.By Will
Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   IAN-MCKELLEN-FILMS (Leeds, England) _ There is something rather
touching about Ian McKellen's new enthusiasm for cinema. Now, at
59, he has acquired an appetite to work in movies, to do what for
the best part of four decades he found unappealing. Is it fame that
he is after? By Alan Riding. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FASCISM-MOVIES (Undated) _ Humor may be, in its essence,
anti-fascistic: It takes what is most self-important, most
unyielding and most unforgiving, and dissolves it into absurdity.
Fascism meets its match in farce. That is the approach, delicately
taken, of the new Italian film ``Life is Beautiful,'' the winner of
the grand jury prize at the 1998 Cannes Film Festival. By Edward
Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-WIT-CANBY (New York) _ In ``Wit'' the main character
dies at the end but, for the next two hours that pass in a wink,
the audience is treated to the kind of theatrical experience of
which legends are made. We come to know and appreciate the mind and
substance of this singular character and of the playwright who
conceived her, as well as the ravishing potential of the singular
actress who plays Vivian: Kathleen Chalfant.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   AZNAVOUR-MUSIC (Paris) _ Charles Aznavour may well be the only
person who remembers his first visit to New York in 1948. This
week, as Aznavour embarks on a new American tour, public
recognition is the least of his problems. Having sold close to 100
million albums, he now enjoys the magical status of international
musical legend. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   JUDY-GARLAND-MUSIC (Undated) _ Until the release of ``Judy'' (32
Records), a four-CD career retrospective that comes with an
excellent video showing highlights from her 1963-64 television
variety show, Judy Garland's recorded legacy was scattered among
several different labels. This set, produced by Joel Dorn and his
son, Adam, with the Garland archivist Scott Schechter, encompasses
the breadth of Garland's recording career. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-NOVELTIES (Undated) _ Planned obsolescence may work well
in the auto industry but less well in classical music, which has
invested the bulk of its holdings in the used-symphony and
used-opera business, and has lots of trouble convincing listeners
that the new models are any good. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE-EDWARD-TV (London) _ Prince Edward, 34, the youngest son
of Queen Elizabeth, is beginning to see some financial success in
his own film production company, Ardent Productions. And although
competitors in Britain's television industry complain that he is
shamelessly trading on his connections to advance his career, he
has managed to insure new-found respect for Ardent by crossing the
all-important continental divide and selling a number of his
programs to the United States. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   MINIATURE-OBJECTS-ANTIQUES (Washington) _ Last month, 70 of
Daniel Brush's exquisitely detailed steel and gold miniature
objects went on view here in ``Daniel Brush: Gold Without
Boundaries,'' a retrospective exhibition at the Renwick Gallery of
the National Museum of American Art. The show, through Jan. 10,
coincides with the publication of an elaborately illustrated book
about the artist's metal works. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (`t' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-POLAND-JEWS (Warsaw) _ Seelking vestiges of Jewish
Bialystok. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TUNISIA (Undated) _ In Tunisia, the Romans built
monuments whose ruins evoke the empire. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Surfing the net: Vacation planning. .
By L.R. Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ How to pack, or when ironing is
not an option. Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Washington Monument closed; All aboard
the Britannia; Touring the Northeast; Easier travel for the
disabled; Gizmo heaven.
</P>
