<SLUG> BC-GLF-DAVIDDUVAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval now contends for Player of the Year
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Duval's story keeps getting more difficult to
comprehend. The guy who could not find a way to win now can't seem
to locate a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   For his first 92 starts in PGA Tour events _ until last year's
Michelob Championship at Kingsmill _ the former Georgia Tech player
had on seven occasions been a runner-up. Since then, through last
week's successful defense at Williamsburg, Va., Duval has won seven
times in his last 23 PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   Equally remarkable, Duval is in reach of a semi-unfathomable $3
million season. With $2,464,408 (already a PGA Tour record by
nearly $400,000), the 26-year old Duval has a firm hold on the
money title and easily could pass $3 million with a repeat victory
in three weeks at the Tour Championship at Atlanta's East Lake Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   And with Duval fairly familiar with the course, having played it
occasionally during his days at Tech, who do you think will be
favored?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there remains yet another possibility. With five
wins _ he defends at the Walt Disney Classic next week _ Duval
could become the prime candidate for PGA Tour Player of the Year.
Two months ago Mark O'Meara seemed an automatic selection with the
Masters and British Open on his record, but things have changed.
Two weeks ago at the Buick Challenge, Duval theorized what could
become reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can say I have a chance to win it, but I think
I'll certainly have to win another event, if not two more, and the
money title to even be considered over Mark,'' Duval said then.
``To win two majors is obviously a huge deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone to beat that, you'd have to win four or five times
and no one else has won more than twice (Duval leads everyone else,
4-2). I guess then you could make an argument either way. If I have
to vote, I'll probably abstain.''
</P>
<P>
   Those major championships _ or the lack of one _ are what leave
a trace of dissatisfaction for Duval and explain why he so respects
the owner of two. With a major secured, Duval would more readily
accept the ``best player in the world'' references.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a bit of a void on my resume,'' Duval said. ``I
do think that the past 12 months I've played as well as anybody
else. But whether that makes me the best player, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics beyond the money list only enhance Duval's case. He
is first in scoring (69.02), putting (1.720 per hole) and birdies
(4.39 per round). He is second in all-around ranking (combined
categories), tied for second in total driving, fourth in greens in
regulation (70.2 percent) and sixth in driving distance (286.7).
</P>
<P>
   For a guy with nearly $6.3 million earned in less than four full
seasons, believe that the money title is meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majors are the majors _ you've got four of them each year
and I'm not belittling them at all and please don't take it that
way,'' Duval said. ``But only one person can win the money title,
so there's got to be something special to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
