<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus out for year
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still pained by his degenerative right hip, Jack Nicklaus, 58,
has canceled the rest of his season, including customary
appearances in the Shark Shootout and Wendy's Three-Tour Challenge.
Nicklaus said he will not play competitively before January if
invited to the Senior Skins Game and might not even take his clubs
to Australia when captaining the U.S. in the President's Cup.
``It's not hitting the golf ball or walking,'' Nicklaus said.
``It's the twisting and turning of the golf swing combined with
walking. I just went bow-hunting in Arizona and we walked 5-10
miles a day and I felt great with just a little Advil. I felt like
I could go play shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus used one of his infrequent rounds to play Atlanta's
East Lake Golf Club last week as a guest of developer Tom Cousins.
Assessing East Lake for the Tour Championship in three weeks,
Nicklaus, who chipped for eagle on the par-5 15th, termed the
Bermuda rough, clipped to about 4 1/2 inches, as tough but fair.
``The golf course is in absolutely wonderful condition,'' said
Nicklaus, who played it earlier in May. ``The players will really
like the club and the golf course. I think the scores will be
reasonable. I don't think they're going to tear it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Crunch time for top 30
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Cink, an East Lake member, inched up to the 31st spot on
the money list by winning $13,894 at Kingsmill Sunday, but still
trails No. 30 Bob Tway by nearly $53,000. Atlanta's Billy Andrade,
another East Lake member, made $10,038 and stands 41st at $690,209.
Realistically, Andrade needs a win at either Las Vegas or Walt
Disney to make the Tour Championship. No. 28 Tom Watson, with less
than a $50,000 cushion, likely will play Walt Disney as his 15th
event for some insurance.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   According to Sports Illustrated, Tiger Woods has extended his
contract with International Management Group past 2004, but has
fired agent Huhges Norton because he felt ``overcommitted'' by him.
Norton had negotiated a reported $150 million in endorsements for
Woods. . . . Jim Colbert's emotional Senior tour win Sunday at The
Trans-America was his first since returning from last year's
prostate cancer surgery. Calling it ``by far the most meaningful
golf tournament I've ever won,'' Colbert cited Arnold Palmer's
continuing battle with the disease. ``I felt like I was playing for
both of us.'' . . . Larry Nelson's previously injured neck is
feeling strong enough to caddie for his son, Drew, at first-stage
PGA Tour Qualifying School this week. Jennings Mill Golf Club in
Bogart, Ga., is the local first-stage site, concluding play Friday.
. . . Corey Pavin, who managed a second top 10 finish at Kingsmill,
has parted ways with long-time caddie Eric Schwarz. . . . With Nick
Faldo having broken up with both his teacher (David Leadbetter) and
girlfriend (Brenna Cepelak), it's been suggested that caddie Fannie
Sunesson might be wise to offer her boss pinpoint yardages from now
on. . . . Denise Kileen (3-under-par 285) was among 24 LPGA players
earning full exemption for 1999 through Q-school at the LPGA
International course in Daytona Beach, Fla. Vicki Goetze Ackerman
(297) missed by eight shots and tied for the last spot of
conditional exemption, joining Augusta, Ga.'s Mitzi Edge. . . .
Stopping at East Lake following the recent Buick Challenge were top
30 members Billy Mayfair and Bob Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
