</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BISHER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It wasn't the big homer, but all the 'little' things
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Finally, this is the year we should rid ourselves of
the old barnacle that goes, ''No team three games down has ever
come back to win a playoff or World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll notice I said should, not will. Prognostication is not my
forte, beyond predicting the next sunrise. When Bruce Bochy went to
the mound Monday night to reel in Kevin Brown, you could see the
dagger between his shoulder blades. What he had done was go for it
all. Put all his chips on the table.
</P>
<P>
   He had defied logic in the sixth inning when he could have
walked Michael Tucker and pitched to John Smoltz, but Tucker
singled off Andy Ashby for one of the five runs he batted in. Now
it was Brown, Padres ace, or nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The move came up snake-eyes. Not that it was Tucker's home run
alone. Somewhat lost in the pandemonium was Tony Graffanino's
double that scored John Rocker, and then himself on the throw that
detoured wide of the plate. That was the safety net between winning
or losing when Greg Myers delivered a two-run homer in the Padres'
last bat.
</P>
<P>
   (Remember that name, Greg Myers? He made a pit stop in Atlanta
when the Braves exchanged a minor league prospect with Minnesota
for him, too late for the postseason, then released him.)
</P>
<P>
   What Bochy had done was take Brown out of the sixth game today,
brilliant a gamble as it appeared to be when the Macon, Georgian
strode in from this bullpen. It was a given. It was over. The
television cast was packing to make a getaway. But wait a minute,
what is this?
</P>
<P>
   Brown was having trouble throwing where he aimed. He went to
several long counts and never got into a rhythm, I think they call
it. Keep in mind, no pitcher is unhittable. The abrupt swing of fan
emotion was excruciatingly depicted by camera vignettes of San
Diegans in the stands, from ecstasy to grief. I don't think I've
ever seen a more riveting ball game in my life, no matter who won.
</P>
<P>
   What this does, then, is wipe out Brown until the seventh game.
It sets up the Braves with Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux to stretch
it to seven games and end it there. It was dramatic doings when
Bobby Cox sent for Maddux to put out the fire in the ninth,
reaching for his own ace in a moment of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   This was oldtime baseball managing. In the days of baggy
britches and train travel, managers never hesitated to call on
their ace when in need. Start one day, work out of the bullpen the
next. The great Walter Johnson came out of the bullpen and saved
the World Series for Washington in 1924. One of the bulls of
pitching was a Texan named Firpo Marberry, as foreboding as his
name, who often started as many times as he relieved in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got his work done in 13 pitches, so it was no more than
throwing between games. That sets him up for the finale. Meantime,
say this for Bochy, his managing in this series would surely have
turned up roses had Tony Gwynn pulled his oar. When the finest
batsman of the decade is hitting .190, your offense has one hand
tied behind its back. All he had to do is hit his weight, which
appears to be approaching a ton.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, carrying on in lockstep is the Braves' Venezuelan
Connection, Andres Galarraga one day, Ozzie Guillen every day.
Guillen is the steal of the year, from the streets of Baltimore to
a World Series, the way it looks from this chair.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the editor of the Atlanta Journal, Atlanta, Ga.
E-mail: furman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
