<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King, Eliades reach agreement on unification bout
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Promoter Don King, blamed by rivals last year for
derailing a heavyweight title unification between Evander Holyfield
and Lennox Lewis, Tuesday became the biggest reason the fight is on
the verge of taking place.
</P>
<P>
   King reached a promotional agreement with Panos Eliades, who
represents Lewis, on division of profits and has agreed, after
prodding by Holyfield attorney Jim Thomas, to accept a percentage
of potential profits instead of a guarantee. That stunned Time
Warner sports president Seth Abraham, cognizant that King asked to
be guaranteed $5 million last December when Holyfield-Lewis
negotiations fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Lewis likely will meet in early March in Las
Vegas. King, joining members of Lewis' camp at a news conference in
London Tuesday night, announced ``the fight is on.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Abraham denied it's a done deal but expressed
optimism negotations could be completed as early as Thursday, when
all parties meet in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be close because Don even wished my daughter a happy
bat mitzvah,'' said Abraham, a former business partner of King's
but a vocal target in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he was ``guardedly optimistic,'' adding, ``I don't
anticipate a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which would distribute the fight on pay-per-view,
will guarantee Holyfield $20 million and Lewis $8 million, and is
open to giving Holyfield a share of profits from pay-per-view
sales.
</P>
<P>
   One hangup is Henry Akinwande, who is due an immediate mandatory
title shot with Holyfield by the WBA. His manager, J.C. Courreges,
said he is open to allowing Holyfield-Lewis to take place on the
condition that Akinwande be given a shot at the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Akinwande also may be given ``step-aside'' money and/or a fight
on the Holyfield-Lewis undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
