<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's post-season hopes could hinge on weekend matchupsBy
Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite their quick rise to national prominence, the Georgia
women's soccer team hasn't yet developed a reputation for winning
in the clutch. This season, they've been hit with injuries and have
had some tough luck, but two key home SEC matches this weekend
could give them the chance to set their post-season ambitions in
order.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs (7-3-1), ranked 23rd this week in the Soccer
Buzz poll, play host to Kentucky Friday at 4 p.m., then entertain
No. 8 Vanderbilt on Sunday at 2 p.m. Georgia, tied with Kentucky
for fourth in the SEC East with a 2-2 conference mark, could clinch
a spot in next month's SEC tournament with a win in either of their
final two home conference matches.
</P>
<P>
   Regaining some momentum, as well as some key players who have
been out, is also a priority. ``We're not at full strength at all,
and we're playing quite well,'' coach Bill Barker said. ``We're not
unhappy with anything we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia let a tie game slip away before suffering a 2-1 loss at
sixth-ranked Portland two weeks ago, and tied at Washington after
hitting the woodwork several times.
</P>
<P>
   Both results were reasonable given that the Lady Dogs were
playing without All-American defender Stephanie Yarem, who scored
18 goals last year but has just one so far because of a stress
fracture in her foot. She hasn't played since Georgia lost at
Florida last month, and the likelihood of her return is evaluated
``day by day,'' Barker said. Also affected by injuries have been
defender Danielle Jordan, midfielders Ali Comis and Jen Lewis and
forward Suzannah Weathersbee.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the LadyDogs have found their new confines at the
Georgia Soccer Stadium to their liking. They were 6-0 there before
Tuesday's home match with the College of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   Rowing news
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech rowing team will take part at the Head of the
Charles in Boston this weekend along with other college teams,
international championship teams and high school teams from the
United States and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day event along the Charles River in Massachussetts is
the most prestigious race in the fall and the largest single
sporting event in the world. Tech's rowing team, which currently
competes as a club sport, was accepted via a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to row with such great athletes,'' head coach
Rob Canavan said. ``This will indicate how good a team we will have
in the spring. If we have a good showing, we might get considered
for varsity status.''
</P>
<P>
   On a roll
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia State women's soccer team takes a nine-match
unbeaten streak into a home match Friday afternoon against TAAC
West rival Troy State. The Lady Panthers are 9-1-1 and have gotten
nine goals from forward Chandra Yorgason, four of them
game-winners.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
