<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-HAMILTON-C     10-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-HAMILTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamilton back on track after QB job was almost lost
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen
reserves the right to talk a little smack on the practice field,
especially to quarterback Joe Hamilton, the trigger man for his
creations and the heartbeat of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Five days before the biggest game of Hamilton's college football
career, against No. 7 Virginia, Friedgen got in his junior
quarterback's ear during a practice Monday night and jokingly told
him he gets intimidated in the big games.
</P>
<P>
   That's progress.
</P>
<P>
   This time during last year's stretch of critical games, Hamilton
was getting an earful about bad decisions and benches. Heading into
the Virginia game last year, Hamilton was coming off maybe the
worst start of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach George O'Leary threatened to bench him for backup
Brandon Shaw during the North Carolina game. Hamilton had committed
the Friedgen cardinal sin, throwing up a prayer over the middle and
hoping something good would happen. He was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most I ever got down on him was after the North Carolina
game,'' Friedgen said. ``He really played poorly. He's even started
out poorly in some games this year, but now he has the ability to
right himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who hasn't thrown a ball like that since, didn't think
his starting spot was in jeopardy but knew he was letting the team
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I thought I was doing what I could do,''
Hamilton said. ``Then I realized if the offense isn't scoring, the
quarterback is to blame. After that, I saw myself differently. I
wasn't doing what was expected. The morning after that game in my
room, I was thinking 'What can I do to help the team?' I decided I
wasn't getting everybody involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Wake Forest in the second game of last season, Hamilton
had thrown an interception in the first half that was returned for
a touchdown. He threw three touchdown passes in the second half,
helping Tech escape with a 28-26 win, but had a hard time shaking
off his bad play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole first half, that's all that was going through my
head was the interception: 'What am I going to do now?' `` he said.
``It's still a process. I'm still growing. But it's becoming less
and less of a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton threw seven interceptions in the first seven games last
year. He's had two in the 10 games since. He leads the ACC and is
ranked eighth nationally in passing efficiency. Much of that has to
do with his confidence and his grasp of this offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if George (O'Leary) would have thought he could
be as far along mentally as he is now,'' Friedgen said. ``Knowing
fronts, knowing coverages, checks, automatics. We'll go into a game
with probably as much or more (plays) than any level I've been on,
college or pro. Sometimes I think I put too much in.''
</P>
<P>
   When first learning Friedgen's offense last year, Hamilton would
get mixed up in the huddle, calling the wrong play with the wrong
formation. Last year, he was getting grades in the 60s and 70s on
Friedgen's Friday night game plan tests. The last two weeks, he's
aced them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes better decisions, he's not pressing to make the play
all the time,'' Friedgen said. ``He has confidence he'll do it.
Once something good happens to him, he keeps getting better. . .
The things he's doing right now, he's putting our whole team in a
position to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   While trying to stay on top of the offense and handle media
responsibilities, Hamilton has raised his grades, maintaining a 2.5
GPA for the last several quarters. He also endured the first real
loss of his life, when his grandmother died in July. He has
dedicated this season to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come a long way, not just in football,'' Friedgen said.
``He's a heck of a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates see a more mature Hamilton, a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what this team would do if it weren't for Joe
Hamilton,'' punter Rodney Williams said. ``Not just on the field.
If he got hurt, we'd survive just because he was on the sideline.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hasn't told his teammates about his personal goals for
the season: first-team All-ACC, conference player of the year, zero
interceptions. The last one may be out, but he still has a shot at
the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has been getting his due around the conference, but he
is never mentioned among elite college quarterbacks nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't hear your name, it makes you think, 'Whatever
happened to me in the mix?' `` Hamilton said. ``It challenges me
inside. Let's get it going, show people there's a quarterback at
Georgia Tech who loves to win and will do anything to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows the Virginia game, along with Florida State on Oct. 25,
will go a long way in meeting his personal and team goals. And if
he momentarily forgets, he always has Friedgen there to remind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really accomplished anything yet,'' Friedgen said.
``We've been a good team, but to be a great team, these are the
people we've got to beat. He's got to be the guy to make the plays
that does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what Friedgen may say on the practice field, he
thinks Hamilton can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any doubt about that,'' Friedgen said.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
