<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnan turns to Sanks to nurse running game to health
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ With his team facing two of the SEC's worst
defenses in as many weeks, Georgia coach Jim Donnan says his
running game will be back. And it appears the Bulldogs will look to
a freshman to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   No, not Jasper Sanks, the former Parade All-American from Carver
High in Columbus, whose season all but appears headed toward a
redshirt year. ``He still doesn't have the speed outside he had in
high school,'' Donnan says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Georgia will probably turn to redshirt freshman Nick
Callaway, a former state sprint champion from Washington-Wilkes
High.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who host winless Vanderbilt this week and then
travel to Kentucky on Oct. 24, will need a strong running game if
they'll have any shot at upsetting No. 5 Florida for the second
straight year. The Gators, who meet Georgia in Jacksonville on Oct.
31, are second nationally against the run, allowing only 68.7 yards
per game.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway, a 5-foot-10, 191-pounder, is comparable to former
Bulldogs runner Torin Kirtsey, who led the Dogs with 603 rushing
yards in 1995. Callaway, the state's Class AA 200-meter state
champion in '96, rushed for 1,014 yards as a prep senior.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway has rushed for 71 yards on only 10 carries this season,
averaging more than 10 yards per attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Callaway) gives us a speed guy that can utilize a little of
our perimeter game that we're going to try and exploit the next
couple of weeks,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   His promotion comes just days after Georgia rushed for a
season-low 59 yards in its 22-3 loss to No. 4 Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan appears fed up with junior Patrick Pass, a prep
All-American at Tucker High in 1995, who left the Tennessee game
with a sprained ankle after only one carry. Pass, bothered by turf
toe earlier this season, has rushed for only 101 yards in four
games, averaging just 3.9 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't say much about that (Pass' status),'' Donnan
said. ``I just don't know. He doesn't have much swelling, but he
told me that it's still real sore. It's on the opposite foot of his
turf toe. It's really perplexing for all of us because he's got a
lot of ability, but you've got to go out there and do it. ... He's
a big-play guy, but he hasn't made the big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   For any of Georgia's backs to be successful, the Bulldogs must
find consistent play from the offensive line. Freshman quarterback
Quincy Carter was under constant pressure by the Vols, who sacked
him three times.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan admits he made a ``tactical error'' in not starting Jonas
Jennings at center. Junior Miles Luckie of Stone Mountain, slowed
by a badly bruised right knee, was named the starter just minutes
before last week's game. Jennings remained at right guard until
moving to center for the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the wrong call,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, a 6-foot-4, 310-pound sophomore from College Park,
will probably start at center this week, with Luckie still slowed
by the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think not having a running game is more of the coaches'
choice,'' Jennings said. ``When you look at the big backs around
the league, they're all getting like 37 carries a game. We've run
the ball, but we haven't pounded it. Our backs have gotten like 30
carries, but they're splitting them up between four people.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan promises more running plays in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big factor is that we're going to have to call the
game around the running game,'' he said. ``We've looked to throw
the ball more than to (run) it. When you do that you're not very
patient and you don't run two or three runs in a row. We're going
to run two or three runs in a row this week, and play around our
defense to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
