<SLUG> BC-BBN-GAME6-PADRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vaughn ready to rejoin lineup in Game 6By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Vaughn thinks he's ready to jump back into the
San Diego lineup.
</P>
<P>
   So does manager Bruce Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   That means finally, a week after straining his left quadricep
muscle on the rain-slick Turner Field grass in Game 1, the Padres'
top power hitter returns today to the NLCS. Vaughn struck out in a
pinch-hitting role Monday night in Game 5, but the return of his
potent bat to the Padres' lineup couldn't come at a more opportune
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready to play, yeah,'' said Vaughn, after the Padres
failed to clinch the National League title in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's all set to go,'' Bochy said.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed hitting Vaughn has fared well in his brief
experience against lefty Tom Glavine, collecting two doubles in six
at-bats. And the Padres need his menacing presence in the middle of
the order, even though John Vander Wal and Ruben Rivera have filled
in capably at the bat and in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine yanking Andres Galarraga or Chipper Jones from the
Braves' lineup. That's what Vaughn meant to the Padres during the
regular season. With his 50 homers and 119 RBIs, he'd have been an
MVP candidate if not for the monster numbers put up by Sammy Sosa
and Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   So Vaughn, the cousin of Boston Red Sox slugger Mo Vaughn,
figures to settle for the comeback player of the year. His average
jumped from .216 to .272, while his home run and RBI totals more
than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   How bad was last season? Not only was he platooned in left field
until Rickey Henderson was traded in August, but when the Padres
tried to peddle him to the New York Yankees, they called off the
deal after taking a closer look at Vaughn's scarred shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   He played a year of football as a strong safety at the
University of Miami and was a standout on the baseball team for
three seasons, barely suffering a scratch in either sport. By his
count, he's undergone nine baseball-related surgeries as a pro,
including five shoulder operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the Yankee deal, it didn't really faze me,''
Vaughn said. ``I mean, what else could go wrong? I wanted to show
people I could play, and that just topped it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew what I could do. I just never had the chance. I
was always in and out of the lineup. When I came here (in 1996 from
Milwaukee), I said: 'Just give me 500 at-bats, then judge me.' I
was being judged on being in the lineup twice a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The same fans who applauded his every move this year were
expressing their displeasure last season. He was booed anytime he
failed to supply the pop for which he was acquired. And as he
tensed up, uncertain when his next start might come, his stride
lengthened and his hitting mechanics fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Vaughn stayed as upbeat as possible. He kept his
anxieties to himself. He talked regularly with Mo Vaughn, his
cousin with the Boston
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to help myself,'' he explained. ``Everybody was trying
to tell me different things. I didn't want to cause a problem with
the manager or other people around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, I always knew what I could do. Two years ago, I had 41
homers (31 in Milwaukee, 10 in San Diego). I had 30 in '93 with
Milwaukee. They had just never seen it here because I never had a
chance to play everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Padres saw for themselves. Today they hope
to see it again.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
