<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HUMMER-COLUMN14-C     10-13 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUMMER-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't be so quick to criticize Atlanta's fans
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's see if we've got this straight. It's not enough
that the customer goes elbow-deep into his change purse to buy the
product. No, he must shout appreciation at the top of his lungs for
the privilege of being a consumer. He must prove his worth.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what critics mean when branding the Braves fans slackers
and ingrates?
</P>
<P>
   Applying these same thoughts to other local enterprises, we must
conclude that you Waffle House patrons are the worst. The booths
are seldom filled, and nearly everyone takes for granted the pecans
in the waffles.
</P>
<P>
   And don't even get me started about that Home Depot crowd. Those
people never get geeked when buying a dimmer switch.
</P>
<P>
   What rubbish. Isn't this claptrap about the blase Braves fans
getting awfully tired? They'll come and cheer when they're darn
good and ready.
</P>
<P>
   I'll start criticizing people for not attending playoff games
the day they deduct the price of admission from my paycheck. They
raised the price of my postseason package, too _ but two times
nothing remains nothing. For the fan, not going actually is a rare
act of fiscal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, a team that draws 3.3 million souls to a devalued
regular season gets more than enough emotional fiber in its diet.
</P>
<P>
   A team that plays in an antiqued palace, that performs to a
far-flung cable audience, that can barely get through its clubhouse
door for the piles of money stacked outside has no reason to worry
about where its next tomahawk chop is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blase'' comes from the French, but that doesn't mean it's a
dirty word. Some of my best friends are blase. And they really
don't care what you think.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as a matter of fact, Braves fans are blase. They've earned
the right.
</P>
<P>
   Those San Diego people can get worked up once every 14 years,
and then go back to worshipping the Weather Channel and an
unchanging local forecast. In Chicago, they can't help themselves
because their little club is so danged cute. Every day is Beanie
Baby day. But, here, the last eight years have brought so many
victories that the folks in the seats can't help but be jaded.
Winning is like a drug, and the addict is always looking for a
higher high.
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to the simple fact that the fan owes nothing to no
one. Just be somewhat civil and don't interfere with a ball in
play. It's not hard.
</P>
<P>
   The team's job is to light the fans' fire, not vice versa.
There's the heavy-handed process _ known as the David Justice
Method. And there is playing your way into their affections, which
the Braves currently are attempting.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just trying to win a game, the Braves are looking to
rewrite history. Staging late-inning outbursts two nights in a row,
they audition to become the first ever to rise from the grave of
0-3. Coming off a game that baseball coroners could spend years
cutting into, the Braves have brought to life all the numbed
senses. It took a desperate plight, but there is a little of that
1991 feeling all over again _ this time with John Rocker playing a
poor man's Sid Bream.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about the Braves fans. They'll show up today for
Game Six. They'll come to play. They'll scream their fool heads
off, they'll ride the emotional Tilt-A-Whirl, they'll profoundly
care. And matter as little in the final reckoning as when they
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hummer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
