<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-TUCKER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bits and pieces from the NLCS
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reading between the lines of the NLCS. . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ You realize that the Braves' winning pitchers in this series
have been a 43-year-old grandfather who a year ago was out of the
game (Dennis Martinez) and a 24-year-old rookie who a year ago was
passed over in the expansion draft (John Rocker)?
</P>
<P>
   _ Rocker has become a big story in the series. While fellow
rookie Kerry Ligtenberg has struggled, Rocker has sprinted into all
five games and allowed nothing _ one hit, one walk, no runs, five
strikeouts _ in 4 2/3 innings; heck, he has scored more runs (one)
than he has allowed. Until this season, the excitable lefty had
caused barely a stir in the Atlanta farm system. But the other day,
when Padres GM Kevin Towers was discussing the Braves' penchant
throughout the '90s of producing new homegrown stars, he mentioned
Chipper Jones, Javy Lopez, Ryan Klesko, Andruw Jones . . . and
Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   _ ''I turned to John Smoltz at one point in the dugout,'' the
postseason novice Rocker said, ''and told him, 'I don't know how
you guys go through this every year. I'd have an ulcer by now.'''
But the postseason isn't entirely new to Rocker, who was in the
stands at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium with his dad during the '92
World Series. He was a high school junior in Macon then.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of Macon, that's home to both the winning and losing
pitchers in Game 5, Rocker and Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   _ The home team has won one of five games so far.
</P>
<P>
   _ That four-time Cy Young winner looked pretty good as a closer.
''He touched 91 (mph),'' Bobby Cox said of Greg Maddux's
ninth-inning performance in Game 5. ''I've never seen him throw 91
before.'' Maddux, though, admitted some culture shock in the
bullpen: ''I felt like a fish out of water down there. I didn't
know what to do, how to act, what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked if Smoltz, who had terrific stuff in his Game 5 start,
will be available in relief if needed in Game 7, Cox said: ''Game
6.''
</P>
<P>
   _ No telling what'll happen in this wacky series next. But in
one respect the Padres' use of Brown in relief on Monday puts them
in the same bind that the Cardinals faced in the '96 NLCS in which
the Braves overcame a three-games-to-one deficit. Two of Atlanta's
wins in that series came against pitchers working on
shorter-than-usual rest.
</P>
<P>
   _ ''The reason I felt we could do it in 1996,'' Braves GM John
Schuerholz said, referring to the comeback against the Cards, ''is
the same reason I think we can do it now: Smoltz and Glavine and
Maddux.'' And then he added that he believes this team's offense is
better _ ''more balanced; greater left-handed, right-handed
balance'' _ than the one that scored 32 runs in the last three
games against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   _ The big difference offensively between the first three games
of this series and the last two? Patience and working the count in
their favor, according to Braves hitters.
</P>
<P>
   _ ''Somebody asked me before the series who the star would be,''
Cox said, ''and I said, 'Someone you wouldn't think of.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wally Joyner, the Padres' first baseman, has played in 1,767
major-league games, and he said of Monday's: ''That might have been
the best game I've ever participated in.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tucker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail: tim(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
