<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-WILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impeachment movement a main weapon for BarrBy D.L. Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No one has more to thank President Clinton for than
Bob Barr.
</P>
<P>
   First, Barr rode anti-Clinton sentiment into office in 1994 by
hanging the president's unpopularity around the neck of incumbent
Democrat Buddy Darden.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 7th District incumbent is riding relentless attacks
on the embattled president to national prominence and a likely
third term in Congress representing Georgia's 7th District.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain continuity to it,'' Barr said. ``He's
basically been doing the same things the past several years and I
have also. I have very substantive and serious differences with
this president.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, 49, is expected to have no difficulty on Nov. 3 defeating
little-known Democratic challenger Jim Williams, an insurance agent
from Cedartown.
</P>
<P>
   The former federal prosecutor was discounted as an extremist
pandering to right-wing voters a year ago when he filed for the
impeachment of Clinton. Early on he had few signing onto the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Starr report made Barr seem like a visionary. The
Georgia Congressman's seat on the Judiciary Committee provided Barr
a bully pulpit he parlayed into appearances on C-SPAN, CNN and
national television news shows.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the full House has voted overwhelmingly to begin a
wide-ranging impeachment inquiry into the president's affairs. And
Barr remains at the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear from an awful lot of people on a daily basis and the
sentiment is very strongly in support of making the president
accountable,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 55, admits he is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   A Polk County commissioner from 1973-77, Williams is virtually
unknown in the 11-county district which spans west Georgia from
Troupe County north to Catoosa County and east into parts of south
and west Cobb County..
</P>
<P>
   He says many Democrats have called with moral support, but few
are willing to open their wallets to fund a little-known challenger
in a solidly Republican district. And, with just $10,000, he won't
be running pricey television commercials or plastering the district
with yard signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least he had the courage to step forward and take on this
right-wing Goliath,'' said Bill Waldrop, Cobb Democratic Party
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is hoping Barr's pit-bull fierceness in attacking the
president will create a backlash that will catapult the Democratic
challenger into Congress. He started the campaign with the slogan,
``Stop the madness, send a moderate to Washington.'' But has
changed that to ``Stop Bob Barr and the radical right, send a
moderate to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainly, the issue is Bob Barr himself and the impeachment
issue. . . people don't like it,'' Williams said. ``Barr has just
totally ignored the district from Day 1 with his drive to impeach
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Some constituents agree.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bryant, a lumber salesman from Cartersville, said he voted
for Barr two years ago but won't again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has really turned into a witch hunt,'' Bryant said
. ``They should really get on with the business of running the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Vaughan, a farmer from White, agreed. He said he had no
interest in the Starr report and no desire to see Clinton
impeached. ``I won't vote for Barr next time for that reason,''
Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the impeachment stand has played well for Barr in much of
the staunchly conservative district.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Farris, a Douglasville CPA and former Douglas County
commissioner, likes Barr's efforts to remove Clinton. He said Barr
has remained faithful to his district by returning regularly and
providing good constituent services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob has been exactly what we expected,'' Farris said. ``I like
the fact that he's a good solid conservative Republican who does
what he says he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Williams' situation, Barr's supporters have opened their
wallets.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Barr's Federal Election Commission campaign disclosure
report will show he has raised more than $1 million and has
$170,000 on hand, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The huge fund-raising lead has allowed Barr to be generous. He
has given $6,000 to various GOP congressional candidates and
another $9,000 to Republican candidates for state House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   D.L. Bennett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
