<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBO earnings surpass analysts' estimatesBy Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ HBO &AMP; Co. beat analysts' earnings estimates, reporting
a 57 percent increase in third-quarter net income Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based health care software and services company
announced a profit of $83.7 million, or 19 cents a share, against
$53.2 million, or 12 cents, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue
climbed to $399.6 million from $307.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus analyst estimate, according to First Call, was 18
cents a share. Despite beating that number, HBO &AMP; Co. shares
slipped 37 1/2 cents to $26.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the decline to the Nasdaq market's slump.
And typically, HBO &AMP; Co.'s shares rise in the days before an
earnings announcement, then fall off.
</P>
<P>
   The company leads the health-care information technology sector
in revenue and profit.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Michael Samols of BancBoston Robertson Stephens said HBO
&AMP; Co.'s growth should continue at least through 1999. ``Health care
must invest more in (information) systems to be more
cost-effective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, HBO &AMP; Co. said software sales rose in each
market segment -- hospitals, health systems, physicians, home care
and insurers. The company said profitability increased more than
revenue because of efficiency gains and cost containment.
</P>
<P>
   For the nine months, HBO &AMP; Co., with headquarters at Perimeter
Center, had income of $222.4 million, or 51 cents a share, on sales
of $1.12 billion. For the nine-month period in 1997, income was
$139 million, or 33 cents a share, on revenue of $862 million,
excluding a nonrecurring charge of $35.4 million, or 5 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Monika Brown, director of investor relations, said HBO &AMP; Co. is
comfortable with analysts' estimates of 20 cents a share for the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
