<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDER-LITTMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longshot or not, Littman up to the challenge
 &HT;    By Peter J. Kent
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What does a long-distance truck driver think about as
the miles roll under his 18-wheel rig?
</P>
<P>
   Vince Littman of Commerce imagines himself in Congress, serving
as the U.S. representative from Georgia's 11th District.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent evening Littman appeared at a political forum in
Jackson County. Next stop was Miami, hauling a load of office
equipment from North Bergen, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be gone the rest of the week,'' said Littman, an
underfunded political novice taking aim at Republican Party
heavyweight U.S. Rep. John Linder of Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   Littman, a 52-year-old native New Yorker with the accent to
prove it, knows he's a longshot, but says he passionately believes
that no incumbent should go unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I didn't have a chance, I would still be out there
because without me there is no race,'' Littman said.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say Littman is a really long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in their right mind would want to run against Linder,''
said Keith Billingsley, a University of Georgia political
scientist. ``He is in a tremendously influential position.''
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee,
Linder controls the fate of GOP House candidates, dispensing
campaign money and advice. Linder also is a member of the House
Rules Committee, which controls the flow of legislation in the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   And Linder has access. ``His real importance is he meets with
the Speaker (Newt Gingrich) constantly. People know that when he is
speaking it is really the Speaker doing the talking,'' Billingsley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the 11th District, stretching from South Carolina to
north metro Atlanta, was drawn as a ``safe seat'' for the GOP,
Billingsley said: ``I believe that somebody in jail could win this
district if he were a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   To Linder, who is not planning any TV advertising, there are no
issues in this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is quite content,'' he said in an interview.
``Approval ratings for Congress are the highest ever. This will be
status-quo election. It will be a light turnout.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Linder works to maintain his popularity. ``He is in the
district a lot,'' said Gwinnett County Republican chairman B.J. Van
Gundy, listing a schedule filled with GOP breakfasts and town hall
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Littman, a high school graduate who works for Graebel Atlanta
Movers, has been in this territory before. After moving his family
to Commerce in 1993, he was angered by the district-swapping that
took place among incumbents after Georgia's congressional map was
thrown out by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who was going to represent us,'' Littmann
recalled. ``I went to a local Republican Party meeting _ it's the
only party meeting they have up here _ and I asked who was going to
our representative. They told me it was probably going to Linder,
who then represented the 4th Congressional District. I said he
didn't even live in the district. Apparently a deal had been made,
with Cynthia McKinney moving from 11th to the 4th and Linder
running in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said if I didn't like, to challenge him.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1996, Littmann borrowed money to pay the qualifying fee
and ran in the Democratic primary. He was trounced by Tommy
Stephenson, former Commerce mayor and state lawmaker, who won 74
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Facing no primary opposition this time, Littman carries little
more than his party's banner. He has received no money from the
state or national Democratic Party. He again took out a bank loan
to pay the $4,101 qualifying fee. Littman said he has gotten a few
donations, including a $50 check he had in his wallet. His war
chest is so meager that his accountant told him he did not have to
report his campaign fiinances to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Linder has about $520,000 in campaign money, according Federal
Election Commission reports.
</P>
<P>
   But Littman is undaunted. He says he is on the campaign trail
for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just not going to quit,'' Littman said. ``Someone must
run against Linder, and someone will as long as Vinnie is here. I
will make him a better congressman.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Littman
</P>
<P>
   Age: 52
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Commerce, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Education: High-school graduate, some college
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Long-distance moving van driver
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: Unsuccessfully ran in 1996 Democratic
Primary for Georgia's 11th District
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Married, four children
</P>
<P>
   John Linder
</P>
<P>
   Age: 56
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Chamblee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Education: DDS University of Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Dentist
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: three-term congressman (first elected in
1992), chairman of National Republican Congressional Committee,
state House member
</P>
<P>
   Personal: married, two children
</P>
<P>
   Peter J. Kent writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
