<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia prison finally privitizedBy Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After two false starts, the first group of Georgia
prisoners is finally in custody of corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   The much-heralded privatization of the state's prison system
began Tuesday when 24 medium-security inmates arrived at D. Ray
James State Prison in Folkston. The prison, owned and operated by
Cornell Corrections Inc. of Houston, will get 50 inmates a week
until there are 750.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got everybody on their jobs,'' said Warden Lowell
Hudson. ``Everything is secure that needs to be secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The inmates were chosen for the private prison near the boundary
of the Okefenokee Swamp because of their job skills, mostly kitchen
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the prison was supposed to start taking inmates in
mid-August but construction delays pushed that date back twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlton County prison is the first of three planned for
Georgia that will be owned and operated by publicly traded
corporations. The other company _ Corrections Corp. of America _ is
building similar prisons in Wheeler and Coffee Counties. All three
have a 1,600-inmate capacity. Both companies have said they will
take inmates from other states if Georgia does not want to lease
the additional beds.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
