<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5251 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-PARIS-COX     10-13 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PARIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sales dip for fashion houses
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, France _ These are pressure-filled times fashion
designers live in.
</P>
<P>
   Adrienne Vittadini's just announced that she can no longer take
the business strain and will resign as her company's design chief
and chairwoman. Lagging sales of Isaac Mizrahi's designs cost him
his French financial backing, so his 10-year-old business is
closing. The LVMH (Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessy) corporation _ which
owns Louis Vuitton, Givenchy, Christian Dior and Celine, among
other brands _ reports its sales are down $1 billion from a year
ago. And Benetton's grown so needy for market share that its
entering into partnership with Sears.
</P>
<P>
   Into this atmosphere of intense scrutiny and doubt comes the
start of the French spring/summer '99 previews. Designers here need
``good spin'' from fashion critics.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard, though, to fathom what prompted the waves of applause
following the preview of Dries Van Noten's spring/summer '99
designs on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The standing-room-only crowd gathered in a baroque theatre
overshadowed by the Arc de Triomphe approved of Van Noten's stark
departure from the spring/summer styles shown already by his
counterparts in New York, London, Milan and Paris. The bulk of Van
Noten's collection resembled what women wore to work in wild west
bordellos. The few outfits Van Noten showed that looked modern,
sleek, colorful and pretty were outnumbered by ensembles that
appeared antiquated, cumbersome, somber and plain.
</P>
<P>
   Van Noten, a brash Belgian with a reputation for avante garde
tendencies, took the stance that there will be far too much color
flooding the stores when warm weather returns. The most colorful
aspects of his show were: the towering Marilyn Manson look-alikes
posted at the entrance to pass out Chupa Chups lollipops; and just
a few peasant blouses and skirts shaded fuscia and mauve.
</P>
<P>
   There was delicacy to some of Van Noten's crinkley fabrications.
But, overall, his styling looked too contrived and impractical for
the modern woman's wardrobing needs.
</P>
<P>
   A youthful, slim womancould, on the other hand, build her entire
wardrobe around the collection shown by the relatively unknown
Christophe LeMaire. LeMaire showed spring/summer clothes that were
highly wearable, if not entirely innovative.
</P>
<P>
   All the requisite facets of modernity _ drawstrings, zippered
pockets, hoods, snap closures, and flat-soled shoes _ were evident
in LeMaire's sporty collection. But he betrayed himself as too much
of a trend-follower by draping pouch-pocketed bandoliers over a few
of his models' shoulders; harkening images of the utilitarian
``body bags'' that Helmut Lang, Miuccia Prada and others have
already shown.
</P>
<P>
   Using iridescent olive, black and brown as his color base,
LeMaire accented his collection with lime, fuscia and aqua and
cobalt shades of blue. His pants _ in both Capris and full lenths _
looked snug but stretchy. His skirts were curve-huggers as well,
with slits up the front and knee-length hems. His jackets spanned
the gamut from athletic to business appropriate. And his
paperweight, shawl-collared blouses looked at once retro and
futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the Van Noten and LeMaire collections is
telling. Van Noten's already earned enough acclaim to indulge in
unwearable whimsy from time to time. LeMaire, who's still seeking
industry approval, assumed the safer posture of a copycat.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
