<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNTRUST-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fees help boost SunTrust's earnings 12%
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A 25.9 percent jump in fee-based earnings propelled
SunTrust Banks to a 12 percent gain in third-quarter net income.
Profit rose to $188.8 million from $168.6 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Net per share grew 13.8 percent on fewer shares, to 91 cents
against 80 cents per share a year earlier. The
Atlanta-headquartered company beat First Call's 21-analyst
consensus estimate by a penny per share.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust Banks, among the first of the major regional banks to
report earnings, closed Tuesday at $64.43 3/4, up 62 1/2 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company earned $293.2 million from fees. That included trust
income, which climbed 17 percent to $92.5 million. Corporate and
institutional investment income rose 86 percent to $16 million, and
mortgage fees increased 55.7 percent to $19 million.
</P>
<P>
   Interest-based income rose more slowly, a near-universal
experience in the banking industry. That amount was $504.4 million
vs. $485.7 million, a gain of about 4 percent. The net interest
margin _ what a bank earns on money minus what it costs to obtain
money _ declined to 3.87 percent from 4.04 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nonperforming loans were $157.7 million, down $33 million. The
provision for possible bad loans increased slightly, to $31.4
million from $29 million. Loan charge-offs for the quarter were
$27.9 million, or 0.26 percent of average loans.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman James C. Armstrong said SunTrust Banks has no exposure
to hedge funds and that its foreign loans, most of which are in
Canada and the United Kingdom, amount to less that 1 percent of the
overall loan portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The banking company had a 1.32 percent return on the average
value of its assets and a 22.5 percent return on stockholders'
equity. It cost SunTrust Banks 61.1 cents, up from 59 cents, to
bring in a dollar of revenue. That increase was attributable to a
19.6 percent climb, to $289.2 million, in personnel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Crestar Financial of Richmond, expected to be merged with
SunTrust Banks by year-end, also reported earnings. In line with
expectations, the company earned $88.9 million, or 78 cents per
share, compared with $79.5 million, or 71 cents.
</P>
<P>
   For the nine months, SunTrust Banks earned $554.7 million, or
$2.64 per share, vs. $495.1 million, or $2.31 per share. As of
Sept. 30, assets totaled $60.7 billion. With the addition of
Crestar Financial, assets would rise to $86.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
