<HEADLINE>
KABC HOST BELL SAYS THREATS FORCING HIM TO QUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorist, UFO aficionado and syndicated radio host
Art Bell announced Tuesday he was quitting the airwaves, hinting
that his family was under a mysterious threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are listening to is my final broadcast,'' Bell told
the audience of his overnight ``Coast to Coast'' call-in show
before signing off about 3 a.m. on local talk outlet KABC-AM (790).
</P>
<P>
   Station officials insist Bell's resignation was not a stunt,
adding that he was not in the midst of contract talks. A KABC
spokeswoman said management was scrambling to find out what was
going on, while a decision had not been made on how to fill Bell's
time slot.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday's broadcast, Bell said ``a threatening, terrible
event occurred to my family, which I could not tell you about.
Because of that event, and a succession of other events, what
you're listening to right now is my final broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Lt. Bill Becht said officers were sent to Bell's home
upon learning of the farewell broadcast. They found him there, with
no evidence of foul play, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any threats were not criminal in nature,'' Becht said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, 51, hosted his radio show from his home in rural Pahrump,
Nev. The program focused on such paranormal activity as alien
abductions, cattle mutilations and secret government programs.
</P>
<P>
   The show was thought to attract more than 6.5 million listeners
on more than 400 stations nationwide. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
KIIS-FM GIVES $1 MILLION-PLUS
</P>
<P>
   Glendale community college student Karolina Khodzhyan feels like
a million bucks, thanks to top-40 KIIS-FM (102.7).
</P>
<P>
   Khodzhyan was awarded a record-breaking $1,000,102.70 by KIIS
morning personality Rick Dees after claiming the winning birth date
in a call-in contest co-sponsored by Rio All Suites Hotel &AMP; Casino
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy _ and shocked, shocked, shocked,'' said
Armenia-born Khodzhyan, 22, a business major who works as a
receptionist at a medical management firm.
</P>
<P>
   Khodzhyan said she would spend her winnings on a house for her
parents, a car for her younger brother and her own education.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime KIIS listener was at her desk at 9:10 a.m. Sept. 30
when Dees announced her birth date _ Feb. 26, 1976. The 10th caller
with the matching birthday would become an instant millionaire,
Dees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept dialing and dialing and finally got through,''
Khodzhyan said Monday. ``I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Khodzhyan was accompanied by co-workers and family members when
she went to KIIS' Burbank studios to claim her prize, which could
amount to roughly $620,000 after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Michaels, chief executive officer of KIIS' parent company,
Kentucky-based Jacor Communications, was program director at
Cincinnati's WKRQ when it set a world record in 1980 for the
largest amount given out in a radio contest _ $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   To break that record, KIIS added $102.70, making Khodzhyan's
gross $1,000,102.70, station spokesman Von Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   KIIS launched a second search for a $1 million birthday winner
Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE GROOVE
</P>
<P>
   Groove 103.1 is gone, and the news isn't good for fans of techno
and dance music.
</P>
<P>
   The Groove stations, Santa Monica's KACD-FM and Newport Beach
simulcast outlet KBCD-FM, were recently purchased for $67 million
by Jacor, which owns 230 properties across the country, including
KIIS.
</P>
<P>
   At noon Monday, the dance music stopped, disc jockeys bade
listeners farewell and a simulcast of KIIS began.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say the new KACD/KBCD format, to be unveiled next week,
will likely be adult alternative, similar to that of now-defunct
KSCA-FM, which was beloved by its relatively few listeners for
giving airplay to Sarah McLachlan, the Dave Matthews Band, Joni
Mitchell and other acts popular with the boomer crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year since KSCA went off the air, KYSR-FM (98.7) _
Star 98 _ KBIG-FM (104.3) and several other outlets have added
adult alternative artists.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there's now nowhere on the dial to hear the
admittedly low-rated Groove's unique mix of techno, r&AMP;b and
four-on-the-floor dance music.
</P>
<P>
   Over at KACD, nobody's talking just yet.
</P>
<P>
   DYLAN DOCUMENTARY
</P>
<P>
   To coincide with the official release this week of an
oft-bootlegged Bob Dylan concert recording from 1966, the Museum of
Television &AMP; Radio in Beverly Hills is hosting screenings of the
rare Dylan documentary ``Eat the Document.'' Screening times are 6
p.m. Thursday and 1 p.m. Friday, Saturday and Sunday, through Nov.
13. ... Rush Limbaugh is on top among talk hosts, says Talkers
radio trade mag. According to the publication's latest survey,
Limbaugh has at least 15 million weekly listeners, followed by Dr.
Laura Schlessinger with at least 14.5 million and Howard Stern with
at least 9 million. &QL;
</P>
