<SLUG> BC-HARLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    John Harland hires CEO for turnaround
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Check printer John H. Harland (ticker symbol JH),
having fallen on hard times, Tuesday hired a turnaround specialist,
Timothy C. Tuff, as president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street greeted the announcement by sending the stock to a
52-week low of $12.25, where it finished, down 18 3/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Tuff, 51, who also was elected a director, previously was
president and chief executive of Boral Industries in Atlanta, where
he managed the North American and European operations of Boral
Ltd., a building and construction materials company based in
Australia. Before that, he was general partner of a Massachusetts
venture capital company that focused on spinoffs of
under-performing divisions of large companies. The native of
England also is a former president of Alcan Aluminum Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Tuff couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken Harland 10 months to find a replacement for Robert
J. Amman, who resigned last January after two years as chief
executive. At the time, Amman cited ``differences of opinion'' over
corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   To boost profitability, Amman cut costs by closing plants. He
also sought to transform the company from a checks and forms
printer to a financial marketing services company.
</P>
<P>
   But Harland's financial results often didn't match Wall Street's
expectations, leading to a slump in the price of the shares, which
traded as high as $33 at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of analysts still cover the stock, which was
removed from the benchmark Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst who still tracks the stock, Joseph A. Gomes of
William Smith &AMP; Co., thinks hiring Tuff is a positive for Harland,
which was founded in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   ``That question is no longer overhanging the company,'' Gomes
said. ``And it looks like he has a pretty strong operating
background, albeit not in the financial services industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gomes said Harland _ which once had 45 years of sales increases
and 43 years of dividend hikes _ still has a rough road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financial institutions apparently are cutting back some of
their expenditures, not only with checks but some of the financial
marketing software the company has as well,'' Gomes said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some see value in the shares. Wealthy investor Richard
C. Blum and affiliates recently boosted their holdings to 5.9
percent of the shares outstanding, paying $13.04 to $15.75 apiece
between July 27 and Sept. 3. Blum is married to U.S. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, a California Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Gomes also likes the stock, predicting it will rebound to $22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The check business, although not a big grower, throws off
tremendous cash flows,'' he said. ``The company also is in the
midst of a restructuring program that should substantially help
earnings when it's completed next year. And it has some attractive
potential growth in its software unit, which allows financial
institutions to better maximize profit from existing customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally expect Harland to earn 83 cents a share this
year and $1.20 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Luke writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
