A5258 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-TALKS-BOS &LR;      10-13 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH PESSIMISTIC ABOUT QUICK AGREEMENT ON BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With little to suggest that a deal was at hand,
Congress and the White House continued negotiating Tuesday on a
budget for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, with disputes over
education, agriculture, and military spending among the remaining
roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am much less optimistic than I was this morning,'' House
Speaker Newt Gingrich said during a mid-afternoon break in the
talks, ``because I am beginning to realize how far apart we are on
the question of whether Washington runs the country in detail, or
local citizens have control over their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he was referring only in part to an impasse over
new education funding sought by President Clinton and Democratic
lawmakers, primarily to hire more teachers and to build schools.
Republicans have said they would approve some of the money, but
only if local officials, rather than the federal government, are
allowed to decide how to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming for a budget deal that the House and Senate could approve
Wednesday, Gingrich, Senate majority leader Trent Lott, and other
congressional leaders met at various times Tuesday with White House
officials, including Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, chief of
staff Erskine Bowles, and Clinton's budget chief, Jack Lew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having difficult negotiations about very serious
principles,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said there was a strong chance that negotiators
would revive a measure sought by high-tech companies to allow more
foreign workers into the United States each year to take skilled
jobs, ranging from computer programmers to nurses and doctors. The
White House and congressional leaders had agreed to that bill
several weeks ago, saying it would ease a shortage of computer
workers. But labor groups opposed the measure, and a small group of
senators effectively killed it on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a senator and a White House official said the
legislation could be attached to a massive ``omnibus'' spending
bill that would also contain what normally would be eight separate
appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospects for including this legislation are very good,
and we'd like to see it included,'' said Jake Siewert, spokesman
for the White House National Economic Council. The legislation
would raise the annual quota of so-called H-1B visas, which allow a
foreigner to work at a skilled US job for up to six years. Many
Massachusetts companies backed the measure, but reviving it might
also give a boost to Senator Barbara Boxer, a Democrat from the
high-tech haven of California in a tight reelection race, who
supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the omnibus bill would control about $500 billion in
spending for health, education, labor, foreign aid, law
enforcement, and other programs _ nearly one-third of the federal
budget. Lawmakers are writing the omnibus bill under a short-term
spending plan that keeps the government operating only through
midnight tonight. By that time, they must approve a new budget,
pass another temporary spending measure, or provoke a repeat of the
government shutdowns of the winter of 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are pressing to finish the budget work so they can
return home to campaign for the Nov. 3 elections. The budget, and a
possible modest, companion tax cut are the last major pieces of
business for the 105th Congress, though House members may return to
take up the impeachment inquiry of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One cause of the delay has been a late push by Clinton and
Democratic lawmakers for several education proposals, including
plans to fund new school construction and to hire 100,000 teachers
over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators were also discussing a Democratic proposal to spend
$100 million for toxic waste cleanup. They aimed to settle on terms
for sending $18 billion to the International Monetary Fund, the
agency that has loaned money to nations struggling amid the global
economic crisis. Also unresolved was a Democratic proposal to
require most federal workers' health plans to cover prescription
contraceptives. Republicans wanted to let insurers opt out if they
had moral objections.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators also were working out a tax cut package. The House
on Monday voted to renew several expiring tax credits, totaling
$9.2 billion over 10 years. But the Senate has its own $8.4 billion
plan, and Clinton complicated matters by proposing that the package
include tax incentives to allow state and local governments to
issue bonds for school construction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has proposed $12 billion or more in so-called
emergency spending, ranging from aid to farmers to money for
federal computer upgrades. That spending package has been growing
in recent days and may include other programs, bringing the
administration's total price tag as high as $20 billion.
Republicans want to spend about $7 billion on improving military
preparedness, a new missile defense system, and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's office said the senator was working to persuade budget
negotiators to include a five-year, $100 million boost in federal
funding for the Big Dig. Aides to other lawmakers said that Kerry
and Representative Jim McGovern, a Worcester Democrat, also lobbied
for the funding, but that House negotiators so far had not agreed
to release the money.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, Massachusetts has received about $830
million annually in highway funds, but Congress pared that to about
$525 million annually in a six-year transportation plan approved in
May.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
