A5263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-PARISLOCAL-COX     10-13 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PARISLOCAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Have legs gone out of style?
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, France _ Though plus-size women seem to be as scarce as
hen's teeth in Paris, the women here are being conspicuously stingy
about showing their legs this fall.
</P>
<P>
   All the covered legs on the street are noteworthy because the
prevailing thought has always been _ as long as there's Paris,
miniskirts will never go out of style. With temperatures hovering
in the mid-50s to low 60s, it's hard to tell for certain whether
the pants and long skirts worn are, more often than not, signs of
climate-consciousness or more modest tastes in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The best of what Parisian designers have to offer for spring and
summer might be showing on the runways around town, but on the
streets, women are firmly rooted in peg-legged pants and skirts
that fall at least to the knee. Grungy girls and grandmothers alike
are wearing heels that add height. Styles on display include
open-toed sandals (with stiff, cuffed jeans), lace-up suede shoes
with 2-inch-thick crepe soles (worn with skirts and thick
leggings), high-heeled ankle boots (worn with the peg-legged pants)
and high-heeled pumps (worn with skirted business suits).
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
