A5278 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI     10-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TAKES ITS CASE TO COURT OF PUBLIC OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outlining its strategy for defending its corporate
practices in court, Microsoft Tuesday asserted that it is not a
monopoly, blamed the Netscape Communications Corp. for its own
problems, and offered detailed defenses of its controversial
relationships with America Online, Apple, Intel, Intuit, Netscape
and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   The defenses came in an unusual 43-page document offered not in
the courtroom but in a paper faxed, e-mailed and hand-delivered to
reporters and posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company's decision to offer a non-legalistic explication of
its position illustrates the importance of public relations to
Microsoft, the defendant in a much-anticipated antitrust trial
scheduled to begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure the American public has the ability to
see both sides,'' said Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report will have no impact on the court case. But
Microsoft is fighting in the court of public opinion, as well as
the court of law, because, as a publicly traded company that
markets products under its corporate brand name, the company needs
to be positively viewed by investors and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft issued its document on the same day that federal and
state attorneys prosecuting the company filed the written testimony
of anti-Microsoft witnesses under seal, making them unavailable to
the news media. The government also was to file overnight a list of
exhibits it plans to introduce at trial, but said it would not make
the list public until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the government urged a judge to reject Microsoft's
request to delay the trial until Nov. 2. The judge strongly
suggested in court last week that he was not inclined to further
postpone the trial, which he had originally hoped to start Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The paper put out Tuesday by Microsoft made no new arguments,
but provided fresh details in its response to a variety of
allegations made by the Justice Department and state officials. The
company provided previously unreported evidence to bolster its case
that it did not bully its competitors in an illegal attempt to
protect a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The company also revealed that it has provided the Justice
Department with more than 3.3 million pages of e-mail and other
documents in response to subpoenas. The company accused the
government of sifting through those documents to find a handful of
incriminating quotations and then selectively leaking them, often
out of context, to damage Microsoft in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokeswoman had little to say about the
company's filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident in our case, and look forward to presenting it
in court,'' said Justice Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   The government will attempt to prove that Microsoft has a
monopoly on computer operating systems and has illegally attempted
to extend that monopoly into the market for Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Tuesday insisted that it does not have a monopoly,
despite the government's contention that its Windows operating
system is used on 80 percent of all Intel-based personal computers
and installed on 90 percent of all new Intel-based PCs. Microsoft
argued that the market for operating system remains open to
competitors, because ``entry costs are very low and profit
opportunities vast.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued that it has not harmed Netscape, but that
``Netscape's own business and strategic failings have contributed
to the decline in usage of Navigator,'' the company's browser.
Microsoft says Netscape's mistakes are legion and have been
conceded by company executives interviewed by newspaper reporters
and book authors.
</P>
<P>
   The government also alleges that Microsoft used its power as a
monopoly to win valuable business supplying the browser used by the
popular on-line service provider America Online. The government
charges that America Online believed Microsoft's browser was
inferior to Netscape's, but chose Microsoft's browser anyway
because Microsoft offered to promote America Online.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Microsoft offered remarks made in 1996 by America
Online chief executive Steve Case, who said ``the more we learned
about the Microsoft technology ... we felt it would allow us to
better meet the needs of our consumer audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Microsoft denied that it did anything untoward in
trying to persuade Intuit to use Microsoft's browser with Intuit's
popular Quicken personal finance program. Microsoft offered
quotations in news articles from Intuit spokeswoman Debra Kelley,
who called Netscape's product ``time-consuming and inconvenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft acknowledged that some of its relationships with other
software companies are complex. For example, Microsoft denied
trying to persuade Intel to give up a product called native signal
processing, but acknowledged that it refused to support the Intel
product because of technical issues.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft denied trying to persuade Apple to drop its
QuickTime multimedia software, but acknowledged that the companies
had attempted but failed to negotiate one multimedia product that
both companies would support.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Microsoft acknowledged making an altered version of
Sun's Java language, but says it was entitled to do so by its
contract with Sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
