<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; tdt-z
j m &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BYLINE &LR;      10-13 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BYLINE 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter G. Gosselin
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Globe Staff
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Masters of the Universe are quaking, not over the
latest initial public offering or a merger gone bad, but over pink
slips. After months of financial turmoil and weeks of frightening
rumors, some of New York's money mavens are finally losing their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Investment giant Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said yesterday that it will
slash 3,400 jobs, or about 5 percent of its work force, and
industry observers say that is just the beginning of the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merrill's opened the floodgate. They're making it that much
easier for other firms to announce layoffs,'' said Edward S.
Orchant, president of A-L Associates, a veteran Wall Street
headhunter.
</P>
<P>
   Orchant said that, unless conditions improve quickly, between
30,000 and 60,000 brokers, bankers and traders will be out of work
by the end of the year. That may not seem like a deep cutback to
most people. But for an industry that employes only a few hundred
thousand worldwide, it is substantial, and for a financial capital
like New York, potentially disasterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about to feel the brunt of the downturn,'' said H. Carl
McCall, the New York State comptroller whose responsibilities
include monitoring the city's financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's sustained, that is serious for New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the first ripples of the stock market turmoil and the
layoffs are already being felt in that most sensitive quarter of
the New York economy _ residential real estate. Apartment prices,
which had been rising at a 15-percent annual clip largely on the
backs of ballooning Wall Street pay packages, have suddenly
stalled, according to industry executives. And owners, especially
of high-end units _ those selling for $1 million or more _ have
actually begun cutting their asking prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of the over-bid are gone,'' said Barbara Corcoran,
chairman of the Corcoran Group, one of the city's largest real
estate companies.
</P>
<P>
   The financial industry's current troubles sprang up
spectacularly fast. As late as mid-August, the industry, which
includes securities firms, investment houses and commercial banks,
was on its way to a third consecutive year of record revenues,
according to Rae Rosen, an economist with the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the spread of the Asian crisis to Russia, Russia's abrupt
decision to stop payment on some foreign debt and subsequent
turmoil in Brazil frightened millions of investors and sent
financial markets spiraling off in unexpected directions.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil took its biggest toll on hedge funds like Long-Lerm
Capital Management LP, a private investment group of wealthy
individuals and institutions that nearly collapsed last month when
its multibillion dollar bets on where markets were headed went
sour.
</P>
<P>
   But the trouble also caused some of the financial industry's
most lucrative lines of business to dry up. Corporate mergers,
which can fetch firms like Merrill handsome fees, went from a pace
of 40-to-50 combinations a month to three or four, according to
Securities Data Corp. Stock and bond underwriting dropped by one
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went from running on all 14 cylinders to park,'' said
Richard Peterson, a Securities Data executive.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the damage began to show itself yesterday when
Merrill and two other investment firms, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Inc. and Paine Webber Group, announced hefty drops in
their quarterly profit.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, the nation's biggest securities firm as measured by
capital, posted a $164 million loss, its first since 1989, after
taking a $288 million charge to cover the cost of layofffs. DLJ,
the nation's eighth largest investment bank, said that its profits
dropped almost 80 percent from $120.3 million a year ago to $25.7
million. Paine Webber posted a more modest 27-percent profit
decline frm $112.8 million to $82.9 million. Analysts expect a
steady stream of disappointing profit announcements from other
finacial firms in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, almost everybody involved in the financial industry
knew that the good times had already lasted beyond most people's
expectations and could not go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be an idiot to work in this business and not
know it's cyclical,'' said Roy C. Smith, a former partner with
Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, industry observers said that Merrill's cutbacks
were not as wholesale as they might have been. ``They are not
exiting any businesses'' and therefore dropping entire divisions of
employes, said Orchant.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said that financial executives are almost certainly
in for more bad news. They said that several firms that have yet to
announce their quarterly profits, especially Citigroup's Salomon,
Smith Barney and Bankers Trust, are likely to make deeper cuts than
Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   And when that happens, they warned, the effects are likely to be
felt well beyond the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general sense of well-being that all New York City
gets from a healthy stock market,'' said Corcoran. ``Right now,
with the battering the markets are taking, New Yorkers are feeling
that things are not as good as they were. It's a clear mood
change,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
