<HEADLINE>
FIREWORKS EXPLOSION IN MEXICO KILLS AT LEAST 10, INJURES 100 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An explosion ripped through a small town known as
the capital of Mexico's fireworks industry on Tuesday, killing at
least 10 people and injuring as many as 100.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the blast in Tultepec, a small town about 30
miles north of Mexico City, was caused by a natural gas leak, which
in turn ignited gunpowder used to make fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion, which occurred at about 9:30 a.m., destroyed at
least nine buildings in a three-block area of the town. Dozens of
other buildings were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The blast ripped roofs off houses, tore doors from their hinges
and shattered windows. People three miles away heard the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Camacho Quiroz, the governor of the state of Mexico where
Tultepec is located, said 10 people died in the explosion and 23
were injured. Some reports, however, put the death toll as high as
16. The Mexican Red Cross estimated that at least 100 people were
injured.
</P>
<P>
   A Red Cross official warned that the death toll could rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be more dead, because they are talking about 15
missing,'' said Alejandro Gomez, head of the Red Cross' emergency
response section.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people desperately dug through the rubble searching
for survivors. By early evening, police had brought in dogs and
heavy equipment to aid the search effort.
</P>
<P>
   Tultepec is famous for its fireworks, both those made in legal
factories and those made clandestinely in homes. About 85 percent
of the town's residents make a living from manufacturing or selling
the devices. Last year, three people were killed in the town after
an explosion in a home.
</P>
<P>
   For hours after the blast, angry residents formed a human
barricade to keep journalists away from the explosion site. Many
people denied that gunpowder played a role in the accident and
attributed the explosion to a gas leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``An explosion of this magnitude is not caused by this type of
gunpowder,'' said Sofia Montes, who works in a family fireworks
factory in Tultepec. ``Explosions of fireworks smell of sulfur.
This was very different. It was like a mushroom cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Santos, head of disaster operations for the state of
Mexico, and other officials said, however, that the explosion was
caused by a combination of gunpowder and natural gas. Police said
the area smelled strongly of gunpowder and gas for hours after the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Montes and other residents said authorities enforce strict
regulations on the production of fireworks, restricting the
manufacture of the devices to two areas of town.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Camacho said he would not speculate on the cause of
Tuesday's explosion until investigators complete their inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature to say what happened or what the cause was,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people killed Tuesday were decapitated by the force
of the explosion. A 10-year-old boy was among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Although laws have been enacted to regulate the sale of
fireworks in Mexico, few are enforced, critics say. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, 62 people in Mexico City died after fireworks exploded
at a market.
</P>
<P>
   Gas leaks have also caused tragedies in Mexico. In 1992, an
explosion that followed the leak of gasoline into a sewer system
killed at least 200 people in Guadalajara and injured hundreds of
others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Downie is a free-lance journalist based in Mexico City. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
