<HEADLINE>
SEA LAUNCH WON'T BLAST OFF UNTIL MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The first blastoff of the Sea Launch rocket has
slipped to March 1999, and the payload will be a dummy satellite,
Boeing said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stories had been swirling for weeks from Boeing's Sea Launch
partners that the satellite would be replaced by a dummy because of
failures of the RussianZenit rocket. PanAmSat Corp. of Greenwich,
Conn., confirmed the rumors Monday by announcing that its Galaxy XI
satellite would be orbited by the French Ariane rocket instead of
Sea Launch, as it had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ariane 4 vehiclewill enable us to reduce potential risk
and ensure the timely launch,'' said Frederick Landman, PanAmSat's
president.
</P>
<P>
   But PanAmSat did not give up on Sea Launch. ``PanAmSat intends
to launh a future satellite on the Sea Launch vehicle during the
fourth quarter of 1999,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dolan, spokesman for Boeing Space Communications, said the
the fourth-quarter 1999 shot is an extra one. Sea Launch still has
orders for 18 shots through 2004, including 13 launches for Hughes
Space &AMP; Communications International Inc. and five from Loral Space
&AMP; Communications Ltd. Analysts estimate each launch will bring in
about $50 million, about one-tenth of 1 percent of Boeing's annual
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket to be launched in March will be a three-stage Zenit
vehicle in a configuration never before used. The two lower stages
are Russian and the upper stage, Ukranian, with satellite fairings
built in the Seattle area. Despite reports that the Zenit 2 has
been launching satellites with only 75 percent reliability, Dolan
said Boeing tests show that the Zenit 3 should work at least 93
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Zenit 3 will have full instrumentation, and will carry a
dummy satellite with the same weight and dimensions as Galaxy XI.
``We think the demonstration launch will be very valuable to
display the system to Sea Launch's present and future customers,''
Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   The launch site is south of Hawaii at 154 degrees west
longitude. Being at the equator, it uses the earth's maximum
rotational force to sling satellites into orbit. An equatorial site
also allows a satellite to be shot into geostationary orbit without
having to change course. Both advantages allow a rocket to save
fuel, and thereby lift larger payloads.
</P>
<P>
   Work on the Sea Launch was halted over the summer by the State
Department because Boeing had discussed technical information with
its Russian and Ukranian partners without a U.S. government
representative present. Although the technology was not sensitive,
the meetings violated the terms of Boeing's license. Boeing agreed
to pay $10 million for fines and program modifications to have its
license reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Work has now resumed, and the converted oil platform that will
be used as the project's floating launch pad has arrived from
Russia at the Sea Launch home port in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, expected in the next 30 days, is integrated
testing of the command ship and the launch platform at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing holds a 40 percent stake in Sea Launch, with the
remainder held by RSC-Energia of Moscow, KB Yuzhnoye/PO Yuzhmash of
Ukraine and Kvaerner Maritime of Norway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
