<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-STOCK-SPI &LR;      10-13 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STOCK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING: PROFITABILITY NEEDED BEFORE NEW ACQUISITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The battering that The Boeing Co.'s stock has taken
over the last year has made new business acquisitions all but
impossible until the company can return to profitability, a top
Boeing executive said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our hoped for acquisitions have had to be put on hold
because you want to do those with stock swaps,'' said Larry
Clarkson, the former head of Boeing Enterprises who announced
Monday that he will retire early next year.
</P>
<P>
   As Boeing struggled this past year through serious production
problems in its Commercial Airplane Group, its stock has lost 40
percent of its value. It closed Tuesday 33 3/8 a share, compared to
its price of 54 3/4 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson, in an interview with the Post-Intelligencer, did not
say what acquisitions Boeing Enterprises had been looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing obviously has to get its core business back on track
and its profitability back on track in order to get its stock price
back on track and be in a position to pursue the basic mission of
Boeing Enterprises,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That mission, when Boeing Enterprises was formed early last year
with Clarkson in charge, was to find new aviation-related business
opportunities for Boeing to invest in. Clarkson, 60, a large jovial
man who become known as Boeing's ``secretary of state'' in his
previous job as Boeing's chief international strategist, went out
and did just that.
</P>
<P>
   Successful ventures include one with General Electric to build
737 business jets and another with FlightSafety International to
train pilots and aircraft maintenance crews.
</P>
<P>
   But while these ventures and several others have taken root, and
even flourished, the company's production woes overtook the promise
of Boeing Enterprises and finally led to a sweeping management
shakeup and reorganization with the firing Sept. 1 of Ron Woodard
as head of the commercial group.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mulally, who had been running Boeing's defense and space
operation, replaced Woodard. Boeing Enterprises was scaled back and
folded into a new customer services group led by Tom Schick, who
had been Woodard's deputy and who now reports to Mulally.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson's job was eliminated and he decided to retire rather
than take another job in Boeing. He is the last remaining member of
the senior staff of former Boeing Chairman Frank Shrontz and he has
represented Boeing in national and international matters during
three administrations since he joined the company in 1987 from
engine maker Pratt &AMP; Whitney, where, in 1982 at age 42, he become
the youngest president ever of Pratt's commercial jet engine
division.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear even before the recent reorganization that Boeing
Enterprises would have a diminished role while the company focused
on getting its commercial operations in order, Clarkson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty much a no brainer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the stock price, we just had to put a lot of things
on hold. That's why the decision was made to downsize Boeing
Enterprises for a period of time until the situation stabilized and
we get the core business back where it should be and the Boeing
stock price back to where it should be. Then Boeing will again be
in a position to make those kinds of acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Clarkson would not say so publicly, company executives
had been counting on Boeing Enterprises to bring in up to $5
billion in additional revenue by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson said he remains optimistic the long-range financial
goals he set for Boeing Enterprises will be realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what's there now, like FlightSafety Boeing
International, and with a couple things I believe the company will
go ahead with, Boeing Enterprises will be well on its way to
achieving those financial goals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The businesses that we now have under our belt will thrive,''
he said. ``And there are one or two more that we are trying to
bring into the tent. But a lot of what we had hoped to do just has
to go on the shelf for a while. Boeing, though, is not going to
abandon this in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Boeing Business Jets and FlightSafety Boeing
International, Boeing Enterprises teamed with Czech national
airline CSA for a 35 percent stake in Aero Vodochody, the largest
aerospace company in the Czech Republic. That deal could help
Boeing land a multi-billion-dollar fighter order.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clarkson, Boeing Enterprises also invested in a Chinese
company that is now repairing and overhauling Boeing jets. And this
past June, Boeing Enterprises formed what's known as Boeing
Modification and Engineering Services. The goal of that unit is to
be much more aggressive in the marketplace in promoting the
aircraft modification work that now takes place mostly at the
company's plants in Wichita and in Long Beach, where the 747, DC-10
and MD-11 passenger jets are converted into freighters.
</P>
<P>
   These various business ventures by Boeing Enterprises, Clarkson
said, ``have paid off pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The company recently announced that FlightSafety Boeing
International will be build its first European training center in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near term, we will be announcing several other
expansion facilities,'' Clarkson said. ``I'm very pleased how well
that's going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Clark detailed the events that led to the
decision to consolidate Boeing Enterprises under Schick as part of
the new customer services business unit.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson said he first talked with his former boss, Woodard, in
early summer about retiring, but Woodard talked him about of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we had gotten Boeing Enterprises off to a good start
and it was going well,''Clarkson said, ``but it was also clear we
were going to have to scale back some of our activities because of
the commercial situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Woodard's organization of the Commercial Airplane Group,
Schick had served as ``Mr. Inside'' to Woodard's ``Mr. Outside,''
Clarkson said. While Schick ran day-to-day operations, Woodard
concentrated on airplane sales.
</P>
<P>
   That changed under Mulally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan's approach to things is different,'' Clarkson said. ``He
doesn't intend to be Mr. Outside. He didn't need a Mr. Inside. So
one of the challenges was what kind of a job could be put together
that made sense and could use Tom's strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Schick came out of customer service and had an airline
background.
</P>
<P>
   So Mulally made Schick head of the new customer services unit.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson said he suggested that Boeing Enterprises be
consolidated into the new customer services business unit at his
first meeting with Mulally after Mulally replaced Woodard. The idea
was then discussed with Schick.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Clarkson said, he and Mulally talked about him
taking on a broad business development role within Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that job went to Nancy Bethel, Boeing's highest ranking
female executive, who was head of sales and marketing but had been
out for several months on sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in good health now, but she must be careful as she goes
forward to protect her health,'' Clarkson said. ``It wasn't clear
initially if she could continue in her sales and marketing role
that she had under Ron's organization. In the days that followed
Alan's appointment, it became clear she could not do that. So the
most obvious role for her was business development . . . That left
me out of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson said he could have stayed with Boeing and would have
been given a job ``with a nice title.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want that kind of job,'' Clarkson said. ``I want to go
out and kill something . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I'm overpaid but I'm paid a lot . . . In this day and
age, when Boeing clearly has to do some major headcount reductions,
if my retiring will let six younger people stay on the payroll, so
be it. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson, who has been active in the Seattle community and has
served for seven years as chairman of the Seattle Opera, said he
and his wife want to stay in Seattle. But he said he expects to
keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm marketable,'' he said. ``I have a lot of contacts
in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clarkson, who did yesterday's telephone interview from
his room at the Waldorf Historia hotel in New York City, planned to
see some of those industry friends last night during a dance at the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will just have to see what develops,'' he said. ``I'm not
in a position where I have to work. But I want to work one way or
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
