<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH14-COX     10-13 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reno prepares to name Rudolph; couple confirms powder sale
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Nashville man who told federal agents he sold
Birmingham bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph the smokeless powder
allegedly used in the Centennial Olympic Park bomb said he and his
wife were subpoenaed to appear before a federal grand jury here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a press conference has tentatively been scheduled for
today in Washington, when U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno is
expected to announce that Rudolph has been charged in three Atlanta
bombings, officials with the Southeast Bomb Task Force said Monday.
A second press conference is scheduled in Atlanta Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   David Mosley, a Nashville businessman who started a sideline
company selling ammunition and other supplies to gun enthusiasts
and hunters in 1993, said he has been told that his evidence is
among the strongest linking Rudolph to the July 1996 park blast
that killed an Albany woman and injured 111 people.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law enforcement officials would not publicly confirm
that Mosley was subpoenaed or that a grand jury is hearing
testimony in the Atlanta bombing cases, citing grand jury secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said he conducted transactions with a man who used the
name Bob Randolph at three gun shows. At the first, in Nashville in
March 1994, ``Randolph'' paid $400 in cash for 8 pounds of 5
Accurate Arms brand smokeless powder and 8 pounds of 9 Accurate
Arms powder, Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randolph'' also ordered ``a bunch of lead bullets'' and 32
pounds of Accurate Arms 7 smokeless powder, which he picked up two
weeks later at a gun show in Sparta, Tenn., Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's wife, who was at the Sparta show, later identified
``Randolph'' as Eric Rudolph when federal agents presented a photo
lineup, Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Sparta show, the man bought 20,000 lead bullets for .45
caliber, .38 caliber, and 9mm handguns and 10,000 rounds of .223
caliber ammunition used in an AR-15, a semi-automatic rifle. A
federal wanted poster for Rudolph says he owns and is probably
armed with an AR-15.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, who has not been charged with a crime, said he
remembered ``Randolph'' mostly from the Sparta show because the
name he gave was the same last name as an Olympian shooter. Mosley
said the orders were not uncommonly large for gun enthusiasts who
reload bullets for hunting and target practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``And believe it or not, he wrote a check to me for $622 using
the name Bob Randolph,'' he said. ``It was the biggest sale I had
ever made. I wrote him a receipt.'' Federal agents have said
Rudolph didn't trust or use banks.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, at a Knoxville gun show, Rudolph bought about
$30 worth of boxed ammunition, Mosley said.
</P>
<P>
   Cherokee County, N.C., Sheriff Jack Thompson said as early as
January that Rudolph sometimes used the name Bob Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph remains a fugitive in western North Carolina where about
80 federal and state law enforcement agents are looking for him. He
is charged in the Jan. 29 bombing of a Birmingham abortion clinic
that killed an off-duty police officer and severely injured a
nurse, and agents have said they want to question him in the
Atlanta bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, three bombs of galvanized steel pipes packed with
smokeless powder and taped together with concrete flooring nails
were left under a bench in Centennial Olympic Park. Not all of them
ignited properly, investigators have said.
</P>
<P>
   Later bombs, in January 1997 at a Sandy Springs abortion clinic,
in February 1997 at a gay club on Piedmont Road and this January at
the Birmingham clinic, were dynamite, federal agents have said.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said investigators told him a powder canister identical
to the ones Rudolph bought from him was found during a search of
some of his belongings found in North Carolina. A federal lab has
confirmed that the powder Rudolph bought from Mosley was consistent
with the powder used in the park bomb, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a task force document, the park bomb was packed
with 7 or 9 Accurate Arms powder, which is manufactured in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said that's an amateur bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he used that,'' Mosley said. ``There's not
enough energy. It won't pack right. There's not enough nitro in it
to make a real big bang. Those are slow-burning pistol powders. I
don't think he knew what he was doing. Black powder would have made
a huge hole in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution in a recent
interview in Nashville that he and his wife were stunned to see
Rudolph's picture flash across their television screen after the
Birmingham bombing. Rudolph was sought for questioning within hours
of that blast outside the abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time she saw it on TV, my wife remembered him,''
Mosley said. ``She said, 'That's the guy we sold the powder to.' At
the time I didn't worry about it. For all I knew, he was just using
it for reloading.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said it wasn't until he told a customer about the sales
that he was questioned by agents. Mosley said he didn't know at the
time his customer was also an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Agents ``have questioned me three or four times and they've
questioned my wife twice,'' Mosley said. Mosley declined to give
his wife's name because, he said, she is ill.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Scruggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
