<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRGIN14-COX     10-13 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faithful amass to hear last pronouncement
 &HT;    By Peter Scott and Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ A church in honor of the Virgin Mary, a saint as
a role model for the young and a call for everyone to be holy
witnesses: This was the final message that Nancy Fowler told the
world she received from the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   As local, national and international news media documented the
drama, more than 100,000 pilgrims packed Fowler's 90-acre farm in
Conyers, southeast of Atlanta on Ga. 138.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my dear little children. God is all loving. And you will
reach him by imitating him,'' a pensive Fowler said the Blessed
Mother told her. ``Please be attentive. My son's heart is drenched
in mercy and love for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said the crowd, which was orderly and well organized, was
Fowler's largest since hordes of people first began flocking to the
farm in 1990 to hear the holy messages Fowler said she receives on
the 13th day of each month.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic, police said, was clogged on highways as far away as
Augusta, 100 miles away, with people trying to reach the farm for
Fowler's last public message.
</P>
<P>
   Worshippers had been praying and singing since daybreak Tuesday
in anticipation of the message, which Fowler was scheduled to
deliver at 1:45 p.m. As the day progressed, the sun bore down,
oppressing some to the point that they passed out from the heat.
Believers collected so much blessed water, the farm's well ran dry.
Around noon, a single white cloud floated across the sky, creating
somewhat of a stir of excitement among the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:15 p.m., though, the cloud had vanished as Fowler emerged
from what she calls her ``apparition room,'' located in the front
of her one-story rustic farmhouse. As Fowler strode to the
platform, a hushed silence fell over the crowd. Only the cries of a
baby could be heard off in the distance, along with a police
officer ordering a pedestrian to get out of the street.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a brown jacket, brown blouse and a brown skirt,
Fowler was flanked by 20 priests from around the world as she spoke
to the crowd:
</P>
<P>
   ``.....Please pray the Rosary. Please pray against the evils of
this age,'' Fowler said. ``Please stop offending God. You have yet
to see the forces of nature. No man is greater than God. No country
is greater than God. If you choose to live apart from God, then you
will fall...''Fowler went on to say that the Virgin Mary also had
implored her to build a church at the farm, which she said she will
do, and she said she was told to tell young people to choose a
saint to emulate. Fowler said that many souls would ascend from
Purgatory on Tuesday as a special grace and blessing, drawing a
thunderous applause from the multitude. Many Roman Catholics
believe souls ascend to heaven on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, Fowler said to the audience: ``Today, our Lady has
come for the last time in this way. We will not be able to see our
Lady again, until we are all in heaven,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   After the 30-minute message, Fowler invited all priests in the
crowd to join her for a special message Mary had for them. Several
later said that Fowler encouraged them to be faithful and loving.
</P>
<P>
   Several people trying to prove the authenticity of Fowler's
visions were on hand Tuesday to speak to the crowds before Fowler's
address. Fowler has said that she receives a holy message on the
13th of each month. She has shared eight messages publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Nancy was tested, what the doctors found was that Nancy
is as normal as you and I,'' said Ron Tesoriero, an Australian
lawyer and television producer who has been documenting Fowler's
claims since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church, however, has not given its blessings to
Fowler's claims
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Castanon, a Bolivian neuropsychophysiologist who
specializes in stigmata and weeping statues, said that he hoped the
Vatican in due time would recognize Fowler as legitimate. He told
the group ``there are visionaries who are not genuine, but Fowler
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Tommy Eaton of the Rockdale County Sheriff's department
said it took 10 hours to get all who wanted access to the farm
inside. It took about six hours to help them leave. Even as Fowler
prepared to give her message, some of the 253 buses and 8,000 cars
at the event were still streaming down White Road to her farm.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Jatcko, a spokesman for Fowler, says that $300,000 was
spent paying for off-duty police and medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said she has more to say to her believers but they have
to get it from the internet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
