<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TOOMBS-HNS &LR;      10-13 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TOOMBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ Two years ago in the high school football
playoffs, Ja'Mar Toombs ended his junior year at Kilgore with a
disappointing loss to Dallas Lincoln.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't a happy night for the powerful running back, but
Toombs soon would find out his disappointment over that defeat
would pale compared to the loss he would hear about the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stepbrother, Christopher, was killed in Louisiana on the
same night of that game,'' Toombs said. ``He was 20. They didn't
tell me until the next day. I couldn't believe it until I went to
the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a bad place at a bad time, shooting dice. A man held
up the place and shot him. There hasn't been a day go by since then
that I haven't thought about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher would not be considered a role model for Ja'Mar, but
Christopher was the person Ja'Mar confided in and listened to about
the struggles of life.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher was three years older than Ja'Mar, but Christopher
had taken the hard road and gotten in with a bad crowd as a high
school dropout. It was a path he wanted to be sure Ja'Mar didn't
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to always tell me to keep my head on straight and go
to college,'' Toombs said. ``He told me the streets weren't for me,
and he wanted me to know there were better things in life than what
he had done.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs is doing some of those better things now as the starting
fullback for Texas A&AMP;M as a true freshman. His dramatic 71-yard run
Saturday set up a touchdown and helped the Aggies defeat No. 2
Nebraska 28-21 for one of the biggest victories in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs rushed for 110 yards and one TD on 10 carries, prompting
the crowd of 60,798 to fill Kyle Field with a collective
``Toooooombs'' every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the other freshman players started it,'' Toombs said.
``When I got the ball on the field, they were doing it on the
sideline, and I think people heard them and started doing it too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what they were doing, but my mom (Angela Belle) didn't.
She thought people were booing me, but (tailback) Dante Hall's mom
told her what they were doing. I like it a lot. It's exciting when
I hear them.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-1 and 260 pounds, Toombs has brought back memories of
former A&AMP;M running back George Woodard, who weighed 280 pounds and
rushed for 2,864 yards in his first three seasons before an injury
and his expanding weight got the best of him. Toombs weighed 270
when he arrived on campus two months ago, but the A&AMP;M coaches
believe Toombs can keep his weight under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Ja'Mar has a lot of self-discipline,'' said A&AMP;M
offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe. ``When you point something
out to him, he'll take care of it. He has lost 10 pounds since he
got here. I wish I could have lost 10 pounds since Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't compare Ja'Mar to Woodard, because I really don't
know anything about Woodard. I think I was 10 when he started
playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs also never had heard of Woodard before arriving at A&AMP;M,
and he has no intentions of following in Woodard's footsteps by
letting his weight get out of hand. Toombs said he has too many
reasons to work hard to succeed, including his 6-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I named him Christopher after my brother,'' Toombs said. ``He
gives me a lot of inspiration. He'll be here with his mom and my
mom for the Texas Tech game (Oct. 24). If I have a good game that
day, I plan on bringing him to the press room when it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs probably would not have been at any press-room gatherings
this season if not for the academic problems that caused A&AMP;M senior
fullback Tiki Hardeman to lose his eligibility two games into the
season. The Aggies already had lost fullback Marc Broyles for the
season because of an illness that affects his vision, so Toombs was
forced into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiki and I became friends, and he taught me a lot,'' Toombs
said. ``I was hoping Tiki wouldn't be suspended. When it happened,
he told me I couldn't be a freshman anymore. I had to step up and
take his place.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs also thinks he is stepping up and doing what his brother
always wanted him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things that keeps me focused,'' Toombs said.
``Not only do I want to do things right for my brother, but I also
want to set a good example for my son. I want him to be able to
have all the things a young boy should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs' college career is just beginning, but he has specific
goals beyond his days at A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my brother that one day I would make it to the pros,''
Toombs said. ``He was a real good barber and used to cut my hair. I
always told him I would open up a barbershop for him, and I still
plan to do it. If I do make it to the pros, I am going to open a
chain of barbershops and put his name on them.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was being recruited as one of the top prospects in the
nation, Toombs was told by coaches in other states that his best
chance of making it to the NFL was to play football outside of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida State and Ohio State were hammering him,'' said Texas
A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum. ``They were telling him you have to leave
(Texas) to play in big games. But he stayed here for his mom and
his family, and his mom couldn't have been prouder watching him
have a big game against Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M had almost 100 recruits at the Nebraska game, and all of
them saw a true freshman help lead the Aggies to an upset victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speaks way more than anything I can do,'' Slocum said.
``I can go into homes and do what I do, but seeing Ja'Mar out there
after turning down Florida State and Ohio State says more than
anything I can tell those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs said he hopes he can convince other Texas blue-chippers
to stay home to play college football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I could be the poster boy for what can happen if you
stay in Texas,'' Toombs said. ``I think kids can look at me now and
see you can stay in Texas and still win the big games against the
top teams. If some stay in the state because I do well, it would
make me feel real good. I know what it would mean for their
families being able to see their sons play.''
</P>
<P>
   Toombs wishes his brother were around to see him play, but
Toombs said he never will forget the things Christopher told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I could become something special if I worked hard and
did the right things,'' Toombs said. ``I always told him I would.
I'm just trying to do all the things he wanted me to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
