</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREASTCANCER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With early detection, breast cancer can be beaten
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evelyn Gresham knows what it's like to come to terms
with the words ``You have breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, she's lived through the diagnosis, scares,
fear, surgeries and drugs, and now she helps others facing the same
questions and uncertainties through the volunteer, nonprofit group
Bosom Buddies of Georgia Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``One weekend, I went to visit a woman who, when she found out
(about her cancer), she bought a casket, she found a cemetery plot
and she just kept crying,'' said Gresham, 41. ``You lose it. You
ask yourself, `Why is this happening to me?' But you need to talk
to women who are surviving breast cancer. They've got the
information. They've got the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's awareness of breast cancer and the need for early
detection were raised when WSB-TV anchor Monica Kaufman disclosed
last week that a small tumor was detected in her left breast. The
popular 51-year-old newswoman underwent a lumpectomy, surgical
removal of the cancerous lump, Friday at Emory University Hospital.
She is reported to be recovering in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman's cancer is said to be intraductal carcinoma, an early
form of the disease that is confined to milk glands and responds
well to treatment. But her early diagnosis was because of a simple
test every woman older than 40 should get annually: a mammogram, or
breast X-ray, to screen for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Early detection of breast cancer, which claims the lives of
43,500 American women a year, is regarded as the best bet for
beating it. The five-year survival rate for breast cancer that has
not spread beyond the breast has improved from 72 percent in the
1940s to 95 percent today, according to the American Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the message that Kaufman's condition is helping
women to hear, health officials say. Emory's Breast Imaging Center
received 400 calls Friday about mammogram appointments, about 100
more calls than usual, after word of Kaufman's cancer was reported
on TV broadcasts and in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. ``The
staff was a little bit overwhelmed by the rush of phone calls,''
said Susan Stewart, spokeswoman for the Emory Winship Cancer
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman's breast cancer diagnosis happened to come during
October, which for the past decade has been Breast Cancer Awareness
Month. Health organizations and hospitals typically remind women
during the month about the importance of annual mammograms as well
as sponsor numerous informational and entertainment events.
</P>
<P>
   Mammograms and self-breast exams are credited for the increase
in early detection, and improved survival rates. Abnormalities most
often appear on the X-ray images of the breast before they can be
felt or seen by a woman or her doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mammograms are wonderful, they really are,'' said Dr. William
Wood, Emory University's chairman of the department of surgery.
``The message really has gotten out about the need to get them
taken annually. However, it's not rare to see someone who's gone
three or four years without getting a mammogram.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of money and access to health facilities are the main
reasons women do not receive the recommended annual exam, doctors
say. Many hospitals and clinics are offering breast screenings at a
discount this month.
</P>
<P>
   While the chance of developing breast cancer does increase with
age and a family history of it, women must remember that gender is
the biggest risk factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being female, that's it,'' said Lynn Dillard, health
specialist with the American Cancer Society's national office in
Atlanta. ``All women are at risk for getting breast cancer. That's
the No. 1 factor.'' (Men can develop breast cancer, but rarely.
It's diagnosed in about 1 percent of men, and about 400 die of the
disease each year.)
</P>
<P>
   And should the news from a mammogram or biopsy be bad, Bosom
Buddies' Gresham, who underwent a mastectomy with immediate
reconstruction, has this one-word recommendation: research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your research. Don't take the first diagnosis,'' says
Gresham, a DeKalb County, Ga. employee and single parent of three
children. ``Get a second opinion. And if you don't feel comfortable
with your doctor, get another one. That's what I did.'' Gresham
says she feels ``great'' after her surgery a year ago, with enough
energy to walk four miles several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   While heart disease is the leading cause of death among American
women, it doesn't come close in evoking the fear and stigma that
breast cancer does, health educators and advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of women are still really reluctant to get screening and
to get a mammogram,'' said Vicki Castleberry, 67, president of
Bosom Buddies, a group she founded in 1983, three years after
undergoing a radical mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   The sessions started with a few women meeting in Castleberry's
Tucker home and have blossomed today to 32 separate groups
throughout Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women sometimes say, `Oh, I don't need a support group. I can
do this on my own,''' said Castleberry. ``But what I tell them is,
`You may not need it but maybe you can come out and help someone
else go through this,' and once they do that, they always come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
