<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VA-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG OFFENDER FACES DEATH, AND STATE IS URGED TO HALT IT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Virginia plans on Wednesday to execute a man who
was 17 when he fatally shot a woman in 1989, in a case that has
drawn wide criticism of the use of capital punishment for juvenile
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The execution of the man, Dwayne Allen Wright, would be the 12th
of a juvenile offender in the United States since 1985, and the
first in Virginia since the death penalty was reinstated there in
1976. Twenty-four states permit execution of offenders under 18 at
the time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's case has drawn requests for clemency from the president
of the American Bar Association, Philip Anderson; the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and Amnesty
International. They say that Wright, of Washington, was brain
damaged at birth, was reared by a mother with mental illnesses and
was committed to a mental hospital himself when he was 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most troubling case for execution I have seen in
my entire life,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the District of
Columbia's delegate in the House. ``If this sentence is carried
out, it will prove that our country has lost its way in criminal
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. James S. Gilmore III of Virginia has a request on his desk
from Wright's lawyers to commute the sentence to life in prison or
to grant a 60-day reprieve so that a more formal clemency request
may be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Wright filed a stay of execution Tuesday with the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   But the office of the Virginia attorney general filed a motion
opposing the defense request. ``The jury considered his age as well
as mental state when it sentenced him to death,'' said David
Botkins, a spokesman for the attorney general, Mark Earley.
``Numerous mental health experts have determined Wright is not
brain damaged, and the U.S. Supreme Court has held that someone
like Wright, who committed a capital murder at 17, may be executed.
The predatory killing of Saba Tekle left three children motherless
and was one of three murders by Dwayne Wright within a five-day
period.''
</P>
<P>
   In four days in October 1989, Wright, then living in Washington,
shot to death Saba Tekle, a 34-year-old mother of three, in
Virginia; a 19-year-old man in Maryland in an attempted robbery,
and a 31-year-old man in Washington in an argument. Wright pleaded
guilty to charges in Maryland and received two life sentences. A
murder charge was dismissed in Washington. But the death penalty
was imposed in Virginia for the Tekle killing.
</P>
<P>
   Wright spotted Ms. Tekle on the highway and followed her from
Washington to her apartment in Annandale, Va. The police in
Fairfax, Va., said he tried to sexually assault her. When she tried
to flee, Wright shot her and stole her car.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's lawyers said he was stopped for driving a stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, said Robert E. Lee, one of his lawyers,
Wright told the police about the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Lila Young, a spokeswoman for Gilmore, said the letter from
Wright's lawyers describing his troubled childhood and more
material filed Tuesday would be reviewed by the governor and
governor's counsel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
