</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons sparked by turnovers
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's not a Falcon player or coach who wasn't
ecstatic Sunday night when reserve defensive end Antonio Edwards
stripped the ball from Giants quarterback Danny Kanell, plucked it
out of mid-air and returned it 2 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers may be the single biggest key to success in the NFL,
and the Falcons, who are 4-1 for just the third time in the 33-year
history of the franchise, are doing quite well in this category.
</P>
<P>
   They're sixth in the NFL in takeaways with 13, and tied for
eighth with a plus-four turnover ratio. They're plus six in their
wins, and minus-two in their loss.
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety William White returned a fumble 18 yards for a TD
in the 51-23 win over Carolina on Oct. 4, making this the first
time since 1991 Atlanta has scored off turnovers in consecutive
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Falcons went 10-6, made the playoffs and beat the
Saints 27-20 in a wild-card game before losing 24-7 at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings (5-0) lead the NFL with a plus-nine ratio. This
Sunday's opponent, the Saints (3-2), are tied for second in the NFL
with a plus-seven ratio and haven't lost a fumble yet.
</P>
<P>
   The worst team in the NFL, the Redskins (0-6), are tied for last
in the NFL with a minus-13 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know if we protect the football ... we have an excellent
chance to win,'' coach Dan Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Jamal Anderson's fumble on the first play of Sunday night's game
set up a New York field goal, the Giants' only lead of the game.
The Falcons came right back to score a touchdown, though. It hasn't
always been this way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Falcons were minus-18 in turnovers, and finished
3-13. They got just six interceptions all season (last in the NFL),
and threw 30. Last year, Atlanta improved to plus-four, with 28
takeaways, getting 18 interceptions (sixth in the NFL) and throwing
11.
</P>
<P>
   This season the Falcons have just four interceptions, three by
cornerback Ray Buchanan and one by White, but they've scooped up
nine fumbles, seven in the past two games. The Falcons worked extra
in training camp on stripping the ball, like reserve linebacker
Keith Brooking did Sunday night when he robbed Giant tight end
Howard Cross, and are on a pace to get 42 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have thrown five interceptions and lost four
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has fumbled just nine times in 806 career
``touches,'' said that when the defense gets a turnover, the
emotional lift puts pressure on the offense. But it's a good kind
of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a double-edged sword because they expect us to
score. But we welcome that,'' he said. ``It's unbelievable man.
We're thrilled. We've gotten to where we're anticipating a fumble
or a pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
