A5356 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JUNEJONES-COX     10-13 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JUNEJONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones' S.D. term likely to be short
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His second incarnation as an NFL head coach figures to
be a short-term experience, but June Jones intends to treat his
interim tenure with the San Diego Chargers as if he is there for
the long-haul and not just the final 10 games of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can speculate about what will happen here at the end of
the year,'' Jones said Tuesday evening, a few hours after
succeeding the deposed Kevin Gilbride as coach. ``I know we have to
get our offense going and we have to win games. If we can do those
things, then I think I'll get some consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the timing of Gilbride's dismissal came as a surprise. It
has long been rumored he could be gone by midseason if the Chargers
did not respond to him, and replaced by the more popular Jones. The
decision to fire Gilbride, whose contract has three more years to
run, actually came Monday night after club officials huddled twice
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbride was 6-16 in his first stint as a head coach. Beyond his
failures on the field, he alienated players and team management and
constantly was at odds with the media.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bobby Beathard, who hired Gilbride to replace
Bobby Ross, said the coach burned too many bridges and the team
lacked direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a sudden or impulsive thing,'' Beathard said.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf argued vociferously on the sideline
with Gilbride after he was removed from Sunday's loss at Oakland,
and players said the exchange between the two men grew ugly.
Ironically, a shouting match with quarterback Jeff George on Sept.
22, 1996, contributed to Jones' demise with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   In his three seasons here, Jones was 19-30. His 9-7 team in '95
was one of just five Falcons clubs to qualify for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 45, acknowledged his tenure with the Falcons was ``a
learning experience,'' but noted he doesn't intend to dramatically
alter his approach to handling players. ``You just don't change who
you are and what you believe in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Gilbride remained, Leaf would have been replaced by veteran
Craig Whelihan for the upcoming game against Philadelphia. Jones
said he will announce the starter today but he is likely to stick
with the struggling Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Chargers owner Alex Spanos, who has the NFL's highest payroll
but just a 2-4 record to show for it, almost certainly will seek a
high-profile coach like George Seifert or Mike Holmgren for 1999.
Seifert, who currently works for CBS, debunked rumors he had been
approached Tuesday about taking over the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
