<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALNOTES-COX     10-13 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AL Notebook: Spotlight on Justice's words
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before the most important game of the season, the
Indians weren't talking about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the focus continued to be on David Justice and his
impromptu press conference Monday when he said he did not ask out
of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been the case in his career for the former Brave,
Justice's mouth got him in more trouble. When asked about the fans
in New York, he said, ``They can't get any rougher on us unless
they show up with Uzis.''
</P>
<P>
   Uzis? Nothing like firing up the other club's fans when your
team needs a victory just to keep the series alive.
</P>
<P>
   Justice was back in the lineup Tuesday, but as the designated
hitter and not in left field. Asked if putting Justice in the DH
spot was for his own personal safety, Indians manager Mike Hargrove
laughed and said, ``No, the decision was made because Brian Giles'
ankle feels good tonight. I read what he said about the fans of New
York and all he was saying is the fans are very as I said
vociferous. To me he was trying to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny? Try telling that to a hardened Yankee fan from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hargrove also defended Justice and his press
conference where he criticized ESPN's Peter Gammons for insinuating
that he begged out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell you this thing completely blind-sided me,'' Hargrove
said. ``If I known that this was going to happen, I would have been
here (Monday) to field questions. At no time did he beg out of the
lineup, did he ask to be taken out of the lineup, did he intimate
to me in any shape, or fashion that he did not want to play. I
think this is a mountain out of a molehill. I called David (Monday
night) when I got back from dinner and we sat down for an hour and
talked about this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception for Knobby
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was wondering what type of reception Yankees second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch would get Tuesday night. The last time
Knoblauch was here he was booed viciously by his own fans for his
mental miscue in Game 2 which helped lead to a loss. But on this
night when he was introduced before the game and his pitcher was
put in center field, they cheered him loudly . Before the game,
Knoblauch said: ``They pay their money, they can do whatever they
want. Like I said, I'm concentrating on the game only and not
anything that takes place outside the line.'' Added teammate David
Wells, ``If they're going to boo us, they might as well boo every
one of us because we're all a team. So we win together and lose
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of talk whether the Yankees will pitch Andy
Pettitte in a Game 7 if there is one. There is also talk of whether
Pettitte will be dropped from the rotation if the team gets to the
World Series. Pettitte was ripped hard in Game 3 and there is a
question of his mental makeup, ... But he said, ``I ain't scared,
I've never been scared and I'm still not scared.'' ... Yankees
manager Joe Torre decided to go with rookie Ricky Ledee in left
field Tuesday. Both Chad Curtis and Shane Spencer have struggled in
the series, with just one hit in 14 at-bats between them. ... It
has been a great series for Indians shortstop Omar Vizquel, who
went into Game 6 with 10 hits in 20 at-bats. The record for a
six-game ALCS is .458 by Kenny Lofton for the Indians in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   I. J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
