<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GAME6-ADVANCE-COX     10-13 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GAME6-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Great theater' an apt description of NLCS drama
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was, Wally Joyner decided, possibly ''the best game
I've ever participated in...Like a chess match played with live
people.'' What felt ''unbelievable'' to Ryan Klesko was simply
indescribable to Bobby Cox. Tony Gwynn's hyperbole grew like the
evening's drama itself: ''A good game...a very good game...great
theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Great theater of the wonderfully absurd. Indeed, what began in
the late-afternoon southern California sunlight ended well beyond
nightfall with the most riveting yet unlikely of classic
confrontations. The best hitter of his era facing the best pitcher
of the era. Gwynn in the batter's box and Greg Maddux in _ good
grief! _ relief? The decade's dominant starter, a closer? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   When Maddux, making his first relief appearance since 1987, got
Gwynn to ground out and finally end Monday's melodrama, it was far
more than Mad Dog's first professional save. It concluded Atlanta's
astounding 7-6 victory over the Padres in Game 5 of the National
League Championship Series, and guaranteed what once seemed an even
more preposterous notion: Game 6, today at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   When the NLCS resumes at 4:20 p.m., the Braves will be halfway
home to a big-league miracle. No team in baseball history has ever
overcome a 3-0 deficit to win a postseason series. But after two
late-inning, life-preserving rallies in San Diego _ Sunday's
gutwrenching, Monday's astonishing _ Tom Glavine and the Braves can
even the series today.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who lost Game 2 3-0 to Kevin Brown, will oppose
Sterling Hitchcock, the Game 3 winner. If there is a Game 7
Thursday, Brown, who threw 41 pitches Monday in a rare relief
appearance, will try to oust Atlanta for the second straight year
and deny the Braves their fifth World Series appearance in seven
seasons. And another chunk of baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the stuff that's happened this year, all the home runs and
everything, don't count the Braves out,'' said Klesko, who, after
San Diego took a 3-0 lead in the series, said, ''You've got to take
it as the seventh game of the World Series, four games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   After Game 5, Klesko amended that: ''Two Game 7's down, two to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the quiet of the manager's office in the visitors clubhouse
after Monday's comeback, Cox said, ''The way I was approaching it
with everybody, we've got a one-game series here. Then, we go to
Atlanta with a two-game series. You've got to pick 'em off one at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still in the driver's seat,'' said Greg Vaughn, the
Padres' 50-homer, 119-RBI left fielder who'd been out with a
strained quadriceps since the fifth inning of Game 1 until he
pinch-hit against Maddux Monday, and struck out. Vaughn will likely
start today. But if San Diego is still in the driver's seat, the
Padres might heed that warning on the driver's side window: Objects
are closer than they appear.
</P>
<P>
   All this after a Game 5 that took more turns than Lombardi
Street in San Francisco, and produced perhaps the most unlikely
postseason homer since Bucky Dent cleared Fenway's Green Monster
and broke Boston's heart in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess tonight was my night,'' Tucker said after striking his
second homer of the postseason, first in NLCS play. Not that Tucker
hadn't hit Brown in the past. He was 6-for-11 (.545) lifetime,
2-for-2 with a walk this season. Tucker, however, finished the
season in a horrible slump (29-for-156, .186), and had just one
homer in the season's last seven weeks and 10 RBIs after the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tucker went 0-for-3 (two strikeouts) against Brown in
Game 2, he felt some confidence when facing Brown in Game 5. A
sense of familiarity with the guy who'd been the dominant pitcher
this postseason. ''After facing him two, three times this year and
last year,'' said Tucker, ''you pretty much have an idea of what
he's going to throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that that helped in Game 2, when Brown struck out 11. Not
that it helped in the seventh inning, when he came on with one on
and none out and quickly retired three straight. Bochy went with
Brown with a 4-2 lead (courtesy of John Vander Wal's two-run homer
off John Smoltz in the sixth), hoping to put away Atlanta for good.
The gamble was bold, and backfired.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people probably felt it was in the bag because
Brownie was in,'' said Gwynn. But Bochy made no Brownie points
Monday. Klesko drew a leadoff walk in the eighth in a terrific
at-bat, working the count full, fouling off two pitches, then
taking a pitch that was just off the inside corner for ball four.
When shortstop Chris Gomez went into the hole and down on the
ground to backhand Javy Lopez's smash, Klesko hustled and slid into
second just ahead of Gomez's throw.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones fouled out, but then Tucker worked the count to
3-1, hit a grounder foul just wide of first, then lasered an 89 MPH
split-finger fastball over the right field wall. It was just the
ninth homer allowed by Brown in 251 regular-season and post-season
innings.
</P>
<P>
   And Atlanta wasn't done. Good thing. Rookie reliever John
Rocker, in his first at-bat, walked on four pitches, then scored
from first on Tony Graffanino's double to left-center. Rocker ran
even harder than he does while racing in from the bullpen, slid
home and upended catcher Carlos Hernandez. When the relay sailed by
and out of play, Graffanino scored, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves needed all of that when ex-Brave Greg Myers hit a
two-run pinch-homer off Kerry Ligtenberg in the ninth. Then Maddux
left an unlikely place _ the bullpen _ for an even stranger role as
a closer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like a fish out of water down there,'' Maddux said of
his time in the pen. ''I didn't know what to do, how to act, what
to say. I don't know the bullpen lingo the way they do.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knew how to close the deal. After fanning Vaughn and
getting Quilvio Veras to ground out, Maddux walked Steve Finley.
Then came Gwynn, a career .435 hitter against Maddux who has more
hits (35) off the right-hander than off any other pitcher. Gwynn
was 0-for-2 with a walk against Maddux in Game 3. This time, Maddux
got Gwynn to ground out to Andres Galarraga to force a Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   And as Glavine said, ''We feel if anyone can come back from 3-0,
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
