<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools unaware served beef was recalled
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two local school systems that served beef patties
linked to possible salmonella contamination weren't aware the
patties had been recalled until Monday, although the recall went
into effect last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and Rockdale school cafeterias served beef patties
included in a nationwide recall of 2 million pounds of beef,
poultry and pork products processed at Zartic Inc.'s plant in
Cedartown.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale served 120 pounds of the suspect hamburgers and
cheeseburgers at lunch Monday; at 2 p.m. school officials learned
of the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite no reports of salmonella-related illness, whose symptoms
include diarrhea and fever, officials from both school systems are
upset that they weren't notified earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to call Zartic. They didn't call me,'' said Wendy
McNamee, Clayton's director of food nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   But Zartic isn't responsible for notifying schools, because it
doesn't deal with institutions that consume its products. Zartic
ships to distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Zartic spent Thursday identifying the affected product batches.
All day Friday, the eight fax machines in Zartic's corporate
offices hummed with detailed instructions to 300 distributors in 34
states. Zartic called its clients Monday morning to confirm
notification.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture is investigating the source
of the contamination. Zartic has indefinitely suspended operations
on the contaminated production lines.
</P>
<P>
   Burgers will return to Rockdale and Clayton's menus, but they'll
be from a different company, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Staff writers Leon Stafford and Delbert Ellerton
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
