<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-OIL-DUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL-DUMPING CHARGE FOR ROYAL CARIBBEAN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One month after Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd.
pleaded guilty to felony charges in the dumping of oil near Miami
and near San Juan, Puerto Rico, and agreed to pay $9 million in
fines and penalties, one of its ships dumped oil in July, federal
prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to present the information to a federal judge in San
Juan on Wednesday at a sentencing hearing for the San Juan
incident.
</P>
<P>
   In June, after Royal Caribbean Cruises pleaded guilty, the
company paid for advertisements in newspapers in Miami and San Juan
in which it said, in part, ``You also have our commitment that we
will do a better job in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the ships involved in the guilty pleas, the Nordic
Empress, dumped oil in exactly the same way in July, the company
told prosecutors that same month, after the guilty pleas. The July
dumping occurred at an unspecified location.
</P>
<P>
   And in the July incident, just as in the first two cases, from
1990 to 1994, which involved the Nordic Empress and the Sovereign
of the Seas, ships officers lied to investigators and falsified
records to hide their actions.
</P>
<P>
   A Royal Caribbean spokeswoman, Lynn Martenstein, said the best
the company could do was to ``provide the training and have the
systems in place to follow policy, and if they're not followed,
deal with them swiftly and decisively.'' And the two engineers
involved in the July dumping have been dismissed, Ms. Martenstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Royal, which also operates Celebrity Cruises from Miami, is the
world's second largest line, after Carnival Cruise Lines, also of
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
