</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKAMERICA-HEDGE-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKAMERICA EXPECTED TO ANNOUNCE HEDGE FUND LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BankAmerica Corp., the nation's fifth-largest bank, is expected
to announce a big hedge fund loss Wednesday in the latest example
of the dangers posed to financial companies from the risky,
sometimes high-flying investment pools.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts estimate that the loss may be about $100 million,
but others say that BankAmerica's overall exposure to the hedge
fund, D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., could be as large as $1 billion, taking the
form of either loans or credit lines. It is not clear whether
BankAmerica owned an interest in Shaw, and the legality of
commercial banks holding such stakes is murky.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica, which reports third-quarter earnings Wednesday,
declined to comment on its hedge-fund exposure generally or its
relationship with Shaw in particular. And a Shaw spokesman declined
to comment on its relationship with BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, BankAmerica, which recently disclosed large trading
losses in Russia, said it had pretax trading losses around $330
million so far in the third quarter and that it expected its
net-interest income in the quarter to be reduced by $65 million
primarily because of ``one borrower.'' Analysts and others close to
BankAmerica widely believe that borrower to be Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators, investors and members of Congress have become
increasingly concerned about hedge fund losses _ and commercial and
investment banks' involvement with the funds _ since the
near-collapse of a giant fund, Long-Term Capital Management, a few
weeks ago. Regulators contend that Long-Term Capital's brush with
disaster threatened to undermine broader financial systems.
</P>
<P>
   If more big banks are wounded by hedge funds and other lending
losses, there is a strong possibility that commercial and
investment banks will rein in lending and underwriting, thus
slowing American economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think BankAmerica has a credit exposure to D.E. Shaw that
could be substantial,'' said Judah Kraushaar, a banking analyst
with Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``Ultimately, if you have a liquidity
crunch, the Federal Reserve may have to take some dramatic action
to make sure that capital markets can continue to function
correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds are unregulated investment pools open only to
wealthy individuals and big institutional investors. The funds'
goal is to outperform market averages by trading stocks, bonds or
other assets, and to weather market downturns better than other
funds.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's hedge fund loss was first reported Tuesday in The
San Francisco Chronicle. In trading Tuesday on the New York Stock
Exchange, BankAmerica's shares rose $1.125, to $53.9375, well below
the 52-week high of $88.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw denies speculation that it is in serious financial trouble,
and Shaw is not a big bond investor, as was Long-Term Capital.
Also, analysts said Shaw was not carrying a huge amount of debt, as
Long-Term Capital did.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Shaw entity has been, or is now, in any form of trouble
financially,'' said Nick Gianakouros, Shaw's vice president. ``Any
reports that we are having financial problems are absolutely,
unequivocally untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, which manages about $1.7 billion in assets, declined to
answer questions about its performance. It has been reported that
the fund has lost 12.6 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's relationship with Shaw, a New York hedge fund that
uses complex, technical mathematical formulas primarily for stock
investments, was engineered in 1997 by David Coulter, BankAmerica's
former chief executive. Coulter will be serving as president of the
new BankAmerica, which was formed through its recent combination
with Nationsbank Corp. of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and others familiar with BankAmerica's operations said
the bank lent about $1 billion to a proprietary investment
portfolio managed by Shaw in exchange for 50 percent of the fund's
profits or losses. One bank adviser said that BankAmerica's
involvement with Shaw also included an equity stake. When Coulter
received a bonus of $4.25 million last year on top of a salary of
$987,500, BankAmerica cited the alliance with Shaw as one of the
reasons for the bonus, and Shaw employees were trotted out at an
analysts' conference that BankAmerica held last year.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' interests in relationships with hedge funds go beyond the
profits that can be gained from such investments. They also give
banks insight into the types of trades made by hedge funds _ which
until recently were considered among the savviest of investors _ in
financial markets. This vantage allows banks a first look at where
hedge funds are betting and enables them to use such information to
make similar trades if they seem desirable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the relationships are risky, as BankAmerica has discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We backed off of BankAmerica a few weeks ago because of
concern about the bank's hedge fund lending,'' said Michael Mayo,
an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``It looks like the old
BankAmerica is somewhat weaker than what was expected at the time
of the merger. We wouldn't be surprised to see Nationsbank curtail
some of the riskier activities of the old BankAmerica as it becomes
part of the merged company.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationsbank officials declined to comment on the hedge fund
losses or what impact they might have on Coulter's role in the
combined bank. Coulter, who is a trained mathematician, has been
designated as supervisor of risk-management practices at the new
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaw is a computer-model-technical-analysis-type approach to
investing,'' said Charles Peabody of Mitchell Securities in New
York. ``If the loss got that big, it might be because human common
sense said the loss could get bigger but the model said it was
OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
