<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-IDENTITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS ENGLAND LOST ITS IDENTITY? OR JUST ITS CLICHES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The English, past masters at turning the raised eyebrow
and the cold shoulder on others, are suddenly feeling looked down
upon and left out in their own land.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the three other regions that make up Britain _
Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland _ have been putting in place
new legislatures to deal with parochial affairs no longer
considered the preserve of the British Parliament in London. Some
in England, traditionally the ruling power in the kingdom, are now
thinking that maybe it should have one too.
</P>
<P>
   The country that created the world's lingua franca and was once
the seat of empire, England still accounts for 83 percent of the
British population and 85 percent of the economy, but its history
with the snub means it knows one when it sees one.
</P>
<P>
   The parceling out of authority to the remoter parts of the
United Kingdom has left English traditionalists, a dwindling
species themselves, anxious about a lot more than not having their
own local lawmakers with a taste for tartans and kilts. Steeped in
pastoral images that have little to do with their up-tempo
modern-day lives, some of them are turning the slight into a sulk
that looks more and more like an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Their frontier passions were stirred by Conservative leader
William Hague at the party's annual conference last week at
Bournemouth in Dorset, the county that inspired Thomas Hardy's
fictional Wessex, itself one of the enduringly mythical places for
the English. In his keynote address, Hague gave prominence to a
proposal to establish a separate assembly for England as one of the
steps that the Tories ought to consider to counter the dominance of
the governing Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   The new legislatures are being organized in Scotland, Wales and
Northern Ireland under Prime Minister Tony Blair's ``devolution''
project of setting up regional authorities for strictly local
matters while the British Parliament keeps its powers over broad
national policy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In the testy mood that their creation has provoked among people
who track English culture, slights don't go unnoticed. Editing
``The Oxford Book of English Short Stories,'' A.S. Byatt looked
through the index of a collection of essays on British culture and
reported that she found 55 page references to the Scots, 28 to the
Irish, 27 to the Welsh, 20 to Caribbean societies and only 3 to the
English. What's more, all three were derogatory.
</P>
<P>
   During almost three centuries of union, the Irish, the Scots and
the Welsh kept their distinct national personalities alive and have
a ready supply of symbols to light patriotic fires. The English, by
contrast, may have let their singular identity become extinguished
within Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Celtic fringe has myths, songs, food, dress and
verse that speak to a robust sense of nationhood. The English, in
need of talismans to raise the blood, find themselves stuck with
the same old stereotypes: stiff upper lip, tepid ale, cool heads,
cricket greens, tweed plus fours and the dead-fish handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Counseled to portray themselves as British instead of English,
the traditionalists are now caught up in flag-waving nationalism, a
sentiment that was long forbidden as insensitive, lacking in
decorum and, well, un-English.
</P>
<P>
   The keenest sense of nationalism the English feel is not to
their nation, but to their land, and not to the land they inhabit
today but to some Arcadian version of it. ``It is not the country
in which the English actually live,'' writes Jeremy Paxman in a new
book, ``but the place they imagine themselves living in. The
English have become exiles from their own country.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxman recalls in ``The English'' that his subjects once had a
sure sense of who they were. ``They were polite, unexcitable,
reserved and had hot water bottles instead of a sex life,'' he
writes. ``How they reproduced was one of the mysteries of the
Western world.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to define their country, Englishmen become anecdotal and
sentimental. Unable to settle on an absolute virtue, they end up
cataloging England's charms.
</P>
<P>
   John Betjeman's list included oil-lit churches, modest village
inns, arguments about cow parsley on the altar, and leaning on
gates and looking across fields.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, in a much lampooned broadcast for St. George's Day, the
English national day, Prime Minister John Major said that England
for him was ``long shadows on county grounds, warm beer, invincible
green suburbs, dog lovers and pools fillers and _ as George Orwell
said _ old maids cycling to Holy Communion through the morning
mist.''
</P>
<P>
   Products of an island culture and tempered by the Reformation,
the English have liked to think they stood for a belief in
individual liberty, respect for eccentricity, a bloody-minded
devotion to privacy and, above all, a sense of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for them, the best-known expression of English
nationalism these days is the behavior of its soccer fans, who are
notorious abroad for drunkenly rampaging through town centers,
tearing up stadiums and beating up opposing teams' fans.
Significantly, the war paint they cover their faces with no longer
form the Union Jack of Britain but the red and white cross of St.
George that stands for England.
</P>
<P>
   An Englishman today is just as apt to have a tattoo on his arms
and hardware on his face as a bowler hat on his head. The country's
most famous diplomats are not the ones at global conferences in
striped pants; they're the ones bounding onto stages in foreign
cities in platform heels and miniskirts.
</P>
<P>
   For all its reputation for snobbery and exclusiveness, however,
England has been the most welcoming part of Britain to immigrants
and has a more ethnically diverse culture than any of the other
parts of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle for the English soul has illuminated the letters
pages of The Sunday Times of London, with some writers offering new
lists of resonant symbols and others frowning on the whole
exercise. ``The whole point about being English is that we do not
care what anybody else thinks of us, `` argued Diane Markwell of
Devizes, in Wiltshire.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bradley of South Brent in Devon sought to have the last
word. ``Anyway, all this English navel-gazing is a metropolitan
media obsession,'' he wrote. ``Nobody down here has the slightest
doubt about who we are or even bothers to think about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
