<HEADER>
A5375 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVER-DONOR-LADN     10-13 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVER-DONOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDMOTHER'S LIVER OFFERS BABY GIRL HOPE FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BHAVNA MISTRY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While grandparents are known for spoiling their
grandchildren, the gift that Sherry Marquez gave her granddaughter
will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the 44-year-old grandmother donated a quarter of
her liver to her 6-month-old granddaughter, providing little Lydia
Hand a chance at a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt she had a part of me from the beginning,'' said
Marquez, a mother of two whose only grandchild is Lydia.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia, daughter of Scott and Nicole Hand of Lancaster, was born
with biliary atresia, a congenital condition in which the biliary
ducts fail to develop, leading to cirrhosis of the liver, growth
retardation and jaundice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to hear that we didn't have a healthy baby,'' said
Nicole Hand, 24. ``We're just thankful that doctors have been there
and God answered our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lethargic and jaundiced, the infant underwent an initial surgery
at age 2 months in an attempt to fabricate ducts. That didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recommended a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The liver of Lydia's father, a computer programmer for
Countrywide Homes in Simi Valley, was too big. Her mother's blood
type did not match.
</P>
<P>
   Marquez, a part-time secretary at Lancaster Baptist Church,
became the choice because of her excellent health and the size of
her liver. Marquez said she was happy to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to do it,'' Marquez said. ``I wanted to give her
anything she needed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 1, Marquez underwent surgery at the University of
Southern California to remove a 12 centimeter by 7 centimeter
section of her liver. The lobe was taken to Childrens Hospital Los
Angeles, where it was inserted into her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The liver transplant was the first in Southern California
between living relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a chair besides the youngster's crib Tuesday at
Childrens Hospital, Marquez played with her red-headed
granddaughter. The girl, with pudgy cheeks and large eyes, sat on
her grandmother's lap, smiling and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've seen Lydia like this,'' Marquez
said. ``She's never looked healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lydia's liver will grow as she does, she may have to take
anti-rejection medication for the rest of her life. She is expected
to be released from Childrens Hospital Los Angeles on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother's liver eventually will grow to replace the
piece it lost, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect fit,'' said Dr. Rick Selby of the University
of Southern California, who, with Dr. Daniel Thomas of Childrens
Hospital, oversaw the procedure. ``Her liver took to her almost
immediately. She will most likely live a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say one out of every 10,000 children is born with the
disease. Three-quarters of them undergo some sort of transplant.
</P>
<P>
   While currently the procedure is available only for infants,
doctors are working to be able to do the same for adults.
</P>
<P>
   As part of her future goals, Marquez is planning to go to the
Department of Motor Vehicles and officially sign up as an organ
donor. She already has entered her name on a list to be a bone
marrow donor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any chance I get I want to encourage others,'' Marquez said.
``Just a little bit of sacrifice could save someone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
