A5384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GAME6-NOTES-COX     10-13 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GAME6-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brown taking blame for debacle
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Letting manager Bruce Bochy off the hook for failing
to deliver a knockout punch in Game 5, Kevin Brown shouldered the
blame for the Padres' loss on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare baseball scene, two of the sport's best starters _
Brown and Greg Maddux _ were summoned from the bullpen to try to
save a game. Brown and the Padres were five outs from the World
Series when Michael Tucker, an unlikely hero, hit a sinker that
didn't sink and saved the Braves from elimination with a three-run
shot into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel particularly bad from the standpoint that people will
second-guess Boch for using me, but it was nobody's fault but my
own,'' Brown said after the game. ``I had the ball and didn't do
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown came on in the seventh and retired the side after Ozzie
Guillen singled. Then in the eighth, Ryan Klesko walked and Javy
Lopez singled past shortstop Chris Gomez. That brought Tucker to
the plate and led to the pitch Brown would love to have back.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you be in that situation and not be disappointed by
the results?'' Brown asked. ``If you're not disappointed, you don't
care about the game. I got through the first inning, but didn't
have the same location in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing much to say beyond that. My stuff was good,
but my location wasn't. The bottom line is that I walked the
leadoff hitter in that inning. If you're going to second-guess,
second-guess that.''
</P>
<P>
   Big deal
</P>
<P>
   In the Padres' media guide, there's a special note on ``The
Trade.'' You might think it has something to do with one of the
whoppers pulled off in the days when Jack McKeon ran the
organization, but it involves a 1994 deal by the current hierarchy
with the Houston Astros. In all, a dozen players changed teams,
including third baseman Ken Caminiti and center fielder Steve
Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley turned out to be a much better player than we ever
thought he was,'' general manager Kevin Towers said. ``Caminiti is
the one that stood out. But, really, it was two organizations
looking to shake things up. Similar organizations, similar
payrolls. It's been beneficial to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers credits the deft work of his scouting staff in keeping
the Padres competitive with the major-market, big-money franchises
like New York and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Tony Gwynn has 35 career hits against Maddux. But in
the ninth inning Monday night, with Gwynn at the plate representing
the winning run, Maddux induced him to hit a grounder to first base
to end the game. Gwynn is 0-for-3 against Maddux in the NLCS,
dropping his career mark against the Braves ace to .438.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   A throwing error by shortstop Chris Gomez in Game 5 put an end
to a Padres streak of eight-plus NLCS games without an error,
dating back to the 1984 postseason . . . Braves first baseman
Andres Galarraga, a former Gold Glove winner, has four errors in
five games _ the most ever in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
