<SLUG> BC-BBN-GAME6-PITCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres rest Brown, go with Hitchcock
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ San Diego will give ace Kevin Brown another day's rest
and go with Sterling Hitchcock today in Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander, who gave up three hits in five good innings to
win Game 3, will go against Braves left-hander Tom Glavine, who
last pitched in the Game 2 loss six days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock made it clear that he was ready to pitch his first
game of the season on three days rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me in last night's game that he wanted the ball for
tomorrow's game,'' pitching coach Dave Stewart said during a
workout Tuesday at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   And because Brown already had the ball in Game 5 in a rare
relief performance, the decision ``wasn't really that close,'' said
manager Bruce Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite as much as (Brown) throws in his bullpen,'' Bochy
said, ``if you go out there and you go all-out for 40-something
pitches, it's going to take a little bit more out of you. So we
just felt it was best to go this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Game 2 winner, entered the game with a 4-2 lead in
the seventh. He pitched 1 1/3 innings in the 7-6 loss Monday, with
Michael Tucker hitting a 3-run homer off the seemingly invincible
Padre in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy's decision to put in his ace has been second-guessed from
coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had my best guy out there,'' said Bochy. ``Hey,
things didn't work out. But it's not a case where I can't use him
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochy said Brown didn't campaign to start today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine,'' said the manager, who reached Brown by telephone
at his home in Macon. ``He does what he thinks is best for the
ballclub _ or what we think. And Sterling's set to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock threw only 93 pitches in Game 3, so the Padres coaches
feel he's fresh. Joey Hamilton, the Game 4 starter, would be
available in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that tomorrow's game could be a game that we can
clinch it,'' Stewart said of Hitchcock. ``I just don't want him to
get too anxious. Go out with a nice, even temperament and give us
an opportunity to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitch is going to have to come out and throw the ball like he
did in Game 3 for us to have a chance,'' said Tony Gwynn, who's
hoping to make his second World Series in a 17-year career. ``The
guys we're facing, they're not giving you much to take a good hack
at.''
</P>
<P>
   By saving Brown, and if the Padres win today, would he be ready
for Game 1 of the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even thinking about that,'' said Bochy. ``We're
concentrating on the Atlanta Braves right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
