<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves fans get back in the game
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the Braves ticket office opened at 8:30 a.m.
Tuesday, about 11,000 seats remained for Game 6 of the National
League Championship Series this afternoon against the San Diego
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   When the ticket windows closed at 6 p.m., virtually every seat
was sold.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's fans, roundly criticized for their lack of numbers and
noise in home Games 1 and 2, seem to have rediscovered pennant
fever. After two rousing victories in San Diego, the Braves trail
3-2 in the best-of-seven series. But they'll be back home before a
packed house at Turner Field this afternoon (4:1520 p.m. on Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Some fans lined up shortly after midnight to be sure to get
seats for today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold, but I wanted to get a jump on Ticketmaster,'' said
Deanna Fuller, along with her sister Tina, arrived at 12:30 a.m.
and sat through the rest of the chilly night.
</P>
<P>
   Between the stadium windows and Ticketmaster outlets, available
seats went quickly. Standing-room tickets will go on sale today at
8:30 a.m. at the stadium. They are $25 and can be purchased only
with cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``After watching the games and seeing how San Diego fans
responded to their team, it sparked a little fire under the fans
here,'' said Paul Adams, Braves director of ticket sales. ``I think
they realized we had the same level of fans here. They're going
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said a few thousand seats remain for a possible Game 7 on
Thursday night. If the series ends today with a Padres win, fans
with tickets for that game will receive a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
