<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 FTC Sets Deadline on Internet Privacy Rules   By Jamie Beckett and Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The Federal Trade Commission is giving the electronic commerce
industry until January to set voluntary guidelines for Internet
privacy before it pursues legislation in Congress, FTC Commissioner
Mozelle Thompson said yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   An FTC survey this year found that 89 percent of all Web sites
collect some form of private information from consumers, but only
14 percent disclose that they're doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web sites sell information they collect from visitors to
direct marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses currently have no legal incentive to disclose their
privacy policies _ including what information they collect and what
they do with it. The FTC cannot require Web sites to do so, but it
can go after those that post policies and then violate them.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he hopes Web sites will voluntarily post their
privacy policies because it's good for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies' economic future depends on making people feel good
on the Internet,'' he said in a meeting with Chronicle reporters.
``People are not going to buy on the Internet if they don't feel
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   A law requiring sites that collect information from children to
obtain parental permission is pending before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Thompson painted the agency as the defender of consumers. The
FTC's recent antitrust actions against proposed mergers of drug
wholesalers, for instance, was designed to make sure the industry
wasn't controlled by giants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A U.S. District Court judge sided with the FTC and blocked the
nation's four largest drug wholesalers, including San Francisco's
McKesson Corp., from merging into two companies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  When companies claim that a merger will allow them to
``achieve efficiencies,'' Thompson said, the FTC asks, ``But for
who? Are you going to make prices lower? Or give a bigger return to
shareholders?''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is pressing an antitrust suit against Santa Clara chip
giant Intel Corp., slated for trial in February. Thompson wouldn't
comment on that case. He also wouldn't discuss other FTC
investigations, or the Department of Justice's case against
Microsoft Corp., but he indicated that the FTC shows no signs of
letting up in its pursuit of antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any competitor wants to be in a dominant market position,''
Thompson said. ``It's a law of nature. ... But to the extent the
company's behavior has a negative effect on innovation or
competition, that presents a problem. ... And if you use strength
in one market sector to achieve dominance in another market sector,
then that's an antitrust problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2211EDT &QL; 
