<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel Beats Street, But Earnings Still Flat   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Citing a rebound in sales of personal computers, Intel reported
record revenue for the third quarter yesterday, along with profits
that beat Wall Street estimates.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Nevertheless, the earnings were flat from a year ago, and
Intel's stock dipped in after-market trading, suggesting that the
performance won't be a big help to other technology stocks today.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors may wait until Compaq Computer, another industry
bellwether, reports its earnings today to decide whether the PC
industry is healthy heading into the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released after the market closed, Santa Clara's
Intel said it earned $1.6 billion (89 cents a share), almost a
carbon copy of last year, when it made $1.6 billion (88 cents).
Analysts had been expecting Intel to earn just 80 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the three months ended September 26 were $6.7
billion, 9 percent higher than the $6.2 billion it had a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Income was flat largely because of the cost of parts Intel
must buy from outside sources to make its Pentium II chips.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, Intel shares Intel dipped to $82.50,
after closing the regular session at $83.56, down $1.88.
</P>
<P>
   Intel chief executive Craig Barrett expressed satisfaction with
the results, noting that the company enjoyed revenue growth nearly
everywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett also predicted a slight sales increase in the current
quarter. In recent quarters, the company has predicted flat sales
or just slight growth.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of Pentium processors set a record in the quarter, the
company said, noting that it now is barely able to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Intel introduced several new products,
including a high-end 450 MHz Pentium II for PCs, an improved
low-end Celeron and the new Xeon, a chip for powerful computer
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said its gross profit margins, which are the envy of the
industry, rose to 53 percent from 49 percent in the second quarter.
The increase resulted from a tilt toward sales of higher-priced
chips, as well as from efforts to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has reduced its head count by about 2,000
since the end of the first quarter, mostly through attrition and
buyouts. It said it's on track to eliminate 3,000 jobs by the end
of the year, out of a total workforce of 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The results were Intel's best in several quarters; its earnings
fell 29 percent in the second quarter. But some analysts predict
that the company may have a hard time sustaining sales in the face
of increasing competition and an uncertain world economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reported a good number at the high end of expectations,
but you're clearly not going to see that kind of pop again,'' said
Jonathan Joseph of NationsBank Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph credited some of Intel's growth to the actions of
PC-makers who stepped up purchases of chips in the quarter after
being forced to slash bloated inventories earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst David Wu said that barring a depression in Asia, Intel
may be out of the woods and back on a pattern of growth. But he
emphasized that 1998 is shaping up overall as a disappointing year
for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is on a pace to have sales of $25.9 billion this year, Wu
said, up slightly from last year's $25.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relative to expectations, today's numbers were quite good,''
he said. ``But relative to last year, it's not something you want
to write home about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
