<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Safeway to Buy Dominick's for $1.85 Billion   By Rebecca Smith  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Pleasanton's Safeway Inc. said yesterday it will buy Chicago's
Dominick's Supermarkets Inc. for $1.85 billion in cash and debt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The combined company will be second only to No. 1 Kroger Co. of
Cincinnati and will have 1,493 stores in 18 states and annual sales
exceeding $26.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the purchase of a Midwest chain may seem
irrelevant to California shoppers who've never stepped inside a
Dominick's store. But industry watchers believe the combination
will result in some ingenious practices migrating to Safeway stores
from Dominick's.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago supermarket chain has found ways to provide fresh,
not frozen, convenience foods capable of stemming the ``defection''
of grocery shoppers to take-out restaurants and fast-food
establishments, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago chain has made a name for itself as an innovator
that has converted half of its 112 locations into ``fresh stores''
with expanded perishables departments. Renovated stores have a
``European open market'' look that includes a bigger selection of
fruits and vegetables, including exotic and organic items not
typically stocked by rival supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Dominick's meat departments have more items already seasoned and
ready for the grill or oven. In-store ``cafes'' offer fresh-baked
pizza, hibachi chicken and other prepared meals that time-pressed
shoppers can take home and reheat for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safeway can learn a lot from Dominick's,'' said Laura
Richardson, retail analyst for Pacific Crest Securities in
Portland, Ore. ``One of the trends we're seeing in industry
consolidation is buyers learning from those they're acquiring,
typically strong companies with good names.''
</P>
<P>
   If Safeway decides to im &LR; l&AMP;5gd!+v7e Rm
</P>
