<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Caspian Sea: White House Presses Pipeline Plan
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House will try to persuade 15 American
oil companies to adopt its plan for building a pipeline from the
oil fields of the Caspian Sea through Turkey. National security
adviser Sandy Berger scheduled a discussion of the project with the
chief executives of the companies for Oct. 22. American officials
say they consider the issue open. Some administration officials,
congressional aides and oil executives said last week that the
companies were expected to recommend building the pipeline from
Baku in Azerbaijan to Supsa in Georgia. The United States wants the
pipeline extended through Turkey to a terminal at Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Campaign Funds Would Be Capped
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ A Parliamentary committee recommended a spending cap of
$34 million for each party in a national election, well below the
$91 million that the Conservative and Labor Parties together spent
last year. The long-awaited report also proposed public disclosure
of contributions that exceed $8,000 and called for tax deductions
on gifts up to $850 to spur small donations. The main
recommendations are extremely likely to become law next year. Lord
Neill, chairman of the committee, said the lack of spending limits
had given rise to ``something of an arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin Reported Recovering
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin will stay at his country house
until Friday to recover from bronchitis, the Kremlin said Tuesday.
The Russian press has speculated that the Kremlin is covering up
the seriousness of the president's illness. The Kremlin press
service said it would not issue regular assessments of Yeltsin's
health because he is merely suffering from a cold.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Leader From The East
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democratic Party said it would nominate Wolfgang
Thierse as president of the newly elected parliament. That would
make him the first politician from eastern Germany to head the
parliament since Germany was reunified in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   KENYA: Corruption Crackdown Set as Condition for IMF Talks
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund said it was prepared to reopen
talks with Kenya over a suspended $250 million aid package if the
country took a stronger stand against corruption. Kenya has been
hobbled by pervasive corruption, and that has kept away investors
and caused the United States and other countries to limit
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Proposal For 2-Round Election
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The president of the National Action Party
proposed that electoral laws be amended to allow for a two-round
presidential election in 2000. The leader, Felipe Calderon, said
that by reducing the field to two leading candidates in the first
round, the winner of a second round would be president with the
backing of a majority of voters. President Ernesto Zedillo's
governing party, the PRI, has opposed two-round balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador: Indians Win Round Against Texaco
</P>
<P>
   Indians from the Oriente rainforest have won another chance to
pursue a $1 billion suit against Texaco. The Indians say the oil
company polluted the forest and rivers during two decades of
pumping oil in Ecuador. The U.S 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals in New
York reversed a dismissal of the case last year, sending it back
the District Court for review. Representing 30,000 residents of the
forest, the suit asks Texaco to pay for health and environmental
damage, cleanup and rebuilding its equipment to meet U.S.
standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
