<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABUSE-JUDGE-COX     10-13 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-JUDGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge McCown is making his mark in public service
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Scott McCown has left his legal imprint on
solutions to some of the most vexing social problems faced by Texas
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   First it was the prison system. Next, institutions for people
with mental retardation. Then the funding of public school
districts in Texas. Now, it's abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   He was pulled to the bull's eye of history by a legal mind
nurtured by his U.S. attorney father and a heart that took him to
the doorstep of the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into the Candler School of Theology at (Atlanta's) Emory
and I got into the School of Law at the University of Texas,'' he
said. ``I got the acceptance letters in the same week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the devil won.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown, that rare 43-year-old who still has a round baby face,
speaks softly but carries a big personal measuring stick. He uses
it to gauge what he believes is a key moral standard: ``How you
take care of people.'' This fifth-generation Texanwants Texas to
provide a standard of care high enough to meet his values.
</P>
<P>
   McCown seems to never let up. He is an overachiever who finished
college in three years and doesn't mind fortifying himself with
Diet Coke until 2 a.m. to write plans for reshaping Texas. He
teaches Sunday school at his Methodist church and is raising a son
and daughter with his wife Maura Powers, an assistant attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, McCown was an assistant Texas attorney general
who was put in charge of the long-running federal lawsuit
challenging conditions in state prisons. He helped fashion a
settlement agreement to reduce crowding and improve medical care
and other services for inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, McCown was one of the assistant attorneys general who
tried to guide the Texas Department of Mental Health and Mental
Retardation through a bitter class-action lawsuit that exposed
shortcomings in state institutions. In one hearing, no-nonsense
U.S. District Court Judge Barefoot Sanders of Dallas challenged
many of McCown's arguments on behalf of the state, but McCown never
lost his composure.
</P>
<P>
   The very next year, McCown had more in common with Sanders than
the state officials he once defended. McCown became a state
district judge, winning his first try for a seat on the bench in
Travis County.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he was presiding over the controversial public school
finance case that threatened to halt state aid to all 1,058 school
districts in Texas. McCown pushed the Legislature to devise a
system for equalizing funding between rich and poor public school
districts. For five years, McCown presided over the case, which
prompted the Legislature to pass a law requiring the wealthiest
Texas school districts to share some local property tax revenue
with the poorest districts.
</P>
<P>
   Behind all the hearings and headlines about school funding,
McCown quietly became an expert on a part of law he never even
studied in law school: family law, and the care and guardianship of
abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   With record numbers of child abuse cases flooding the docket in
Travis County, McCown and fellow state district Judge Jeanne Meurer
volunteered in 1992 to split all the cases in which a judge must
determine whether abused children stay with their families or go
into foster care. Now, McCown spends every Friday doing nothing but
these Child Protective Services cases.
</P>
<P>
   McCown estimates he has presided over 1,400 cases involving
2,500 children who were abused or neglected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you asked me what's the most important thing you do, this
is it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He even bought a home computer to research and write the
graduate school thesis-like report for his new one-man crusade on
behalf of overlooked children.
</P>
<P>
   This unprecedented report once again propels McCown to the
forefront of a Texas crisis. ``What I couldn't live with myself on
is not having spoken up,'' he said. ``It wasn't somebody else's
responsibility. It was as much my responsibility as anybody
else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
