<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-MACKAY-DEBATE-CO     10-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MACKAY-DEBATE-COXA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacKay cites cash stash in debate with Bush
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley and Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Talking about suitcases filled with cash and a
felon who fled with $200 million, Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay took every
opportunity Tuesday during his second statewide debate with Jeb
Bush to say that Bush's business background is at best
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   After the debate MacKay admitted that he does not have specific
information that Bush has done anything improper but he insists
that Bush is not telling everything he knows about his business
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapid response, Bush's press secretary was passing out
rebuttal information to reporters while the debate was still under
way. During the debate, Bush rebuked MacKay for what he said were
unfounded charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this what it's gotten down to?'' Bush asked as his
supporters jeered MacKay. ``Is this what it's gotten down to? Gross
distortions? Gross distortions of facts that have already been
written about by every major newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong radio debate was broadcast by the Florida Radio
Network from a stage at the Disney Institute and aired live by 33
stations. The audience was overwhelmingly pro-Bush, and several
quietly held small Jeb! bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were asked by a panel of journalists and audience
members chosen at random.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who won the coin toss and chose to speak after Bush,
went on the offensive almost immediately, rattling off the names of
Bush's former business partners and the various deals that MacKay
hopes will become the focal point of the race's final three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been involved in a school board, he's never been
involved in a city or county commission. He says: Look at my
business record. And I say, yes, look at his business record. It's
very different from what he portrays,'' MacKay said. ``His business
record is one of questionable deals, it is one of mismanagement.
And I think people really ought to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay also tried to make the most of Bush's career as a Miami
land developer, and asked voters whether they really wanted to
trust Florida's fragile environment with such a man.
</P>
<P>
   Bush countered that he had no problem letting voters rate him
based on his two decades in private business. ``The fact that I
would be a developer all of a sudden has an evil connotation,''
Bush said. ``I'm quite proud of the fact that our business, which
started with two people in 1980, has grown to have 200 employees,
200 families that are involved in activities that are providing
quality growth that pays for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush in his answers tried to push the debate toward the themes
he has worked on all summer, including education, prevention of
drug abuse _ ``The drug problem is a quiet poison in our
community'' _ law enforcement and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   As in the previous debate, Bush touted his plan to test each
public school, rewarding those that excel or improve while
``holding accountable'' those that don't. And, as he has for the
past several weeks, he tried to downplay his support of vouchers _
or scholarships, as he prefers to call them _ as only a last resort
for a limited number of poor children stuck in chronically bad
schools.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time before a large audience, though, Bush did
allow that he would indeed consider expanding vouchers to more
students. ``If it works, and there is broad consensus that we could
build on that, I would consider it, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, though, MacKay would return to Bush's business
dealings, calling for thorough explanations. On a question about
HMOs, MacKay veered off onto the topic of Miguel Recarey, a felon
who stole $200 million from Medicare and fled to Spain. Bush, with
his father in Washington, called a federal agency on Recarey's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he did not know of Recarey's criminal history, nor
did he help the man commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay also questioned Bush's role with Jacksonville-based
Ideon, a credit card services company that went belly-up when Bush
was on the board of directors. Bush has said he didn't know the
company was in so much trouble when he took the position.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay's most aggressive attack, though, came on a partnership
Bush entered with a Deerfield Beach man, David Eller, whose company
was trying to sell water pumps to Nigeria. MacKay asked Bush to
explain why the pilot of one of the planes that once flew Bush to
Africa told The Miami Herald that he saw suitcases full of cash
taken there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot said there were five suitcases, they were heavy, one
of them opened and it was full of cash. Don't you think that Jeb
ought to give an answer for that?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday did have an answer: It's all hogwash. ``I mean
this thing about money, suitcases, planes . . . I mean, come on.
This stuff's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and MacKay meet at 7 p.m. Tuesday for their final statewide
television debate before the November election. The debate will be
broadcast on NBC stations throughout Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley and Shirish Date write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
