<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-ABUSE-REPORT-CO     10-13 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-ABUSE-REPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge sends out report on Texas' child protection system
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The world never knew Nakia Cole, a 6-week-old
boy who bled to death last year in an Austin house so squalid that
cockroaches had taken over the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nakia lived just a mile from the Capitol with eight other
children, one of whom was his teen-age mother. He died in a crib
after his infected lungs hemorrhaged, possibly from a virus from
the feces of rats that overran the dilapidated house.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny boy died in obscurity just two weeks before Austin was
shocked by the Oct. 14 discovery of 9-year-old Victoria Barr, who
lived liked a prisoner in a rat-infested house in the trendy
Clarksville neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Nakia and Victoria still brings tears to the
eyes of Travis County state District Judge Scott McCown, who
oversees the placement of abused and neglected children into safe
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem has grown and grown and grown, and Child
Protective Services' performance is the worst in a decade,'' McCown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McCown has turned his outrage into a manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   Using a citizen's grievance procedure outlined in the Texas
Constitution, McCown today is delivering an unusual petition to
Gov. George W. Bush and the Legislature. In it, he details with
charts and graphs a child welfare system buckling under a crushing
workload and calls for more state resources to ease the strain. Jim
Hine, executive director of the Texas Department of Protective and
Regulatory Services, says he has no argument with the findings or
the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   McCown recommends that two cents of every dollar from the
state's anticipated multibillion-dollar surplus be earmarked for
abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the judge's report arrived, a spokeswoman for the
governor said that if Bush wins re-election, he will seek more
money from the next Legislature for Child Protective Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush agrees with Judge McCown that we need to do more,''
said his spokeswoman Linda Edwards. McCown estimates his two-penny
formula would put an additional $200 million into the Department of
Protective and Regulatory Services, which runs Child Protective
Services, and several other agencies with programs for abused and
neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are too few investigators and too many cases,'' he said.
``That results in cases that need to be investigated not getting
investigated, cases that are investigated being inadequately
investigated, and children who need help not getting help.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown has devoted countless hours over the past year
researching and writing an unprecedented document he titled: ``A
Petition in Behalf of the Forsaken Children of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every citizen has the right to petition their governor and
their Legislature for the redress of their grievances,'' McCown
said. ``If a kid dies because we know the system is overwhelmed and
we don't have enough people on the job and we know that, then that
is my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 42-page report, McCown points out that the number of
abuse and neglect investigations is at a five-year low and that the
per capita investigation rate is at an eight-year low.
</P>
<P>
   McCown also notes that Texas falls far below the national
average in handling child abuse cases. Texas child abuse
investigators carry an average of 27 cases each while the Child
Welfare League of America recommends a caseload of 12 cases per
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case for action is overwhelming,'' he writes. ``Since
1985, the state's investigations of child abuse and neglect have
deteriorated in both number and quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the population of children in Texas has increased 16
percent from 1985-98, to more than 5.5 million, the number of
children found to be abused or neglected fell 28 percent in that
same period, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decline is not attributable to better lives for children
in 1998 as compared to 1985; instead, the decline is attributable
to less resources for investigations by the Child Protective
Service,'' McCown writes.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders have estimated that Texas may have a budget
surplus of $3 billion to $6 billion in the 2000-2001budget period.
McCown said his state government sources say the budget surplus
will be closer to $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Other constituencies already are lining up to try to get part of
the windfall.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, Democratic
Rep. Rob Junell of San Angelo, said lawmakers will have to weigh
all needs along with the shortcomings in the child protection
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably we need to put some money into it,'' he said. But,
``We'll consider it as we do all other requests for funding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could make a case that higher education is
underfunded, that health and human services is underfunded, that
public education is underfunded, that the Department of Public
Safety is underfunded,'' he said. ``Highways. They're saying they
are underfunded. It's a question of taking resources and
distributing them in a reasonable manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998-99, Child Protective Services is operating with $990
million, more than half of which pays for residential services such
as foster care. The agency has requested a two-year budget of
$1.067 billion, again with most of it to pay for residential care.
</P>
<P>
   But Hine, the protective and regulatory services director, said
the budget increase would not be enough to reduce caseloads.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you triple the number of kids in care, what (McCown) is
saying is that the percentage of time that our staff spends on kids
in care has had to increase, and as a result, something has had to
suffer. His conclusion is that investigations are what suffered,''
Hine said. ``I think he's made a correct analysis of that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown's report shows that in 1985, the state had 2,252 workers
to help 8,806 children, of whom 5,226 were in foster care. By 1997,
the state had 4,437 workers to care for 23,595 children, with
17,485 of them in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state received no reports of neglect in Nakia's
case, records cited by McCown show that Child Protective Service
workers received 10 reports about neglect of children in the East
Austin home in the three years before he was born, one six months
before his birth.
</P>
<P>
   Hine acknowledged that children will slip through the cracks as
long as workers remain overloaded. But he said a death like Nakia's
is ``the exception rather than the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to tell you that with over 100,000 investigations a
year, we're going to have cases where that happens,'' Hine said.
``I don't like it. I think it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, you have workers who are overloaded with
investigation caseloads. And when you have that happen, there's an
occasional problem that occurs and it's unfortunate that in this
business, when it happens it can have really tragic results.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of report Findings
</P>
<P>
   Texas investigated only 60 percent of child abuse and neglect
allegations in 1997-98, the lowest rate in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Staff per 1,000 children in state custody has declined 24
percent since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Average caseload for Texas child abuse investigator _ 27.
Average caseload recommended by Child Welfare League of America _
12.
</P>
<P>
   Number of investigations that confirm abuse or neglect has
dropped from 56 percent to 28 percent since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranked 30th among 35 states reporting data on removing
children from abusive or neglectful homes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   1997 survey found one in four Texans witnessed an incident of
child abuse or neglect in past year.
</P>
<P>
   1.8 children per every 1,000 Texas children were in state
custody in 1985. In 1997, 4.3 children for every 1,000 children
were in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Earmark 2 cents of every dollar in the Texas budget surplus
for abused and neglected children. With federal matching funds,
this could add $200 million to child protective services.
</P>
<P>
   _ First, increase money for prevention. Second, more money for
early intervention. Then, add to budget for finding permanent homes
for abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   Visit www.austin360.com/news/newstop.htm to see the full report.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Gamino writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
