<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-RULING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge overturns previous ruling, says plan is legal
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The state's $763 million plan for cleaning up the
Everglades is legal, a federal judge ruled Tuesday _ weeks after
another judge decided the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler said he won't
necessarily give water managers until the end of 2006 to finish the
cleanup, as the state plan allows.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the sugar industry's pleas that he dismiss a
decade-old Everglades pollution lawsuit, Hoeveler said he intends
to watch over the cleanup as long as he must.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler also issued what some lawyers interpreted as a veiled
warning to state lawmakers against meddling in the cleanup. He said
he was ``mindful'' of two bills that Gov. Lawton Chiles vetoed last
spring after environmentalists claimed they would send restoration
costs soaring.
</P>
<P>
   The judge delayed deciding some of the most crucial questions
facing the cleanup, however. Among them: Is the Everglades really
suffering irreversible damage from sugar farm pollution, as
government scientists say? Or, is the pollution already declining,
as growers' researchers argue?
</P>
<P>
   The judge promised to schedule a hearing within a month to
consider that question. The hearing also would deal with the
proposed 2006 deadline and could address suggestions that he
appoint a federal overseer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no real surprise here,'' said Barbara Markham,
general counsel for the South Florida Water Management District,
the agency in charge of the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists said they were elated. They said the judge
showed skepticism about the need for later cleanup deadlines, and
about the trustworthiness of state lawmakers to oversee the cleanup
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good day for the Everglades,'' said Peter Antonacci, an
attorney for the Florida Audubon Society. ``He's not going to let
go of this case while the Florida legislature is hovering around
with great potential for mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler's rulings came a month after Chief U.S. District Judge
Edward Davis declared that the state's plan violated the federal
Clean Water Act by weakening anti-pollution rules. Davis didn't
overturn the state law but ordered federal regulators to scrutinize
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler upheld the same cleanup plan using a different
yardstick: the clause in the U.S. Constitution that prohibits
states from interfering with contracts. The Miccosukee Indian tribe
had argued that the plan clashes with an earlier promise by the
state to finish the cleanup in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler acknowledged the conflict between the rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That presents a problem, doesn't it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither judge is bound by the other's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler's ruling kept alive a 1988 lawsuit in which the federal
government accused the state of funneling polluted farm water into
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The suit prompted the state to enact a cleanup law in 1994. The
feds later asked Hoeveler to accept the law and its 2006 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Hoeveler also issued what he called a ``note of
warning'': He said future actions by state lawmakers could prove
illegal if they delay the cleanup, changing the leadership of the
project or ``unnecessarily increasing the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Chiles vetoed two bills that environmentalists
claimed would force the state to pay more money for sugar farmland
needed for the cleanup, while allowing lawmakers to interfere with
federal restoration plans. Industry lobbyists said the measures
would protect small landowners and ensure the state a share in
crucial decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup plan is separate from a $7.8 billion federal
Everglades restoration proposal that Vice President Al Gore
unveiled Tuesday in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   That federal proposal is aimed at restoring natural flows to the
Everglades and ensuring South Florida's supply of drinking water by
the year 2050. It assumes that the state cleanup will have removed
the pollution by then.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
