<SLUG> BC-GORE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore arrives in South Florida ready to raise funds
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore began his daylong trip
to South Florida Tuesday by downing a shot of vodka at a
conservative synagogue, then walking to a $5,000 a plate luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel less stiff already,'' Gore joked to about 150 members
at Temple Emanu-El. ``I've never been to a religious ceremony quite
like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, accompanied by Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Boca Raton and New
Jersey Sen. Robert Torricelli, arrived in West Palm Beach about
10:40 a.m. for a day of Democratic money-raising events that
included lunch at the Palm Beach penthouse of S. Daniel Abraham,
founder of Slim-Fast Foods Co., followed by a reception and dinner
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, the vice president unveiled a $7.8 billion draft
plan to restore the Everglades by rebuilding South Florida water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   While the plan received the biggest applause _ about 50
environmentalists gathered on the tarmac at Palm Beach
International Airport _ Gore spent most of his day hobnobbing with
Democratic elite at the luncheon. A block-long motorcade carried
the vice president on a route through downtown West Palm Beach,
drawing the attention of office workers and stopping traffic for
blocks, to the synagogue where members began celebrating Simchat
Torah at sundown Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous affair, which involves the imbibing of much
vodka, marks the day when Moses delivered the torah to the Jewish
people.
</P>
<P>
   Leonid Feldman, the popular rabbi who became the first Russian
Jew in America ordained in a conservative synagogue, welcomed the
vice president with a shot of kosher vodka, followed by a bite of
pickle and pumpernickel bread.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning the Monika Lewisky scandal, Feldman praised
Gore for standing by the president in troubling times. Gore, in
turn, praised the Jewish people for supporting his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirit of Israel is eternal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the temple, Gore and his entourage walked a block with
Abraham _ who said he does not drive on the holiday _ to the Palm
Beach Biltmore.
</P>
<P>
   At the eighth-floor penthouse, where the floors are lined with
marble and walls with murals and stretched silk, a trio playing the
harp, cello and violin welcomed Gore (and even played the theme
from Titanic at one point). Fifty supporters seated around five
tables in a room overlooking Palm Beach and the Atlantic, just past
the home's ``north'' gym, mingled with the vice president during a
lunch of whitefish caviar, seared salmon and sorbet with biscotti.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Koch, wife of Palm Beach millionaire Bill Koch, sat to
Gore's left while Monte Friedkin, a generous contributor to the
party, sat to his right.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the lunch were Friedkin's wife, Skeets, Bill Koch,
attorney Mitchell Berger, Rep. Wexler, Torricelli, former U.S. Rep.
Wayne Owens, D-Utah and Rep. Elaine Bloom, D-Miami Beach. Abraham
began a string of introductions, that included Democratic party
chairman Steve Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke on four issues: education, Social Security, HMO
reform and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Gore mentioned crowding that forced some schools to served lunch
as early as 9:30 a.m., drawing gasps from the group.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also slammed Republicans for bringing on the budget impasse
by ``entrenching themselves and working very hard to go back to old
retro-nomics.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore ended by urging the group to support gubernatorial
candidate Buddy MacKay, who spent the morning in Orlando debating
opponent Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay joined Gore back at the airport where the vice president
unveiled the plan and praised environmentalists who helped draft
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a century ago, President Truman dedicated Everglades
National Park with words you know: For all people, for all time,''
he said. ``Today, we remain dedicated to exactly that vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He then boarded Air Force II for Miami where he planned to stop
at an elementary school and retirement home before attending the
reception and dinner, an aid said. He was scheduled to leave for
Washington at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
