u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SER-CONTRACTORS-COX     10-13 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SER-CONTRACTORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Union leaders blast privatization amid job program claims
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Critics of the state's attempt to farm out some of its
duties to contractors such as SER Jobs for Progress Inc. are
renewing calls against privatization following disclosure of SER's
alleged problems as manager of jobs training centers for the
unemployed in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Tuesday's American-Statesman detailed former SER
employees' claims that they were told to falsify records to make
the agency look better as it sought continued funding. The story
pointed out that state and federal investigators are examining the
employees' claims.
</P>
<P>
   SER, a private, nonprofit company, was chosen to manage the
state's two Capital of Texas Workforce Centers in Austin beginning
in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SER officials have denied that they had anything to do with the
falsified records. They said disgruntled employees made the
falsifications to make the company look bad because the employees
were laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Texas AFL-CIO President Joe Gunn issued a
statement that said SER's problems are ``proof that private
companies with conflicting allegiances are unequipped to manage
programs that invoke the public trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Texas State Employees Union, a member of the
AFL-CIO that stands to lose members under privatization, seized
upon SER's problems to complain about state functions being
contracted out to private companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got organizations that aren't accountable to the
taxpayers using taxpayer money, they have every incentive to cut
corners and mislead us,'' said Ted Melina Raab, legislative
director of the state employees union.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Workforce Commission, which helped oversee the
privatization of the Austin job centers and similar centers
statewide, defended the move.
</P>
<P>
   Raab's comments ``sound an awful lot like sour grapes,'' said
David Beshear, spokesman for the commission. Beshear said the
contract with SER wasn't really privatization because SER is a
nonprofit company.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization, Beshear said, ``puts decision-making ability
closer to the people and more accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Golz writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
