A5451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALLAS-COWBOYS14-COX     10-13 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-COWBOYS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys give Jones happy birthday, season
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones was beaming so
proudly Tuesday, he looked like he had just won an Ed McMahon
sweepstakes contest.
</P>
<P>
   Over a plate of fried chicken, green beans and mashed potatoes,
Jones spoke about the quick getaway his Cowboys have had. The team
with a 4-2 record and a soft schedule has given its owner reason to
be satisfied with this football season.
</P>
<P>
   On his 56th birthday, Jones had plenty to be thankful for.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the changes we've made around here, it was important
to gain a measure of confidence,'' Jones said. ``Six games into the
season, I don't know if I've ever felt better about our future.
We've got a long way to go, but I don't know how you could ask for
a better birthday present.''
</P>
<P>
   These are happy days in Valley Ranch. Less than a year after the
Cowboys sank to a 6-10 record and released Coach Barry Switzer,
Jones is talking about the playoffs again. And why not? The leaders
of the NFC East are 3-0 against division opponents and show no
signs of falling apart for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only am I excited about this year, I'm excited about what
we have the chance to accomplish over the next several years,''
said Jones, in his 10th season as owner of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The owner's optimism stems from the NFL's most improved offense.
The Cowboys, 20th in the league in offense last season, have bolted
to No. 4 this year. Even more surprising is the emergence of Emmitt
Smith, the leading rusher in the NFC with 529 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers felt Smith was washed up after last season. The
29-year-old running back can thank the big blockers in front of him
for his turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we've ended up singing the blues around here is when we
haven't been able to move the football,'' Jones said. ``Every time
we've had success moving the football, we've gone on to win Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are much better on the offensive line this year. In my
mind, our offensive line is as responsible for our 4-2 record as
anything else. That's where we had the most glaring problems
heading into the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones cited three other factors for the team's early success:
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Daryl Johnston has overcome a neck injury and provided
solid blocking for Smith and Chris Warren. Last year Johnston
missed the final 10 games, one reason the Cowboys lost their last
six.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Jason Garrett has filled in nicely at quarterback during
Troy Aikman's four-game absence. The Cowboys are averaging 25
points and 346 yards per game with Garrett as the starter. The Ivy
Leaguer is expected to sign a new contract to remain in Dallas
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   The players have responded favorably to first-year coach Chan
Gailey's innovative offense. The Cowboys rank fifth in the league
in rushing offense and 10th in passing offense, and have yielded
only seven sacks in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of factors for the offensive success,''
Gailey said. ``It has a lot to do with the continuity of the
offensive line. (Tight end) David LaFleur is a very strong blocker.
(Johnston) is healthy. And Emmitt's healthier than he has been. The
combination of all those factors creates the opportunity for this
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing sweeter than the birthday cake Jones shared with
friends is the team's upcoming schedule. The final 10 opponents on
the Cowboy schedule are a combined 23-35. That includes games
against 1-5 Chicago, 1-5 Philadelphia and 0-6 Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has been so busy preparing the Cowboys for Sunday's game
against the Bears that he forgot one minor detail Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he bought Jones for his birthday, the new coach
said he was unaware his boss turned 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to go out and get a card,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES _ Wide receiver Billy Davis (sprained foot) is not
expected to play Sunday. Ernie Mills will take his spot, and Jeff
Ogden likely will be activated as a backup receiver. . . . Jones
said Nate Newton has played so well on the offensive line that he
will be asked to return next year. . . . In the 1990s, the Cowboys
are 26-8 in games played in October.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
