NYT-10-13-98 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADE-PLAN-COX     10-13 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADE-PLAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed plan to save Everglades unveiled
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore unveiled a $7.8
billion plan by Tuesday to restore the Everglades while providing
freshwater to farms and South Florida's 6 million residents.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of fund-raising, Gore, flanked by Lt. Gov. Buddy
MacKay at Palm Beach International Airport, hailed ``the next
crucial step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a century ago President Truman dedicated Everglades
National Park with words you know: For all the people, for all
time. Today we remain dedicated to exactly that vision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,500-page plan, spearheaded by the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers, outlines projects necessary to provide South Florida
with flood protection, preserve its water supply and restore the
Everglades delicate ecosystem, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   It includes 60 projects and will undergo 11 public hearings in
South Florida through November and December. A final version will
be sent to Congress for approval in July. If approved, the federal
government would split the bill over 20 years with state and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore first announced the plan in 1996, he said it would
include buying land crucial to the restoration, speeding up
research and increasing money.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's detailed draft explains how a network of levees and
canals created in 1948 over 18,000 square miles need to be
improved. The system was designed to provide water to 2 million,
not today's population of 6 million. The number is expected to rise
to 8 million over the next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're starting to see people thinking of the consequences of
not doing the (plan),'' said Frank ``Sonny'' Williamson, chairman
of the South Florida Water Management District board. ``If we get
in the water wars of Tampa Bay, a generation will lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan can be reviewed via the Internet at www.restudy.org, at
county libraries or by CD-Rom. For more information, call
(904)232-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
