<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drunk driving arrest could mean jailtime for Mack
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Bengals safety Tremain Mack faces possible jail
time and suspension by the NFL after his second drunken driving
arrest in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, 23, was arrested Tuesday after police found him asleep at
the wheel of his car in the right lane of northbound I-75 near
downtown Cincinnati at 4:44 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, Mack failed a field sobriety
test and then pushed the arresting officer, who subdued him with
the help of a chemical spray.
</P>
<P>
   The report said officer Ryan Jones found Mack passed out at the
wheel of a 1992 Pontiac Grand Prix with the keys in the ignition.
Mack smelled of alcohol and failed a sobriety test, then resisted
when he was arrested, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Mack allegedly pushed the officer, who sprayed him with mace.
When Mack pushed Jones again, the officer punched him in the
stomach three times and got him into the police car, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mack faces a sentence of up to six months in jail and a $1,000
fine if convicted of drunken driving. The resisting arrest charge
carries a maximum 90-day jail term and $750 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Mack was charged with drunken driving, resisting arrest and
driving without a license. He was released from the Hamilton County
Justice Center on $6,000 bond. Arraignment is at 9 a.m. today in
Hamilton County Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Mack _ a former University of Miami (Fla) star who had been
arrested six times in a four-year span before the Bengals picked
him in the fourth round of the 1997 draft _ was still on probation
from a drunken driving conviction after his October 26, 1997 arrest
in Clermont County.
</P>
<P>
   He could be ordered to serve up to 330 days in jail _ the
suspended part of his previous sentence _ if he is convicted on the
latest charges.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said the league will investigate Mack.
He could be fined and suspended for four games under a substance
abuse policy set forth by the league and NFL Players Association in
the collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A first offense is usually a fine _ half a game check up to a
maximum of $20,000,'' Aiello said. ``Repeat violations would lead
to increased discipline and possible suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   A four-game suspension would cost Mack $38,588 _ four pay checks
from his 1998 salary of $164,000. He's in the second year of a
three-year, $710,000 contract.
</P>
<P>
   Mack remains on the Bengals' 53-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mack's situation falls under the jurisdiction of the NFL's
alcohol policy,'' Bengals president Mike Brown said. ``Announcement
of any football-related discipline in this case will be made by the
league office. It would be improper for the club to comment further
until it becomes known what actions local courts and the NFL will
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack couldn't be reached for comment. His agent, Marc R.
Pollack, said: ``It's a tough situation. It's obviously very tough
for Tremain and it's tough for us. We hope it all works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Following his arrest last year, Mack entered an NFL-approved
treatment center and was activated for the last month of the
season, but did not play.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals' top kickoff returner this year, Mack had a 97-yard
touchdown at Baltimore on Sept. 27. The players were off on Monday
and Tuesday after a 25-20 victory over the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
