<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bochy calls Braves' bluff; Cox responds in kind
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was the right call.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a total failure, like the Edsel; like Ed
Asner in shorts and a tank top; like Roseanne singing the National
Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Bochy had to do it.
</P>
<P>
   When the San Diego manager brought on Kevin Brown, his best
starting pitcher, in relief Monday night against Atlanta, the
risk/reward ratio was as clear as the aquarium at Sea World.
</P>
<P>
   Risk: If Brown failed to hold the 4-2 lead, it would not only
remove his aura of invincibility, it would also wreck the Padres'
pitching plans for the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Reward: If Brown held, there would be no rest of the series.
There would be fireworks in the sky, and Qualcomm Stadium would
turn into Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the second game of makeup doubleheader in August.
This was Game 5 of the National League Championship Series, the
Padres were nine outs away from winning it, and all Bochy needed
were six of those nine outs from Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Then he had Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Although the second-guessing in San Diego is rampant, Bochy
should ignore it.The door was ajar, Atlanta had its fingers in the
door; you slam the door.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, Bochy tried to slam the door, and his house fell
down.
</P>
<P>
   I've never understood why Michael Tucker hasn't made it big.
</P>
<P>
   He was Kansas City's No. 1 prospect with a sweet, quick
left-handed swing that promised more than it ever delivered. It
took the Royals portions of just two seasons to give up on him.
</P>
<P>
   So here he was Monday night after a lousy season facing Brown in
with two on and one out in the eighth in what well could have been
his last at-bat in a Braves' uniform.
</P>
<P>
   If he made an out, and Brown and Hoffman finished the job,
there's a good chance he'd be somewhere else in 1999 because
.244-hitting right fielders generally don't hang around one team
very long, plus the Braves have a kid, George Lombard, whom they
think might be the next Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the beauty of baseball. A guy hitting .194 (6 for
31) over the past two postseasons was matched against a guy who had
given up one earned run in 23 postseason innings over the last two
weeks, and the guy hitting .194 jacked one 380 feet into the first
row in right field between a couple of palm trees.
</P>
<P>
   Logically that couldn't happen. It was as if John Starks beat
Michael Jordan in a game of one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta held on to win 7-6 in a game so marvelous that, like
Game 6 of the 1975 World Series (Carlton Fisk's 12-inning home run
beat the Reds), even the losers were gushing later.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Padres' Wally Joyner: ``That might have been the
best game I ever played in. It was like a chess match with live
people. When you go back and start looking for one play you find
about 20 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley called it ``unbelievably exciting'' and Tony Gwynn
called it ``exciting theater,'' a game that ended with the best
starting pitcher of the '90s, Greg Maddux, making his first relief
appearance in 11 years, facing the best hitter of the '90s, Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   As chants of ``Tony! Tony! Tony!'' filled the San Diego night,
Gwynn bounced out to end it after 3 hours, 17 minutes of nerves
rubbed raw.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has been having postseason parties since 1902, and in
all those years, no team down 3-nil has ever come back to win. Now
the Braves, once down 3-nil, are halfway there.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are again, in this scream of a season, peeking once
again at possible history, just as we did all summer as Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa played Top This.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy said, ``Top this,'' and the Braves did.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
