<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Buckeye poll' not the usual ranking
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ It's called ``The Buckeye Poll'' and this week
Ohio State opponent Minnesota (3-2) is No. 1 in it. Next week, OSU
foe Northwestern (2-4) will be the top-ranked team, according to
Buckeye tailback Joe Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the underdogs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Ohio State fans panic, know that the ``The Buckeye Poll''
was concocted by Montgomery and has no bearing on which teams go to
the national championship Fiesta Bowl in January. The fictitious
poll is just the tailback's way of trying to create some motivation
heading into games against unranked opponents Minnesota (Saturday)
and Northwestern (Oct. 24).
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Buckeye Poll or Montgomery-Buckeye poll, as fellow
tailback Michael Wiley refers to it, is probably the most elaborate
motivational tool being used by an OSU player. But it shows the
kind of mental gymnastics some of the players are using to stay
focused and sharp heading into the last six weeks of their season.
During that time, they will not face an opponent currently ranked
in either the Associated Press or USA Today /ESPN coaches' top 25.
</P>
<P>
   OSU quarterback Joe Germaine, who, like the rest of Montgomery's
teammates, said they had never heard of the Buckeye poll,
nevertheless admitted that taking an underdog mindset wasn't a bad
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow tri-captain and OSU linebacker Jerry Rudzinski agreed. He
said the Buckeyes have been 5-0 before _ in 1995, '96 and last
season, in fact _ so this is nothing new. What would set them apart
from previous 5-0 squads is finishing the year undefeated. For
Rudzinski, striving for that perfect season is his motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Antoine Winfield said revving up competition among
his OSU teammates is one way he's trying to stay hungry each week.
</P>
<P>
   He said the defensive backs have been battling to collect the
most interceptions each game, which, he admits, may have led to two
pass interference calls in the Illinois game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secondary, we wanted to see who could get the first
interception,'' he said. ``That's why Ahmed and I got those pass
interference calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they'd be as overly aggressive against a more feared
foe such as Michigan, Winfield smiled and said, ``We're not that
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn State coach Joe Paterno, whose Nittany Lions were No. 1 at
times last season, said discipline and guidance, not mind games,
are key to staying on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have strong leadership and I think Ohio State
does,'' Paterno said. ``John (Cooper) seems to have them where they
ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State defensive coordinator Fred Pagac believes as long as
the Buckeyes continue to concentrate on their performance, they'll
continue to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of letdowns are caused by opposing teams,'' he said. ``I
think the key thing is staying focused and treating each game with
equal weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
