<HEADLINE>
UNCLE MILTIE IS 90 
LAWYERS SUE `MCBEAL' STAR 
A SCHIZOPHRENIC LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON AND AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No wonder Goldie Hawn put on her sunglasses. Long
before President Clinton arrived at the G&AMP;P Charitable Foundation's
party honoring Milton Berle on his 90th birthday, the photographers
were busy. First they took pictures of Ms. Hawn alone.
</P>
<P>
   Then she was introduced to Sarah Ferguson, the Duchess of York,
and there was another round of snap-snap, flash-flash. ``I'm so
pictured out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then she went to Berle's table, and bowed. He stood up and
kissed her. More snap-snap, flash-flash.
</P>
<P>
   One can only imagine what it would have been like if her
longtime companion, Kurt Russell, had been there. ``He flew to
Washington to see Boston,'' Ms. Hawn said. It sounded like a
punchline from her days on ``Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In,'' but no.
Russell has an 18-year-old son, Boston, who is a student at
Georgetown University. In Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Berle left the cocktail party for the ballroom where
the dinner was about to begin, it was his turn for some snap-snap,
flash-flash with his wife, Lorna. ``She keeps telling me how happy
I am,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Katie Couric, an anchor on the ``Today''
show, dressed in Armani. Maybe it was just that she had stayed up
past her bedtime, but when she went over to greet reporters who had
been corralled behind a rope, she said: ``Can you believe it? I've
never had a really nice dress before.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a man from the Philippines introduced himself, saying that
he watched her every morning. He asked if he could shake her hand.
She agreed. Then he asked if he could kiss her hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' she said. ``Why not?'' So he did.
</P>
<P>
   Unflattering Suit
</P>
<P>
   This is probably not something they will talk about in the
unisex bathroom on ``Ally McBeal'':
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, the star with the thigh-climbing skirts and
the dancing-baby hallucinations, is being sued by a real-life
Manhattan law firm, which says she owes the firm 5 percent of
everything she earns from the prime-time series.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm _ Frankfurt, Garbus, Klein and Seltz _ which says
it reviewed the contract she signed when she got the part,
maintains that the fine print in that document promises the firm 5
percent of her ``Ally McBeal'' earnings, which total $780,000 as of
last week. Frankfurt, Garbus is accusing her of breach of contract
for failing to pay $39,000.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed in State Supreme Court, the firm laid out
the financial arrangements it says Ms. Flockhart agreed to. The
firm says the contract called for her to take home $50,000 for the
pilot episode and $30,000 an episode once the series went on the
air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made absolutely every effort to resolve this,'' said
Maura Wogan, who filed the lawsuit for the firm. But a spokesman
for Ms. Flockhart said, ``She doesn't owe them any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Dividing Her Time
</P>
<P>
   So how does Isabel Allende find time to write? Tuesday she was
in New York, doing the things authors do: being interviewed in the
morning and appearing at a ceremony in the evening. She left the
ceremony, at the Hudson Theater on West 44th Street, with the
$200,000 Dorothy and Lillian Gish Prize. But back to the question
of time to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very schizophrenic life,'' Ms. Allende said. ``One
part is about being out there, and one part is private, quiet.
Fortunately, I don't have to take care of my kids anymore. They're
grown and gone.''
</P>
<P>
   She told an interviewer that the ceremony was the first time her
parents, her son and a Chilean friend had been in the same place at
the same time in 25 years. She also said that she had just finished
another novel, about the California gold rush. ``My mother is the
only person who corrects my manuscripts,'' Ms. Allende said. ``She
said, `I'm so pleased that for the first time we're not in the
book.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
