<HEADLINE>
GIANTS UNLIKELY TO COOPERATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The San Francisco Giants do not sound like they are
going to grant the hated Dodgers permission to talk to Dusty Baker
about the vacant managerial position.
</P>
<P>
   Giants general manager Brian Sabean said Tuesday at the club's
organizational meetings. ``(Baker) is under contract, that's all I
can say,'' alluding to the two-year extension that kicks in this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Baker led the Giants to a wild-card playoff game against the
Chicago Cubs this past season after winning the National League
West in 1997. He will earn $700,000 this coming season. At the time
Baker signed the extension, the Giants said they wanted him to be
with the club in 2000 when they open their new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is under contract, the Dodgers have to receive
permission to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone has not set up
an interview with Davey Johnson, who also is being considered for
the manager's job in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After rushing to hire Felipe Alou, who stayed with Montreal,
Malone said he will be more patient in the next round of
discussions. He hopes to have a manager in place by his own
organizational meetings, Oct. 28-Nov. 1 in Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tigers' payroll is not expected to climb above $30
million next season, Johnson clearly is hoping the Dodgers act
soon. They are expected to have a $75 million payroll in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
