<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EXECUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CRUEL AND UNUSUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   Executing a mentally impaired person for a crime committed while
still a juvenile does not serve the interests of justice. Gov.
James Gilmore of Virginia should recognize that as he weighs the
clemency application of Dwayne Allen Wright, who is scheduled to be
executed Wednesday evening by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Wright had just turned 17 in 1989 when he went on a four-day
spree of violence that resulted in three murders. He was later
convicted of two of the homicides and confessed to the third. No
one is challenging his guilt. At issue is whether to execute
someone who was a teen-ager when he committed the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   America remains one of only a handful of countries _ Iran,
Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and Yemen are others _ that have refused to
ban executions of juvenile offenders. Eleven juvenile offenders
have been executed since 1976, when the death penalty was
reinstituted in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the issue of age is Wright's mental history. At the
age of 13 he was diagnosed with organic brain damage and acute
mental illness requiring treatment he never received in the
juvenile detention facilities where he was confined. Also, like
many others on death row, Wright had the misfortune of being
represented by an inexperienced counsel. The serious nature of his
impairment and its impact on his behavior was never conveyed to the
jury, which might well have declined to impose death had it known.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court could still grant a stay to allow it to
consider legal questions that remain in the Wright case. But the
chances are that Gilmore will have the final word on Wright's fate.
Surely the circumstances here ought to trouble even a staunch death
penalty supporter like Gilmore. He has the power to commute
Wright's sentence to life imprisonment without parole. He ought to
use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
