</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: YOU DON'T NEED A MAP TO PINPOINT PERFECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Tony Boselli is the Jacksonville Jaguars'
supreme offensive tackle, and he is intelligent, animated and
talkative. He grew up in Boulder, Colo., and earned a degree in
business administration from Southern California. He was the
Jaguars' first-ever draft pick and was the second player chosen
over all in the 1995 draft.
</P>
<P>
   But only a few days before being drafted, he did not know where
Jacksonville was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was probably in Alabama,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   And he was not joking.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan McCardell is the Jaguars' splendid receiver, obtained as
a free agent in 1996. He was born in Houston, played at Nevada-Las
Vegas and earned a degree in business management. McCardell is
intelligent, animated and talkative. But before arriving in
Jacksonville, he too, did not know that this city was in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I'd ever heard of Jacksonville is from the
Jacksonville Bulls of the old United States Football League,''
McCardell said. ``I thought Jacksonville was maybe in
Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was not joking.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Huyghue is the Jaguars' senior vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling my wife, Kimberly, that I was taking the
job and that we were moving to Jacksonville,'' Huyghue said. ``She
jumped out of bed and grabbed an atlas.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joking. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville may not have been the end of the pro football
world, but it certainly was a stop easy to miss. This city
steamrolled seemingly from nowhere and beat the odds _ beating
favored cities bidding for teams including Baltimore and St. Louis
and Memphis _ and along with Charlotte, N.C., won a new franchise
in 1993 and began play in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars trudged to a 4-12 record the first year. Then they
were 11-8 and lost at New England in the American Conference
championship game in 1996. Last year they were 11-6 and lost a
first-round playoff game at Denver. And now the Jaguars are among
the NFL's elite.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from a 28-21 victory over the visiting Miami Dolphins on
Monday night, the Jaguars are 5-0, leaving them, the Denver Broncos
and the Minnesota Vikings as the only teams still unbeaten in the
NFL. In their last 26 regular-season games, the Jaguars are 21-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you can't get people to leave,'' Huyghue said.
</P>
<P>
   Alltel Stadium, where the Jaguars play, is a sparkling, spiffy
place. It is modern, charming and efficient. Football fans here for
years had identified with the NFL through Miami and the Dolphins,
through Don Shula and his Super Bowl teams. Now Jacksonville's
identity complex has come full circle: the Jaguars beat the
Dolphins on national television in full view for their fans and for
the world to see. Everyone saw an exciting, young, fast team that
can play the game in a variety of entertaining ways. Everyone saw
Jacksonville, too.
</P>
<P>
   Psssst. It's in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe now they see why the Jaguars will be heard from in the
playoffs this fall. The Jaguars have a two-game lead on Pittsburgh
in the AFC Central and play at Buffalo on Sunday. They have a
mobile, strong-armed, quick-legged and daring quarterback in Mark
Brunell. They have a big-play defense and strong leadership from
the top in owner Wayne Weaver, Huyghue and head coach Tom Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go as far and be as good as we're willing to work,''
Boselli said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars do work. Coughlin is viewed as a taskmaster, and he
works his players full throttle. He has made the game into his own
science and those close to him say that there is no area of his
team _ from working with snappers and holders to monitoring his
defensive backs' backpedal _ that he does not master. He is
detailed and prepared and his team is playing that way.
</P>
<P>
   The team is exhibiting a penchant for winning close games. The
Jaguars won by 1 point in the season opener at Chicago, by 5 points
at home against Kansas City and by 5 at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Jaguars slipped by the Dolphins on Monday night
showing that they know how to start and how to finish. Jacksonville
scored the game's first 14 points, Miami scored the next 21 and
then Jacksonville scored the final 14. McCardell produced touchdown
catches of 23 and 56 yards from Brunell early and late in the
fourth quarter to win it. The final one came with 2 minutes 36
seconds left, the first play after Miami's Olindo Mare missed a
54-yard field-goal attempt that would have given Miami a 24-21
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have players hand-picked by the coaches and the
organization that fit their mold,'' McCardell said. ``Guys who work
and are willing to sacrifice. Something special is in the air
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell added: ``The way we played the fourth quarter against
Miami is the way this football team is: It's a group of fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   If they get there, if they get all the way to Super Bowl XXXIII
on Jan. 31, guess where the game will be played? In Miami, of
course, in Pro Player Stadium. Right in Florida, in the Dolphins'
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's official. We're state rivals now, almost like something
from the colleges,'' linebacker Kevin Hardy said. ``Jacksonville is
a nice place and Miami may be a bigger city. We want to be the
bigger team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the Jaguars are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
