<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WALLSTREET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REVERBERATIONS OF A FADING BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Oct. 14:
</P>
<P>
   There are great advantages for New York in being the financial
capital of the world. But there is a downside. When financial
markets are roiled, and investors grow hesitant, Wall Street
inevitably cuts back. Those cuts are likely to have a larger impact
on the New York region than on other areas. It would be wise for
city and state officials to start planning now for reduced tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The rounds of Wall Street layoffs are just beginning, and could
be larger than those that followed the 1987 stock market crash.
Merrill Lynch, which Tuesday announced plans to lay off 3,400
employees and 900 consultants _ about 1,500 in the metropolitan
area _ believes it erred in 1987 by not reacting quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is being hurt by more than lower stock prices.
Securities firms make much of their business underwriting new
securities and selling them to investors. But the volume of such
underwritings has fallen sharply as investors have shunned bonds
from all but the safest companies. Merrill pointed to bond markets
and to emerging markets _ Asia and Latin America _ as the areas
where the cuts would be steepest.
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, the securities industry is not a very big part
of the local economy. Stephen Kagann, Gov. George Pataki's top
economist, notes that just 3.3 percent of the people with jobs in
the city and its New York suburbs work for Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street's economic importance is far greater than that
figure would indicate. Not only are there workers in related
industries, such as banking and insurance, but the Wall Street jobs
have been both the best-paying and the fastest-growing. The average
income for those who work in the securities business in New York
was $172,000 last year, or about four times the average for all
downstate New York employees. That figure is inflated because many
of Wall Street's lower-paying back-office jobs are now in New
Jersey, but it remains impressive.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is likely to fall. Much of the Wall Street payments
come in the form of bonuses paid early in the calendar year. Even
for those who keep their jobs, next year's bonuses are likely to be
sharply lower. That has negative implications for high-end
retailers and expensive home sales, as well as for state and city
income-tax collections. New York politicians accustomed to the
budget surpluses that have been generated in part by the Wall
Street boom had better trim back their expectations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981013.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT &LR;      10-13 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' PROBLEMS COVER THE ICE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even if the Rangers signed Zigmund Palffy from the
Islanders and Scott Niedermayer from the Devils today, they would
still be three or four players short of a good team. And they
aren't about to sign either restricted free agent and risk the
wrath of other National Hockey League teams.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy is a sharpshooter and Niedermayer is a puck-carrying
defensemen. The Rangers could use both, as they have demonstrated
in being outscored by 12-3 while starting their season 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   But even with those two, the Rangers would still need a young
power forward to crash the corners and the opposing goal crease.
They would still need a dependable, veteran center to win face-offs
and anchor a second line. They would still need a young,
defense-oriented defenseman with skating skills to clear the slot
with intimidating checks. And they would still need a goalie to
give up fewer than the eight goals that Mike Richter has allowed in
his last two periods of work.
</P>
<P>
   So with the hockey season less than a week old, two of the local
teams are already in distress while it is too soon to judge the
third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, as always, get the most attention, so let's start
at Madison Square Garden. Their 4-2 loss to St. Louis on Monday,
more embarrassing than the score suggests, exposed several flaws in
what remains an old, slow, soft team. Left wing Esa Tikkanen,
signed as a free agent in training camp and awarded a first-line
spot next to Wayne Gretzky, had to be demoted to center on a lower
line in the third period Monday. Gretzky and the coaching staff
lobbied for Tikkanen in the preseason. They all remember Tikkanen
fondly from their happy days in Edmonton, a decade or so ago. So
much for cronyism and wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, earning more than $5 million on a free-agent contract,
looked great for the first five periods of the season. Since then,
his play has been alarming, particularly on the long shot from the
neutral zone that gave Al MacInnis his second of three goals
Monday. Will Coach John Muckler go with young Dan Cloutier when the
Rangers play host to the Devils on Friday night?
</P>
<P>
   But their biggest problems are at the other end of the ice,
where they are averaging fewer than 20 shots per game. Brian
Leetch, the captain, happened to mention: ``We don't have a guy
who's going to get 50 for us, or something.'' Last season, they
lacked one who could score 25.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy could score more, and the Islanders don't seem inclined
to sign him. Their reckless and belligerent management is too busy
picking fights with politicians and landlords and treating Long
Island fans as suckers. And so Palffy sits idle in Slovakia while
the Islanders start the season at 0-2. It must be just a
coincidence that so many NHL teams are refusing to bid for each
other's restricted free agents and so many good ones are without
jobs. Certainly the compensation requirements are stiff _ up to
five first-round draft choices. And collusion is so hard to prove,
isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   There were several unrestricted free agents, good ones, too,
available last summer. Players such as Ron Francis and Uwe Krupp
might have filled Ranger needs. But Rangers president and general
manager Neil Smith did not compete financially for them. Perhaps
the new Cablevision owners have stepped on his cash cord. With Phil
Esposito finally being dismissed as Tampa Bay general manager
Tuesday, the buzz around the league will soon be: Who's next?
</P>
<P>
   As for the Devils, 0-1 so far, they seem stable. A contract
dispute such as Niedermayer's is nearly a yearly thing for Lou
Lamoriello, who talked so tough during the 1994 lockout. He is one
of few general managers able to enforce the collective bargaining
agreement to his advantage. Most of his stars work for less than
market rate, as Niedermayer probably will when he signs. If they
don't like it, he ships them out. Devils' owner John McMullen
threatened to move the team to Nashville while winning the 1995
Stanley Cup. But compared with the heavy-handed newcomers on Long
Island and the cold-blooded calculators running the Garden,
McMullen seems like a warm and fuzzy philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Garden, with its corporate tentacles, that most
threatens all local hockey fans. The Cablevision ownership now
controls television rights to all three hockey teams, as well as to
all basketball and baseball teams. With monopoly control,
Cablevision is now dropping Islander telecasts, with little notice,
at whim. Cablevision, not the viewer, decides what the viewer
watches. Certainly such shabby treatment is what Islander
management deserves, but it is an abuse of the fans and is ominous
for the future of local sports on television.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps this is too harsh or ``hysterical,'' as Commissioner
Gary Bettman likes to call news media critics. So let's look at the
bright side. Maybe all three local hockey teams will be so bad this
season that even hockey fans won't care to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
