<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Oct. 14 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-TOURIST-KILLED (Los Angeles) _ The world turned its eyes
on Santa Monica on Tuesday, the day after a German tourist was shot
and killed during an armed robbery. Police said 50-year-old Horst
Featz was probably killed because he couldn't understand the
demands of his assailant, who shot him after he refused to turn
over a bag. With international travel agents in Los Angeles to
begin a convention, they say tourists are viewing the death of
Featz as a black eye for all of Los Angeles. By Michael Coit and
Yvette Cabrera. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-RESTAURANT-GRADES (Los Angeles) _ County supervisors will
consider changing the restaurant grading system to include a D for
the worst-scoring restaurants. The letter grade would replace a
numeric score and lead to automatic closure of offending
establishments. By Douglas Haberman. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LIVER-DONOR (Los Angeles) _ Doctors from Los Angeles County/USC
Medical Center will hold a news conference to discuss their first
``living-related liver transplant,'' in which 6-month-old Lydia
Hand of Lancaster received a lobe from her grandmother's liver.
Lydia, her parents and the grandmothers are expected to be at the
briefing.By Bhavna Mistry. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   CA-ALAMEDA-CORRIDOR (Los Angeles) _ Fourteen years after being
proposed, the $2 billion Alameda Corridor project will officially
begin Wednesday following Los Angeles City Council approval Tuesday
of final documents for the project. When completed in 2001, the
project is envisioned to be a high-speed corridor to bring goods
from the Los Angeles and Long Beach harbors to Union Station and
then across the country. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``f''
financial and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   TEKELEC-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ Shares in Tekelec rose more than
15 percent on news that Sprint will use its equipment in their
local and long distance services. The Sprint deal follows news
Sept. 1 that AT&AMP;T also chose Tekelec machines for its wireless
division. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
files.)
</P>
