<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' JONES TALKS OF RE-SIGNING NEWTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. and Kevin Lyons 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said yesterday that
the team is so pleased with guard Nate Newton's play and
conditioning that they will try to re-sign him in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   There was much talk after the Washington game Oct. 4 about how
the Cowboys wore down the Redskins' $57 million defensive-tackle
combo of Dana Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson, who both looked tired
and out of shape in the fourth quarter. One of the players
responsible for wearing them out was the 36-year-old Newton, who
was supposedly so old and out of shape last year that the Cowboys
forced him to get him in shape. At 318 pounds, Newton is 52 pounds
under last season's playing weight of 370. He can become a free
agent after this season.
Davis unlikely to play
Wide receiver Billy Davis most likely will not play Sunday against
the Chicago Bears because of a strained left foot, coach Chan
Gailey said. Davis will be replaced in the starting lineup by Ernie
Mills.  &LR; name:_ Clarence E. Hill Jr.
More Deion on offense
Gailey said wide receiver/cornerback/punt returner Deion Sanders
will get more work on offense in practice this week and during the
bye week after Sunday's game against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he wants Sanders, who has played primarily in the
four-receiver sets, to get more time in the two- and three-receiver
packages. Teams can't load up on receiver Michael Irvin with
Sanders in the game, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has caught four passes for 71 yards in the past four
games.  &LR; name:_ Kevin Lyons
</P>
</TEXT>
