<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     10-13 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA BATTLE FOR BUCKS IS FAN-TEDIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't know about you, but my neighbors did not drape their front
hedges in black over the news yesterday that the NBA is canceling
games.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there were no ``Free Scottie Pippen'' signs. No one,
as far as I could tell, went door to door asking for spare change
to help feed David Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, we are left speechless as we ponder the vexing issues.
Somebody help me with this.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, who signed a $2.64 billion TV deal with NBC and
Turner, are locking out the players, who stand firm on their
negotiated right to command contracts of $100 million?
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, home of the beloved Rockets, this is news. In
Chicago, where Michael Jordan is the elixir that warms their
blustery winters, this is news.
</P>
<P>
   But here, as in most of the country, this is dog bites man. Or
better still, dog bites dog.
</P>
<P>
   Yawn. Somebody wake us when something new happens.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the only thing new in the NBA these days is
commissioner Stern's gray beard. The star of the show, Jordan,
threatens retirement. The next generation, namely Kevin Garnett,
turned his back on college, turned his back on a $100 million
contract offer and eventually signed with the Minnesota
Timberwolves for $126 million.
</P>
<P>
   He is 20 years old. The Larry Bird rule protected his right to
do so. The Bird exemption has made a mockery of the proud NBA's
salary cap and made $100 million players of people like Juwan
Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Juwan, you're no Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Shaquille O'Neal, another of the NBA's
100-Million-Dollar Babies. But for once in his adult life, Shaq
showed astounding depth and insight last week as he answered an
Associated Press reporter's question about the effects of the NBA
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans would be very upset, and our game would be slightly
tarnished, like baseball and hockey when they left their fans,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to alienate the fans. ... Once you start this,
20,000 to 30,000 fans at the arenas becomes 8,000 or 9,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq isn't old enough to remember, or care, but the NBA was not
always the planet's league of choice. Once upon a time, circa the
late 1970s, franchises hopped from Buffalo to San Diego, from New
Orleans to Utah. Teams flew by commercial _ and some by cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But along came His Airness, Jordan. He flew all by himself. And
with him, so did the NBA soar _ into malls and onto cable TV,
across the oceans, and even into the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   What are you NBA idiots doing?
</P>
<P>
   It is the owners who keep raising ticket prices, who keep
leasing luxury suites and who keep finding more room for courtside
seats. It is the owners who, when Garnett balks at $100 million,
say here, take $126 million.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a hard salary cap is wrong. Anybody want to argue
that Michael Jordan is not worth $126 million? $150 million? $200
million?
</P>
<P>
   Players are worth what owners _ foolhardy owners? _ are willing
to pay them. Remember Jon Koncak? Once again, though, we have a
sport where the owners want the players to help the owners save
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost certainty,'' NBA owners are calling it. ``Profit
certainty'' seems a more accurate term.
</P>
<P>
   The frog in the NBA witch's brew is that the players of the '90s
have only a cursory connection with their fans. Even Jordan, who
wages wars of words and nerves with Jerry Krause and Jerry
Reinsdorf, barely acknowledges that it's the fans whose ``costs''
know no cap.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq, the '90s philosopher, is right. If the NBA cancels its
Christmas, or more, the fans might not come back.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, even with its self-destructive ways, had the advantage
of being the game many of us were born with. Pro football survived
its labor problems because it owns Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Pro basketball, let me suggest, is not the communion of choice
in most American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Out of sight, out of mind. Oh _ out of Jordans?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
