<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GARRETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT SHOWING HIS DEEP SIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys quarterback Jason Garrett has shown he
can throw the deep ball.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the then-shocking performance on Thanksgiving Day 1994
when he passed for 311 yards and two touchdowns in leading the
Cowboys to a comeback victory against Green Bay? Garrett threw deep
balls of 35 yards to Alvin Harper and 45 yards to Michael Irvin for
touchdowns in that victory.
</P>
<P>
   And since taking over for injured starter Troy Aikman, Garrett
has continued to go deep. In the past four games, Garrett has
completed 21 passes for 17 yards or more _ including nine Sunday in
the 27-20 victory against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett maintains that he does nothing special, saying he merely
puts the ball up and lets receivers make plays. But the Cowboys say
their success has a lot to do with Garrett's skill in making the
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason can throw the deep pass,'' said receiver Billy Davis,
who has hauled in receptions of 36, 55 and 80 yards from Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey: ``He knows how much heat to put
on the ball and whether to throw it hard or soft. He has great
touch.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Cowboys aren't throwing the deep pass merely
because Garrett is in the lineup. Receivers coach Dwain Painter
said the go route, in which a wide receiver speeds straight
downfield, is one of five basic routes of the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks coach Buddy Geis said that Aikman and Garrett have
been working on the deep throw since spring and that both have
improved their ability to make the throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do that drill every day,'' Geis said. ``The more you throw
it, the more you work on it, the better you get. Jason and Troy
throw the ball as well as I've seen. Both have such fine touch on
it and have good location of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the premise seems simple _ throw the ball up and let the
receiver make a play on it _ there are several keys to making the
play successful.
</P>
<P>
   For sideline routes, Painter said the key is positioning by the
receiver, who must ride the defender to the inside and fade to the
ball thrown one or two yards off the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Ernie Mills' 18-yard touchdown catch against the
Panthers, Geis said it's also about trajectory and timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great example was Ernie on the touchdown,'' Geis said.
``Ernie wasn't down the field 6 or 7 yards and the ball was out of
Jason's hands. Eighteen yards later he's catching it in the end
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   And if defenses continue to play eight-man fronts to stop
running back Emmitt Smith and continue to leave cornerbacks
one-on-one with Cowboys receivers, the deep ball will remain a big
part of the Cowboys' arsenal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
