r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-OFFENSE     10-13 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSIVE LINE CAPTURES RATINGS COUP IN TEXAS A&AMP;M VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M offensive line coach J.B.
Grimes never intended for his starters to take every snap against
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were holding up good and they kept telling me they
weren't tired,'' Grimes said. ``So I decided, `I'm dancing with
you, then.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M eventually danced into the night with a 28-21 upset of the
defending national champions, a victory that vaulted the Aggies
(5-1, 2-0) to No. 10 in The Associated Press college football
rankings heading into Saturday's game against Baylor (2-3, 1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Much of the background music that triggered the triumph was
played by members of a rebuilt offensive line that opened running
lanes for two 100-yard rushers and turned in its best performance
this season. For the first time in A&AMP;M's six games, every offensive
lineman that played received a ``winning performance'' rating from
Grimes, who bestows the honor only if a player achieves his goal as
a blocker on 75 percent of the Aggies' offensive snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen our line play that well against this type of
team since I've been here,'' said tight end Dan Campbell, a
fifth-year senior from Glen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew the talent was there. They just needed to get
their blocking schemes down,'' said taiback Dante Hall, who rushed
for a game-high 113 yards against Nebraska. ``At the first of the
year, they fired off the line, made contact and that was it. Now,
there's contact and a push. The other guys are moving backwards.
That's a big-time difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers support Hall's claim. The ground-bound Aggies did
not have a 100-yard rusher in any game until Oct. 3, when Hall
romped for 177 yards in a 24-21 victory against Kansas. They got
two more against Nebraska, from Hall (32 carries, 113 yards) and
fullback Ja'Mar Toombs (10 carries, 110 yards), upping the season
total to three.
</P>
<P>
   That is a far cry from the season opener, when A&AMP;M managed only
33 yards on 31 carries in a 23-14 loss to Florida State. Grimes,
who is blending the talents of three first-year starters and a
fourth player who shifted positions this season, said incremental
improvement has been evident each week.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M had only two linemen earn ``winning performance''
recognition in its first two games. The past four weeks, at least
five players have earned such acclaim, although the only
across-the-board declaration for every participant came after the
Nebraska game.
</P>
<P>
   That coincided with the iron-man efforts of the Aggies' front
five, who did not sit out a single snap: left tackle Rex Tucker,
left guard Cameron Spikes, center Seth McKinney, right guard Semisi
Heimuli and right tackle Andy Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, Heimuli is the only player who started at the
same spot in 1997. Spikes moved from right tackle to left guard
during spring drills. The others moved up in the depth chart
because of voids left by departing seniors.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, a redshirt freshman, is the youngest. Spikes and
Tucker are the only seniors. All have felt lost at times, McKinney
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning of the year was bad, especially for me,''
McKinney said. ``I was getting yelled at all the time for letting
my pads get too high. We'd been feeling a lot of pressure because
we weren't putting points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M still has not topped the 30-point mark this season. But no
one is complaining about hanging 28 points on a Nebraska defense
that has allowed an average of 14.8 per game. The best part, Spikes
said, was the confidence boost the Aggies gained by winning the war
in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means the world to us. From an offensive line standpoint,
we controlled the line of scrimmage,'' Spikes said. ``And we did it
against a great team like Nebraska. It was by far the best game
we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   By no means, Grimes said, will the Nebraska game signal an end
to a rotation system among A&AMP;M offensive linemen. Grimes, who came
to A&AMP;M after overseeing offensive lines at Virginia Tech (1993-97)
and Arkansas (1989-92), described his decision to avoid
substitutions against the Cornhuskers as rare but not unprecedented
in his coaching tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are still learning to work together, so they need
to keep playing. The more they play together, the better they'll
get,'' Grimes said. ``If they stay healthy, they're making the kind
of progress where they can be big-time good before this year's
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, they've been good enough to provide the background
music to a victory dance against the defending national champs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-13-98 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
