<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-ALAMEDA-CORRIDOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARGO RAIL LINE ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Fourteen years after the Alameda Corridor rail
line was proposed, $700 million in contracts will be signed
Wednesday to begin construction in the $2 billion project.
</P>
<P>
   After years of pleading for funds and resolving disputes, the
Alameda Corridor Transportation Authority board is ready to sign
the contract with Tutor-Saliba for the high-speed rail line, 20
miles long, connecting the ports of Los Angeles and Long Beach with
Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the largest public works transit project in
history,'' Councilman Rudy Svorinich Jr. said Tuesday after the
City Council approved a series of resolutions giving the authority
board power to issue the contracts and $1.3 billion in bonds to
begin the work.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was the last city to sign off on the project. The
rail line eventually will go through seven cities to transport
goods to and from the harbors and across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some have likened this to the Panama Canal,'' Svorinich said.
``When it's completed, upwards of 30 percent of all goods coming
into the United States will use the Alameda Corridor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, favoring the rail line since his 1993
election, has said it will be a major step in the region's
evolution as an international trade hub.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's one step closer to reality,'' said Riordan
spokeswoman Noelia Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Svorinich said the city had to overcome a lot of suspicion and
jealousy. ``Not everyone was happy with this, but I think everyone
came to believe it is of importance to them,'' Svorinich said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is scheduled to begin in early 1999 and to be
completed by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the project will create more than 8,100 jobs, and
officials project it could lead eventually to more than 100,000
jobs in businesses related to importing and exporting.
</P>
<P>
   The rail line alone is expected to bring in $70 million a year
in revenue, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
