 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Oct. 14.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Brussels, Belgium) _ The Clinton administration
has won enormous concessions from the Yugoslav President, Slobodan
Milosevic, but the agreement on Kosovo seems fraught with the
dangers that have long bedevilled the West in Bosnia. A news
analysis by Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   GAZA-INDUSTRIAL-PARK (Gaza City, Gaza Strip) _ The grandly named
Gaza Industrial Estate will employ up to a thousand Palestinians in
several small-scale manufacturing ventures. It is a measure of the
Gaza Strip's economic desperation that this tentative, modest
project looms so large for Palestinian planners. By William A. Orme
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CLEANUP (Panama City, Panama) _ For nearly a century, the
U.S. military has used the jungle terrain surrounding the Panama
Canal as a testing ground for explosives and chemical weapons. Now,
a little more than a year before those ranges must be handed back
to Panama, Washington is balking at cleaning up some of the most
hazardous of the ordnance its troops are leaving behind. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CLINTON (Broomfield, Colo.) _ While the election in
three weeks has been portrayed in Washington as a referendum on
whether President Clinton should be impeached, the scandal has not
become a central part of the discourse _ or the candidates'
strategies _ in the closest House and Senate contests in the
country. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILER-GIRL (Dixon, Ill.) _ Watching classmates strut past in
designer clothes, Wendy Williams sat silently on the yellow school
bus, wearing a cheap belt and rummage-sale slacks. One boy stopped
and yanked his thumb, demanding her seat. ``Move it, trailer
girl,'' he sneered. It has never been easy to live on the wrong
side of the tracks, but in the economically robust 1990s, with
sprawling new houses and three-car garages sprouting like
cornstalks on the Midwestern prairie, the sting that comes with
scarcity gets rubbed with an extra bit of salt. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo cients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTOPSIES (Undated) _ Autopsies are on the decline in
frequency and accuracy, researchers report in the journal Nature.
By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-BANKS (Toronto) _ John Cleghorn showed what a formidable
competitor he can be when he played center on the McGill University
football team that won the intercollegiate championship in 1960.
Now that he is chairman of the Royal Bank of Canada, the country's
largest, and campaigning vigorously for government approval to make
it a lot larger by merging with the Bank of Montreal, he is acting
as though he still thinks no one can get past him. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BANKAMERICA-HEDGE-LOSS (Undated) _ BankAmerica Corp., the
nation's fifth-largest bank, is expected to announce a big hedge
fund loss Wednesday in the latest example of the dangers posed to
financial companies from the risky, often high-flying investment
pools. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Eastman Kodak Co.
reported third-quarter earnings of $398 million, up 72 percent from
the same quarter last year. It was way ahead of schedule on its
cost-cutting campaign. It had stanched the peristent cash
hemmorhage from its digital portfolio. Yet investors reacted as
though they had been kicked in the stomach, and sent the
photography giant's shares plummeting. The reason: Kodak's earnings
may have been up, but its revenues declined. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Viewers of television shows like
``The Practice'' and ``Law and Order'' may be momentarily confused
next month when American Honda Motor Co. starts a $50 million
advertising campaign for its new Odyssey minivan. One of the ad's
scene-setting shots is intended to be mistaken for network
programming. By Andrea Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-BAD-ART (Boston) _ Arts in America: Boston's Museum of
Bad Art. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTI-THEATER-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Corpus Christi,'' a
controversial play, at the Manhattan Theater Club. Reviewed by Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd writes about the sordid
scene these days in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich comments on the killing of a
gay college student in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times on the
Yankees. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-PADRES (Atlanta) _ The Braves force a Game 6 in
Atlanta on Wednesday by rallying from the brink of elimination two
games in a row. The Braves will go with Glavine in Game 6, but what
will the Padres do? By Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MASHED-POTATOES (Undated) _ Comfort food _ that buzz phrase
embracing all the bland, soft satisfactions of childhood eating _
doesn't quite have the cachet now that it did a few years ago, when
restaurants everywhere were trying to outdo each other in the
evocation of home and hearth. But somehow, one of those
quintessentially comforting foods, mashed potatoes, has not only
held on in popularity but also managed to ease right into the
turbulent mainstream of today's creative cookery. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   EATZI-MARKET (New York) _ It's not a restaurant. It's not a
grocery store. It's Eatzi's Market and Bakery, the food store that
ate Dallas. Now, in the boldest out-of-town incursion since George
Steinbrenner bought the Yankees, it has planted its cowboy boots
right in Macy's basement. As stunned shoppers in Dallas, Houston
and Atlanta already know, Eatzi's means high-energy and high-volume
(in both senses of the word). It's a prepared-food store in which
dozens of chefs, working in open kitchens, turn out hundreds of
dishes every day, with Puccini arias blasting away in the
background. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONAL-FOOD (New York) _ It's autumn in New York. A chill is
nudging through the last trace of summer's warmth, and the leaves
hint of turning. The signs are impossible to miss _ except, maybe,
if you're a chef. After all the lip service New York's best cooks
have given to the virtues of seasonal cooking, some of them have
decided that they'll cook seasonally, all right, but they'll be the
ones to choose exactly which season. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   MASTIC-ICE-CREAM (New York) _ Of the eight Greek dessert choices
on the menu at Molyvos, the one ordered least is mastic ice cream
with Commandaria and fig sauce. Mastic ice cream? True, the dessert
suffers from a name-image problem: it's not exactly loaded with
lyricism. It's unfamiliar, too, except to those who know this rare
and costly flavoring; at $60 to more than $100 a pound, mastic
might be called the caviar of flavors. By Suzanne Hamlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
