   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BOSTON-BAD-ART-2, 10-13 --
Jerry Reilly, executive director of the Museum of Bad Art in
Boston. ``There are millions and millions of people who paint but
have no aspirations to be the next Monet,'' he says. ``Just as
someone singing in the shower is not singing to be the next Frank
Sinatra. They just sing because they love it. These are paintings
from people who just paint because they love it.'' (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BOSTON-BAD-ART-1, 10-13 --
``The Pirate King,'' is among the rigorously selected works at the
Museum of Bad Art in Boston. Though the museum might seem at first
to be nothing but a joke, an elaborate sendup of the snooty
pretension and dictated taste of the professional art world, it
also has a positive point, its founders say. ``We say we're
celebrating the right to fail,'' says Scott Wilson, an antiques
dealer who is the museum's curator. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CARMEN-OPERA-REVIEW, 10-13
-- Beatrice Uria-Monzon in the title role and Franco Farina as Don
Jose in the Franco Zeffirelli production of ``Carmen'' at the
Metropolitan Opera. Ms. Uria-Monzon, making her Metropolitan Opera
debut in the first ``Carmen'' of the season, is an exceptionally
beautiful woman who gives us a lithe, small-framed and unabashedly
seductive Carmen. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- PIMPERNEL-THEATER-3, 10-13
-- Rachel York unveiling the new sign for the revamped ``Scarlet
Pimpernel'' with Rex Smith, center, and Douglas Sills. The musical,
based on the 1905 novel by Baroness Orczy, had been foundering. But
the people who did go kept giving standing ovations and, in July,
Cablevision Systems Corp. announced that its Radio City
Entertainment division was acquiring the show, which reopened
Saturday. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- PIMPERNEL-THEATER-2, 10-13
-- Rachel York in the opening scene of the revised ``Scarlet
Pimpernel.'' In July, Madison Square Garden's parent, Cablevision
Systems Corp., allowed its Radio City Entertainment division to
acquire the show in a joint venture with financier Theodore
Forstmann, who is one of the production's original producers. And
on Saturday afternoon, the curtain rose on the new ``Pimpernel.''
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- PIMPERNEL-THEATER-1, 10-13
-- David Checketts, president of Madison Square Garden, is one of
the people behind the major overhaul of the troubled Broadway show,
``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' which reopened Saturday. ``When you
start talking about businesses that have risks - the New York
Knicks, the New York Rangers - we're kind of used to that,'' says
Checketts, who saw ``Pimpernel'' several times and felt it deserved
to continue. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BINLIDS-THEATER-REVIEW,
10-13 -- James Doran, at center, with other cast members in the
play ``Binlids.'' In two somber hours, the play, written and
performed by residents of West Belfast, tells the story of three
decades of bloodshed and anguish in which the conflict in Northern
Ireland, known as the troubles, has engulfed their hardscrabble
community. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- MASTIC-ICE-CREAM, 10-13 --
Of the eight Greek dessert choices on the menu at Molyvos, the one
ordered least is mastic ice cream with Commandaria and fig sauce.
The special dish, which blends fennel, anise and mint, is
unfamiliar to most, but not to those who know this rare and costly
flavoring; at $60 to more than $100 a pound, mastic might be called
the caviar of flavors. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- MASTER-CHEF, 10-13 -- This
is the first of eight columns by Francois Payard, the chef and
owner of Payard Patisserie and Bistro in Manhattan. Payard's
collaborator on these columns is Dorie Greenspan. (Joyce
Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- EATZI-MARKET-2, 10-13 -- The
takeout salad area in the new Eatzi's in Macy's basement. It's not
a restaurant. It's not a grocery store. It's Eatzi's Market and
Bakery, the food store that ate Dallas. Now, in the boldest
out-of-town incursion since George Steinbrenner bought the Yankees,
it has planted its cowboy boots at Macy's. (Suzanne DeChillo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OLD WESTBURY, N.Y. -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- EATZI-MARKET-1,
10-13 -- Eatzi's is already established on Long Island, at the
Carle Place Shopping Center near Old Westbury. Now, on to Macy's.
Eatzi's means high-energy and high-volume. The prepared-food store
employs dozens of chefs who work in open kitchens, turning out
hundreds of dishes every day as Puccini arias blast in the
background. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- MASHED-POTATOES-2, 10-13 --
Somehow, one of those quintessentially comforting foods, mashed
potatoes, has not only held on in popularity but also managed to
ease right into the turbulent mainstream of today's creative
cookery. At Bouley Bakery, the kitchen follows the mashed potato
recipe of the French chef Joel Robuchon, and the resulting dish is
a creamy delight. (Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- MASHED-POTATOES-1, 10-13 --
Mashed potatoes are the starting point for many creative dishes. At
Fresco in Manhattan, parsnips embellish a creamy mound. (Kiyoshi
Togashi/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
