<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/13/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PARIS -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- PARIS-FASHION, 10-13 -- The
only vision more disturbing than the Goth panorama that Olivier
Theyskens displayed in his spectacular show Monday was the
suggestion of the return of wasp waists and full skirts a la Dior.
From left, Pleated olive top and military-inspired trousers by John
Galliano; White poncho and hot pants by Marc Jacobs for Louis
Vuitton; Theyskens's Goth leather jacket. (Dan Lecca/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BANKAMERICA-HEDGE, 10-13 --
David Shaw, founder of the D.E. Shaw hedge fund, in the trading
room. BankAmerica Corp., the nation's fifth-largest bank, is
expected to announce a big hedge fund loss Wednesday in the latest
example of the dangers posed to financial companies from the risky,
sometimes high-flying investment pools. Some experts say that
BankAmerica's overall exposure to the Shaw fund could be as large
as $1 billion. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MONTREAL -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CANADA-BANKS, 10-13 -- John
Cleghorn, the chairman of the Royal Bank of Canada, wants to merge
with the Bank of Montreal in order to compete with giant foreign
institutions. ``If you're going to play in the big leagues, you've
got to be equipped,'' says Cleghorn, 57, who turned down a chance
to play for a professional Canadian football team. (Christopher
Morris/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SILVER SPRING, Md. -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND-2,
10-13 -- While all the meetings were going on in the Capitol,
President Clinton was attending an event in Silver Spring with,
from left, Rep. Albert Wynn, D-Md; Ralph Neas, a House candidate in
Maryland; Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, who spoke to
Clinton; Gov. Parris Glendening, Lieut. Gov. Kathleen
Townsend-Kennedy and Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND-1, 10-13
-- Erskine Bowles, President Clinton's chief of staff, left,
shuttles Tuesday between meeting rooms in talks on the budget.
Speaker Newt Gingrich, right, enjoys a break from one of the
numerous meetings. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) UNDATED -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CAMPAIGN-CLINTON, 10-13 --
Robert Greenlee, left, a Republican businessman, and Mark Udall, a
Democratic state representative, are in a close race in Colorado's
2nd Congressional District. Neither is using the Clinton scandal as
a campaign issue. ``Everybody's been walking a high wire on this,''
Udall says. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-4, 10-13
-- David Cone pitching against Cleveland on Tuesday night in the
sixth game of the American League Championship Series. The Yankees
lead the series, 3-2. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-3, 10-13
-- Chili Davis of the Yankees hitting a sacrifice fly to score Paul
O'Neill in the 1st inning against the Cleveland Indians on Tuesday
in the sixth game of the American League Championship Series. The
Bronx Bombers lead the series, 3-2. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-2, 10-13
-- No, it's not war, just baseball. A fan at Yankee Stadium on
Tuesday night tries to place the proper perspective on game six
against the Cleveland Indians in the American League Championship
Series. The Yankees lead the series, 3-2. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-1, 10-13
-- Fans at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday night expressing the fervent
hope that the team will wrap up its 35th pennant against the
Cleveland Indians and avoid a seventh game in the American League
Championship Series. The Yankees lead the series, 3-2. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CORPUS-CHRISTI-PROTEST,
10-13 -- Marchers protesting the opening Tuesday night in New York
of Terrence McNally's ``Corpus Christi.'' The play, about a gay
Christ-like man from Texas, was canceled when producers received
threats, but revived after an outcry from artists and civil
libertarians. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) DIXON, Ill. -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- TRAILER-GIRL-2, 10-13 --
Wendy Williams, 13 - a seventh grader with so much promise, and so
many obstacles - has been growing up at Chateau Estates, a fancy
name for a tin-plain trailer park. In the economically robust
1990s, with sprawling new houses and three-car garages sprouting
like cornstalks on the Midwestern prairie, the sting that comes
with scarcity gets rubbed with an extra bit of salt. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DIXON, Ill. -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- TRAILER-GIRL-1, 10-13 --
Wendy Williams, 13, with her cat, Katie, near the trailer park
where she lives with her parents in Dixon. In a world of Disney
World vacations and stylish clothes, Wendy has to struggle to keep
up her self-esteem. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PHILADELPHIA -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- MARRIAGE-EDUC, 10-13 --
Nineteen students at Martin Luther King High School in Philadelphia
are learning marriage skills. Most, citing their own broken
families, say they took the elective course to avoid their parents'
mistakes. (Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 --
SCI-NOBEL-PHYSICS-CHEMISTRY, 10-13 -- The Nobel Prizes in Physics
and Chemistry were announced Tuesday by the Royal Swedish Academy
of Sciences. Dr. Horst Stoermer, 49, a German-born professor who
works at both Columbia University in New York and at Bell
Laboratories in Murray Hill, N.J., is one of the three winners of
the physics prize. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- GAZA-INDUSTRY,
10-13 -- Israeli soldiers at a Gaza checkpoint examine a shipment
of Palestinian-grown potatoes headed for Israel. American advisers
hope to modernize such customs bottlenecks to simplify the flow of
commercial traffic. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN FRANCISCO -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- SANFRAN-ARTS-DONOR,
10-13 -- Philanthropist Phyllis Wattis in San Francisco. Admired
not just for her generosity, but for her discernment, she is known
for her thoughtful gifts, from an English horn for a teen-ager in
the San Francisco Youth Orchestra to the more than $20 million that
recently helped the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art buy works by
Robert Rauschenberg and others by Duchamp, Mondrian, Anselm Kiefer
and Wayne Thiebaud. (Jenny Thomas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BOSTON-BAD-ART-2, 10-13 --
Jerry Reilly, executive director of the Museum of Bad Art in
Boston. ``There are millions and millions of people who paint but
have no aspirations to be the next Monet,'' he says. ``Just as
someone singing in the shower is not singing to be the next Frank
Sinatra. They just sing because they love it. These are paintings
from people who just paint because they love it.'' (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- BOSTON-BAD-ART-1, 10-13 --
``The Pirate King,'' is among the rigorously selected works at the
Museum of Bad Art in Boston. Though the museum might seem at first
to be nothing but a joke, an elaborate sendup of the snooty
pretension and dictated taste of the professional art world, it
also has a positive point, its founders say. ``We say we're
celebrating the right to fail,'' says Scott Wilson, an antiques
dealer who is the museum's curator. (Ed Quinn/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Oct. 13, 1998 -- CARMEN-OPERA-REVIEW, 10-13
-- Beatrice Uria-Monzon in the title role and Franco Farina as Don
Jose in the Franco Zeffirelli production of ``Carmen'' at the
