<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-13 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALGAME-14-COX     10-13 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALGAME-14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yanks slug way into Series
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It ended much like the series started, the Yankees
flexing, showing why the word great is sometimes used to describe
them, and the Indians crumbling, proving again it's impossible to
overcome bad pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 9-5 win for Yankees Tuesday night, the Bombers
taking the American League pennant in six games and now having a
few days to sit back, relax and wait for their World Series
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fall Classic begins here Saturday night, and no matter who
comes to town, whether it be the Braves or Padres, the Yankees have
cleaned up their act and will be the favorite to take it all.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees celebrated their 35th AL title in a game that had
some very interesting moments, including a grand slam by Jim Thome
that for an inning had everyone thinking of the possibility of the
series going to a seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led 6-0, as David Cone totally dominated the Indians
for the first four innings and Scott Brosius hit a three-run shot
in the third. But in the fifth, Cone got sloppy, walking in a run
with none out. One out later, Thome blasted a grand slam into the
upper deck in right field.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleveland couldn't keep it close, thanks partially to the
bullpen, an error by shortstop Omar Vizquel and right fielder Manny
Ramirez, who misjudged a ball that may haunt him forever. The
inning started with Vizquel's first ever postseason error in 47
games (237 chances). Then, with runners at first and second and one
out in the sixth, Derek Jeter drove a ball to right-center. Ramirez
thought it was going out and leapt at the wall. Meanwhile, the ball
dropped about 10 feet in front of him. It ended up being a triple,
the Yankees scoring twice. They would add another, get some solid
relief pitching and then danced along with their fans to Frank
Sinatra singing ``New York, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange series. After blasting the Indians in the
opener and then losing two straight, the Yankees took three
straight. But it was not until Tuesday that their bats came alive,
against right-hander Charles Nagy, about the best the Indians have
to offer on this pitching-poor team. He was gone by the fourth. The
Yankees had been hitting .198 in the series, but on this night they
never stopped swinging the bats.
</P>
<P>
   By I.J. Rosenberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
